<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KNICKS-PISTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PISTONS DEFLATE KNICKS, 80-71 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ This was so close to being a revival for
Allan Houston. He was about ready to raise his hands and say, Amen,
in the Palace where his demons live. He was almost ready to lead
his teammates out of the eternal problems that have haunted them
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Pistons stuck the voodoo pins into Houston and the
Knicks and their playoff standing. What looked to be a Knick
celebration turned into the kind of dejection that has etched the
face of this team all year. Once again, the Knicks unraveled in the
fourth quarter beneath a flurry of turnovers, defensive blunders
and frazzled shot selection to lose to the Pistons, 80-71, Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   With just 10 games left, the Knicks went from potentially tying
the Pistons for the sixth spot in the playoffs to dropping out of
the picture and into ninth place in the Eastern Conference
standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't blow our intensity, we blew the game,'' said a
frustrated coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``It's hard to put into words. But
there is a certain amount of pride you have to take in how you
finish games. I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks vanished in this game with Houston down the stretch.
After scoring 17 first-half points on 6-for-10 shooting, he
finished with 23 on 9-for-18. Even more devastating was the
3-for-13 effort from the field by Latrell Sprewell, who was coming
off a 5-for-18 performance in a loss to the Wizards on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both players were part of the Knicks' fourth-quarter debacle in
which they scored just 10 points, had 7 turnovers and shot 5 for
16. After the Knicks had been leading by 9 points with 9 minutes
left, Grant Hill gave the Pistons the lead on a driving layup to
cap a 14-4 run. Over the next two minutes, the Knicks turned the
ball over four times, including once by Houston with one minute
left. Just before that play, Sprewell got sucked inside on the
penetration of Hill. Hill fired the ball out to Jud Buechler, who
was wide open to hit a 3-pointer with 1 minute 5 seconds left in
the game to give the Pistons a 73-69 lead that left the Knicks
deflated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a bad play,'' Van Gundy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to make plays down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the injured Patrick Ewing for the second straight night,
Houston knew he had to deliver. Once he slumped, the team slumped
with him, and the Knicks scored just 24 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, it's not what you do at the beginning of a game but
the end,'' Houston said. ``It would have been better to do it in
the second half. We just stopped attacking. We couldn't even get
our shots up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had a 10-point lead late in the third quarter, but it
was shaved to 4 points, 65-61, with 7:25 left in the game. The
Pistons cut the Knicks' lead to 69-68 after a runner by Joe Dumars
with four minutes left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Pistons took the lead when Hill drove by Larry Johnson for a
layup with 2:23 left in the game. On the Knicks' next possession,
Charlie Ward missed a 3-pointer, and the loose ball came to
Johnson, who was stripped by Hill under the basket with 1:55
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson made a steal only to turn the ball over, the
Pistons came up with Buechler's big shot to help decide the game.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, this had seemed like Houston's night of redemption.
Houston finally found some gumption and stood up to the ghosts that
had left him with a mental block against his old team. Until Friday
night, he had been unsettled by a city of people who still feel he
betrayed them by leaving for New York three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the nine times he had faced the Pistons, Houston had vanished
in their presence and shot just 30 percent from the floor and 26
percent from 3-point range. He had never scored more than 12 points
against Detroit. This time, he was not backing down and scored 17
points on 6-of-10 shooting from the field to give the Knicks a
47-43 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks took that momentum into the locker room and out on
the floor to begin the third quarter. Relying on defensive
pressure, the Knicks held the Pistons to 1 for 8 in the first six
minutes of the third and took a 52-45 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That lead grew when Houston delivered a bullet pass to an open
Marcus Camby underneath the basket for an easy dunk to give the
Knicks a 57-47 edge with 3:50 left in the third quarter. But
Houston suddenly stepped back as the action went on without him. He
did not score in the third and turned the ball over in a sloppy
three minutes to end the quarter with the Pistons within striking
distance, 61-55.
</P>
<P>
   Houston gave the Knicks a 47-43 lead after scoring 17 points in
the first half. For once, he shrugged off the fans' boos and took
on a look of determination that has been missing this year.
</P>
<P>
   It just didn't last.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   PATRICK EWING missed his second straight game with a sore left
Achilles' tendon. During pre-game warm-ups, Ewing took some jump
shots before deciding he could not play. In March. Ewing missed six
games with the same injury. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
