A2368 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FIRES-FIGHTERS17-     04-17 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-FIGHTERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firefighters lament what went unsaved
 &HT;    By Thomas R. Collins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ The blazes burned more than 2,400 acres,
yet hundreds of homes went unscathed. But the sooty, sweaty,
dazed-looking firefighters recuperating in the lunch room at St.
Lucie West Middle School Friday couldn't banish from their minds
one painful fact: 48 homes no longer exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very depressing,'' Division of Forestry firefighter Eric
Potter said after eating lunch with a group of his fellow,
gray-faced workers. ``You think about the families in situations
like this, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   He said he and others ``only had about two or three hours'' of
sleep Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Worn down by the grind of the heat and toil of blaze-battling
that, for some, stretched on for as long as 23 hours, firefighters
sat together and took little solace in the houses that still stood
or the reprieve they got in the recovery room. Some just sat alone
silently.
</P>
<P>
   St. Lucie County firefighter J. P. Smith said he was ``just
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trained firemen and when you're out there seeing all the
houses go up and there's nothing you can do, you really feel bad
about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at the middle school were doing as much as they could do
make matters better for the firefighters, who showed up to the
cafeteria in waves after emerging from the charred woods and
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Smith, who wore a white T-shirt dark with ash and soot,
said he'd been taking food and drinks to firefighters for nearly a
day after hearing about the blazes on the radio as he drove home
from work Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I'm not going home, I'm going out to help,' '' Woods
said.
</P>
<P>
   Publix, Winn-Dixie, Food Lion, and a variety of other businesses
and individuals donated water, soda, pastries, and other
refreshments for the firefighters, said Kathy McGinn, the food and
nutrition services director for the St. Lucie County schools.
</P>
<P>
   One boy brought in a big bag of beef jerky, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went like hotcakes, too,'' McGinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the cafeteria, Charlotte Bowes had a board set up and
gave free massages to any firefighter who asked. Bowes, who runs a
business called Massage in Minutes, said she does that kind of
thing all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I volunteer,'' she said. ``Whenever I hear it on the (police)
scanner or on TV, I go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
