A2373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-ORANGE-MURDER-NYT &LR;      04-17 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ORANGE-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR FREES MAN HELD IN DEATH OF ORANGE POLICEWOMAN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six days after they charged a man with murdering an Orange,
N.J., policewoman, the authorities let him go Friday night, saying
that he could not have been at the scene of the shooting when it
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Essex County Prosecutor Patricia Hurt, who released the man,
Terrance Everett, refused to say if there was another suspect in
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt also refused to say where she thought Everett had been
around 8:30 p.m. on April 8, when Officer Joyce Anne Carnegie was
shot. Everett had pleaded not guilty on Thursday to charges of
murder, robbery and criminal possession of a weapon
</P>
<P>
   ``I have concluded that Everett is not the person who committed
this crime,'' Ms. Hurt said. ``It is my responsibility to see that
justice prevails, and it would be unjust to detain Everett now when
it would have been impossible for him to have been at the scene.''
She also acknowledged that he had passed a lie detector test.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's lawyers have said that he was eating with his family
at a fast-food restaurant 10 blocks from the shooting when Carnegie
was killed. After his release Friday night, Everett, 24, of
neighboring East Orange, was driven away from the Essex County
Courts building in his lawyer's black sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt's terse announcement capped a week of baffling and
unsettling developments in the investigation into the death of
Carnegie, who was shot in the head and abdomen when she stopped her
car to question a robbery suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested Everett at the home he shares with his
mother on Saturday, two days after the shooting, and said that he
was the killer. But on Sunday, three more people were arrested as
part of the investigation, and one of them died in the custody of
the Orange police; his family said he was beaten.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Everett, who was being held in lieu of $1 million
bail, appeared in court with bruises on his face that his lawyers
said had been inflicted after his arrest. On Tuesday, television
newscasts reported that Everett had passed a lie detector test.
</P>
<P>
   As some law enforcement officials quietly opined that the
authorities had the wrong man and Ms. Hurt retreated behind a wall
of no-comments, the chief assistant prosecutor, Patrick Toscano,
resigned abruptly on Wednesday. Toscano had professional
differences with Ms. Hurt over the handling of this and other
cases, a county official who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   After his release last night, Everett, who had appeared fearful
and confused at his court appearance on Monday, told News 12 New
Jersey, a cable news station, that he did not know why he had been
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt said last night that witnesses to the three robberies
Carnegie was investigating and ``someone who allegedly witnessed
the shooting'' all identified Everett, whose mug shot was on file
because he has a police record, as the man they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, why me, of all the baldheaded people with
goatees? That was just hard for me to understand,'' Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Everett's lawyers, Raymond Hamlin, said Friday night that
his client was ``relieved'' and that he planned to meet with him
Saturday to figure out his next move. When asked if he planned to
sue the authorities for false arrest, Hamlin replied, ``That
prospect certainly exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin and Ronald Hunt, Everett's other lawyer, had maintained
from the start that their client had an alibi. The lawyers filed
papers to get both the results of the lie-detector test and
surveillance videos and receipts from a Wendy's restaurant where
Everett said he had eaten at the time of the shooting. The
Star-Ledger of Newark quoted the restaurant's manager Friday as
saying that Everett had been there while the crime was occurring.
The manager also said that he had turned over the receipts and the
security videotape to the police.
</P>
<P>
   Where the investigation into Officer Carnegie's murder goes now
is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   According to various law enforcement officials, Officer
Carnegie, 38, a four-year veteran of the force, she stopped a blue
1986 Honda Accord near an overpass to Interstate 280, about 8:30
p.m. on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   The driver was wearing a black leather jacket that fit the
description of one worn by a suspect in two armed street muggings,
which had occurred a few blocks away minutes before.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Everett and the man who died in custody, Earl
Faison, the authorities arrested a man named James Coker on drug
charges on Sunday in what they said was part of the investigation
into the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Essex County Sheriff, Armando Fontoura on Friday night refused
to link Coker with the killing and said he had simply been arrested
on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Fontoura maintained that while Everett turned out to have been
unconnected to the murder, the authorities had acted in good faith.
 &UR;  &LR; ``That arrest was a lawful, proper arrest,'' he said. ``It's not
the first time we've arrested the wrong person, and I've been in
law enforcement for 35 years. It's happened before, it'll happen
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
