<SLUG> BC-PLANES-SHORTAGE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHIDBEY NAVAL AIR STATION EXPERIENCING SHORTAGE OF EA-6B PROWLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Last week a television crew at Whidbey Island Naval
Air Station went out to the aircraft ramp for video of planes
taking off and landing, normally an easy shot, given the traffic at
the base.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, there weren't any planes. Traffic was light on
Whidbey's increasingly empty flight line, a scene that has become
increasingly common as squadron after squadron deploys for combat
in the Balkans or the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Spreading U.S. forces so thin is a point of concern for national
security experts who warn that the downsized military can no longer
sustain wars on several fronts. The sudden scarcity of Navy EA-6B
Prowlers at Whidbey Island is a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Navy stations all but one of its 15 Prowler
electronic-warfare squadrons at Whidbey, located about 50 miles
north of Seattle. Seven of the squadrons are gone, far more than
normal.
</P>
<P>
   Five of them are in combat, and NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark
has asked for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does, to some significant extent, compromise our ability
to fight two major theater wars, like Desert Storm,'' says Andrew
Krepinevich, executive director of the Center for Strategy and
Budgeting, a Washington, D.C.-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   America is running out of the planes, which cost $60 million
apiece. And if something else breaks out on the globe _ say in Iraq
or Korea _ the Prowlers will be among the first to get the call.
The commander of all Navy electronic-warfare units declined a
request for comment on the increasing demand for his planes. But if
Clark gets his way and more Prowlers are sent to the Balkans, there
may not be enough to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at this from a national security standpoint, the
U.S. is supposed to be able to fight two wars and a major
contingency (regional conflict) at once,'' says Richard Bloom, a
national security expert at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in
Daytona Beach, Fla. ``Look at us now _ we've got one contingency
going and we're maxed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Prowlers are essential to the nation's air war plans. The planes
with their four crewmen protect other, faster aircraft by jamming
enemy radar with energy pulses and missiles that home in on active
radar sites.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their high cost, there are relatively few Prowlers.
The Navy has about 100, the Marines about 24, usually organized in
squadrons of three to six planes.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps has four squadrons, two now deployed in support
of the Kosovo airstrikes and a third squadron split between Turkey
_ where it is supporting the northern no-fly zone over Iraq _ and
Italy, where it flies in support of the Yugoslavian strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth Marine Prowler squadron just returned from a
six-month tour in Japan. The Marine Corps has about seven Prowlers
available for what is known as standoff jamming, which involves
hanging back from the battlefield and covering a large area with
electronic impulses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very embarrassing,'' said Glen Buchan, a senior
defense analyst with the Rand Corp., a Santa Monica, Calif., think
tank that often consults with the military. ``It's not like it
slipped through the cracks. People knowledgeable about this have
been screaming for years that this was going to happen. But there's
been a vacuum. While people were messing around, the world passed
us by.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force once had its own standoff jamming planes, the
EF-111 Raven, but retired them in the early 1990s. The brunt of
standoff jamming then fell on the Prowlers.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, the Air Force deployed 24 of its jamming
aircraft, the F-16CJ, to Italy from Shaw Air Force Base in South
Carolina to help in the Kosovo airstrikes. However the Air Force
plane is a converted fighter, not built from the ground-up as a
jamming aircraft, and doesn't offer the protection a Prowler does.
</P>
<P>
   To provide that better protection, the military has stripped
assets from the Persian Gulf to cover the air war in Yugoslavia.
But that has had its own effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be less aggressive there in getting them to turn on
their radars so we can go and kill them,'' Buchan says of the Iraq
situation. ``It's like we've had to say `Unless you do something
really bad, we're going to be less aggressive about trying to kill
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clark continues to request more long-range Tomahawk
cruise missiles, AWACS planes and Prowlers. To satisfy Clark's
request, the Pentagon may have to take equipment and crews from
other areas, such as the Persian Gulf or the Western Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we can't fight two major wars,'' Buchan says. ``This
is just emblematic of the major problems we have with other assets
as well. We're just spread too thin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
