<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-DRAFT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FACE DIFFICULT DECISION ON FIRST-ROUND PICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A somber mood hung over the Cowboys' Valley
Ranch training complex on the eve of the 1999 NFL draft in the wake
of the news that star defensive tackle Leon Lett violated the NFL's
substance-abuse policy and faces an indefinite ban from the league.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, who is not commenting on
the Lett issue because of league confidentiality rules, huddled
behind closed doors for most of the day with other team officials
outlining plans for today's draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also worked on a contract with 6-foot-3, 250-pound
free-agent linebacker Quentin Coryatt. The two sides were close to
a deal last night and could have it done before the draft begins,
Coryatt's agent, Steve Zucker, said.
</P>
<P>
   However, topping the team's list of concerns was the decision
regarding the 22nd pick _ one of eight selections the Cowboys have
in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are focusing on Louisiana Tech receiver Troy Edwards
(5-9, 190 pounds) and Louisiana State defensive tackle Anthony
McFarland (6-foot, 299), and will have a team representative with
both players during today's draft. If neither is available, then
Saginaw Valley State defensive end Lamar King (6-3, 299) is a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland appears to be at the top of the Cowboys' wish list.
According to a league source, the Cowboys have been making a hard
push to find a way to get McFarland, who is considered the best
defensive tackle in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   There is a chance that McFarland might be there when the Cowboys
pick at No. 22. A draft-day trade, however, also is a possibility.
Jones, who has made a deal in the first round in four of the past
five drafts, has made it clear to teams around the league that the
Cowboys are willing to listen to trade offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make a deliberate effort to let other teams know that
want to talk and to be sure to pick up the phone if they've got a
trade in mind, and we will do the same,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are also high on the speedy Edwards, who led NCAA
Division I in receptions last season and is also considered to be
the best runner with the ball among all draft prospects, including
Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Drafting Edwards might indicate that Cowboys officials quietly
believe that Lett's situation might not be as bad as it seems.
</P>
<P>
   Lett is enrolled in stage three of the NFL's substance-abuse
program and has been suspended twice previously _ the last being
for the final three games of the 1996 season and the first 13 games
of 1997. As a part of the program, Lett is tested up to 10 times
per month.
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Greg Aiello, citing league rules, declined to
comment on Lett's recovery program. However, he said that when a
player flunks a drug test while enrolled in stage three of the
program that he is subject to a indefinite suspension of at least a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys consultant Calvin Hill, who oversees the team's
behavioral department, disputed Aiello's statement. He said the
league's drug program doesn't call for a definitive ban when a
player slips up a second time while enrolled in stage three.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the first time a player is put in stage three, a
yearlong suspension is mandatory. But he said the second time, the
suspension is indefinite.
</P>
<P>
   Precedent was set in 1997 when former Cowboys cornerback Clayton
Holmes, who signed with the Miami Dolphins after a yearlong
suspension, flunked a second test while enrolled in stage three.
Holmes' suspension was six games.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the ban is determined by NFL commissioner Paul
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   Lett was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York Times'' reported in Friday's editions that Lett
is appealing his failed test and that it is currently under review
by Tagliabue. Lett's agent, Jim Steiner, said: ``There is no appeal
going on.'
</P>
<P>
   If Lett is suspended, his salary _ $2 million for the 1999
season _ will not count against the salary cap during his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Lett was the Cowboys' best defensive lineman last season when he
recorded 51 tackles, four sacks, 20 quarterback pressures and a
team-high seven tackles for losses. His presence was considered a
big reason the Cowboys' run defense improved from 24th in the
league when he missed 13 games in 1997 to 12th in 1998.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
