<SLUG> BC-VALLI-TRIAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY DAVID GREENBERG 
</HEADLINE>
 
WIFE OF '60s SINGER FACES FINE, JAIL 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. _ The wife of '60s teen idol Frankie Valli was
found guilty Friday of slapping the owner of a tony rural
restaurant during a brawl that erupted after crooner Frankie Avalon
complained about high menu prices.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Valli, a 39-year-old mother of three, faces a possible
$1,000 fine and as much as six months in jail for her conviction on
misdemeanor battery. Randy and Frankie Valli, along with Avalon and
his wife, Kay, had testified that restaurateur Sandra ``Alex''
Sofsky was the aggressor in the Oct. 7 fracas, but jurors
apparently rejected their story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury was able to hear all the evidence and they came to
the right decision,'' Deputy District Attorney John Lonergan said
after the hearing. ``In a lot of trials, they try to demonize the
victim. But we had numerous witnesses _ eight witnesses _ to offer
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant and numerous other witnesses perjured themselves
on the stand. They have nobody to blame but themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Valli's lawyer, Louis ``Chuck'' Samonsky, called the verdict
``the most outrageous I have ever seen'' in 26 years as a lawyer,
including nearly nine as a prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught (Sofsky) in unambiguous lie after lie,'' he said. ``I
don't think this evidence supports the verdict in any way, shape or
form.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors slipped out of the Ventura County courthouse without
commenting on their deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Herbert Curtis rejected Samonsky's request
to throw out the verdict. He set sentencing for May 28, when he
also will hear Samonsky's motion for a retrial.
</P>
<P>
   Valli, of Calabasas, was not present for the verdict and learned
of the verdict from Samonsky's call.
</P>
<P>
   ``She started to cry,'' Samonsky said. ``She was not able to
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Lonergan would not say whether he would seek a jail sentence for
Valli.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to look at what happened in the trial,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses testified that problems started when Frankie Avalon
complained about prices at the Secret Garden, where entrees average
about $30 and are served on Limoges china.
</P>
<P>
   Sofsky said that Randy Valli became loud and abusive and slapped
her across the face before storming out with the rest of her party.
</P>
<P>
   But Valli repeatedly denied slapping Sofsky and said she merely
pushed the restaurateur after Sofsky pulled her chair away from the
table in an attempt to make the foursome leave.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant is married to Frankie Valli, known for hit songs
such as ``Big Girls Don't Cry'' and ``Walk Like a Man.'' Avalon
gained fame starring in the 1965 movie ``Beach Blanket Bingo'' and
for his hit single ``Venus.''
</P>
<P>
   Samonsky said he doubted that Randy Valli would have been
prosecuted had she not been married to a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is all about the celebrity status of the people
involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lonergan said his office investigates all battery complaints
and prosecutes those it can prove beyond a reasonable doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The county does battery cases all the time,'' he said. ``It
had nothing to do with celebrity. We don't look at somebody's name,
whether it's Valli or Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
