</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOS TOP METS, 6-4 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Leiter is still looking for his first victory. He
was undermined Friday night by a fluke hop on a little grounder
that left Robin Ventura staring at the third-base line with a dazed
expression on his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain it,'' Ventura said of rookie Michael Barrett's
single. A little dazed is how Leiter had to be feeling, too. Even
though he allowed just four hits against the Montreal Expos through
seven innings at Shea Stadium, they all came in the fourth and led
to four runs.
</P>
<P>
   After Leiter allowed two more runs in the eighth on Barrett's
two-out, two-run single, Montreal was up by five runs on its way to
a 6-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be a little more distraught and a little more concerned if
I felt I had no clue,'' said a mystified Leiter (0-2). ``But my
stuff is as good as it's ever been in my career. I'm just not
making that big pitch to get out of an inning. But I feel too good
to get depressed about it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was the Mets' second in a row after five straight
victories and left them at 7-4. The loss also marked the first time
that Ventura went hitless as a Met after opening the season with
hits in the first 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, meanwhile, was simply outpitched by Dustin Hermanson
(2-0). Or was it that simple, after all? Through seven innings,
both pitchers had allowed just four hits, but the Mets trailed by
4-1.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Leiter _ whose earned run average is 5.95 _ allowed six
runs on six hits in seven and two-thirds innings. Perhaps Leiter,
who walked three and struck out eight, would have been better off
if the tarps had never come off the soggy field. And so might have
Rickey Henderson, who singled as a pinch-hitter in the eighth
before asking to be removed with a tight right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It knotted up,'' said Henderson, who has had well-publicized
troubles with his hamstring before. ``I don't think it's bad at
all. It might just be strained.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked if he would be able to start in left field this
afternoon, Henderson just shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' the 40-year-old outfielder said. ``I've got to
wake up in the morning and see how it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   When Leiter looked out his window Friday morning he could not
have been too pleased. ``Guess who's pitching,'' John Franco said
facetiously before the game. ``The Rain Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter just grimaced. Early last season, every time it was
Leiter's turn to pitch, it also seemed to be raining.
</P>
<P>
   But Leiter also enjoyed his finest season in the majors last
year, winning 17 games against only six losses with a 2.47 earned
run average, tied for third-lowest in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   And considering that Leiter, who signed a four-year, $32 million
deal with the Mets in the off season, was winless in his first two
starts this season after a rough spring (0-4, 5.84 ERA), perhaps a
little rain was a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   That was the way things looked as Leiter breezed through the
Expos' lineup through three and a third hitless innings after rain
delayed the start by 1 hour 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But then Leiter's struggles inexplicably began with the Mets
ahead, 1-0. With one out in the fourth, Rondell White drilled
Leiter's first pitch just inside the foul pole in left. The home
run was not only White's second of the season, it was also his
second off Leiter this season. And it tied the game at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Guerrero followed by drawing a five-pitch walk. Then,
Barrett pushed a little grounder up the third-base line. The ball
took a strange hop off the chalk line and to the right of the base.
Ventura, who had sidled over to where the ball would have been
traveled over the bag, could only look at the spot where it had
taken the bad bounce in disbelief. Guerrero raced to third, Barrett
had a gift single, and there was still only one out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it hit,'' Ventura later said. ``If there was
a hole, I could understand. But there was nothing there. It just
took a chop 10 feet the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Up stepped Chris Widger, who lined a single to center to score
Guerrero. Wilton Guerrero, Vladimir's brother, followed with a
two-run triple the other way to right field. And now it was 4-1,
Montreal. And not even Todd Pratt's two-run homer in the bottom of
the ninth could rescue the Mets before Ugueth Urbina came on to
record the save.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mets finally recalled catcher VANCE WILSON from Class AAA
Norfolk and optioned outfielder TERRENCE LONG to the Tides.
</P>
<P>
   _ MIKE PIAZZA (knee) is expected to come off the disabled list a
week from Sunday when the Mets are in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOE McILVAINE, the former Mets general manager, was arrested
this week in Hutchinson Island, Fla., where he maintains a
residence, and charged with public lewdness for allegedly
sunbathing nude on a public beach. McIlvaine is currently a scout
for the Minnesota Twins. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
