A2394 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-HATCHER-TEX     04-17 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HATCHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATCHER-LESS STARS TO TEST METTLE AGAINST COYOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Stars' playoff depth will be tested today.
</P>
<P>
   And what a test it will be.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into likely one of the most physical games of the season
_ a 3 p.m. battle against the Phoenix Coyotes at America West Arena
_ the Stars will rely heavily on youngsters such as Brad Lukowich,
Petr Buzek, Blake Sloan and Jon Sim, and role players Brent
Severyn, Brian Skrudland, Tony Hrkac and Doug Lidster.
</P>
<P>
   The massive changes are a result of injuries, rest for some
players and the suspension of Stars captain Derian Hatcher, who is
being held out of today's game pending an announcement of a
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher and Stars general manager Bob Gainey met with NHL
director of operations Colin Campbell yesterday in New York. No
decision had been made on Hatcher's fate, but Campbell is expected
to make one today.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher and Gainey could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension also has a hand in making the challenge so
daunting. Hatcher was disciplined for a hit on Wednesday that broke
the jaw of the Coyotes' Jeremy Roenick, ending his season. The
Coyotes might seek some vengeance today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say what will happen,'' Hatcher said before
leaving for New York. ``It could be a rough game or both sides
could say we've had enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes winger Rick Tocchet was coy about the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we need is for Keith Tkachuk to get in three
fights and break his thumb,'' Tocchet said. ``What we want is for
when Dallas gets on their plane, that they're sore. You have to
play a miserable game within the rules, and fighting is within the
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are dressing a tough lineup. While Hatcher and Richard
Matvichuk (groin injury) are out, Severyn, Craig Ludwig and Brian
Skrudland don't mind getting physical. But they said they aren't
predicting a war, only reacting to what happens on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ever predict what's going to happen in any game,''
said Severyn, the team's designated enforcer. ``In my role, you
have to be ready every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig added: ``We're not a team that gets a lot of penalty
minutes, we're a team that frustrates other teams and tries to draw
them into penalties. At the same time, we're not going to back
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock was matter-of-fact about the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a game ... and we're going to show up and play,'' he
said. ``Stuff like this is generally taken care of by the players
on the ice, not by the coaches or the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix fans are already whipped into a frenzy about the game
and the chance for revenge against Hatcher, the way Stars fans were
hoping for revenge against Roenick, who had knocked Mike Modano out
of a game on March 23 with a blindsided hit.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick underwent 5 1/2 hours of surgery on Thursday and will
have his jaw wired shut for four to six weeks. His wife told the
``Arizona Republic'' she would push for the 29-year-old center to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock is taking care of his own players as best he can,
sitting out the top scoring line of Modano (34 goals), Brett Hull
(32) and Jere Lehtinen (20) as part of his plan started Sunday to
rest players.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we've had planned for a while,'' Hitchcock
said. ``We have back-to-back games getting ready for the playoffs
and we don't need all of our players playing both games.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is a one-game tryout for several players trying to
earn ice time in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   While defensemen Matvichuk (groin) and Sergei Zubov (bruised
wrist) are expected to be ready to play when the playoffs begin on
Wednesday or Thursday against the Edmonton Oilers, the Stars still
need defensive depth. Lukowich, 22, has proved himself a worthy
replacement in 12 games with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't look out of place at all,'' Hitchcock said. ``He's
really come in and looked good.''
</P>
<P>
   Buzek could play a few games until Matvichuk and Zubov are
healthy, but Lidster also has proven a consistent defenseman and
hasn't been prone to mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Up front, the top three lines are pretty much set, which means
veterans Skrudland, Hrkac, Severyn and Dave Reid will compete with
youngsters Sim and Sloan for playing time in the playoffs. In the
past, Hitchcock has used those playing best at playoff time and
will give no favors to veterans. Last season, Hitchcock played Juha
Lind and Jamie Wright instead of Reid in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who doesn't care how long you've played or how much
you make, he's concerned about who can help him win a game,''
Skrudland said of Hitchcock. ``Each one of us has to prove to him
what we can do.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
