<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEEN-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGER IS SHOT TO DEATH OVER JACKET, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lamar Harris died Wednesday night with five dollars
in his pocket, still wearing the stock-car racing jacket that led
to his slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar, who was 16, had just walked a friend home to a building
on East 173rd Street in the Bronx when he was fatally shot in the
back by a robber who wanted the red and blue jacket, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar's mother, who had just returned from burying her grandson
at the time of the shooting, arrived at the scene moments after her
son's heart had stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him as I ran to the corner _ saw him on the ground and
the blood,'' his mother, Thelma Jackson, said Friday from her
apartment on Morris Avenue, just blocks from where her son was
killed. ``I just kept asking why.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors who saw the shooting, she said, told her that the
assailant wanted Lamar's jacket. ``I should have never bought it
for him,'' she added. ``But I didn't know someone could be so cruel
as to shoot someone down for a jacket. If they had just asked, he
probably would have given it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing was one of two incidents just 12 hours apart in
which people lost their lives at the hands of robbers. In
Manhattan, homicide detectives were busy in Morningside Heights on
Friday investigating the slaying of Jacqueline Frezza, 34, who was
shot to death Thursday morning on Broadway by a young man trying to
steal a bag of clothes that she was carrying to the cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   Both deaths shocked those living in the neighborhoods where they
occurred, places described by residents as pockets of civility and
family life, largely spared the violence that sometimes swarmed
nearby. Friday, friends and neighbors tried to make sense of the
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Outside 221 E. 173rd St., Lamar's body has been replaced by a
makeshift shrine of candles and flowers, his name scribbled across
an old piece of cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   On the stretch of Broadway near La Salle Street where Ms. Frezza
was shot, two roses, one red and one yellow, were attached by crime
scene tape to the fence surrounding the General Grant Houses, one
of four city housing projects where surveillance cameras have been
installed to deter crime.
</P>
<P>
   One of the cameras captured the image of a suspect as he rode
his bicycle away from the scene of Ms. Frezza's killing. On light
posts Friday, officers put up wanted posters displaying two frames
from the videotape, although police officials said Friday that they
had few strong leads in either slaying.
</P>
<P>
   At Morningside Gardens, a co-op on Broadway and 123rd Street
where Ms. Frezza, a freelance marketing executive, and her sister
both lived, relatives declined to speak to reporters Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the door remained open at Lamar's fifth-floor apartment in
the Mount Eden section of the Bronx, where friends arrived by the
dozens Friday to pay their respects and relatives recalled a
promising child's life.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar and his twin brother, Lamont, were well known in their
neighborhood for dressing alike and displaying the same sense of
kindness as they walked the streets. Both were active in Friendship
Community Church in the Bronx, and were often seen ferrying
groceries to elderly neighbors who could not get outside. Relatives
said the teen-agers once spent weeks helping a woman in their
building after she had eye surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Like country doctors, they would make house calls, running
errands and helping her with her medications and eye drops.
</P>
<P>
   From about the age of 4, when he saw a fire truck go screaming
by, Lamar had dreamed of being a firefighter and wanted to save
those around him, his mother said, holding back tears and speaking
of regret that she had ever agreed to buy her sons the $200 race
car jackets they so desired.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont was emblazoned across the back of Lamar's cotton jacket,
while Lamont's advertised Good-wrench. Many neighborhood youths
were envious of the stylish jackets, relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   His mother added that there had been similar trouble over
Lamar's clothing a few years before; he had been robbed at gunpoint
of his jacket and sneakers outside school. ``He came home
barefoot,'' she said. ``But he didn't fight them.''
</P>
<P>
   On the night of his killing, Lamar went to visit his friend
while his mother and other relatives attended the funeral of her
4-year-old grandson, Charles Hunter Beck, who recently died of an
aneurysm. The burial was in an Elizabeth, N.J., cemetery that
already held one of Lamar's older brothers, John, 27, who died of
cancer three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rough time all around,'' said Ms. Jackson,
recalling the telephone call that came to her home just after 11
p.m. Wednesday and the sound of the scared boy on the other end,
telling her that Lamar had been shot.
</P>
<P>
   When she arrived, neighbors told her that her son had been shot
in the back after an argument over his jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jackson said Lamar's friend told her he had heard a sudden
noise just after Lamar left. When the friend went downstairs, he
saw some youths in a car and Lamar on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``There he was,'' Ms. Jackson said. ``I just couldn't take it,
because I knew right away that he was dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
