r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SUNS-TE     04-17 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-SUNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX'S KIDD, ROOKIE HAUNT MAVS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Jason Kidd continues to torment the Mavericks. Last
night his vendetta against his former team was joined by another
former Mavericks player.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Pat Garrity, who was drafted by the Mavericks on the
first round last summer and traded to Phoenix on draft day, haunted
Dallas with a 20-point effort as the Suns scorched the Mavericks,
92-85, before 18,623 at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing their modest two-game winning streak snapped, the
Mavericks (13-26) will play host to Portland at 7 tonight at
Reunion Arena. This will be the third game in three days for
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   With Kidd and Garrity executing, the Suns rolled to a 75-66 lead
after the third period. Kidd scored 24 points and dished out 12
assists, and Garrity scored nine of his points in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The performance by Kidd and Garrity overshadowed a phenomenal
display by Mavericks rookie Dirk Nowitzki. The 7-footer scored a
career-high 29 points on 10-of-16 shooting, and also picked off
eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Without Nowitzki, who grabbed a career-high 13 rebounds against
San Antonio on Tuesday, the Mavericks would have been hopelessly
behind by halftime. That's because Michael Finley, who had averaged
29.5 points the previous two games, was held to just six points on
3-of-11 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Center Shawn Bradley did not play because Mavericks
coach/general manager Don Nelson did not like the matchup
situation, even though the 7-foot-6 six-year veteran could have
given the Suns all sorts of matchup problems with his overwhelming
height advantage. It's the first game Bradley has missed this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix played without center Luc Longley, who has a
hyperextended left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, 9-1 against the Mavericks, flipped in an alley oop pass
from Rex Chapman, and scored again inside for an 81-66 Suns cushion
early in the fourth period.
</P>
<P>
   Kidd's driving yo-yo layup over Nash lifted the Suns ahead,
43-36, late in the second period. But the Mavericks scrambled back
and eventually knotted the score at 43-all after baskets by Hubert
Davis and Robert Pack (17 points, seven assists), sandwiched around
a three-point field goal by Nowitzki.
</P>
<P>
   But with Kidd assisting on a pair of baskets, the Suns nudged
ahead, 50-45, at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki had gotten the Mavericks off to a good start. The
7-footer banged in a 3-point field goal, then posted up Clifford
Robinson for his sixth and seventh points and a 12-9 Mavericks
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Trent's two free throws made it 14-9 Mavericks. Pack's
driving layup and subsequent free throw gave Dallas a 25-24 lead
after the first period.
</P>
<P>
   But the first quarter belonged to Nowitzki and Trent. Each
player scored nine points in the period. Trent grabbed five
rebounds and Nowitzki had three rebounds and drew an offensive foul
from Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Mavericks couldn't keep up the pace.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
