<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL FOR WASHED-UP QB WILL PROVE STEAL OF DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Strictly from a playing standpoint, the
Seahawks have already butchered Saturday's college draft by
squandering a second-round pick on an overweight, washed-up
quarterback who hasn't managed a game spiral in almost 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, given the Seahawks' draft history with quarterbacks,
he's typical.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the latest Seahawk deal the NFL's worst use of draft
picks on an old quarterback. Fans of the Green Bay Packers recall a
draft under then-coach Dan Devine in which five high picks were
sent away for imminently decrepit veteran QB John Hadl. The
transaction is known bitterly among the ice-fishing houses of
Wisconsin as the Lawrence Welk trade: ``A one, a two, a
one-two-three.''
</P>
<P>
   So giving up a No. 2 for Mike Holmgren won't be cause for
editors of sports-history books to call for massive rewrites.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Holmgren looks at it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm such a steal.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the Seahawks coach/general manager's amused view this
week of the deal that brought him to Seattle. And because he is the
coach and general manager as well as the second-round draft choice,
there is almost no one in local football authority to challenge the
evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   A steal? He might have a point. In the most memorable recent
episode of a team surrendering draft picks in order to pirate a
coach under contract, the New York Jets, to get Bill Parcells, had
to give to New England third- and fourth-round picks in 1997, a
second-rounder last year and a first-rounder in Saturday's draft.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe Holmgren is a steal. Either that, or he's about a
quarter of the coach that Parcells figures to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I talked to Ron (Wolf, Packer GM) about getting that
pick back,'' said Holmgren. No deal, however: The Packers figure to
have sent away way too much to Seattle already.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual transaction came about because of the Seahawks'
indirect dalliance with Holmgren two years ago at the Super Bowl,
when his Packers beat Parcells' Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   While the fractious relationship between Parcells and Patriots
owner Bob Kraft became a media sideshow, Seahawks president Bob
Whitsitt was sniffing hard around Holmgren to see whether he might
fill the long-vacant GM job in Seattle. But since he was under
contract to Green Bay, formal contact would have been tampering, an
act in the NFL of semi-high treason.
</P>
<P>
   Since Holmgren wanted to be coach as well as GM, nothing
transpired _ except for formalizing Holmgren's desire to be
double-titled, something that would never happen in Green Bay as
long as the well-regarded Wolf stayed in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers agreed to an addendum to his contract that said he
would have a 21-day window after the 1998 season to pursue a
coach/GM job.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they'd never say no to me pursuing such a job,'' he
said. ``But they needed compensation. If I did interview and take
another job, we had to sign the (second-round) pick over.''
</P>
<P>
   The compensation is believed to be the first of its kind for a
big-time coaching vacancy in Seattle, which normally has been a
place for retreads, the unemployed and the disengaged.
</P>
<P>
   The most remarkable thing about the compensation is that the
Seahawks can afford it, and it has nothing to do with owner Paul
Allen's billions.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in many seasons, the Seahawks do not enter
the draft screamingly desperate for something. This week's
free-agent signing of veteran Sean Dawkins eliminated the most
glaring need: a quality pass-catcher also big enough to block in
Holmgren's West Coast offense.
</P>
<P>
   No team that has finished 8-8 for about half a decade can say
with a straight face that it needs nothing from a draft, but the
fact is that most needs are relatively patchable from current
resources. In other words, the Seahawks don't need to trade a bunch
of future picks to move up to select a studhoss, such as they did
for Curt Warner, Cortez Kennedy, Shawn Springs and Walter Jones.
</P>
<P>
   With little damage, they can even trade down in the draft in
exchange for more picks, including the second-rounder gone to Green
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they can expend a draft choice on an assistant paperwork
shuffler. During a media chat Wednesday, Holmgren hinted that the
dual roles sometimes leave his eyebrows stuck in the up position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not being as efficient with my time as I will be,'' he
admitted. ``I'll get there, but it's a load.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's work is compounded by his newness with holdover
Seahawks personnel, as well as the installation of changes from his
predecessor, Dennis Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   Under Erickson, Holmgren said, the week prior to the draft was a
light one because much of the work had been done. Under Holmgren,
it's known as a ``power week'' when most of the decision-making for
Saturday will be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing it differently than last year,'' he said. ``I've
told all the people who were here last year, `Don't fight me, meet
me halfway.'
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's cramming three months into one week, because I've
been doing other stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   At least he's saving some time on the second-round pick. He's
scouted the pick since childhood, likes the talent and figures no
other team has a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
