<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ NATO pilots claimed one of their
most successful nights in the air campaign against Yugoslavia,
destroying several tanks and artillery sites and damaging a large
air base Thursday night. The warplanes also gathered new
photographic evidence to back up reports of mass killings of Kosovo
refugees. By Philip Shenon. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ The confusion about whether NATO
accidentally bombed civilian refugees in Kosovo reflects both the
novelty of the first real air war the alliance has ever fought and
the determination of its U.S. military commander to control
everything NATO says about airstrikes even while he runs the war.
By Craig R. Whitney. WITH MAP.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Brazda) _ The flow of ethnic Albanians fleeing
Kosovo into Macedonia surged again with more than 6,000 refugees
pouring out of the Serbian province, including families that had
been forced by Serbian forces to turn back more than a week ago and
had gone into hiding. By David Rohde. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes) _ There is growing concern here in the
Kukes area, where there are 100,000 refugees, that the city will be
hit by a Serbian attack. On Thursday, Serbs shelled a nearby
encampment of the Kosovo rebel group, the KLA. By Anthony DePalma.
WITH PHOTO and MAP.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SCENE (Urosevac) _ Evidence of `ethnic cleansing' is
written upon the doorposts of their houses and upon their gates. On
the streets of this quiet, modest city in southern Kosovo, many
doors and storefronts bear a spraypainted Christian cross with a
Cyrillic `C' in each quadrant _ a widely understood sign that the
owners and occupants are Serbs. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VOICES (White Plains, N.Y.) _ For all the wrenching
scenes of Kosovo refugees and burning buildings, of starched
military men talking damage assessment, of monochromatic video
clips of exploding targets, the bombing campaign against Yugoslavia
was beginning to fade to a remote concern for many people. Now, the
news that up to 33,000 reservists may be called up to reinforce
attacks on the Serbs, a portent of widening U.S. involvement, has
once again brought the war into sharp focus. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-COHEN (Washington) _ Defense Secretary William Cohen
accused Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic of an `Orwellian
twisting of language and logic' to describe the bombing of a Kosovo
refugee convoy Wednesday, while `not allowing his people to see the
kind of horrific damage that he is causing to hundreds of thousands
of people.' By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N.-REFUGEES (Geneva) _ The U.N. refugee agency accused
Yugoslavia of trying to expel the entire ethnic Albanian population
from Kosovo, where Albanians had made up 90 percent of the
population. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POW (Washington) _ Albanian rebels in Kosovo have
captured a Yugoslav army officer and turned him over to Albania,
which Friday turned him over to the U.S. Army in Albania's capital.
By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
