<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNED-RUSSIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMILE RETURNS TO SCARRED FACE OF BURNED BOY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With red scars and burns still marking his pale
face, 10-year-old Denis Nefedova stood close to his mother Friday _
and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   The simple smile was reason enough to celebrate for this Russian
boy: He hasn't been able to smile for more than a year, since
flames engulfed him during a horrible household accident, scarring
his face and hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling better and better everyday,'' the little boy said,
speaking softly through an interpreter and peeking out from beneath
the brim of his blue Anaheim Angels cap.
</P>
<P>
   After two surgeries on his face at the Grossman Burn Center at
Sherman Oaks Hospital, Denis said on Friday that he's ready for
some fun and knows exactly where he wants to go: ``Universal
Studios,'' he said, showing off two new English words he's
mastered.
</P>
<P>
   Denis also plans to join other patients from the Sherman Oaks
center on a white-water rafting excursion in May.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors still must operate on the left side of his face,
which Denis said doesn't feel like his own flesh. ``My right cheek
is now softer, like my own,'' he said, smiling again.
</P>
<P>
   Denis was alone at his family home on Sakhalin Island, just
north of Japan, last year when a candle he lighted toppled and
ignited fumes from fuel being stored in the apartment. After two
months of surgeries near his home, Denis underwent advanced
treatment in Moscow, which he described Friday as painful.
</P>
<P>
   Russian doctors were unable to perform the reconstructive
surgeries with much success.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he had surgeries in Russia, it was more painful after the
surgery,'' his interpreter Mila Chennetsky explained. ``But after
the surgeries here, he says he feels better. He has some hope
now.''
</P>
<P>
   In what is expected to be a yearlong series of procedures at the
Grossman Burn Center, surgeons will focus on Denis' cheek, nose and
eyes next month.
</P>
<P>
   The delay in treating Denis' wounds properly will work against
their odds of totally restoring his boyish good looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wounds heal best if they're treated right away,'' said Dr.
Peter Grossman, a surgeon who will be working on Denis' hands, and
the son of A. Richard Grossman, the lead surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the process goes on without treatment, scar tissue replaces
healthy tissue,'' he said. ``It starts to pull and contract and
does not have the normal elasticity.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the elder Grossman cut away a flap of coarse, thick
scar tissue from Denis' right cheek and covered it with cadaver
skin to protect the wound. The slice of flesh was about the size of
a piece of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Grossman grafted a thick layer of skin from
the inside of the boy's thigh to his right cheek, and then attached
a thinner layer of skin from another spot on his leg to the thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Operations on his badly mangled hands will follow and may
include tendon grafting to improve his flexibility, said Peter
Grossman.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, the boy's plight came to the attention of Dr.
Michael Pomo of North Hollywood, who was volunteering on Sakhalin
Island. After being contacted by Pomo, A. Richard Grossman, the
burn center's founder, Grossman's son and other surgeons agreed to
donate their services to defray costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we would not really be talking about where he is
because it's so early in the healing process,'' Peter Grossman
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Denis wanted to thank everyone for their generosity,
Grossman said. He wanted to stand next to his mother, Janna, and
smile again.
</P>
<P>
   (ITAL) When Denis is not in the hospital, he and his mother stay
at a nearby home for aging and retired Russian women. The
Children's Burn Foundation is looking for more suitable
accommodations for the two, preferably with local Russian-speaking
families and schooling for Denis. To offer assistance, call (818)
907-2822. (END ITAL) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
