<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2413 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     04-17 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN WASN'T LAKERS' ONLY PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Let's hope Jerry Buss learned his lesson.
Whatever that lesson might be.
</P>
<P>
   Don't hire power forwards who sob at good-news press
conferences? Don't hire players whose idea of unselfishness is
sitting out the final minutes of tight games to give the rookies
some floor time? Don't hire 38-year-old men who have the fashion
sense to color-coordinate high heels and wedding dresses but lack
the foresight to wear socks and sneakers to basketball practice?
</P>
<P>
   Buss, the Los Angeles Lakers' owner who wanted Dennis Rodman,
won't make those mistakes again.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the opportunity is likely to come up again anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   The failed experiment with Shoeless Dennis was a
once-in-a-lifetime thing, a freak occurrence in more ways than one.
And now, rather than stew in their disappointment or allow the
Rodman ``distraction'' to remain an excuse, the Lakers have to
forget about him and get on with solving bigger problems in the
three short weeks before the NBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So tie those laces in double knots, guys, and strap on your
thinking caps.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Rodman signing, undone in the seconds it took to
phone the league office, this season's other Lakers personnel moves
have caused damage that won't be easy to repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``With him (Rodman) or without him, we were going to have to
correct a lot of things on the basketball court,'' coach Kurt
Rambis said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Said forward/guard Kobe Bryant of the Lakers' position, fifth in
the Western Conference: ``I don't think we can pin the blame on one
guy (Rodman).... It's everybody's fault.''
</P>
<P>
   The players, the coach and the management.
</P>
<P>
   The season began _ late, because of the lockout _ amid
well-founded Lakers optimism. They had nine of last year's dozen
playoff players and they had the same veteran X's-and-O's coach,
both advantages going into a concentrated schedule in which
practice time would be scarce.
</P>
<P>
   They had a young, deep roster that the front office expected to
grow together into a perennial contender.
</P>
<P>
   And they shared _ or said they shared _ a commitment to the
belief that defense wins championships.
</P>
<P>
   The season opened Feb. 5. Within 18 days they had changed
coaches, firing Del Harris and promoting the untested Rambis, and
within 33 they had shaken up the roster, trading their best
defender and their front-court depth to acquire Glen Rice from
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers now feel they'll need every minute of their
newfound peace and quiet to put the pieces together, no wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman told a TV interviewer he's being made a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. If the Lakers wanted to distract us from the real causes
of their 25-15 record, which is six games behind last year's pace,
they'd keep him on the team. Without him, it's easy to see what
else is missing:
</P>
<P>
   _Defense. They're allowing 95.6 points a game, fifth worst in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play defense. That has to be (priority) No. 1,'' Bryant said,
making it sound like Nos. 2, 3, 4, 5 and 6 as well.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Eddie Jones, their leader in steals for four straight
seasons, for Rice, a shooter who missed training while recovering
from an injury, has hurt more than expected. They can only hope to
make up for that with improved defensive teamwork as the new lineup
gets acquainted.
</P>
<P>
   _Depth. At only one position can the Lakers be considered as
deep in talent as they were in '98. That's small forward, where
Rick Fox and Robert Horry back up Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Both center and power forward are shallower without Elden
Campbell, traded to Charlotte with Jones. Shooting guard finds
Bryant, who's better at small forward, without a set backup, after
Bryant backed up Jones last year. And point guard has an undefined
rotation of Derek Fisher, Derek Harper and Tyronn Lue instead of
Fisher and '98 All-Star Nick Van Exel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't think we could advance to the (championship) level
we needed to with the team we had,'' general manager Mitch Kupchak
said of the trade _ and, significantly, he insists the deal would
have been made even if Rodman hadn't been signed first.
</P>
<P>
   _Leadership. Rambis, the interim, rookie head coach, is doing as
well as can be expected and is only going to get better. It was
good to hear Kupchak say Friday that he and executive vice
president Jerry West like Rambis' chances of keeping the job for
1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   But this was the wrong time to break in a new coach, forcing him
to deal with the trade and Rodman's misbehavior during a hurried-up
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   If they'd kept Harris, in retrospect, the guess here is that the
Lakers wouldn't lead the Western Conference, but they'd be closer
than they are.
</P>
<P>
   First place, and the playoff home-court advantage that comes
with it, is out of reach with 10 games left in the season. But
there's time for the Lakers to get in stride.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that they all have their running shoes on. The
bad news is they have a long way to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
