<HEADLINE>
LUCAS, FOX BEGIN PREPPING `PHANTOM' ALLOCATION LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Attention ``Star Wars'' campers _ the final
decision on which movie theaters will screen ``Star Wars Episode 1:
Phantom Menace'' should come in about two more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A top 20th Century Fox executive said Friday that contracts will
be signed between the studio and theater operators after trade
screenings take place around May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to see the film before they can sign the contract,''
said Tom Sherak, chairman of Fox Domestic Film Group. ``There are
no deals yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherak's comments came after Daily Variety reported Fox and
``Star Wars'' creator George Lucas had begun making
``allocations,'' industry jargon for a distributor issuing a ``wish
list'' of theaters allowed to book the film.
</P>
<P>
   The paper, citing unnamed industry sources, said local
allocations included Mann's Chinese and the Mann Village _ both of
which saw fans start camping out last week _ along with Loews
Cineplex Century Plaza Cinemas in Century City, the Mann Criterion
6 in Santa Monica and the General Cinemas Galleria 16 in Redondo
Beach. But Sherak said no names would be released until after
contracts are signed.
</P>
<P>
   The trade paper also reported that AMC had been passed over in
several key competitive Southern California zones, including
Century City, Santa Monica, Pasadena, Orange and Ontario, but AMC
spokeswoman Brenda Nolte asserted the chain remains in the running.
``The final booking decisions will not be made until after the
screenings,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Loews Cineplex spokesman Marc Pascucci said the Century Plaza
theater had been allocated the movie but added no decision had yet
been reached on the Universal City 18.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and Lucas have told exhibitors they will only select
theaters with the best presentation capabilities for ``Phantom
Menace'' and have indicated that the prequel will be booked at
about 2,000 theaters and on about 4,000 screens _ less than one in
eight of the more than 34,000 auditoriums in U.S. theaters.
Proposed terms reportedly include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A minimum run of eight weeks on the largest screen in a
multiplex.
</P>
<P>
   _ Total trailer time before movies will be limited to eight
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ No on-screen advertising prior to the film for the first two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and Lucas proposed earlier this month that ``Phantom
Menace'' ticket sales be restricted to same-day sales for the first
two weeks in order to limit scalping. But Fox recently indicated it
was discussing with exhibitors some kind of advance sale so fans
won't have to camp out before the movie opens in order to see it.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
