<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HOW GRETZKY SAW THE GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's a reason Wayne Gretzky has collected
assists for the past 20 years as easily as most NHL players collect
bruises or broken teeth. Gretzky's breadth of view has been the
nearest thing to God's on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   In street clothes he looks as unassuming as the kid hunched over
his desk in the back row of Algebra class. But put a few pounds of
padding on him and place a hockey stick in his hands and he becomes
a real-life Will Hunting.
</P>
<P>
   NHL rinks have been his blackboard, his genius patently evident
in the way he goes to a spot and the puck just naturally follows,
as if there's some magnetic force at work. His success was never
predicated on his speed, but on his computer-like reads.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Rangers' veteran center sees the game a few frames
ahead of everybody else, his prescience reducing a coach's
intricate Xs and Os to tic-tac-toe.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday Gretzky showed us that in the game of life, just as in
the game he has played without peer for 35 years, his vision is so
telescopic the rest of us might as well be looking through the
wrong end of the binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   Number 99 announced that he will retire in '99, after the
Rangers' regular-season finale Sunday against Pittsburgh, his
timing impeccable to the end.
</P>
<P>
   To see Gretzky, 38, play in person was a profound experience,
the modern-day equivalent of being at the Sistine Chapel with
Michelangelo or inside the Globe Theatre with William Shakespeare.
To have that kind of genius in our midst is such a rare and
wondrous thing, we hardly could be blamed for begging Gretzky to
come back for just one more year, to thrill us one last time.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, teammates, political dignitaries, hockey emissaries,
his wife. There seemingly wasn't anyone, great or small, who didn't
try the last few days to get Gretzky to double back on his decision
the same way he sometimes would when he was controlling the puck
and not his future.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jean Chretien, Canada's head of state, was among
those who tried to talk Gretzky out of retiring. To be sure, the
argument for playing another year or two was a sound one.
</P>
<P>
   His skills, like the blades on his skates, can still cut quite a
figure. Gretzky tied for the NHL assists lead in 1997-98 and he
earned MVP honors at this year's All-Star Game. He leads the
Rangers this season with 52 assists and 61 points in 69 games,
which is middling only by his own mind-boggling standards.
</P>
<P>
   We wanted to see him back next season because Gretzky on his
worst day is better than 99 percent of NHL players on their best.
</P>
<P>
   Only Gretzky, with his peripheral vision, saw the bigger picture
that the rest of us, in our myopia, missed. Leave it to the guy a
teammate once described as having a rear-view mirror in the back of
his head to see what was gaining on him fast.
</P>
<P>
   It was youth, not as represented by Paul Kariya, Teemu Selanne
and Jaromir Jagr but as personified by his three offspring.
Paulina, Ty and Trevor are growing up _ too quickly, as kids are
wont to do.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983-84 Gretzky collected at least one point in 51 straight
games, but more recently he couldn't count on making it to two
school events in a row. When he stood before reporters Friday and
said of his family, ``there are new adventures ahead of us,'' he
was referring to the mundane events that make parenting so
priceless.
</P>
<P>
   His firstborn Paulina is 10, the same age her father was when he
scored 378 goals in one unforgettable season while playing against
kids three and four years older. She has her own interests and so
do Ty, 8, and Trevor, 6. The boys are playing hockey, rising early
for practices the same way their dad once did, motivated by the
same passion for the game that drove their father to the end.
</P>
<P>
   The only difference is Gretzky has not been able to be there for
them in every way, as his father Walter was for him. Gretzky's dad
didn't have a lot of money to lavish on his children but that was
immaterial. He showered them with something even more valuable: his
attention.
</P>
<P>
   It was Walter who laced up Wayne's first pair of skates almost
as soon as his son could walk. And it was Walter who flooded the
backyard in the winter and put Wayne through myriad drills and
drummed into his head to ``skate to where the puck is going to be,
not where it has been'' and kept the young boy's head from getting
too big when success came fast and furious.
</P>
<P>
   It is in no small part because of Walter that Gretzky grew up to
be a giant and a gentleman, ``the consummate ambassador'' for the
NHL, in the words of commissioner Gary Bettman.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's unfailingly politeness, his willingness to give
everybody and his editor a minute of his time over the years, has
set him apart as much as his play. But unlike his talent, his time
is limited. Gretzky's children have paid the biggest price for his
superstardom, their own activities superceded by their father's
games.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Gretzky told a poignant story of how Paulina wept
inconsolably when the NHL schedule precluded him from attending a
father-daughter event at her school.
</P>
<P>
   So worry not how Gretzky will fill his idle days. ``I think that
I've got a tremendous family,'' he said. ``That'll give me a lot of
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   No one carried a greater burden night-in and night-out than
Gretzky, yet he never failed to see the contributions made by
others to his success. He took a few moments Friday to acknowledge
some of those people, from his childhood coaches to NHL trainers,
equipment managers and public relations directors.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, who in 1993 led the Los Angeles Kings to their only
Stanley Cup Finals appearance, has meant as much to the NHL as
Michael Jordan did to the NBA. Only he's too humble to publicly
admit it. How else to explain Gretzky, at his own farewell
conference, bemoaning that Jordan ``left too early. I have kids who
idolize him. I wish he was still playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of Gretzky, of course. But we won't rue
his retirement. We trust he has a few more memorable assists in
him. He was right to call his retirement ``a celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Paulina, Ty and Trevor Gretzky won something on Friday
that is more precious than the Stanley Cup. The prize they'll now
be able to show off is their dad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
