<SLUG> BC-POLICE-KILLING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANDLER POLICE OFFICER KILLED IN GUNBATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDI VILLA  
 and JIM WALSH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHANDLER, Ariz. _ A Chandler police SWAT team officer storming
an apartment complex to arrest suspects in a jewelry heist was
fatally wounded Friday before fellow officers killed one of the
suspects with return fire.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Jim Snedigar is Chandler's first to be killed in the
line of duty. He also is the second Valley officer shot to death in
the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Police took two other men into custody a short time after the 3
p.m. shootout at a gated apartment complex where the robbery
suspects had fled after a 2-mile car chase from Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Pursuing officers fanned out and, upon finding a broken arcadia
door at one of the units, called in the Chandler SWAT team as
residents were individually telephoned and ordered to stay inside.
The officers tossed stun grenades into the apartment and were
starting in when they were met by gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Snedigar, who was wearing body armor, fell just inside the
apartment, police said. Authorities had no identity on the dead
suspect, who also wore a bulletproof vest.
</P>
<P>
   A former Army paratrooper, Snedigar was a member of the bicycle
squad who volunteered for SWAT detail on occasion, a co-worker
said.
</P>
<P>
   He left behind a wife and two young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a hard-charger, he didn't like to sit on his behind,''
said Chandler Officer Eddie Cuthbertson, 30, a five-year veteran.
``I remember he used to tell me, `What are you sitting down for?
There's criminals out there. Let's go put them in jail.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His death is ``like someone just ripped your heart out of you,''
Cuthbertson said.
</P>
<P>
   A shaken Police Chief Bobby Joe Harris told reporters Friday
afternoon, ``The officers are not doing well. They're emotionally
upset, as I was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to go through this, but we will make it.''
</P>
<P>
   The shooting struck hard at the rank and file of law enforcement
Valley-wide, many of whom are still recovering from a series of
shootings of police officers that occurred last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just unbelievable,'' said Terry Sills, president of
the Phoenix Law Enforcement Association. ``I'm numb. What in the
world is going on?'' &QL; 
Sills said he got the news Friday as he was preparing to tell a
Phoenix police squad about efforts to have a park named for Officer
Marc Atkinson, who was ambushed and shot to death March 26. He
broke the news of the Chandler officer's death to the Phoenix cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about some sad faces,'' Sills said. ``I mean, is this
open season on us right now? I know I'm just stunned. It was just
silence. My gosh, `Not again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's incident began at 11:50 a.m. when Tempe police received
a 911 call from Crescent Jewelers, 1310 W. Elliot Road. The caller
hung up, but police went to the scene and discovered that an armed
robbery had been committed, said Officer Pat McDonnell, a Chandler
police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Two robbers had gone inside the store, while the third had
stayed behind in the getaway car, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe officers pursued a stolen black Ford Mustang described by
witnesses as the robbers' vehicle to the Sierra Palms Apartments, a
gated complex on 54th Street just north of Ray Road in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler police said the suspects were able to drive into the
complex because of a broken security gate.
</P>
<P>
   There, the men tried to kick down the door of one of the
residents, who called 911, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Police alerted administrators of nearby Kyrene de Las Manitas
Elementary School to keep children in the classrooms until the
situation was under control.
</P>
<P>
   The children who live on the western side of Interstate 10 were
able to get onto buses and get home safely, but those who live on
the eastern side of the freeway were kept in their classrooms after
the last bell rang, said Mary Padilla, assistant to the
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, police alerted the management of Sierra Palms, which
called tenants individually to instruct them to stay inside.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Parker said he had just hung up with his mother when he
got the call. He looked out the window and saw officers who
motioned him to stay back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned to look at the TV,'' he said. ``We heard Boom! Boom!
Boom! on the door. It scared the hell out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Other residents peeked anyway and caught glimpses of officers
approaching the apartment unit where the shooting later broke out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty scary. We've just been trying to stay behind
walls,'' said Sonsee Shively, who was inside her home with her
2{-year-old daughter Payton. The police ``were aiming their guns
into the unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Shively said after the shooting she saw four officers take out a
man who had a nylon stocking mask over his head, with a hole that
exposed the man's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary knowing that we were so close,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About two hours following the shooting, a somber McDonnell,
blinking back tears, announced in a media briefing, ``The officer
has been killed.''
</P>
<P>
   The apartment complex remained cordoned off as investigators
piece together the details that led up to the deadly outcome. Chief
Harris was joined at different times by Tempe Police Chief Ron
Burns, Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley and Sheriff Joe Arpaio,
whose department was called in after the shooting to serve as
backup to Tempe's SWAT unit.
</P>
<P>
   Snedigar's death hit the Chandler Police Department hardest of
all.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler Officer John Shearer, who works in the Professional
</P>
<P>
   Standards Unit, said his colleagues used to remark about how
fortunate the department had been not to lose one of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk became more muted when motorcycle Officer Jed Gunter
was seriously injured in December, struck by a driver who was later
determined to be legally drunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occasionally, people will discuss that we've been lucky for so
long,'' Shearer said. ``I guess before, there was talk (that) we're
due.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Gunter's incident, two other Chandler motorcycle officers
have been injured, and on March 17, officers serving a warrant on a
suspected drug house shot dead a man who pointed a gun at one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd gone years, all through the mid-'90s, where we had good
luck,'' Shearer said. But ``When it rains, it pours,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Summers, a retired Chandler police captain, recalled Friday
that Snedigar spent a day riding around in a motorhome, delivering
presents to children during the holidays as part of KNIX radio
personality W. Steven Martin's annual Christmas toy drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always a gentleman, always thoughtful and
considerate,'' Summers said. ``He's pretty quiet, but he had a
really good dry sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he was hired, Snedigar's hearing declined, Summers
said. But Summers, who wears hearing aids, assured him he could
continue his career if he also wore hearing aids.
</P>
<P>
   Snedigar went on to have a distinguished career, Summers said.
His daily assignment was with the Neighborhood Response Team. Said
Police Chief Harris, ``He is one of the best we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities labored into the night to clear the scene. They
evacuated scores of apartment residents by bus so officers could
conduct a door-to-door search and ensure there are no outstanding
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Salvation Army officials provided food, water and diapers to
accommodate the displaced residents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judi Villa can be reached at (602) 444-7972 or at
judi.villa(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Jim Walsh can be reached at (602) 444-7984 or at
jim.walsh(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Richard Ruelas and Laura Trujillo contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
