<HEADLINE>
EXPERIENCE CREATES HEAVY FAVORITES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Experience over youth.
</P>
<P>
   If Friday's qualifying round were any indication, the PPG-Dayton
Indy Lights Championship in the Toyota Grand Prix of Long Beach
could have a different outcome than last month's Indy Lights
Championship in Homestead, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The top eight qualifiers on Friday each have raced at least a
season in Indy Lights. At Homestead, the series' first event of the
season, Mexico's Mario Dominguez won and New Zealand's Scott Dixon
finished third. Both are rookies.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Dixon finished the highest of six rookies in the
qualifier, but ended up ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's Felipe Giaffone, Monte Carlo's Philipp Peter and
England's Guy Smith finished in the top three. Giaffone's best lap
was 68.721 seconds at an average speed of 95.552. Peter's best lap
was 69.081 at 95.024, and Smith's was 69.189 at 94.905.
</P>
<P>
   Add that the next five qualifiers are Indy Lights' veterans, and
it would seem experience helps in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say why (the rookies lagged in the qualifier),''
Peter said. ``Maybe they're getting a little slow.''
</P>
<P>
   But then again, the qualifier is not necessarily a sign of what
to expect in Sunday's race. If it is, then Brazil could continue
its dominance in the Indy Lights portion of the Toyota Grand Prix
as the past two winners Helio Castro-Neves and Cristiano da Matta
were from Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The qualifier, however, simply is for drivers to make
adjustments and get used to the track. There is another Indy Lights
qualifier, the final one, this morning at 11:15 a.m. in which the
race positions will be determined.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of this qualifier was Long Beach's revamped track,
which has been extended from 1.57 miles and seven turns to 1.824
miles and 11 turns to accommodate the new Aquarium of the Pacific.
The top three finishers agreed that the turns added spice to the
race.
</P>
<P>
   The revamped track could have helped Giaffone, who had trouble
the first day of the Toyota Grand Prix last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be first (on Friday) is a big improvement, but for sure the
track will be faster (today),'' Giaffone said. ``So we must improve
the car again if we want to stay at the front.''
</P>
<P>
   Constant improvements and adjustments are being done to the cars
of the 19 Indy Lights racers. David Pook, a Long Beach native and
son of the Grand Prix's founder Chris Pook, is doing the same
thing. Pook finished 15th with a best lap of 70.772 at 92.377. He
wasn't disappointed with his finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make as many positive changes as possible,
instead of pounding down the fastest lap time,'' Pook said. ``...
Our best days are ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   This 30-minute qualifier had just two interruptions. In the
first interruption, Bakersfield's Casey Mears hit the tire barriers
in turn four a new turn.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with eight minutes left, Santa Monica's Cory Witherill hit
the wall in turn seven.
</P>
<P>
   The session resumed with three minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   A practice session in the morning preceded the qualifier. A
five-minute stoppage highlighted the session when Chris Menninga
hit the tire barriers in turn six. Pook also skimmed a wall, but it
didn't seem to affect him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
