<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-SONICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LED BY BURRELL, THE NEW-LOOK NETS BLOW AWAY SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ By their own admission, the New Jersey Nets are hard
to figure out. Without explanation, they lose convincingly to two
of the worst teams in the league and Friday night play nearly
flawless basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Coach Don Casey's call to play with pride, the
Nets beat the SuperSonics badly on the backboards, smothered them
defensively, executed with precision in the halfcourt, and ran
effectively in transition to rout Seattle by 121-91 before a
sold-out crowd of 17,072 at Key Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, in which the Nets led comfortably from the second
quarter on and matched the highest point total in the league this
season, ended the disappointing West Coast road trip on a high. The
121 points were the most this season in a regulation game and were
the product of a well-balanced attack that placed all five starters
and the sixth man in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   That sixth man was Kerry Kittles, whose poor play cost him his
starting job before the game. Casey, who had taken to sitting
Kittles during the critical stretches of games, moved Scott Burrell
into the first unit as a small forward and slid Kendall Gill over
to shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles, who signed a six-year, $52 million deal on March 13,
claimed not to be disappointed and said the reduced role would
relax him. He was right. Playing his most efficient game in weeks,
Kittles made 7 of 10 shots in scoring 15 points, and keyed the
game-turning run by scoring 11 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected blowout could be attributed to Seattle's fatigue
because the Sonics were playing their third straight game and had
edged Sacramento in overtime Thursday night. But the Sonics (19-20)
are fighting desperately for a Western Conference playoff spot, so
they should have been hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was the Nets who played as if there was a position
in the post-season on the line. Burrell, playing his best game of
the season, and Stephon Marbury led New Jersey with 18 points
apiece, while Gill and Keith Van Horn added 15. Jamie Feick scored
14.
</P>
<P>
   The shuffling of the lineup paid off immediately as Burrell
played some of his best basketball of the season in the first
quarter. With the Nets trailing by 3 points, he scored 8 straight,
including 6 on consecutive 3-pointers. The Sonics regained the lead
briefly, but when Kittles replaced Gill with 4 minutes 7 seconds
left in the quarter, the Nets took off.
</P>
<P>
   After missing his first shot _ a 3-pointer from the left wing _
Kittles scored on a driving four-footer over two defenders, then
slapped away a defensive rebound from an unsuspecting Sonics player
and finished with a layup. Marbury, who played a tremendous floor
game in recording eight assists in the first half, followed with
two free throws to give the Nets 34 first-quarter points, their
most this season.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles continued to play the slick game that made him one of
the league's brightest young stars and scored 5 more points as the
Nets completed a 15-0 run to take a 16-point lead two minutes into
the second quarter. When Kittles hit a stylish reverse layup in
transition to put the Nets ahead by 41-25, the home team was loudly
booed by its fans.
</P>
<P>
   While Kittles did his thing on the perimeter, Feick dominated
inside the paint. Feick _ who was hustling to outplay Olden
Polynice and the beleaguered four-time All-Star Vin Baker _ matched
his season high for points with 12 in the first half. He also
grabbed seven rebounds to lead the Nets to a 30-21 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles, Burrell and Feick, who combined for 36 first-half
points, were so potent that the Nets took a 54-43 lead into the
locker room despite little production from their leading scorers,
Marbury and Van Horn. Though he distributed the ball superbly,
Marbury hit only 2 of 11 shots in scoring 7 points, and Van Horn
was unusually inactive with just 4 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
