<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-SHARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SHUT OUT SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Earlier in the year, Ray Ferraro was talking
about retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But as his 15th season reaches its conclusion, Ferraro isn't
talking about it anymore. He wants to keep playing, and he wants to
play for the Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro scored 17 seconds Friday night's game against the San
Jose Sharks, and with Stephane Fiset stopping 32 shots, it was the
only goal the Kings would need as they recorded a 2-0 victory
before a crowd of 17,483 at the San Jose Arena. Fiset's shutout was
his third this season and the 15th of his career. Rob Blake scored
the game's other goal, on a power play four minutes after Ferraro's
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours earlier, Ferraro had scored twice, including
the overtime winner, in a 4-3 victory over the Mighty Ducks at the
Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to show you can play,'' said Ferraro, 34, who
acknowledged a week ago that he has decided to continue his career.
``I want (Kings management) to know I'm still hungry, I still have
desire. Obviously, a few goals don't hurt, either.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the third in a row for the Kings (32-44-5), who
conclude the season Sunday afternoon at the Forum against St.
Louis. The victory enabled the Mighty Ducks to clinch sixth place
in the Western Conference, setting up a first-round playoff date
with the two-time defending Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks (31-33-17) had hoped to overtake the Ducks by beating
the Kings on Friday and the Ducks tonight in San Jose, but instead
will settle for seventh place and a daunting first-round series
with powerful Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ferraro, he acknowledged Kings management already may
have reached a decision on his future. General Manager Dave Taylor
is deferring personnel decisions until after the season. Ferraro's
contract expires with the conclusion of the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd imagine they already know what they want to do,'' he said.
``I'd imagine I'll find out next week whether they want me or not.
I sure as heck hope they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro's goals Thursday snapped a 24-game goal-scoring drought.
He has 13 goals this season, and less than a week from now, he'll
be in Bristol, Conn., serving as a studio analyst on ESPN playoff
telecasts. But he said no full-time television offer could sway him
from returning to the ice for at least another season, if not with
the Kings then elsewhere in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still want to play,'' he said. ``Hopefully, they feel the
same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky tribute: The Kings will delay the start of Sunday's game
to show the telecast of the Wayne Gretzky retirement ceremony on
the video scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Galley update: Defenseman Garry Galley said the next two or
three weeks will determine whether or not he will need surgery to
repair a torn abdominal muscle that has sidelined him for the last
two weeks of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Galley, who turned 36 Friday, said he thinks the tear dates to
two years ago when he was with the Buffalo Sabres. He was able to
rehabilitate the original injury without surgery and is hoping to
do the same thing again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' Galley said. ``It would have been nice
to finish the year, even though it was bothering me.''
</P>
<P>
   Galley said if he needs surgery, recovery time will be 6 to 8
weeks, meaning he'll be ready for the start of training camp in
September.
</P>
<P>
   In other injury news, rookie defenseman Jan Nemecek suffered a
bruised knee Thursday night against the Mighty Ducks and did not
play against the Sharks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
