<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-ANGELS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPERS FLARE IN M'S LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ They held Friday night's Mariners-Angels game
at the wrong Disney theme park. A more fitting setting would have
been Frontier Land, not Edison Field, because that wasn't a
ballgame as much as a wild West showdown.
</P>
<P>
   The principal gunslingers were Mariners left-hander Jamie Moyer
and Angels hitters Troy Glaus, Andy Sheets and Todd Greene, with
both managers and third-base coaches, and even fans, getting
involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels won, 9-5, sending the M's to their fourth defeat in a
row after being swept at home by the Texas Rangers. They did it
when a pitcher's duel morphed into insanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of crazy things happening,'' said Greene, the
Angels' DH whose seventh-inning grand slam drove Moyer from the
game. ``Any time you're playing division games, those games are
important. These games against Seattle count just the same as the
ones at the end of September.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer and Angels right-hander Tim Belcher were tied, 2-2,
heading to the bottom of the sixth. Moyer, who struck out the side
in the fifth, got one out, then allowed a double off the top of the
left-center field wall to Angels rookie Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   Greene followed with a fly out, and Charlie O'Brien grounded to
the hole between third and short. Giomar Guevara went to his right
for a nice stop, but rushed his throw, bouncing it three times and
pulling David Segui off first, allowing the slow-footed O'Brien to
reach on a single. That scored Glaus, giving Anaheim a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The light-hitting shortstop Sheets, an ex-Mariner, followed with
a homer to center field off a 1-2 change-up that Moyer called a
``horrible pitch.'' That put the Angels ahead, 5-2, and, coming as
it did after the O'Brien hit, accentuated the loss of shortstop
Alex Rodriguez, who is out three to five more weeks with torn knee
cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We not only miss Alex in the field, but we miss him at the
plate,'' said Moyer, who did not need to mention that Seattle had
only five hits. ``It's not one-sided. I know they're out there
doing their best, you can't fault them for that. We're all human
beings. What are you going to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 39,635 thought it knew what Moyer was doing. He hit
Orlando Palmeiro, coming inside with a fastball on the Angels
lead-off hitter, who had been taking Moyer the other way and, Moyer
said, needed to be moved off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that precipitated a seventh-inning shouting match
between M's third base coach Steve Smith and Anaheim third base
coach Larry Bowa is unknown; neither participant nor manager was
commenting. Whatever the cause, the blow-up _ which occured with
Seattle batting and Smith in the field _ was just the first of the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the seventh, after allowing a pair of one-out
singles, Moyer hit Glaus on the hip. Glaus motioned toward Moyer,
players rose to the top step in both dugouts, and home plate umpire
Mike Reilly warned both benches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm going to throw at someone to load the bases,
No. 1,'' Moyer said. ``No. 2, who am I going to intimidate? No. 3,
we're still in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   As Angels manager Terry Collins argued the warning, Mariners
manager Lou Piniella emerged from Seattle's dugout, irate at a fan,
who said he had called Piniella an ``idiot'' for leaving Moyer in
the game. Piniella had to be restrained by security officials as he
berated the fan, who was escorted from his seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy there doesn't even belong in a ballpark,'' Piniella
said. ``He belongs in a mental hospital. He was just yelling the
whole time, threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   The fan had laughed last. The next batter Moyer faced was
Greene, who hit his first career grand slam off a high change-up
and gave the Angels a 9-2 lead. Moyer left to boos, tipping his cap
on his way off the field. The fan, who remained in the park in a
different seating area, was later cheered by the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows the idiocy of some people,'' Moyer said. ``They
perceive what they see and they're entitled to their opinion, but
when it gets to the point where they're screaming and hollering at
people _ I'd be interested to see 25,000 people go up to the
workplace of those fans and hoot and holler at them and see how
they crumble under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer (1-2) allowed nine runs on 12 hits over 61/3 innings,
running his earned-run average to 10.42. Belcher, gave up two runs
in seven inning and won his first game for the Angels. Seattle had
shown interest in Belcher before backing out, and the right-hander
got $10.2 million over two years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the players Seattle signed instead, outfielder John
Mabry, was a bright spot Friday night, throwing out two runners and
hitting a three-run homer in the ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 0235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
