<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING BUT NETS IN BLOWOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A day after winning what Sonics coach Paul Westphal
deemed the ``biggest game,'' there was no escaping the trend that
has followed his team.
</P>
<P>
   Things immediately got worse for the Sonics, who fell flat
Friday night at KeyArena during a disturbing 121-91 loss to the New
Jersey Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal, who jumped around frantically after Thursday's
emotional overtime victory in Sacramento, wasn't even around for
the end of this one. He was excused with 6:43 left in the fourth
quarter after receiving back-to-back technical fouls for arguing a
call.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal's ejection was the only fire the Sonics showed on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics (19-20) tied their worst defeat this season _ Utah
pummeled them 110-80 on Feb. 20. Defensively, the Sonics gave up
the most points in an NBA regular-season game this season.
</P>
<P>
   The ramification of the loss was just as brutal.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Suns beat the Dallas Mavericks Friday night which,
combined with the Sonics' loss, dropped Seattle to the eighth seed
in the Western Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are now half a game behind the Suns, whom the Sonics
face Sunday at America West Arena. Phoenix has already beaten the
Sonics twice, clinching the tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State moved ahead of Sacramento and is now just two games
behind the Sonics for the last playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the schedule caught got us,'' Westphal said, ``but I'm
not quitting on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it would just be simple to say that New Jersey (11-28)
caught the Sonics at a most opportune time.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were the Sonics playing their third game in three days,
but they were also coming off a victory. These days that spells
trouble for the Sonics, who have been in a win-one-day,
lose-the-next whirlwind the past nine games.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Sonics won back-to-back games was March 14-16.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you can do is try to get as much rest as
possible,'' said Hersey Hawkins, who scored 21 points on 9-of-16
shooting. ``That's the remedy when you have three games in three
nights. I could see that we were tired. The rotations weren't as
crisp, and getting back on defense wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics appeared drained and unable to keep up with the Nets'
younger, fresher legs from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Still the Sonics' 40-percent shooting was mystifying considering
their opponent. The Nets gave up 120 points to Denver on Wednesday
night, and 109 points to the Los Angeles Clippers the night before.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey, which is 4-17 on the road, could be considered the
most disappointing team in the league. But the Nets have also been
one of the more handicapped _ New Jersey players have missed a
total of 119 games because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets were even without their leader and best rebounder,
Jayson Williams, who is out for the season with a broken right leg.
Nonetheless, the Sonics were the ones crippled most of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Their defense gave up open jumper after jumper, and could not
contain the Nets' dribble penetration.
</P>
<P>
   Fans booed the team's effort for the second time this season at
KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans didn't like it. We didn't either,'' Westphal said.
``I don't want to make anything sound like excuses but the reality
is we know we can play better than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are banged up, guys are tired and we have some older
players.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the team's youngest contributors is hurting the most
among the starters. Vin Baker was limited again by his sore right
knee. He played just 28 minutes and finished with just two points
and one rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton's 29 points and 11 assists led the Sonics. Without
Baker, though, the team was weakened inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hurting,'' Baker said. ``I'm too thick-headed sometimes
about playing. But I'm hurting my team more than I'm helping.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine the Sonics would have done much better with
a healthy Baker. New Jersey had things going its way that much.
</P>
<P>
   Leading 54-43 at halftime, the Nets opened a 21-point lead in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Tempers flared in the fourth when Sonics center Olden Polynice
was called for a flagrant foul while trying to block Jamie Feick's
shot. Just seconds later, Sonics rookie Rashard Lewis drew a foul
guarding Kendall Gill.
</P>
<P>
   That is when Westphal blew up at the officials.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the sequence, New Jersey shot eight straight free
throws. The Nets went ahead 104-78 with 5:11 left in the game.
Their biggest lead was 33 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing good about a loss like this is that it's easy
to bounce back,'' Hawkins said. ``Not to say that I like our
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think we're better than what we're showing. It just
would have been much tougher if it had been a close game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
