A2436 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-L     04-17 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MARINERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' GREENE SLAMS MARINERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Lou Piniella and Jamie Moyer gave Friday
night's Angels-Mariners game the spark it needed and Todd Greene
responded by setting off the fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   Pennant fever in April? The atmosphere certainly coaxed that
sentiment into a matchup that had practically everything you'd find
in a similar meeting in late September.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's first career grand slam highlighted a wild four-run
seventh inning as the Angels did the talking with their bats in a
9-5 victory in front of an enthusiastic 39,635 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Belcher sparkled on the mound for the Angels, coming through
with the kind of performance the team expected from him after
signing the right-hander to a $10 million contract in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher (1-1) went seven innings, striking out four, allowing
two earned runs and limiting the Mariners to four hits while
throwing 96 pitches and getting stronger as the game progressed. He
retired 16 of the final 19 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was outstanding tonight,'' Angels manager Terry Collins
said. ``He threw the ball great, he moved it around, he changed
speeds. It really was impressive and that's the Tim Belcher we
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher's performance, along with the Angels continued torrid
hitting, were accompanied by several episodes of bravado from
Seattle's coaching staff and by its pitcher, Moyer, who plunked two
Angels in two innings as the game began to get out of hand, drawing
the ire of the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella, the Mariners' manager, had to be restrained by a
security guard in the bottom of the seventh after a fan near the
dugout continued a tirade directed at him following Moyer's second
hit batsman.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Mariners third-base coach Steve Smith got into a
shouting match with Angels coach Larry Bowa, briefly interrupting
the top of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy does not belong in a ballpark,'' Piniella said of the
fan, who was momentarily ejected from his seat before being moved
to one farther away from the Seattle dugout. ``He belongs in a
mental hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene followed the Piniella incident with a line-drive shot to
left-center, making it 9-2 and sending the crowd into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of stuff that went on in that inning,'' said
Greene, who has three homers this season. ``That helped seal the
game. As it turned out, it was a pretty big hit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the ninth, Seattle's John Mabry blasted a
three-run homer off Shigetoshi Hasegawa.
</P>
<P>
   An inning earlier, the Angels began to break the game open.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus got things going with his major-league-leading 10th
double of the season _ his second of the game _ with one out. He
finished 3 for 3 on the night.
</P>
<P>
   After a sacrifice fly to left by Greene, which moved Glaus to
third, Charlie O'Brien came up with a key infield single to short,
his first hit in 13 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The ball was backhanded in the hole on a dive by Seattle's
Giomar Guevara, but his throw to first took three bounces before
reaching David Segui, pulling him off the bag and allowing the
slow-footed O'Brien to reach safely and Glaus to score for a 3-2
lead. No.9 hitter Andy Sheets followed with his first homer of the
season to dead center, giving the Angels a 6-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to win at this level, you gotta do it throughout the
lineup,'' Collins said. ``Different guys are doing it right now and
that's nice.
</P>
<P>
   And the way Belcher was pitching, the cushion Sheets provided
made it all the easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``That helps,'' Belcher said of the run support. ``We've been
pounding out a lot of runs and that's nice to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, it appeared Belcher might be headed to an early exit,
much as he did against Texas in his last start when he lasted only
3-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell smacked the first pitch of the game for a hard single
to right, and in the second inning Belcher walked Mabry before Russ
Davis drilled his fourth homer of the year to tie it at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Belcher began to find his groove and the Mariners
never threatened against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
