<HEADER>
A2443 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      04-17 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, April 18, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the section dress page:
</P>
<P>
   NATO-ANTIWAR-REVIEW (Brussels) _ NATO's 50th anniversary summit
meeting may be the first war council of the Cold War's
anti-warriors. Leaders who had reputations as draft-dodgers or
anti-missile demonstrators will gather and vow to continue doing
things many of them vowed in the 1960s never to do. But then,
Kosovo is a liberal's kind of war. Bombs away in the service of a
fight against inhumanity. By Craig R. Whitney. (`i' categeory)
</P>
<P>
   DISABILITY-SUITS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Supreme Court will
tackle one of the most critical questions arising from the
Americans With Disabilities Act: What is the legal threshold for
being considered disabled? The issue is whether people whose
conditions can be medically corrected so they can function normally
_ insulin for diabetes, or eyeglasses for impaired vision _ are
still entitled to sue for discrimination. By Leslie Kaufman. (`a'
category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   CONTEMPT-OF-COURT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Contempt of court findings
have a varied and even noble history in the annals of American law.
President Clinton's contempt citation in the Jones case seemed
oddly out of synch with other famous examples. Ronald Goldfarb,
author of `The Contempt Power' notes that many of the great legal
struggles of the century _ in civil rights, anti-war protests,
McCarthyism and the labor movement _ were triggered by contempt
citations. By Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-MISLEAD-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Pentagon's
missile-defense spinmeisters spun out of control after a test of
the Army's experimental Theater High-Altitude Area Defense system,
which has cost taxpayers $3.9 billion. They claimed that the it
achieved 16 of 17 objectives _ even though it failed to shatter the
target. A better count is 2 of 4 main goals, eliminating 14 of the
claimed successes, officials now say sheepishly. By William J.
Broad.
</P>
<P>
   MIND-HEALTH-REVIEW (Undated) _ Mind over matter: Modern medicine
has until recently not seen mental and physical health as
inextricably entwined. Now a growing number studies appearing in
mainstream medical journals demonstrate the impact of psychology on
physiology, such as alleviating arthritis by having a patient write
about their distresses. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-PROPS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at how American
politicians and protesters increasingly rely on political props (or
visuals, in spin-doctor lingo) to dramatize complex policies, razz
adversaries or snag a few seconds on the evening news. By David
Wallis.
</P>
<P>
   WHITEHOUSE-MEMOIRS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Political memoirs
often reflect sharply different memories. Case in point: George
Stephanopoulos' `All Too Human: A Political Education' vs. Dick
Morris' `Behind the Oval Office: Getting Re-Elected Against All
Odds.' The books often convey utterly dissimilar points of view,
reflecting the cutthroat infighting that prevailed when their
authors were advisers to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SAFEWAR-REVIEW (Washington) _ The NATO campaign against
Serbia has been designed to minimize casualties _ Baby Boomer
warfare. Bill Clinton and Tony Blair were born too late to
experience World War II, and they have grown up in an age
mesmerized by technology. They are impressed by their ability to
kill from afar, with almost no risk of retaliation against those
firing the weapons. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   SOVEREIGNTY-REVIEW (United Nations) _ The erosion of national
sovereignty over the past decade is reflected in U.N. support for
the campaign against Yugoslavia, the creation of international
tribunals to try crimes against humanity in Yugoslavia and Rwanda,
in Spain's effort to extradite former Chilean leader Augusto
Pinochet from Britain to try him for crimes against humanity, and
in the impending trial of two Libyans before a Scottish court in
the Netherlands over the bombinh of an American jetliner over
Lockerbie. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA-REVIEW (Kuala Lumpur) _ Malaysia as a parable of
globalization: the downfall of former Deputy Prime Minister Ibrahim
Anwar shows how outside economic forces can sunder the political
culture of even a well-governed country. Before the Asian crisis
devastated Malaysia's economy, Anwar and Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohammed Mahathir rarely disagreed. Now, they are locked in a
bitter feud. The economic crisis unfolded into a political crisis,
with changes in regimes throughout the region. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-WALK-REVIEW (Tokyo) _ Some scholars here argue that
from ancient times until perhaps 150 years ago, in a sign of
reduced social regimentation, Japanese were taught to walk in a
special style called the namba, in which the right arm and leg
swing forward at the same time, and then the left arm and leg swing
forward. Try it: these days it seems counter-intuitive. Almost
everybody in the world now walks the opposite way, with the right
leg and left arm moving forward at the same time, and vice-versa.
By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-POLICY-REVIEW (Washington) _ David Sanger examines the
Clinton administyration's foreign policy record.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Photo-Graphics editor is Deborah Marchand
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 603-1036
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: marchand(at)nytimes.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TECHNICAL PROBLEMS: &LR;  Peter Trigg
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
