   MALAYSIA-REVIEW (Kuala Lumpur) _ Malaysia as a parable of
globalization: the downfall of former Deputy Prime Minister Ibrahim
Anwar shows how outside economic forces can sunder the political
culture of even a well-governed country. Before the Asian crisis
devastated Malaysia's economy, Anwar and Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohammed Mahathir rarely disagreed. Now, they are locked in a
bitter feud. The economic crisis unfolded into a political crisis,
with changes in regimes throughout the region. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-WALK-REVIEW (Tokyo) _ Some scholars here argue that
from ancient times until perhaps 150 years ago, in a sign of
reduced social regimentation, Japanese were taught to walk in a
special style called the namba, in which the right arm and leg
swing forward at the same time, and then the left arm and leg swing
forward. Try it: these days it seems counter-intuitive. Almost
everybody in the world now walks the opposite way, with the right
leg and left arm moving forward at the same time, and vice-versa.
By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-POLICY-REVIEW (Washington) _ David Sanger examines the
Clinton administyration's foreign policy record.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
