<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2448 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ANTIWAR-REVIEW-9     04-17 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ANTIWAR-REVIEW-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DOVES OF YESTERYEAR FLY OFF TO A DIFFERENT WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (jt)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Think of NATO's 50th anniversary summit
meeting as the first war council of the Cold War's anti-warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders who had reputations for avoiding the draft or
demonstrating against nuclear missiles will gather at the end of
this week in a building named for Ronald Reagan and vow to continue
doing things many of them vowed in the 1960s never to do.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Kosovo is a liberal's kind of war. Bombs away in the
fight against inhumanity, say President Clinton, Prime Minister
Tony Blair of Britain, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany and
the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Their stated goal is to force one of the world's last Communist
dictators to stop terrible outrages against the ethnic Albanian
population of Kosovo, the worst crimes against humanity in Europe
since Hitler, and let the refugees return under international
protection.
</P>
<P>
   This is a war aim acceptable to all but dyed-in-the-wool
pacifists. But the political landscape of this war is also more
complicated than that. Not all Cold War doves were pacifists by any
means, and Kosovo has revealed shifts in the geopolitical strategic
ground on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   In France, political followers of Gen. Charles de Gaulle, who
kicked NATO headquarters out of France in 1966 because he thought
the alliance was an instrument of American domination, are now
letting the American Supreme Allied Commander, Gen. Wesley Clark,
have all the Mirage-2000 and Super Etendard warplanes he asks for.
The French hate the actions of Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan
Milosevic, as much as the Americans do.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, Social Democrats and Green Party pacifists, who
earned their left-wing credentials opposing the deployment of
American nuclear missiles to Europe in the 1980s, are now sending
Luftwaffe Tornado fighter-bombers to the Balkans. It is democratic
Germany's first combat action abroad, and it was unthinkable only a
few years ago in a country still struggling with the legacy of its
actions in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, Prime Minister Massimo d'Alema, who protested Italy's
support for the Persian Gulf War in 1991, has made the entire
country into one giant aircraft carrier for the daily blitz across
the Adriatic.
</P>
<P>
   And in America, President Clinton is being challenged to be even
more hawkish by an unlikely coalition. It is made up of
conservative Republicans who thought American political leaders
stabbed the military in the back during the Vietnam War, and many
liberal Democrats who opposed that war altogether. Together, in the
name of the refugees, they are asking a former draft avoider to do
what Lyndon Johnson tried 35 years ago: Send in ground troops to do
what air power alone can't do, and win the war.
</P>
<P>
   All these ironies have rich and complex overtones.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton may be wary of being pushed down the slippery
slope of a ground war in Kosovo partly because some of the loudest
advocates of a stronger policy are the same political opponents who
tried to bring him down with impeachment earlier this year _ and
because he is aware of how destructive the Vietnam War proved to be
for Johnson's domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some of the loudest advocates of staying out
of Kosovo are conservative Republican Cold War hawks like Pat
Buchanan. In the Washington Post last week, he wrote that ``America
must retrench and rearm,'' and not go ``marching into the Big
Muddy,'' a phrase last heard on the lips of Pete Seeger in the days
when anti-Vietnam demonstrators tried to levitate the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have opposed the Kosovo involvement from the start
include former Vice President Dan Quayle. On the other hand,
Elizabeth Dole visited refugee Albanians in Macedonia last week,
declaring, ``This is genocide'' and ``This is a war we must win.'`
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials expect Clinton to tread carefully through the
ground-force minefield at the three-day summit, which opens on
Friday in Washington. And many of his European partners will be
doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who voted against German defense
budgets in the early 1980s because of the American missile plans,
is now called ``the war chancellor'' by his Social Democratic
Party's left wing.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also put forward a detailed peace plan worked out by
another erstwhile peace movement activist, Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer, to bring Russia and the United Nations into the search for
a diplomatic settlement. The plan would suspend NATO bombing, 24
hours at a time, if Milosevic starts withdrawing forces from Kosovo
and lets the refugees go back.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder also got his European Union partners to offer to put
Kosovo under European protection in an eventual settlement, showing
that for all their solidarity, the European allies believe NATO
alone cannot impose a lasting solution in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's new generation of leaders are bombing Kosovo more
for moral reasons than for the classic Realpolitik aim of
preserving NATO's credibility in an unstable environment. Allied
leaders may endorse such a broad aim at their meeting, but their
greatest concern in Kosovo is bringing an end to the ordeal of the
refugees.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
