what Lyndon Johnson tried 35 years ago: Send in ground troops to do
what air power alone can't do, and win the war.
</P>
<P>
   All these ironies have rich and complex overtones.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton may be wary of being pushed down the slippery
slope of a ground war in Kosovo partly because some of the loudest
advocates of a stronger policy are the same political opponents who
tried to bring him down with impeachment earlier this year _ and
because he is aware of how destructive the Vietnam War proved to be
for Johnson's domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some of the loudest advocates of staying out
of Kosovo are conservative Republican Cold War hawks like Pat
Buchanan. In the Washington Post last week, he wrote that ``America
must retrench and rearm,'' and not go ``marching into the Big
Muddy,'' a phrase last heard on the lips of Pete Seeger in the days
when anti-Vietnam demonstrators tried to levitate the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have opposed the Kosovo involvement from the start
include former Vice President Dan Quayle. On the other hand,
Elizabeth Dole visited refugee Albanians in Macedonia last week,
declaring, ``This is genocide'' and ``This is a war we must win.'`
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials expect Clinton to tread carefully through the
ground-force minefield at the three-day summit, which opens on
Friday in Washington. And many of his European partners will be
doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who voted against German defense
budgets in the early 1980s because of the American missile plans,
is now called ``the war chancellor'' by his Social Democratic
Party's left wing.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also put forward a detailed peace plan worked out by
