<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2449 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ANTIWAR-REVIEW-N     04-17 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ANTIWAR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BRUSSELS: the refugees . 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the modern world, it seems, democracies go to war only for
moral war aims, but morality, like truth, can easily become the
first casualty. Incidents like the NATO bombing of a bridge last
week that accidentally killed Serb civilians on a train, or like
the mistakenly dropped bomb that killed Albanian refugees traveling
in a a convoy of vehicles, can test public support for the bombing,
and Clark is acutely aware of the danger. He has repeatedly
stressed that the allies are not trying to make war on civilians,
Serbs or Albanians. But innocent victims of the bombing are
inevitable the longer and more intense the air campaign becomes.
</P>
<P>
   Such jingoism as the allies muster depends mainly on having a
diabolic adversary. France's Gaullist president, Jacques Chirac, is
as hard as Clark on ``Milosevic,'' who doesn't even rate a ``Mr.''
from the French leader any more. ``The spirit of Munich,
isolationism and compromising have never brought anything but
misfortune,'' Chirac told the French last week in his third
television address on Kosovo, sounding for all the world like
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   The French Socialist prime minister, Lionel Jospin, like Chirac
a military veteran, pacified left-wing critics of the bombing,
including some within his own government, by saying that France was
not just slavishly following the American lead on Kosovo but
prosecuting the war in its own national and European interest.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most vehement of the allies are the British. Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, whose left-wing pacifist activities in the
1980s made American officials worry when Prime Minister Tony Blair
named him to the post, has become one of Albright's closest
friends.
</P>
<P>
   And Blair sounds positively Churchillian, in vehemence if not in
eloquence: ``There is not going to be a halt to the NATO action
until the demands that we have set out, which are entirely
reasonable, humane, civilized demands, are met in full,'' he said
last week. ``And the determination of the whole of not just Europe
but, I think, of the vast majority of people in the international
community to see this thing through is absolute.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are two things that all these European left-centrists
agree on. One is that sending ground troops into Kosovo, even in a
peacekeeping force, is not going to happen unless the United
Nations gives the alliance an explicit mandate to do so. That means
Russian acquiescence to an operation that probably would not be
feasible until a lot more bombing has taken its toll on the Serb
forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the present circumstances, the potential loss of life among
our service men and women, to say nothing of civilians, would be
considerable,'' Blair told Parliament last week.
</P>
<P>
   And the other is that Europe cannot forever go on depending on
the United States to deal with recurrent European crises like
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   So Clinton will probably be confronted in Washington with strong
calls by the allies, led by France and Britain, for the creation of
a strong and independent European defense pillar within the
alliance. Blair and Chirac agreed last year that Europe should have
an autonomous defense capability to ensure the stability of its own
back yard.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sea change for Britain, which in the past has seemed
to the French to be a NATO sycophant.
</P>
<P>
   Life is full of surprises these days, even in the alliance. ``I
never dreamed I would be spending my 51st birthday at a NATO
foreign ministers' conference,'' Fischer mused last Monday. But
there he was, and who ever would have thought it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
