<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2451 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONTEMPT-OF-COURT-REV     04-17 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTEMPT-OF-COURT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAW FIT FOR A KING ENSNARES A PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(jt) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the climactic scene of ``... And Justice for All,'' Al
Pacino, playing an idealistic young lawyer named Arthur Kirkland,
has to defend a distinguished judge accused of raping and battering
a young girl. Learning that his influential client is guilty and
has manipulated the system to get off, Pacino turns on him in the
courtroom, calling him ``a slime'' and declaring, ``If he's allowed
to go free, then something really wrong is going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   To which the presiding judge responds, `` Kirkland, you're out
of order!''
</P>
<P>
   Pacino, pointing at the judge and others, famously retorts:
``You're out of order! You're out of order! The whole trial is out
of order!''
</P>
<P>
   The chaos, which ends with bailiffs dragging Pacino out of the
courtroom, is not typical of the American judicial process. But it
is a cinematic reminder that contempt of court has a rich tradition
in American law.
</P>
<P>
   Last week brought a notable anomaly in this tradition of public
defiance over principle, a judge's contempt citation against
President Clinton for giving ``false, misleading and evasive
answers'' in the Paula Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald L. Goldfarb, author of ``The Contempt Power'' (Columbia
University, 1963), said that most of the great legal struggles of
the century _ over civil rights, anti-war protests, McCarthyism,
the labor movement _ grew from contempt citations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contempt is really the crucible within which the great issues
of the times have been thrashed out,'' Goldfarb said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyer William M. Kunstler was cited for contempt by
Judge Julius J. Hoffman in the 1969 trial of the Chicago 7
political dissidents, and sentenced to four years and 13 days for
his tactics, but this was hardly a stain on his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wore the Chicago contempt as a badge of honor because in
those cases he was standing up to tyranny,'' said Ronald L. Kuby,
his longtime partner and protege.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was speaking truth to power, as opposed to Clinton, who was
speaking lies to the powerless,'' Kuby said.
</P>
<P>
   Such cases are seen as acts of civil disobedience, efforts to
convey a political message, said Stephen Gillers, professor of
legal ethics at New York University School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's act as a defendant was different, he said. ``He didn't
do something notoriously, publicly. He did it secretly and was
discovered.''
</P>
<P>
   In the practice of law today, most lawyers see resisting a court
order as something that should be reserved for only the most
extraordinary cases.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Tribe, professor of constitutional law at Harvard Law
School, said, ``The only circumstance in which I can imagine
thinking it to be a badge of honor would be a case in which the
judicial order clearly violates fundamental human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s defiance of a
court order prohibiting a civil rights march in Birmingham in 1963,
which landed him in jail. Although it was clear that the statute
being enforced was invalid, the Supreme Court affirmed the
conviction, Tribe said, ``essentially saying that you can't take
the law in your own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts trace the contempt power back to English common law and
the notion that the king could do no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic notion was that the courts acted for the king,''
Goldfarb said, ``and someone in the presence of the court was in
the presence of the alter ego of the king, and was therefore worthy
of summary punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   In trials with political overtones, the contempt power
illustrates the adversarial tension between judicial authority and
its challengers, but its main purpose in the American system is to
maintain the orderly administration of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Susan Webber Wright cited the president for civil
contempt, a tool that is generally used by judges to compel, say, a
reluctant witness to testify in a court proceeding, by threatening
jail if he continues to refuse. Or it can be used to force a
company or union to obey a court order, or face a large daily fine.
</P>
<P>
   Judges may also file a criminal contempt charge to punish a
violation that has already occurred. Some commentators last week
suggested that Clinton would have been more appropriately charged
with criminal contempt, since the Jones case is over.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, both forms are used, as in the case of Susan
McDougal, who served 18 months in jail for civil contempt after she
refused to cooperate with investigators for Kenneth Starr and
refused to answer questions put to her before a grand jury. Then,
last May, after finishing her jail sentence, she was charged with
criminal contempt and obstruction of justice. Last week, a jury in
Arkansas acquitted her of the obstruction charge, while failing to
reach a verdict on the contempt charges, leading the judge to
declare a mistrial on those counts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal saw her resistance as a principled stand against
politically motivated pressure from Starr. Some lawyers said this
week that had Clinton wanted to take a more principled stand, he
could have refused to answer questions in his Jones deposition,
rather than offer misleading answers.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the case may simply show that lawyers and defendants like
Clinton are capable of what Tribe calls ``garden variety and not
terribly noble forms of defiance in which they are trying to get
away with something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3821 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONTEMPT-OF-COURT-REV     04-17 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTEMPT-OF-COURT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LAW FIT FOR A KING ENSNARES A PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
