<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2454 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIND-HEALTH-REVIEW-2T     04-17 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIND-HEALTH-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU'RE MIND MAY EASE WHAT'S AILING YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(jt) 
 By ERICA GOODE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Medical science, focused on curing the ills of the body, has
often treated the mind like an annoying younger brother: a presence
to be ignored whenever possible, humored when unavoidable and used
as a scapegoat when the need arises.
</P>
<P>
   What modern medicine, until recently, has not done, in any
systematic fashion, is to view mental and physical process as
inextricably entwined. Though most paid homage to the importance of
treating the ``whole patient,'' medical scientists by and large
have remained faithful to Descartes' conception of mind-body
dualism, dutifully dividing the psychiatric from the physical. They
accepted that patients often respond emotionally to physical
disease. But doctors have largely disdained the possibility that
emotional state _ be it anxiety, anger or optimism _ might itself
alter the course of a physical illness, or that treating
psychological distress might improve physical health.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, it has become increasingly clear that to take
a strictly Cartesian view is problematic. For one thing, such a
view does not make room for the growing number of studies appearing
in mainstream medical journals that demonstrate the impact of
psychology on physiology. Most recently, researchers reported last
week in the Journal of the American Medical Association that
writing about traumatic experiences measurably improved the health
of some patients with chronic asthma or rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Of 70 patients in the study who spent 20 minutes on each of
three consecutive days writing about ``the most stressful
experience they had ever undergone,'' 47.1 percent showed
significant improvement on objective measures of disease severity
four months later, compared to 24.3 percent who improved in a
control group. The findings will have to be replicated by other
researchers, and many questions were left unanswered: How could a
simple writing exercise have such a substantial impact on patients'
health four months later? What factors make it more likely that an
individual patient will benefit from such a treatment?
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is difficult not to conclude, as Dr. David Spiegel,
associate chairman of psychiatry and behavioral sciences at
Stanford University, did in an editorial accompanying the study,
that ``the authors have provided evidence that medical treatment is
more effective when standard pharmacological intervention is
combined with the management of emotional distress.'' In this study
and others, he noted, ``it is not simply mind over matter, but it
is clear that mind matters.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1989 article in the British journal Lancet Spiegel and his
colleagues reported longer survival rates for breast cancer
survivors who took part in support groups emphasizing emotional
expression and active coping skills. Other researchers have
reported comparable findings for melanoma and lymphoma patients,
though three studies failed to find that psychosocial support
lengthened survival for cancer patients. A 1988 study by a team led
by Dr. Jon Kabat-Zinn found that meditation, a stress-reduction
technique, increased rates of improvement in psoriasis patients who
were also receiving standard medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Equally intriguing are studies that tackle the mind-body
equation by finding links between severe stress and illnesses. A
large study published last year found that people who suffered
abuse in childhood, had a parent who was alcoholic, an addict or a
battered woman, or endured other stressful situations, were two to
four times more likely to suffer serious illnesses like heart
disease, emphysema, and stroke than other adults. The frequency of
disorders, the researchers reported, increased with the number of
``adverse childhood experiences'' a person had been exposed to.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists have found that veterans with post-traumatic
stress disorder also were more likely to suffer from a variety of
severe maladies, including heart disease and diseases of the
respiratory, digestive and musculoskeletal system than were
veterans without the stress disorder. An artificial division
between conditions that belong to ``psychiatry'' and those that
belong to ``medicine'' is ``nonsense,'' said Dr. Matthew Friedman,
executive director of the National Center for Post-Traumatic Stress
Disorder, ``because stress is something that happens to the brain.
It's not something in the ether that happens to the mind. Stress is
very real. It has lots of medical effects. It also has
psychological effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuroscientists, who are slowly unraveling the complex
interrelationship of genetics, chemistry and cellular function in
the brain, seem considerably more comfortable jettisoning the
dualism of Descartes than many clinicians in routine medical
specialities. With the help of new tools, including PET and MRI
scanning, gene knockouts and other technologies, they are revealing
the brain as much more plastic than was once thought. Brain
chemistry and structure, studies have shown, may be altered by
``psychological'' experiences, including learning and stress.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a much more integrated view of human functioning.
``We now realize that the brain is a lot more involved in governing
many different functions in the body,'' says Dr. Bruce McEwen,
director of the laboratory of endocrinology at Rockefeller
University and an expert on stress. ``Appetite, sleep, food intake,
emotions, health-promoting and self-destructive behaviors _ all
these things are both controlled by and in turn influence the
brain.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
