<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2458 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-PROPS-REVIE     04-17 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-PROPS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL PROPS AND CAMPAIGNS THAT TAKE OFF, OR CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(jt) 
 By DAVID WALLIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week in Washington, the Titanic was involved in another
disaster. Just before advocates for senior citizens planned to
hoist on stage a 24-foot cabin cruiser bearing the slogan
``Medicare Vouchers Are a Titanic Mistake,'' the Capitol Police
sunk their efforts. Judging the symbolic Titanic too heavy for the
stage, authorities banished it to the side, thereby depriving Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy and other speakers of a camera-friendly backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge disappointment,'' lamented the rally's
organizer, Patrick Burns, director of communication at the National
Council for Senior Citizens. ``Most people would rather have their
teeth pulled than read a story about Medicare, so we have to
present a story: If you are well-to-do, the voucher becomes a
subsidy that you can use to buy yourself into a lifeboat. If you
are a poor, working-class stiff with a fixed income like most
seniors, you're in steerage.''
</P>
<P>
   American politicians and protesters increasingly rely on
political props (or visuals, in spin-doctor lingo) to dramatize
complex policies, razz adversaries or snag a few seconds on the
evening news. Ross Perot-style charts and candlelight vigils no
longer make the cut when network news shows must compete for
viewers with niche cable channels and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television is not a news medium _ it's an entertainment
medium,'' noted Michael Deaver, President Reagan's legendary
prop-master. ``People have become increasingly sophisticated about
what they will or will not stop on.''
</P>
<P>
   Deaver, famous for promoting the presidential practice of
saluting citizen heroes _ human props _ at State of the Union
Addresses, recalled a rare Reagan speech at a B-1 bomber factory,
rare because Deaver avoided military backdrops.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a perception that Reagan was more likely to get us
into a war,'' he said. ``In '84, they convinced me that 40,000 jobs
in California depended on the B-1 bomber. That was the only event
we did that was military in nature. But we draped the plane with a
sign that read: `Prepared for Peace.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Rep. Jim Nussle of Iowa didn't need high-priced
military hardware to draw attention to colleagues who bounced House
checks; he placed a paper bag over his head to symbolize his shame.
``It was the most impactful speech I've ever given,'' recalled
Nussle. ``I've spoken about a number of other important topics like
rural health care and agriculture. Boy, no one has ever heard
those.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before CNN, leaders understood the power of the prop. King
Solomon grasped a baby to show his even-handedness. And in American
history, the tradition goes back to pre-Revolutionary times, when
patriots held mock funerals for Lady Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   William Henry Harrison was one of the first politicians to play
with props, drinking hard cider from a wooden barrel and posing in
front of log cabins at campaign rallies during the 1840
presidential contest, now known as the Log Cabin campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harrison was very old, so the Democrats considered him a
pretty weak candidate,'' said Sean Wilentz, a professor of history
at Princeton. ``One guy in a Baltimore newspaper wrote that they
ought to pension off granny Harrison so he can go back to his log
cabin and drink cider. The Whigs picked up on that and said `Aha!
Harrison is a man of the people!' and turned the log cabin and
cider into popular symbols.''
</P>
<P>
   But like faulty grenades, props can explode in a candidate's
face. In 1988, Michael Dukakis, who looked more like a driving
instructor than a gunnery sergeant, climbed atop a tank and crushed
his chances at victory. TV news played the clip of the tank ride
over and over, reinforcing the faux pas. Four years later, George
Bush stumbled badly. To combat the notion he lacked the common
touch, he shopped at a Wal-Mart, only to betray astonishment at the
invention of the checkout scanner. Both candidates flouted the
Deaver rule of prop management: ``Don't use anything that's
inconsistent with the candidate or what's being said, or the
history and character of the person.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, politicians seem to have learned little from these
legendary goofs. Rep. Dan Burton of Indiana fired a shotgun in his
yard at a head-shaped object (believed to be a pumpkin) to
determine whether Vincent Foster was murdered. And last month,
Senator Dianne Feinstein Dukakis-ized herself, brandishing a
menacing-looking assault weapon at a press conference to highlight
her support for gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The sideshow atmosphere in Washington rankles Rich Noyes of the
Center for Media and Public Affairs. ``The dangerous thing for
society would be when we start to pay more attention to the
politicians with the good props than the politicians with the good
arguments,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   With elections approaching, voters can expect to see more props
repeated endlessly thanks to the eight-second picture-bite. At the
least, one politician has gotten the message about the importance
of staying on message when it comes to props. In 1996, Lamar
Alexander wore his trademark red-and-black plaid shirt constantly,
often looking un-presidential. This time he plans to keep his
wardrobe as conservative as his politics. ``My main goal,''
Alexander announced, ``will be to get the voters to pay more
attention to my beliefs and message and not to any prop I might
bring along.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment heartens Wilentz. ``Props don't add to the
dignity of American politics,'' said Wilentz, ``but then again,
American politics have rarely been known for dignity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
