<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3850 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-POLICY-REVIEW     04-17 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-POLICY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FOREIGN POLICY: ATTENTION TO KOSOVO, INATTENTION TO CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(jt) 
 &HT;     
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In their new book ``Preventative Defense,'' former
Defense Secretary William Perry and a former Pentagon colleague,
Ashton Carter, argue that 10 years into the post-Cold War,
Washington forgets that some nations matter a lot more than others.
</P>
<P>
   There is a short ``A list'' of nations that could some day pose
a threat to ``the survival or way of life of Americans'' _ a Russia
that goes the way of Weimar Germany, or a China that becomes a
hostile superpower.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is a well-stocked ``B list'' of ``imminent threats to
U.S. interests,'' including the fractious Persian Gulf states and
North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   And finally comes the ``C list,'' which the authors say is
composed of ``the Kosovos, Bosnias, Somalias, Rwandas and Haitis''
_ all urgent, but places where American interests are usually hard
to define.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, it sounds reasonable and orderly. But the C list looms
vivid on live TV, making it all-consuming for Washington while far
less dramatic A list problems are put on the back burner.
</P>
<P>
   And that appears to be exactly what happened over the last 10
days as China's savvy prime minister, Zhu Rongji, drove up to the
White House ready to resolve one of the most complex issues in
Sino-American relations _ a huge trade deal that is really about
China's influence in the world and America's influence on China.
Problem was, he arrived at a moment when a president who has
pressed ``engagement'' with China was elsewhere engaged.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a weeklong White House fumble that left the
Chinese angry, the president embarrassed, the business community
enraged and Congress confused. In the end, Zhu left the United
States with a hastily telephoned assurance from Clinton that China
would get into the World Trade Organization this year, with
American blessing, if China kept its promises and gave a bit more.
But the whole messy handling of China's premier reformer left some
administration officials wondering whether this White House can
bomb Belgrade and negotiate with Beijing at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a classic case of distraction,'' one White House
official conceded late last week, trying to explain why the White
House had to issue three separate joint statements with Zhu in five
days.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, the man bringing market reforms to China even as millions
wander the countryside unemployed, decided earlier this year that
China was either going to get globalized fast or get lost in the
race. ``Either we look like Singapore or we look like Russia,'' one
of his aides commented recently. ``And that's not a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   So Zhu offered market-opening concessions in agriculture,
telecommunications, banking, insurance and other industries that go
far beyond what most American officials thought possible. And the
morning of his arrival here, Clinton made the strongest case yet
for ushering China into the World Trade Organization, arguing it
would not only mean billions for American firms, but that it would
bring the rule of law to China. And, breaking new ground, he argued
that an economically weak China was far more dangerous to America
than a strong China.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, though, Clinton walked away from the deal, at least
for the time being. China had not given enough, his aides argued.
He was worried, his advisers say, that the Democratic left, backed
by the unions, would kill off any deal once they allied with
conservatives saying there should be no deal with a China that
steals nuclear secrets and represses dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critical middle that you need to support a deal like this
is shrinking,'' said Commerce Secretary William Daley, explaining
why the White House needed what he called ``a bulletproof deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But in trade, nothing's bulletproof. American textile makers
will never like a deal that lets China expand its presence in the
American market. Nor will steel makers, or steel unions. Many in
Congress argue that China has no intention of fulfilling its
market-opening promises. But the vast majority of big businesses
say that if Clinton doesn't sign soon, the huge gains made in many
areas will be eaten away as soon as Zhu returns to Beijing and
faces bureaucrats screaming: ``You gave away what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes this such a critical moment,'' said Edward
S. Steinfeld, a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology who has studied China's state-owned enterprises. ``This
agreement puts tremendous pressure on China to change its
industrial structure, and to some degree its politics. It will be
painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the question is, how can you say that you want a
market-based China, enmeshed in a global legal system, and walk
away from this?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
