<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, April 18:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Questions or reruns: (888) 346-9867. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The day supervisor is Ned Kilkelly.
</P>
<P>
   The late supervisor is Henry Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Technical problems: &LR;  Peter Trigg.
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (212) 499-3332.
</P>
<P>
   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Coded `i')
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DECISIONS (Undated) _ January 19th is already seen as a
pivotal day in the Clinton presidency. But it may turn out to be so
less for the Senate impeachment hearings and State of the Union
address than for the moves toward war over Kosovo. The Times
reconstructs the decisions by the Clinton administration that led
to NATO's bombing campaign in Yugoslavia. Written by Elaine
Sciolino and Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Brussels, Belgium) _ Developments. By Craig R.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Politics makes strange bedfellows. Then
there is Russian politics, which seemed this week hellbent on the
downright weird: a menage a trois of Russia, Belarus and
Yugoslavia, bedding a wobbly democracy, a Soviet-style dictatorship
and an international pariah three borders removed from either of
them in death-do-we-part union. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (Paris) _ Responding to complaints from the U.N.
war crimes tribunal in The Hague, the United States and Britain
have pledged to provide more information to prosecutors that may
enable them to indict the top Yugoslav civilian and military
leadership. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Skopje, Macedonia) _ The Kosovo Liberation Army
is proving stubbornly resistant despite the Serbian forces' massive
offensive. For example, although wounded on March 24, their
31-year-old commander, who goes by the name of Axhaika, continued
leading his troops for another 10 days before heading out for
treatment. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-OPINION (Washington) _ The war for public opinion in the
Balkans, waged through a taut control over information and an
assiduously managed dissemination of it, entered a new, more
intense phase this week. Reports that NATO had inadvertently bombed
civilians led Yugoslav authorities to suddenly whisk reporters on a
selective tour of ambiguous carnage and NATO officials to give
newly painstaking explanations about how airstrikes were conducted.
By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INTERNATIONAL (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POLITICS (New Delhi) _ The Hindu nationalist-led
government that turned India into a declared nuclear power
collapsed Saturday. It lost a vote of confidence by a margin of 269
to 270, the narrowest parliamentary defeat for a government in
independent India's 51 year history. The opposition, now led by
Sonia Gandhi, the Italian-born widow of an assassinated prime
minister, will now try to cobble together a new government. By
Celia Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-HEALTH-CARE (London) _ The waiting list for treatment
through Britain's National Health Service appears to be growing
precipitously, even as the Labor government says the wait is
shrinking. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Pinarbasi, Turkey) _ After a campaign that has
been distinctly short on enthusiasm, few Turks expect the elections
Sunday to lift the political paralysis into which their country has
fallen. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-STREET-MARKETS (Beijing) _ The demolition of hundreds of
street markets this spring is officially described as part of a
``beautification'' program as Beijing prepares for celebration of
the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic on
Oct. 1. But it is also part of a master plan to cut the number of
rural migrants living and working in the city. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL-ROOMS (Undated) _ Private rooms in hospitals were once
only for those affluent patients willing to pay as much as $300 a
day extra, but now a growing number of hospitals are eliminating
shared rooms and offering all patients their own rooms, often at no
extra charge. The shift is largely a byproduct of the revolution
wrought by managed care. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-TEEN-SURVIVORS (New York) _ Because of medical advances,
many children born with HIV are thriving into their teens and
beyond. And as these children grow, the normally turbulent issues
of youth _ like dating and independence _ are colliding with their
chronic terminal illness in ways that their families never
envisioned when the children were babies. By Lynda Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-WOMEN (Undated) _ Sarah A. Gavit, 37, is leading an
invasion of Mars. Built under her direction are two craft now
speeding toward a December rendezvous with the red planet to help
see if it harbors life. Her top aides are also women; they are all
pioneers pushing back frontiers of inquiry, technology and gender.
By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-WASTE-FIGHT (Skull Valley Goshute Reservation, Utah) _
The tiny Skull Valley Band of the Goshute tribe has signed a
50-year lease with eight electric companies to use 840 of the
reservation's 18,000 acres to store more than half the nation's
nuclear waste. But Governor Michael O. Leavitt, who grew up
downwind of atmospheric nuclear tests, says he will do whatever it
takes to stop the plan. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   FLYING-UPSIDE-DOWN (Denver) _ United and other airlines are
starting to train their pilots on what to do when a jumbo jet rolls
nearly upside down, even though that is such a rare event that the
lesson may seem pointlessly exotic. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   UNEARTHED-BORDELLO (Washington) _ Archeologists have happened
upon the historically tantalizing story of Mary Ann Hall, a
determined 20-something who built and managed one of this city's
finest 19th-century bordellos. Her three-story brick house
flourished for four decades just down from Capitol Hill _ a
monument, in its way, to capital power and sex but also to a level
of discretion that seems rare in modern Washington. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BUDGET (Washington) _ Congress tells itself year after
year to craft a budget carefully and stick to it when spending the
tax money Americans send in. Last year, it failed miserably, but
this year could be worse, many members say. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   PARKS-POLLUTION (Washington) _ As part of regulations that could
be announced by President Clinton as early as Thursday, which is
Earth Day, states will be asked to assess the haze problems in
national parks and wilderness areas and submit plans for cleanup
strategies by 2008. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary by Bob Herbert on the case
of Lacresha Murray, a teen-ager imprisoned in Texas for the beating
death of a 2{-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Commentary by Maureen Dowd on Hillary
Rodham Clinton's plan to write a book on the joys of entertaining
and decorating.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving later: &LR;
</P>
