<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2462 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-17 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS HIGHLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Loss for Starr in the McDougal Case ...
</P>
<P>
   The once-sprawling investigation by Kenneth Starr, the
Whitewater prosecutor, wound down and its Arkansas phase appeared
to end on a note of defeat when an Arkansas jury acquitted Susan
McDougal of obstruction of justice. The jury deadlocked on the two
remaining counts of criminal contempt, and the judge declared a
mistrial on those charges. The case stemmed from Ms. McDougal's
refusal to testify about President and Mrs. Clinton's financial
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   ... And Some Questions From the Senate
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Starr defended his prosecutorial tactics and
judgment in the investigation of the Lewinsky matter and reacted
indignantly when senators referred to him as a legal zealot. During
more than three hours before the Senate Governmental Affairs
Committee, which is considering changes in the independent counsel
law, Starr insisted he had followed Justice Department rules.
</P>
<P>
   And when Starr announced that he opposed reauthorizing the
statute that had created his multipronged inquiry, Democrats
expressed incredulity.
</P>
<P>
   Tougher Rules Planned for Sport Utility Vehicles
</P>
<P>
   Large sport utility vehicles and pickup trucks may not be
allowed to go on emitting several times as much pollution as cars.
The Clinton administration is in the final stages of drafting rules
that would tighten emissions standards for cars, minivans, small
sport utility vehicles and small pickups by 2007 and would require
large sport utility vehicles and pickups to meet the new, more
stringent standards by 2009.
</P>
<P>
   To help automakers do this, the administration will also require
oil companies to sell much cleaner gasoline. All of this could mean
cleaner air but slightly more expensive gas and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   For Campaign Finance, Another Push
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance overhaul hit an unyielding gauntlet of
Republican opposition last year and promised to be met by the same
obstacles this time around, but that did not stop House Democrats
from taking up the cause once again. They launched a petition drive
to force Republican leaders in the House to allow, in the next few
months, a vote on an overhaul bill.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to get the ball rolling earlier, so that it might
gather enough velocity to break through barriers of resistance. But
its momentum was stalling and its fate uncertain by the end of the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Kevorkian Gets 10 to 25 in Assisted Suicide Case
</P>
<P>
   Saying the law does not bluff, a Michigan judge meted out a
10-to-25-year sentence to Dr. Jack Kevorkian, who had dared the
courts to jail him for giving a lethal injection to a terminally
ill man. The death of Thomas Youk, who suffered from amyotrophic
lateral sclerosis, or Lou Gehrig's disease, was broadcast on a
television program last fall. The man's widow and brother issued
emotional courtroom appeals on behalf of Kevorkian. But the judge,
Jessica Cooper, said Kevorkian had no right to take the law into
his own hands. ``Consider yourself stopped,'' she told him.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle Tries Again
</P>
<P>
   Announcing his candidacy for the Republican presidential
nomination, former Vice President Dan Quayle declared, ``I will
lead the fight for our values _ and our families.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, returning to electoral politics nearly seven years after
he and President Bush were defeated, touched on his proposal for a
tax cut and recalled his foreign policy experience. But his
overriding message was that after ``a dishonest decade'' of the
Clinton-Gore administration, he would restore values to the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   A Medicaid Gap
</P>
<P>
   A side effect of the 47 percent drop in welfare rolls has been
an increase in the number of low-income people who have lost their
Medicaid and have no other health insurance. Almost everyone who
leaves welfare for work is entitled to keep Medicaid, but studies
show that some states have improperly discouraged people from
seeking it.
</P>
<P>
   Another Solar System
</P>
<P>
   We are not alone _ we as in the solar system. Astronomers had
long assumed that some star out there had the requisite planets in
regular orbit, but now it's official. Our solar fellow, spotted by
two different teams, is called Upsilon Andromedae and is 44
light-years away. In the words of one scientist, ``This is exciting
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   World's Richest Babysitter
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gabrieli, a Boston venture capitalist, discovered that his
live-in babysitter was a multi-millionaire like him. The
babysitter, a 54-year-old Chilean immigrant named Maria J. Grasso,
told Gabrieli's wife, Hilary, who then told him, that she had won
the $197 million Big Game jackpot, the largest lottery prize ever
won by one person in the United States. ``I'm a very down-to-earth
person,'' Mrs. Grasso said at a news conference, with the Gabrielis
beaming nearby. ``I work hard in my entire life. I'm one of six
children, and so I always try to be low, down-key, and I'm going to
continue that way.'' Mrs. Grasso chose a lump sum payment of $104
million _ $70,244,814 after taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
