<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3855 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITEHOUSE-MEMOIRS-TE     04-17 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE-MEMOIRS-TEXT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MAN'S MEMORY IS ANOTHER'S MEMOIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(jt) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Political memoirs are like the film ``Rashomon,'' in which an
experience is transmogrified by sharply different memories. Case in
point: George Stephanopoulos' ``All Too Human: A Political
Education'' (Little, Brown) versus Dick Morris' ``Behind the Oval
Office: Getting Re-Elected Against All Odds'' (Renaissance). The
books often convey utterly dissimilar points of view, reflecting
the cutthroat infighting that prevailed when their authors were
advisers to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, they maintain a mutual non-admiration society
regarding their respective works. Stephanopolous called ``Behind
the Oval Office'' ``more than 300 pages of the rooster taking
credit for the dawn,'' while Morris wrote that ``All Too Human'' is
``the most gripping tale of a man's successful battle against his
conscience since Albert Speer's cliffhanger, `Inside the Third
Reich.'''
</P>
<P>
   No, Morris and Stephanopoulos didn't have a lot in common. Here
are contrasting excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Before serving in the White House, both underwent background
checks. Questioned by Webster Hubbell, the Clinton aide,
Stephanopoulos had a tough time sounding like anything other than
the ex-altar boy he once was:  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After racking my brain ... I even told Webb about the night
before I left for college, when I went out egging cars with my high
school buddies one last time.
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Morris _ later to endure the disclosure of his
affair with a prostitute _ already had a piquant resume:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I had a lot to hide. I had fathered a daughter by a woman to
whom I was not married and I knew that were I to become well known,
the story could eventually leak out.
</P>
<P>
   Early in my tenure with Clinton, Erskine Bowles (the chief of
staff) approached me and asked that I tell him anything ``the
president needs to know'' about my past. Determined not to mislead
the president, I told him about my daughter, and said that I paid
$4,000 a month for child support.
 &UR; When Morris and Stephanopoulos first met over dinner at a
Washington restaurant in May 1995, Morris thought Stephanopoulos
wasn't that bad of a guy:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Over his whiskey and my cognac, the conversation loosened, and I
felt a warmth toward him that continues still ... His intensity
matched mine, and our skills were complementary.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Yet the feeling wasn't mutual. Stephanopoulos on Morris at the same
dinner:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   He was a small sausage of a man encased in a green suit with
wide lapels, a wide floral tie, and a wide-collared shirt. His
blow-dried pompadour and shiny leather briefcase gave him the look
of a B-movie mob lawyer, circa 1975 _ the kind of guy who gets
brained with a baseball bat for double-crossing his boss. But his
outfit was offset by the flush of power on his pasty face ...
</P>
<P>
   I noticed at once that Dick was missing a gene: He literally had
no shame.
 &UR; After the Democrats' disastrous 1994 loss of Congress, Morris, ever
the poll-oriented guru, groped for a way for President Clinton to
retake the political stage:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I blurted out the strategy I proposed in a single word:
triangulate. I found myself shaping my fingers into a triangle,
with my thumbs joined at the base and my forefingers raised to meet
a point at the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Triangulate, create a third position, not just in between the
old positions of the two parties but above them as well.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   I saw triangulation as a way to change, not abandon, the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; But for Stephanopoulos, triangulation was an abdication of
principles:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Dick explained his theory in elaborate terms, but it boiled down
to a relatively simple proposition: Steal the popular-sounding
parts of the Republican platform, sign them into law, and you'll
win. The fact that it would anger Democrats was not a drawback, but
a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Morris was self-effacing about his role in foreign policy:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One day I asked Clinton what role he wanted me to play in
foreign policy. His instructions were strict, and I followed them
closely: ``Never talk to me about foreign policy in the presence of
a third person. Always do it one-on-one with me.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   I began to consult outside experts and to channel their advice
directly to the president ... From my role as a conduit, I learned
how Clinton gradually put his own stap on foreign policy, making it
 &UR; his  &LR; policy ...
 &UR; But Stephanopoulos credits his nemesis with considerably more
influence:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Bad enough that he was wreaking havoc with domestic policy. On
national security matters, ad hoc decisions could be dangerous, and
his involvement would open the president up to attack for turning
to an amoral pollster on matters of war and peace. In May, after
Morris tried to end run the NSC (National Security Council) and
rewrite U.S. policy on terrorism and trade with Japan, Tony Lake
(the national security adviser) had gone to Clinton and secured his
commitment that Morris would be walled off from the national
security policy-making process. But by July, Dick was on a power
jag. He was building his campaign empire, and he had the run of the
government ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Morris and Stephanopoulos even disagree about Clinton's ability to
handle criticism. According to Morris:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants to be challenged, Subordinates who give way
unnerve him.
</P>
<P>
   If in the first five minutes after you meet Clinton, you don't
mention something he's done wrong, you've lost him. He's bored by
what he's doing right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Yet Stephanopoulos' old boss didn't appreciate negative reviews of
his Marlon Brando imitation on ``Larry King Live'':  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As the president cheerfully removed his makeup with a Handi
Wipe, he asked me how it had gone. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You avoided any  &UR; big &LR;  mistakes, but, umh ... you know ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You may get a little too much attention on this Brando thing.
It was a  &UR; good &LR;  Brando, probably too good. The morning shows won't
be able to resist it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton screwed up his face as if I'd just served him sour milk
and turned away in search of a second opinion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Self-serving though the memoirs may be, neither author claims
infallibility. Morris got flak in 1995 for suggesting that
according to his polls, a camping vacation for the president would
play well with swing voters:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was not happy. This was carrying things too far. ``Can I
golf?'' he asked in a question dripping with sarcasm. ``Maybe if I
wear a baseball cap?'' he bargained ...
</P>
<P>
   He began to pose hypotheticals. ``What if I hike, set up my
campsite, and go fishing but I don't catch anything? Will that be
OK?''
</P>
<P>
   I deserved the ribbing. This advice was the ultimate in carrying
polling to a mindless extreme.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stephanopoulos found himself ``a wreck'' in 1993 when the
president's TelePrompter, which was supposed to unspool a major
health care address, instead showed the last State of the Union
address:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This screwup might not have been my fault, but it was my
responsibility. ``This is the worst thing that's ever happened,'' I
muttered. ``I dunno,'' replied Mike Feldman, the vice president's
aide, ``the Holocaust was pretty bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
