<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 12:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2469 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-17 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: COLD, COLD HEARTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I sense the hidden hand of Harold Ickes.
</P>
<P>
   It is just too delicious, too dripping with irony, not to be an
idea that Harold and Hillary concocted one night with a full moon,
laughing maniacally and munching on Ickes' favorite canape, Ritz
crackers and peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   Surely they cooked up this ``First Hostess'' how-to book in a
deeply Machiavellian moment as a strategy for the New York Senate
campaign, a way to outpace the workaholic mayor with swing-voting
soccer moms upstate and life-style-obsessed yuppies in Manhattan. I
hope so. Otherwise, it is plain weird.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster announced that Hillary Clinton _ she who
bridled at the term first lady, she who bristled at the thought of
staying home and baking cookies, she who preached two for the price
of one, she who brazenly reverted to Rodham once the coast was
clear, she who insisted on being in the West Wing with the boys,
she who went boldly where no president's wife had gone before and
hijacked vast precincts of social and legal policy _ will produce a
book on the joys of entertaining and decorating.
</P>
<P>
   In ``An Invitation to the White House,'' the Simon &AMP; Schuster
press release gushes: ``Mrs. Clinton will discuss the challenges
and pleasures of being the First Hostess; how she has showcased the
best of American design, cuisine and culture; how changes in the
type of food and style of service have been initiated; and how she
has increased the number and diversity of people who enjoy the
hospitality of the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   It was better when Mrs. Clinton was channeling Eleanor
Roosevelt. Eleanor was a more natural soulmate for her than Martha
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The publishers are not at all troubled by the fact that the
esthetic and cultural standards of the Clinton White House have
been abysmally low. Kaki Hockersmith, the Little Rock decorator who
redid the White House in High Hot Springs, will help with the book.
</P>
<P>
   It's insulting that Mrs. Clinton is using her waning days in
power to chirp about matching the color of the roses to the rim of
the china.
</P>
<P>
   After the anguished year of Monica, you'd think the Clintons
would spend quiet time on true things.
</P>
<P>
   A book nattering about how delightful that Clinton hearth is _
when we know how strained it is _ brings to mind old British
movies, where characters make insipid, incessant small talk to
cover up something awful going on.
</P>
<P>
   When guests go to the White House now, they are not marveling at
what Simon &AMP; Schuster calls its warmth, elegance and innovation.
They are checking to see whether Hillary can muster an adoring look
for her husband, or whether she attempts to avoid him as they work
the room.
</P>
<P>
   The book will include more than 30 recipes. But we know that her
life's interest is not Gingered Pheasant Consomme and Blue Cheese
Fritters. Her most dog-eared recipes are Bill in a Stew, Seared
Husband, Grilled Staffers and Glazed USA.
</P>
<P>
   She is creating a Potemkin hearth, where she is the comfy, bring
the prez his socks-and-slippers first lady, rather than an
emotionally battered wife and celebrity victim doing a
county-by-county analysis of New York politics.
</P>
<P>
   This first lady is not chic, like Jackie Kennedy. She is not
anti-chic, like Barbara Bush. She just doesn't live in that
universe. She lives in a bleaker universe without wallpaper or
table placement, where she is, as her staffers say, a warrior.
</P>
<P>
   When she stoops to playing wifey, inviting gossip columnists for
lunch, writing a book about Buddy and Socks, posing for a Vogue
glamour cover the same month her husband was impeached, heralding a
book on the cozy hearth after she failed to come home from North
Africa when the president began stumbling through a war, it comes
across as counterfeit.
</P>
<P>
   She keeps remaking and remaking herself. There was a time when
if you asked about Hillary's style, her best friend, Susan
Thomases, would bite your head off. Hillary was supposed to be
spine, while Bill was no spine. She was supposed to be the
conscience for his agile, flexible, fallible self. Now, like her
husband, she tries to be all things to all people, but it just
makes her seem unformed. It is unsettling, and unentertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Hillary Clinton is that we don't know her
placement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
