<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-ART-N     04-17 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKS YAWN AT VOTE AS ISSUES FESTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINARBASI, Turkey _ Like a visiting celebrity, Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem drew a crowd of a couple of hundred people before the
local police station this week when he stopped in this cow town in
central Anatolia to appeal for votes.
</P>
<P>
   But the applause was perfunctory in a campaign that has been
short on enthusiasm, as few Turks expect the elections Sunday to
lift the political paralysis into which their country has fallen.
</P>
<P>
   One Istanbul newspaper captured the public mood with a
front-page headline that asked: ``Why Are We Holding These
Elections?''
</P>
<P>
   Cem pledged that if re-elected he and his mentor, Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit, would work together for more jobs, better education
and health care for all.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by the capture of the Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah
Ocalan, Ecevit appears to be running strong. But even if his party
finishes first, it will almost certainly take less than 25 percent
of the vote. That would force it to assemble a coalition with one
or more other parties.
</P>
<P>
   The next government, then, whether or not Ecevit heads it, will
probably have no ideological cohesion and will find it difficult or
impossible to come up with strong measures to confront Turkey's
central problems, particularly the Kurdish insurrection in the
east. Most voters are acutely aware of those frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey has been politically adrift since the last election in
1995. That election produced an Islamic-led government that so
upset secularist military commanders that they forced it from
office after one year. The government that was installed in its
place also proved unable to survive, and after it collapsed in
November, Ecevit took over as a caretaker to lead the country to
early elections.
</P>
<P>
   This year's campaign has been distinguished by its silence on
pressing issues. There has been little debate about ways to expand
democracy and increase respect for human rights, and even less
about how religious and secular impulses in Turkish society can be
harmonized. Most remarkable of all, the Kurdish war that has been
tearing at the national fabric for a decade and a half has barely
been mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a problem has dragged on for 15 years in a country,'' the
commentator Mumtaz Soysal wrote in a newspaper column this week,
``if that country has lost more than 30,000 dead and tens of
thousands of wounded due to that problem, if hundreds of thousands
of people have been forced to migrate from the eastern part of the
country to the west, leaving behind deserted towns and villages and
settling in overcrowded cities, if people are still carrying out
suicide attacks and trying to kill public officials, one would
expect this problem to be a main topic in an election campaign. Is
it not utterly incomprehensible that a country can go to elections
without addressing its most urgent problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Military commanders have ruled out any discussion of new
approaches to the Kurdish issue, and even the mere suggestion that
they reconsider their rejection of Kurdish nationalism can bring a
prison sentence. Urging a greater role for religion in public life
is also taboo.
</P>
<P>
   Ideology has all but lost its meaning in Turkish politics. Two
parties, including the one headed by Ecevit, call themselves
center-left, and two others say they are center-right. But to the
extent that they offer programs at all, they are barely
distinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   Under these circumstances, the election revolves largely around
the personalities of the half-dozen bosses who run the country's
main political parties like private fiefs. All are veterans of
years or decades in politics, and none has succeeded in rousing
much public enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most interesting result of Sunday's voting will be
the strength of the Islamic-oriented Virtue Party, whose religious
appeal puts it outside the popular consensus and makes it anathema
to the ruling establishment. The Virtue party governs the country's
two biggest cities, Istanbul and Ankara, and has won a reputation
for honesty and efficiency that has broadened its appeal beyond
Turkey's limited circle of rigorous Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Several of Virtue's top leaders are facing prosecution on
accusations of making subversive public statements, and in
response, the party has begun urging repeal of laws that limit free
expression. This presents the odd spectacle of a party running on a
platform of increased democracy while fending off accusations from
enemies that it harbors a secret plan to impose fundamentalist rule
and destroy democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Virtue party and Ecevit's Democratic Left party are widely
believed to be competing for first place in Sunday's voting. But
even if Virtue finishes first, it is uncertain whether it will be
given a chance to form a government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support Virtue because it is so different from the other
parties,'' Necmettin Dincer, a 60-year-old dairy farmer, said as he
sat in a general store in Pinarbasi. ``It gives voice to our desire
for democracy, for a country where people are not sent to jail for
poems.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month one Virtue leader, Recep Tayyip Erdogan, a former
mayor of Istanbul, was jailed after reciting a poem that was judged
to be an incitement to religious rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   One other party is defying the political consensus in Turkey. It
is People's Democracy, which asserts that it speaks for the
country's Kurdish minority. Prosecutors failed in efforts to close
down the party before the election on the ground that it maintains
``organic links'' with Kurdish guerrillas. But the police have
banned and broken up its rallies, and this week journalists were
forbidden to travel to the southeastern provinces where it is
based.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish law requires that parties take 10 percent of the vote
nationwide in order to win seats in Parliament, and People's
Democracy is not expected to reach that level. If it runs strongly
in the southeast, though, it will solidify its claim that it speaks
for many Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   Voting is mandatory for the 38 million eligible Turks, and those
who do not wish to risk a fine will be able to choose from among 21
competing parties. Many will do so reluctantly, among them an
accountant in Pinarbasi, Burmanettin Karakol.
</P>
<P>
   Although his office faces the town square where Cem, the foreign
minister, spoke on Thursday, Karakol did not bother to listen to
what he had to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy hasn't taken root here,'' he said over tea. ``We
have a country where courts close political parties and where
people aren't allowed to speak their minds. Instead of discussing
our problems in Parliament, we fight them out in the mountains. So
can you wonder why most people find this election boring?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
