<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2476 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNEARTHED-BORDELLO-AR     04-17 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNEARTHED-BORDELLO-ART-895(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST BROTHEL IN OLD WASHINGTON WAS DISCREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Enough of ``Monica's Story.'' Archaeologists
digging in the Mall have happened upon the historically tantalizing
story of Mary Ann Hall, a determined woman who built and managed
one of this city's finest 19th-century bordellos.
</P>
<P>
   The three-story brick house of the entrepreneurial Ms. Hall
flourished for four decades just down from Capitol Hill _ a
monument, in its way, to capital power and sex, but also to a level
of discretion that seems rare in modern Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was obviously a successful, independent woman and she
clearly maintained connections throughout her life,'' Donna
Seifert, an archaeologist who unearthed the dregs of Ms. Hall's
brothel _ champagne bottles and gilt dinnerware shards _ said in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   It is now a grassy stretch of the Mall where the Smithsonian
Institution's new National Museum of the American Indian is to be
built beginning in September, immediately east of the Air and Space
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we never found her little black book,'' said
Elizabeth Barthold O'Brien, an archaeology historian, who also
worked on the dig three years ago and co-wrote an archaeological
report with Ms. Seifert that amounts to a new chapter in the
underlife of historic Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Without impeaching a soul in retrospect, Ms. O'Brien and Ms.
Seifert documented through city and court records Ms. Hall's place
in Washington life and the way she profited elegantly near the
Capitol in an era when lawmakers lived more of the bachelor's life
and the lobbying arts included what historians say were the
services of prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a moralizing era, as ever in Washington, but Ms. Hall and
her employees never came close to entry on the police blotter, even
as hundreds of streetwalkers and prostitutes in shoddier houses
were written up routinely as nuisances, despite the legality of
prostitution. Rather, Ms. O'Brien found Ms. Hall listed on city
records as an upstanding taxpayer as her property value compounded
over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The doughty madam stood out as the rare woman who became wealthy
across the go-go years of the Civil War. Far from any whiff of
Brothelgate, she succeeded scandal-free at a time before houses of
prostitution were banned here in 1914 in a wave of civic
righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Hall was the antithesis of all the moralizing warnings of
her day,'' Ms. O'Brien said. ``She lived a long life, made a lot of
money, and left a gorgeous grave.'' Her towering stone memorial in
the once-rural Congressional Cemetery, a mile southeast of the
Capitol, and just down from a phalanx of smaller stones of departed
lawmakers, depicts a beautiful young woman wistfully pondering
life's passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pored over tons of documents, but Mary Hall remains a
mystery,'' said Ms. O'Brien, speaking of such unanswered questions
as how the young woman found the money and pluck for her
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The two researchers tracked a good deal of lost information but
found no photograph of Ms. Hall. She maintained a classic ``parlor
house,'' their report concludes, a sanctuary where ``men of wealth
and distinction'' were wined, dined and sexually served by women
``noted for their youth, beauty and social refinement.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Ms. Hall rented her property to a women's health
clinic in her retirement years, about 10 years before she died.
This was when prominent Washington women had begun crusading openly
in behalf of their ``fallen sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Respectable women bravely introduced Washingtonians to the
novel concept that some women turned to prostitution by necessity
rather than choice,'' the archaeology report notes of days when
cities were largely devoid of economic opportunities for single
women.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hall's death in 1886 at the age of 71 brought on a court
fight by siblings over her fortune and an obituary in The
Washington Evening Star that praised her civic integrity and ``a
heart ever open to appeals of distress.'' Finding the old
litigation record, Ms. O'Brien discovered the contents of Ms.
Hall's top-of-the-line brothel, from expensive Brussels carpets to
suites of red-plush furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her memory will be kept green by many who knew her sterling
worth,'' the obituary concluded. But her memory, as with the dust
of her myriad clients, was well faded until the researchers dug
into the history of the proposed construction site, as required by
federal preservation laws. Their report was entered into the
archives without fanfare in this city of endless homage and
ceremony for the more idealized aspects of Americana.
</P>
<P>
   The archaeologists found no mention of Mary Ann Hall in history
books. But they uncovered bureaucratic records of her bordello in a
day when ``prostitute'' was an accepted occupation in the federal
census.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hall's house at 349 Maryland Ave., with 18 ``inmates'' and
fine food and furnishings, was rated at the top of the list of 450
brothels cataloged by the federal provost marshal's office in 1862,
when the city teemed with transient men, encamped soldiers and an
estimated 5,000 prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Her house stood out in what was then the city's tenderloin,
dubbed ``Louse Alley,'' a canal-laced warren adjacent to the
sprawling ``Hooker's Division'' neighborhood _ a popular word-play
on Gen. Joseph Hooker, whose Union troops bivouacked on the future
Mall and patronized local prostitutes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In undertaking the assignment to research the construction site
for John Milner Associates, historic research specialists, Ms.
Seifert and Ms. O'Brien delved into a time when sex and politics
seemed to have been a far less public sensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, what's going on here?'' Ms. Seifert related when
Ms. Hall's old garbage dig yielded masses of corks, bottles and
broken plates of long-ago revels, giving her the first clue to the
human endeavors that had taken place there. By coincidence, she had
previously researched the underpinnings of the new Ronald Reagan
Building to the west, near the White House, and there, too, found a
brothel's remains.
</P>
<P>
   A muckraking book from 1883, ``Mysteries and Miseries of
America's Great Cities,'' told of the finest prostitutes being
employed by corporate lobbyists to influence legislation. ``The
type of house she ran, as well as its proximity to the Capitol,
would certainly have made it a possibility,'' the archaeological
report carefully concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hall managed an ``upper-10'' establishment _ a 19th-century
New York term for the very best in private trysting places. Ms.
O'Brien diligently searched criminal court records for any charges
against Ms. Hall, but all she found was mention of an angry
defendant demanding to know why the authorities never troubled Ms.
Hall's house.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some evidence that women came and left with
Congress,'' Ms. Seifert said, suggesting a certain seasonal aspect
to the life of democracy. ``It was just treated as part of the way
things were,'' she said of the fact of prostitution and the
corollary notion of the time ``that men couldn't really be expected
to control their sexual appetites.''
</P>
<P>
   In the scandal-weary eyes of modern Washington, there may be
particular relief in the fact that the researchers uncovered no
profiteering kiss-and-tell narratives about this buried part of
Washington's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Ann Hall's brothel was a large and prosperous household
that offered material comforts to its inmates and guests and made
Hall a wealthy woman,'' the researchers concluded with all the
sensibility of the departed madam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2480 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-OPINION-900&AMP;AD     04-17 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-OPINION-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WAR IN WHICH EACH SIDE CREATES ITS OWN REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Until last week, the clampdown had been fairly
thorough, the details relatively scarce.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav authorities kept most reporters out of Kosovo and away
from the physical evidence that might confirm the extent of
Yugoslavia's campaign to drive ethnic Albanians from their homes,
while American and NATO officials provided only the barest
information about airstrikes, which were almost invariably
portrayed as successful.
</P>
<P>
   Then came reports on Monday that NATO had inadvertently bombed a
train carrying civilians in Yugoslavia, and, several days later,
that a NATO pilot had hit trucks carrying displaced persons in
Kosovo. And the war for public opinion, waged through a taut
control over information and an assiduously managed dissemination
of it, entered a new, more intense phase.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Yugoslav authorities were whisking reporters on a
selective tour of carnage and NATO officials were giving newly
painstaking explanations of how airstrikes were conducted.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials even let reporters attending a news conference on
Thursday hear the voice of a pilot, which crackled from an
audiotape in an intimate, earnest assertion of how easy it was to
make a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   More than ever since this conflict in the Balkans began, it was
clear last week that the battle between Belgrade and Washington
involved more than aircraft and artillery, F-16 jets and M-84
tanks. It involved diction, images and feuding versions of reality.
</P>
<P>
   That is almost always true of military engagements, but there
was a difference this time, as there was for the initial stretch of
the war in the Persian Gulf. The absence of American troops in the
combat zone _ and of American reporters with them _ meant there was
little opportunity to sift through competing and often
contradictory accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a situation where you don't have any access to make a
determination about truth,'' noted Kathleen Hall Jamieson, a media
analyst who has been carefully examining the pictures and words
from the Balkans. ``The ability for each side to create its own
reality is almost unlimited.''
</P>
<P>
   Media analysts and news executives said that to this point in
the conflict, accounts from NATO and American officials seem more
trustworthy and candid _ but often no more complete _ than those
from Yugoslav sources, which have said several times, for instance,
that NATO jets have been shot down, though they have produced
evidence of only one such episode.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO and American officials have been alternately reticent
or voluble, depending on where their interests lay. Clinton
administration officials have been deliberate in their language,
using words like genocide combined with blurry photographs
suggestive of mass graves to conjure up the Holocaust, even when
they were not explicitly invoking it.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Americans are getting a view of what is going on in
the Balkans that, accurate or not, is stage-managed and subjective.
Because American officials have more direct lines of communication
to American reporters and citizens, their efforts have greater
effect and are more easily scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   During the first weeks of airstrikes, news media analysts noted,
NATO and American military officials did such a concerted,
convincing job of describing the efficacy of an ``ordnance'' (a k a
bomb or missile) in avoiding ``collateral damage'' (a k a civilian
deaths) that they had to spend recent days elaborately explaining
something that they then described as all but inevitable: the death
of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've created an expectation that war is a low-cost
endeavor, and it's not at all,'' noted Ed Fouhy, a former network
news executive. ``War is a very dirty, bloody business.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that American officials have no stomach for
descriptions of violence. When it comes to the brutal actions of
Yugoslav forces in Kosovo under the control of the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, the terms that officials employ are
duly evocative, designed to build support among many Americans for
the military actions in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Attributing the vast array of horrors in the Balkans to the
whims and will of Milosevic, administration officials have
presented Americans with an identifiable portrait of malevolence
much easier to demonize than amorphous ranks of anonymous Yugoslav
soldiers. Early last week, when Milosevic's visage appeared on the
cover of ``Newsweek,'' it was framed by raging hell fires and
identified as ``The Face of Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Media analysts noted that there was ample factual justification
for such a description, but that American officials were in other
instances letting their outrage get out ahead of provable
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, refugee reports that Yugoslav soldiers were using
rape as part of their campaign of forced expulsion from Kosovo went
from an assertion to an assumption of a systematic pattern in the
span of a day.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, was
at least pointing out that ``it takes time to confirm these
reports'' while condemning the rapes ``in the strongest possible
terms.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, President Clinton was alluding to the crimes in
question as a given.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot simply watch as hundreds of thousands of people are
brutalized, murdered, raped, forced from their homes, their family
histories erased, all in the name of ethnic pride and purity,'' he
told a gathering of newspaper editors in San Francisco.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Later in the speech, he said that if the possibility of
unintended civilian deaths prevented military action in Kosovo,
``then we're saying it's okay with us if Milosevic displaces over a
million Kosovars, kills and rapes thousands upon thousands of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   News media analysts and news executives noted that while that
may eventually be proved accurate, some of the presumptions about
Iraqi atrocities during the Persian Gulf War were later challenged,
as were Pentagon boasts about the efficacy of ``smart bombs'' and
Patriot missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``One must always be skeptical about official military
information,'' noted Marvin Kalb, a longtime correspondent for CBS
News who now heads the Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics
and Public Policy at the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   Television news executives said they were trying to signal such
skepticism in their reports, or at least make clear how, where and
from whom they were getting the information and images they
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've often taken some pains with our reporting from Belgrade
to point out that our report had to go through a censorship
process,'' said Bill Wheatley, executive vice president of NBC
News.
</P>
<P>
   But, he noted, ``To a considerable degree, we're dependent on
information from the Serbs and from NATO. The Serbs have shared
very little information about their military activities, and the
NATO people have shared more, but it's been limited, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School for Communications at
the University of Pennsylvania, said that in light of that, the
audience should be wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be very careful about asking, what do we really
know?'' she said. ``What is our firsthand experience of it? The
answer at this point is, we can't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
