<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-HEALTH-CARE-N     04-17 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-HEALTH-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN'S PRESCRIPTION FOR HEALTH CARE: TAKE A SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Every patient in Britain knows about the notorious
National Health Service waiting list, which tells how many people
are waiting for hospital treatment for anything from varicose vein
removal to hip replacement surgery. Never a short list, it
currently boasts 1.12 million members.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting has always been part and parcel of the British health
service, a price patients pay for free medical treatment. But there
is another list, one that the government, which has vowed to
improve health care, does not officially acknowledge and that
patients are just learning about. This is the waiting list to get
on the waiting list _ and it appears to be growing precipitously,
even as the Labor government proudly announces that the official
list itself is shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   How does this work?
</P>
<P>
   Take Tony Nelson, a 54-year-old resident of the tiny village of
Irby-in-the-Marsh in Lincolnshire. Several months ago, he presented
himself at his general practitioner's office seeking help for a
chronic problem: rheumatoid arthritis that has hurt his hands, his
legs and especially his back. As a self-employed heating contractor
whose disability means he can work only part of a week, Nelson
needs a back operation to allow him to work full-time again.
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson got some unwelcome news. Not only would he have to
wait for treatment, the doctor said, but he would have to wait for
another doctor to confirm he needed treatment, for a total of about
two and a half years. The first wait, of 18 months, would be for an
appointment with a spinal specialist. The second wait, of about a
year, would be for the operation itself.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, until he saw the specialist, the doctor said, Nelson
could not get on the official waiting list. He would not even be
allowed the pleasure of being a government statistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an obvious trick if you want to reduce the number on
the waiting list,'' said Ann Widdecombe, the Tory shadow health
secretary. (The Tories say there was a waiting list for the waiting
list when they were in office, too, but that it was much shorter _
247,500 people in March 1997 compared with 468,000 at the end of
1998.)
</P>
<P>
   ``But the problem is that until you get in to see the
consultant, no one has made a judgment about the urgency of the
case,'' Miss Widdecombe said. ``It's literally playing politics
with people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, as successive governments have struggled to
keep health spending down and avoid raising taxes the waiting list
has become a potent political issue. That is why Tony Blair's Labor
government said in the fall of 1997, only months after assuming
office, that it would devote a large portion of the extra $880
million it allocated to the Health Services $67 billion annual
budget toward getting the numbers under control.
</P>
<P>
   But the rising underground waiting list raises doubts about the
usefulness of the Labor government's effort, which set specific
targets for hospitals and the health care authorities that control
them to reduce the waiting list. Among other things, the program
provided for an ``action team'' that travels the country and helps
hospitals shorten their lists, and awards money to hospitals that
meet their targets.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Britain's health secretary, Frank Dobson, proudly
announced that the effort was paying off. Between April 1998 and
the end of this February, he said, the number of Britons waiting
for treatment fell by 189,310, to 1.12 million _ the lowest since
February 1996. Moreover, he said, no one on the list now has been
waiting for more than 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``These record results have come about because the 1 million
staff of the NHS have made massive efforts, with massive dedication
and skill, to deliver what everyone in the country wants: fewer
people on the National Health Service waiting lists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the 468,000 people waiting to wait? ``The Tory
figures are not incorrect,'' a Department of Health spokesman said
in an interview. ``But traffic throughout the Health Service has
increased, so that more people are seeing doctors in the first
place. That increases the wait for outpatient appointments.''
</P>
<P>
   In many parts of the country, the wait for appointments with
neurologists, orthopedic surgeons and ophthalmologists can stretch
to well past a year, thus delaying a patient's diagnosis and
ultimate treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors say they suspect that this is directly due to the
government's waiting-list initiative, which has led hospitals to
use all sorts of stratagems to meet the government-imposed targets.
</P>
<P>
   Such tricks include giving priority to minor operations that can
be more easily disposed of, while making more serious cases wait;
canceling treatment or transferring patients to different
specialists so that they have to start their wait all over again,
but are statistically treated as if they have just begun waiting,
and spending huge amounts of money to have waiting-list patients
treated in private hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Because the figures can be so easily manipulated, many medical
experts say, the waiting list is a poor gauge of the overall health
of the system. ``What we're concerned about is overall waiting
time,'' said a spokeswoman for the British Medical Association, a
doctors' group.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors on the front lines agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to spend money doing relatively trivial
operations instead of doing procedures that really affect people's
lives, then I think it's immoral,'' said Stephen Swindells, a
consultant anesthesiologist at St. James' Hospital in Leeds. ``If
you talk to elderly patients who are in pain and waiting for a hip
or knee replacement, they see a wait of 18 months as quite
devastating. If they're only going to live for five more years,
that's a huge portion of their life wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   The waiting list is the system's way of rationing care, said Dr.
David Cartwright, who is the general practitioner for Nelson, the
heating contractor with rheumatoid arthritis. ``The government
can't have it both ways,'' he said. ``They can't say, on the one
hand, that we have no rationing, and on the other hand keep
everybody at bay by making them wait two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Nelson waits, wishing that he had taken out private
health insurance years ago instead of depending on the National
Health Service. He is tired of being patient. He is tired of being
in pain and he is tired of being among the uncounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I said to one of my customers, `There's an 80-week waiting
list before I can see you,' there are two things he could think:
either this guy's grossly overworked, or he doesn't want the job,''
Nelson said. ``Either way, it isn't right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
