<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION SPURS HOSPITALS TOWARD ALL PRIVATE ROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ark., Calif., Fla., N.J., Ohio)  (Eds: Also will move in `f' category.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Private rooms in hospitals were once for only those affluent
patients willing to pay as much as $300 a day extra for some peace
from the chatter, beeping machines and groans coming from the next
bed. Now a growing number of hospitals are eliminating shared rooms
and offering all patients _ Medicare and Medicaid, rich and
indigent _ their own rooms, often at no extra charge.
</P>
<P>
   The shift toward private rooms is largely a byproduct of the
revolution wrought by managed care. Most hospitals are under
pressure to compete for patients. Insurers used to pay hospitals
based on a semiprivate room rate. Now they typically pay the same
flat amount no matter what the type of room.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is also a factor, as hospitals need more space for
increasingly sophisticated life-support devices. Indeed, many
hospitals want to build rooms that can be easily converted to
intensive care units, which health planners project as a growth
area over the 30-year life of a typical hospital building.
</P>
<P>
   So while building private rooms is more expensive than shared
rooms, many hospitals say the extra cost is worth it to fill a
higher percentage of beds and to prepare for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everybody is building hospitals with private rooms
only,'' said C. Thomas Smith, president of VHA Inc., a national
purchasing and consulting network of 1,850 hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Big university hospitals have recently completed buildings with
only private rooms in Chicago and Little Rock, Ark. Construction
will start this summer for an all-private medical center in Los
Angeles. Other current projects include a new Florida center of the
Cleveland Clinic, a county hospital near San Bernardino, Calif.,
and a new regional center for the South Jersey Hospital System in
Bridgeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   At 315 square feet, many rooms in the new medical center at the
University of California at Los Angeles will be almost as big as
some Manhattan apartments. In the new building at Northwestern
Memorial Hospital in Chicago, the rooms will be 225 square feet,
with separate sinks for patients and nurses and a vanity in the
hotel-style private bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The new private rooms have a number of health care advantages,
hospital executives say. They help protect patients from infections
in the hospital. They also encourage family members to stay with
the patient and become more engaged in the patient's care. In the
end, that helps because managed care has in many cases shortened
hospital stays and patients need all the help they can get, in the
hospital and at home.
</P>
<P>
   An independent study found that patients recovered faster in a
cooperative care unit at New York University Hospital, where family
members stay with them in 40 private rooms, than patients in
traditional units.
</P>
<P>
   Faye LeDoux, an architectural project director for Ellerbe
Becket, a Minneapolis-based firm, added, ``If you are in a room
with a person who requires a lot of care and a lot of noisy
equipment, it can be very stressful for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Thelma Waln, recovering from hip surgery after a painful fall,
enthused over the all-private attractions of Bernardino County's
new Arrowhead Regional Medical Center in Colton, Calif. They
include ``my own bathroom, my own TV.'' Teasing, she told a nurse,
``This is going to lead to malingering.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Waln, 64, was transferred to Arrowhead on its opening day,
March 30, from a 1940s building with a radically different
ambience. Her old room had six beds and a television that attracted
``20 or 30 people who came in every day'' to watch soap operas. She
remembers opening her eyes there, still woozy from anesthesia. ``I
thought I was in a garage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital executives say the economics of private rooms makes
sense in many parts of the country. Medicare, which typically
covers half of a hospital's budget, pays a flat sum that varies
with the diagnosis. Some managed care plans also pay this way;
others negotiate a daily rate for each patient, and some pay a
monthly fee for each plan member that is supposed to cover expenses
for those who require care.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the private rooms do not add directly to costs for
insurance companies and employer health plans. Instead of billing
the patient, many hospitals now absorb the relatively minor costs
of the larger, private room.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a hospital can do it, great,'' said Ben Zelman, a vice
president of Medical Mutual of Ohio, a big insurance company based
in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   As they pursue patients, many hospitals have eliminated extra
charges for private rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always reluctant to charge a differential rate for a
private room,'' said Gary Mecklenburg, chief executive of
Northwestern Memorial Hospital in Chicago. ``It would not be
positive public relations, when somebody is already paying a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   A scattering of hospitals around the country have had
all-private facilities for a number of years. Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center in Los Angeles has long had all-private rooms at no extra
charge. In Cleveland, the University Hospitals system opened Lerner
Tower, a 210-bed, all-private unit for adult patients, five years
ago. More than 90 percent of the beds are usually occupied, which
helps generate above-average profit levels for the system. On
average, only 61 percent of available beds are occupied in
Cleveland hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, where space is short and building costs are high,
the newer hospitals have not gone the all-private route, though
many have luxury accommodations for those who can afford it. ``The
economics are prohibitive in New York, compared to other places,''
said Kenneh Raske, president of the Greater New York Hospital
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary plans for a new children's tower at Presbyterian
Hospital, for example, include both semiprivate and private rooms.
</P>
<P>
   It would cost the average hospital in New York City $25,000 more
a bed to convert to private rooms, said Robert Larsen, a principal
in the architectural firm Larsen, Shein, Ginsberg &AMP; Associates.
That would mean $750,000 more for a standard 30-bed floor.
</P>
<P>
   But in most places, in the accelerating race to draw on a
shrinking pool of generally sicker patients, it can be easier to
fill private rooms than to scramble to match up people by gender
and compatible ailments.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals are building ``as many private rooms as real estate
and financial conditions will allow,'' said Larry Neiterman, global
director of health care for the Deloitte Consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   George Mann, a professor of architecture at Texas A&AMP;M
University, said: ``The trend is toward a model more like a hotel.
At the Holiday Inn or the Marriott, you don't get a stranger as a
roommate when you check in.''
</P>
<P>
   The downside, he said, is that the patient in a single room
``can be pretty isolated and far away, if something happens and you
can't reach that emergency cord.'' The new hospitals rely on
electronic patient-monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   Jocelyn Frederick, a principal with Perkins &AMP; Will, an
architectural firm in Chicago, said, ``It is often cheaper to build
new buildings with the correct support space for medical technology
and the correct floor plan than to convert an older building.''
</P>
<P>
   Planners at Northwestern Memorial said that converting a 1940s
structure would have cost more than erecting the new building. In
some of the old areas, it was just not feasible to install 1990s
technology, said Meredith Zelewsky, a spokeswoman for Northwestern.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1 Northwestern Memorial will open the $580 million
center, with 400 private rooms and 92 more for intensive care
patients. The big teaching hospital will shut an older facility
with 680 beds, 200 of which were often empty.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms are equipped with fiber optic wiring so that nurses
and doctors can plug into a patient's medical records or digitally
stored X-ray images. Specially programmed air systems screen out
harmful bacteria to protect rooms with cancer or AIDS patients who
have weak immune systems. The systems also screen air coming from
rooms with patients who have contagious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some health care experts see the move toward private
rooms as driving up overall health care costs, which are now rising
6 percent a year after several years of slow growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately the private rooms do drive up the cost of health
care,'' said Uwe Reinhardt, a health care economist at Princeton
University. ``But it is amazing how cheap the costs per square foot
are compared to the costs of supplies and staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospital buildings cost $120 to $250 a square foot around the
country, except in California, where earthquake protection raises
the cost, and in New York, where building costs are especially
high.
</P>
<P>
   Spending on building and equipment is typically spread over a
number of years and represents only about 7 percent of a hospital's
annual operating expenditures, with most of that for the equipment,
said William Cleverly, who heads the Center for Healthcare Industry
Performance Studies in Columbus, Ohio. Buildings with all private
rooms, he said, may raise total operating costs, including labor,
supplies and capital spending, by five-tenths of 1 percent at most.
</P>
<P>
   Making the rooms at the new UCLA medical center all private
accounted for tens of millions of dollars of the $600 million total
cost, said Dr. Michael Karpf, director of the medical center, which
is part of a new $1.3 billion research and teaching complex.
</P>
<P>
   But the private rooms will allow more treatment to be done in
the rooms, as ``the tendency of patients being sicker and sicker''
continues, he said. Most of the 525 private rooms are being
designed to convert easily to intensive care units.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assume that as technology is improved and miniaturized,
patients will get more done in their own rooms,'' Karpf said. Among
other things, they may have a dialysis machine, multiple
intravenous drips and an aortic balloon to assist the heart.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the extra cost will be ``well worth it,'' he said.
``If the new building was antiquated 20 years after it was built,
it would have wasted a lot of money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
