<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2516 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-610&AMP;A     04-17 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-610&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., BRITAIN VOW TO GIVE WAR CRIMES TRIBUNAL MORE DATA ON TOP
YUGOSLAVS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Responding to complaints from the U.N. war crimes
tribunal in The Hague, the United States and Britain have pledged
to provide more information to prosecutors that may enable them to
indict the top Yugoslav civilian and military leadership.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Clinton administration's chief human rights
official traveled to The Hague to talk about the immediate needs of
tribunal investigators, including information gathered by American
intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have discussed ways for the United States to improve the
timely delivery of information about events in Kosovo to the office
of the prosecutor,'' Assistant Secretary of State Harold Koh, the
chief American human rights official, said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Tribunal officials have said that even as Western political
leaders were promising to provide detailed evidence to the court,
the tribunal found itself hampered by a lack of information about
the Yugoslav high command that only government agencies can supply,
like orders issued to commit atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, such orders can be best documented through
classified intelligence, like electronic surveillance, that
governments have either been reluctant to share or have hesitated
to allow to be presented in open court because of their fear of
exposing intelligence-gathering methods.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have been gathering such classified evidence to
indict President Slobodan Milosevic and the Yugoslav high command.
The British government on Friday also reinforced its commitment to
the tribunal by naming a ``Kosovo war crimes coordinator,''
responsible for sharing information with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Among Western foreign ministers, British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook has been the most outspoken in linking the crimes in Kosovo to
trials in The Hague. In announcing the new war crimes post in
London, Cook said: ``The message this appointment sends to
Milosevic is this. We know who you are. We know what your troops
are doing. There will be no hiding place.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook has also been unusually direct in addressing Milosevic on
television. During a recent broadcast, he taunted Milosevic to go
ahead and tell the Serbian people, who are deprived of many goods,
about the villas the president keeps in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Other European political leaders have hardened their language
about the Yugoslav leader as hopes for a political settlement in
Kosovo have faded. A few days ago, French President Jacques Chirac
referred to Milosevic for the first time as ``the dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the leading NATO countries, France until recently was the
least cooperative with the tribunal, which was set up by the United
Nations in 1993. On several occasions, France refused to let its
military officers testify in The Hague, apparently to protect
classified information.
</P>
<P>
   But the tribunal has pressed Paris, and Gen. Philippe Morillon
of France, the former commander of U.N. forces in Bosnia, is now
expected to testify soon.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, though, tribunal officials have been saying
that they cannot work effectively unless they get more cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   They say it is one thing for politicians to say who is in
command and who is responsible for war crimes in Kosovo, as
American and NATO spokesmen have done recently, but it is another
thing to demonstrate that in court.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors need to provide the evidence to establish
responsibility. To indict a political or military leader for
``command responsibility,'' prosecutors must show what orders were
issued, or failing that, they need to demonstrate that a commander
knew of crimes committed by people under his responsibility and
failed to stop them or punish them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The office of the prosecutor says that it has gathered enough
evidence of war crimes in Kosovo to indict lower-level police and
army officers. But the prosecutors want more detailed information
about orders given within the Yugoslav command, which, if
available, is likely to be classified intelligence. Even when the
tribunal was given such intelligence in the past in connection with
crimes during the war in Bosnia and Croatia, prosecutors say they
have not been allowed to use that as evidence in the courtroom
because governments do not want their intelligence-gathering
methods exposed.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Kosovo, prosecutors put together a team of
investigators a year ago, as the Yugoslav police were stepping up
their repression against ethnic Albanian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   As refugees now keep pouring out of Kosovo with accounts of mass
killings and abuse, investigators for the tribunal working in the
region are obviously overwhelmed, tribunal officials say. They are
assisted by dozens of specialists from the Organization for
Cooperation and Security in Europe and by other groups.
</P>
<P>
   Koh, of the State Department, said in The Hague on Friday that
the American government was providing a grant to the Coalition for
International Justice of the American Bar Association to document
cases of humanitarian law violations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say that the list of war crimes they have already
compiled is very long. ``Proving ethnic cleansing and massacres is
not very difficult,'' an official said.
</P>
<P>
   But given the magnitude of the violence in Kosovo, the tribunal
will not be able to investigate events village by village. The main
targets of their investigations are people in positions of
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing lessons from their slow progress in investigating war
crimes in Bosnia and Croatia, where they sifted through many events
on the ground, they changed strategy in their work on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, prosecutors have focused on top government
officials in Yugoslavia and the most senior commanders in the
military and the police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
