<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2521 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT &LR;      04-17 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNLIKELY UNION OF RUSSIA, BELARUS AND YUGOSLAVIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Politics makes strange bedfellows. Then there is
Russian politics, which seemed this week hellbent on the downright
weird: a menage a trois of Russia, Belarus and Yugoslavia, bedding
a wobbly democracy, a Soviet-style dictatorship and an
international pariah three borders removed from either of them in
death-do-we-part union.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a week after Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic first
proposed it, Russia's lower house of Parliament voted Friday by 293
to 54, with one abstention, for just such a marriage of nations.
Belarus' eccentric strongman, President Aleksandr Lukashenko, was
in Belgrade on Wednesday, making arrangements with Milosevic for
the linkup.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Communists were jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is busy leading a new world order,'' Gennadi
Seleznyov, the Communist Speaker of Parliament's lower house, told
the news radio station Echo Moskvy on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is a leader regarding this idea of a new world
order. Therefore, let those of us who do not belong to NATO put our
heads together and state what kind of world order we see.''
</P>
<P>
   That the union is in fact highly unlikely to take place soon, if
ever, was almost irrelevant. Whatever the talk of world order and
thumbing Washington's eye, the drumbeat here for marriage with
Yugoslavia is far more a matter of domestic politics, not foreign.
</P>
<P>
   In the context of the despair and helplessness that seem to
drive much of Russian politics these days _ despair over Russia's
plight and the West's comparative supremacy; anger over the
helplessness to do much about it _ talking up a union with Belarus
and Yugoslavia begins to look like very good strategy indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like demonstrations near the U.S. Embassy, which reflect
not the desire of the majority of Russians to get into a
confrontation with the West, but some remnants of some imperial
feelings,'' said Andrei Smirnov, a political writer for the Russian
daily Segodnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the majority of the population, the visibility of
confrontation flatters them.''
</P>
<P>
   To the Communists and supernationalists who are the major
backers of union, the notion is that flattery will get them
somewhere in the parliamentary campaigns that are just beginning to
crank up across Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Voters will choose all 450 members of Russia's politically
dominant lower house in elections this December. Already the idea
of reasserting lost Russian glory has become both the subtext of
parliamentary politics and a main theme of the house's effort to
impeach President Boris N. Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   This year's elections in Belarus are canceled, courtesy of a new
Constitution that Lukashenko pushed through in a referendum widely
condemned as rigged. But from the start, he has based his regime on
the proposition that Soviet power should be rebuilt to counter
Western influence. In the last year, as Belarus' state-planned
economy has run aground, he has used the West more and more as a
foil for the country's troubles, and promoted reunification of the
old Soviet empire as the solution.
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread popular support for the idea of unification
with Belarus _ and a formal announcement of plans for economic and
semipolitical union this winter _ the idea so far has gone almost
nowhere. In part, that is because Russia is too preoccupied with
its own problems to be able to absorb the 10 million residents of
Belarus, who are in even worse economic straits.
</P>
<P>
   In part, it may be that neither Yeltsin's camp nor Russia's
Communists and nationalists want Lukashenko, a charismatic and
cunning politician, as a rival in future elections.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, a union with Yugoslavia seems equally appealing to
many Russians. One poll of 3,108 Russians, taken last week by the
Moscow-based Center for International Sociological Research, showed
that 71 percent of respondents supported a
Russia-Belarus-Yugoslavia pact and that more than three-quarters
would consummate it now rather than later, after the NATO campaign
has ended.
</P>
<P>
   For Yeltsin, who wants to avoid a military or political
entanglement in the Yugoslav crisis, such support has been a
problem. The president initially said he would favor a union of the
three nations after the Communist speaker, Seleznyov, met with him
last week.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, his aides have backed away from the idea,
calling it premature and even wrongheaded because of the danger
that it would drag Russia into a European war.
</P>
<P>
   Smirnov, the poltical writer, suggests that Yeltsin's opponents
will seize on his foot-dragging in the coming parliamentary
elections and the presidential campaign that will follow to attack
the president's supporters and any successor he may endorse.
</P>
<P>
   That said, support for a three-nation union is hardly unanimous.
Some analysts point out that the idea has serious implications that
Yeltsin has raised obliquely and that Communists and nationalists
have yet to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Almost unmentioned, but clearly on everyone's minds, are race
and religion.
</P>
<P>
   Communists and nationalists have promoted the merger as a
``pan-Slavic union''; the patriarch of the Russian Orthodox Church,
Alexy II, endorsed it as a ``great miracle'' and a ``guarantee of
our common spiritual triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia's 20 million Muslims, almost a seventh of the nation's
population, may see things differently. Already, leaders of some
predominantly Muslim regions in southern Russia have warned that
the union threatens to further split Russia's already fractious
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such initiatives have very dangerous implications since they
propel the non-Slavic part of the Russian population to adequate
measures and steps,'' Farid Abdullovich Asadullin, the Moscow
adviser to the Mufti, the Muslims' spiritual leader in Russia, said
in an interview on Friday. ``I think this initiative won't find
support either in the Cabinet of ministers nor from our
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the prospect, however remote, that a union with
Yugoslavia would bring with it a mutual defense agreement, the
stationing of Russian troops and a direct confrontation with a
nuclear-armed NATO.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Russian politicians underscored that prospect last
week. ``The worst thing Russia can do is respond to insanity with
insanity,'' Grigory Yavlinsky, the liberal leader of the Yabloko
political faction in the lower house, said in a statement on
Friday. ``For the first time in history, it opens the possibility
for actual military confrontation between the leading nuclear
powers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
