<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-NYT &LR;      04-17 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 NATO COMMANDER CONFERS ON POSSIBLE USE OF GROUND TROOPS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Top American military officers flew here
Saturday in an apparent effort to lay the basis for deploying more
American forces _ possibly including ground troops _ in NATO's
effort to stop Serbs from driving ethnic Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley K. Clark, the NATO commander, arrived at
midafternoon and immediately drove from the once decrepit airport,
now swarming with helicopters and relief supplies, to meetings with
Albanian government officials.
</P>
<P>
   His trip was arranged so suddenly that U.S. Air Force press
officers at the airport had no inkling of it until queried by
journalists in the late morning.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's second in command, Lt. Gen. Dan Coffee, the deputy
commander in Europe, was here Friday on a mission to assess the
resources available in this desperately impoverished country, which
has taken in more than 300,000 Kosovo refugees. He also examined
the local military situation. There has been sporadic shelling
across the border from Kosovo into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   While military officials were tight-lipped as usual about their
plans, it is possible that the visit could foreshadow some change
in NATO tactics of relying on bombing alone, which while inflicting
considerable damage on the Yugoslav infrastucture, does not appear
to have broken the Serbs' spirits or interfered with their brutal
effort to clear Kosovo of its ethnic Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a wave of about 13,000 new refugees crossed the Albanian
border at Kukes during the night. Relief workers here and in
Macedonia were bracing for a further influx of traumatized people.
Many of the new refugees, relief workers say, are people who have
been hiding in the woods and mountains for weeks. They are
suffering from exposure, hunger and dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   A large group appears to have been driven from the area around
Mitrovica in northern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO estimates that another 100,000 refugees may be trying to
cross Kosovo's borders.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of a key vote in Congress on a special appropriation
measure to finance the military campaign and the relief effort, a
congressional delegation flew in to visit the swarming refugee
camps.
</P>
<P>
   Standing slightly apart from the senators and representatives
dispensing interviews, Maj. Gen. Randy West of the Marines quietly
eyed the scene, taking a longer view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to gather my own intel,'' West said, referring to
intelligence information he might need in the event that Marines
are sent here in large numbers. West is the commander of the 2nd
Marine Expeditionary Force based at Camp Lejeune, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   One Marine expeditionary unit from the 6th Fleet is already in
the area, and another is on the way, West said. But, he added, he
wanted to be ready for the possibility that larger numbers of
Marines might be called on.
</P>
<P>
   A Marine expeditionary unit is a strike force roughly the size
of a regiment, which is based on a ship, with its own attached
helicopters, Harrier jump jets and other close-in support aircraft
and some small amphibious armored vehicles. It numbers
approximately 2,000 to 2,400 troops and is commanded by a colonel.
</P>
<P>
   During the Kurdish refugee crisis in southern Turkey after the
Gulf War of 1991, Marines, who can be quickly deployed from their
ships, were used to provide relief and to protect Kurdish refugees
seeking to return to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Marines could also be used to provide perimeter security for the
long awaited _ and so far unseen _ Apache attack helicopters that
Clark says are coming to the region.
</P>
<P>
   But, the major strength of the Marines is as a quick mobile
strike force, capable of attacking enemy positions in helicopter
assault or opening a beachhead for more heavily equipped
conventional forces.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the Marine expeditionary units, known in military terms
by their acronym of MEU (pronounced mew), that do six-month
rotations with the 6th Fleet _ the 24 MEU and the 22 MEU _ are also
qualified for special operations, meaning that they are trained in
unconventional small-unit tactics like fighting terrorists or
rescuing hostages.
</P>
<P>
   A captured Serbian officer was turned over by members of the
Kosovo Liberation Army to NATO officials at the airport Saturday.
NATO spokesmen in Brussels issued a statement saying that the
captured Serb was being well-treated and had access to religious
counseling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
