<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2533 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-17 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: No. 99 ALWAYS GAVE 100 PERCENT  
(jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There isn't much to write or say that would improve upon the
tribute paid to Wayne Gretzky by Mike Lalor, who brought his sons
to the retirement news conference Friday and said: ``Guys, history.
Once in a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   This, from a fellow hockey player, a ``defensive defenseman,'' a
recently retired 12-year veteran of the National Hockey League.
Lalor just happened to be in from Boston, visiting a former
teammate, the Rangers' Todd Harvey. He didn't wear a suit, like
Gretzky's teammates, who solemnly marched in like a bunch of
grieving relatives. Lalor dressed up for the occasion with
11-year-old Jordan in the seat next to him, 8-year-old Mac plopped
on his lap.
</P>
<P>
   The boys, both with cropped blond hair, didn't fall asleep, as
did Gretzky's young son. They weren't as rapt as their father was
either, and the older boy said his favorite players were the
Russians, Sergei Fedorov and Pavel Bure. That wasn't the point. It
was about what was important to Dad, and what he wanted to share.
</P>
<P>
   Lalor, out of southern Ontario, played on a 1986 Stanley Cup
champion in Montreal, a year Gretzky's Edmonton Oilers took a
breather from winning it all. Gretzky was his country's hero, his
generation's standard, a father's teaching model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you're out on the ice and you're trying to show the
kids something, you always use Wayne as your example,'' Lalor said.
``It was the way he conducted himself, on or off the ice. You heard
him. He never put himself above his teammates or the game.''
</P>
<P>
   No one shatters nearly every offensive record without ego, and
plenty of it. Gretzky just always managed to keep his in
perspective, control it as he did his stick. He allowed himself to
presume Hall of Fame induction on Friday afternoon, acknowledged
that he'd made a great deal of money for himself and a few others,
too. But when he got around to thanking ``people behind the scenes
who made it easy for me to get on the ice and just play hockey,''
he certainly did not mean his agent.
</P>
<P>
   For all the invective hurled at the Rangers for not providing
Gretzky with enough winning resources, he was afforded the
opportunity to play three years in the news media capital and prove
that you don't have to make the last shot to go out on top.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Checketts, the Madison Square Garden president, admitted
that Gretzky was pained by losing, and sounded more sincere than
politically correct when he said it made the Rangers' slide that
much worse for him. ``I think everyone could detect how hard it was
for him,'' Checketts said. ``It was personally difficult for me to
take. It was a legend, and he wasn't going to get what he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky played on, without apparent bitterness, or complaint.
Checketts recalled a late-season game against the Islanders last
year, the Rangers long out of playoff hope, when he went to his
general manager, Neil Smith, and the coach, John Muckler, to
suggest shutting the battered icon down. Gretzky wouldn't hear of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the point?'' Checketts asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I can't help it,'' Gretzky said. ``It's the way I
was taught.''
</P>
<P>
   I sure hope people don't get into the habit of holding up
Michael Jordan whenever a great athlete is faced with an age-old
dilemma, of choosing the right time to quit. Obviously, Gretzky
doesn't. Twice during his news conference, he said he wished Jordan
hadn't retired because his kids loved watching him play. So did
mine, and especially for the sake of the 9-year-old in the house
who thought the man infallible, I found myself hoping Jordan would
pass the championship trophy on like a torch, send a message around
the world that he played to win, but the greater experience was
having played.
</P>
<P>
   As extraordinary an experience as it was watching Jordan hit the
championship shot last June in Utah _ even if we only wondered at
the time if it might be his last _ I can't say it is any more
memorable than watching Martina Navratilova lose her last match at
Wimbledon, the 1994 final against Conchita Martinez. On the way out
of the world's most famous tennis stadium, Navratilova bent down
and plucked a souvenir blade of grass. No one could ever convince
me this wasn't a true champion's proper exit.
</P>
<P>
   Boxers are a different category, of course. Muhammad Ali
suffered serious damage by hanging on, though history hadn't seemed
to hold it against him. The body of work ultimately speaks for
itself, no matter what the body looks like in the last scene. More
power to Willie Mays that he squeezed out an extra season or two
when he was a shadow of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every great athlete has to determine when the right time is
and there is something special about every great athlete's
retirement,'' said the Rangers' goalie, Mike Richter.
</P>
<P>
   There will be such moments Sunday afternoon, when Gretzky plays
his last game at the Garden against Pittsburgh. Mike Lalor is
taking the boys, but he hoped they were listening Friday when
Gretzky was asked if he would bother with Saturday's practice, now
that the definitive word was out.
</P>
<P>
   ``My last one,'' he said. ``I've got to be out there with
everyone else.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
