<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2537 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAYWATCH-IN-AUSTIN18-     04-17 0289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAYWATCH-IN-AUSTIN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Help from `Baywatch' a lifesaver for Austin
 &HT;    By Andy Alford
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With more than a billion viewers worldwide,
stars of the ``Baywatch'' television series may be unfamiliar only
to the Barton Springs salamanders. But on May 1, even the
salamanders will get get an eyeful.
</P>
<P>
   The show, known for its slow-motion shots of muscled men and
buxom beauties jogging to the rescue of imperiled surfers on the
California coast, also promotes water safety.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Salano, who plays the character Manny Gutierrez on
``Baywatch,'' and Kimm Collinsworth, a six-year extra and a former
student in the Round Rock school district, will visit Barton
Springs Pool to help the city recruit 650 lifeguards for its 47
public swimming holes.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, like other urban areas nationwide, has had difficulty
recruiting enough seasonal workers to keep all of its pools open
for the length of the swimming season, which runs from March to
September this year. The usual prospects, high school and college
students, have been taking advantage of the Austin area's low
unemployment rate by finding higher paying summer jobs. The city
currently has about 250 lifeguards on its payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to have such celebrity support for our recruiting
efforts,'' said Phil Halbrook, a spokesman for the city's Parks and
Recreation Department.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council in March voted to raise the pay rate for
lifeguards, and Parks and Recreation teamed up with Austin
Triathletes, Run-Tex and Capital Fitness to invite the ``Baywatch''
stars. The television series is paying for their visit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
