<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2538 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DALAILAMA-AUTHOR18-CO     04-17 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALAILAMA-AUTHOR18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book incorporates peace, positivity of Dalai Lama
 &HT;    By Judy Tarjanyi
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Westerners in search of peace of mind
and soul have long turned to the religions and holy men of the East
for the kind of spiritual guidance that they perceive as absent
from their own religious traditions.
</P>
<P>
   So it's hardly surprising that many would warm to a book on
happiness by one of the most popular religious figures of the East:
His Holiness, the 14th Dalai Lama of Tibetan Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what Phoenix psychiatrist Howard Cutler had in
mind when he proposed the idea for such a book in 1991. Although
the Dalai Lama has written eight other books, most of them on
Buddhism, ``The Art of Happiness'' (Riverhead, $22.95), which he
co-wrote with Cutler, is the first geared to a general Western
audience and it is getting an enthusiastic reception, rising on the
best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler agrees that a big part of the book's appeal is the Dalai
Lama himself. ``He is a wonderful illustration of how a person can
put these principles into practice in daily life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama's magnetism is more than star power, though,
Cutler said. ``I do think it has to do more with his personal
characteristics and qualities. When people meet him, they are
generally struck by his warmth, sincerity, genuineness, and basic
humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Tibetan Buddhist leader, who has been exiled from
his homeland since 1959, declared during a 1991 visit to the
University of Findlay in Ohio that he bears no anger toward the
Chinese who occupied his country and committed atrocities against
his people.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said, ``I see sufficient reason to develop
compassion,'' a quality he described as having ``good heart,''
which also happens to be the title of his 1996 book offering a
Buddhist perspective on the teachings of Jesus Christ. Cutler says,
``He does have that `good heart,'''
</P>
<P>
   Cutler first met the Dalai Lama in 1982 in Dharamsala, India,
``and I think it's really genuine. Like everybody else, sure, he
gets irritated, frustrated, but he doesn't turn it into intense
feelings of anger. If you see him, you can just sense he's really
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   What better person then, Cutler thought, to tell Americans and
other Westerners how to find happiness? Cutler said that he was so
impressed over time by the Dalai Lama's serenity and sense of
fulfillment that he determined to identify what it was that enabled
the Tibetan Buddhist leader to achieve such a state. In the book,
he wanted to name and convey a set of practices that could be
applied to the lives of non-Buddhists in search of happiness,
strength, and the absence of fear.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler, who is Jewish, said he approached the book more from a
secular, psychological perspective than a religious one. ``I
purposely didn't talk about Buddhist doctrine, beliefs, even
Western traditions. There's a distinction between spirituality as
religion and spiritual values like kindness, forgiveness,
tolerance. The Dalai Lama has written so many books on Buddhism ...
I wanted more something for daily life.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, which is subtitled ``A Handbook for Living,'' is
divided into sections on the purpose of life, human warmth and
compassion, transforming suffering, overcoming obstacles, and
living a spiritual life. In it, Cutler invites the reader into
private conversations he had with the Dalai Lama in Arizona and
India, asking such questions as ``Is happiness a reasonable goal
for most of us?'' and ``Do you ever get lonely?''
</P>
<P>
   The answers, which also incorporate material from a series of
public talks the Dalai lama gave in Tucson in 1993, often were
surprising. For instance, Cutler was completely unprepared for the
Dalai Lama's simple ``No'' answer to his question on loneliness.
``I never expected to confront anyone who never felt lonely,''
Cutler writes.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama explained that because he looks at human beings
from a positive angle, his attitude immediately creates a feeling
of affinity and connectedness with and to them, evaporating any
sense of loneliness a single, celibate male in exile might
otherwise feel.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler also was shocked when the Dalai Lama responded ``I don't
know'' and shrugged his shoulders when asked to assess the case
history of a patient who persisted in self-destructive behavior.
Seeing his questioner's surprise, the Dalai Lama said, ``Sometimes
it's very difficult to explain why people do the things they do ...
You'll often find that there are no simple explanations.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in every instance, the Buddhist leader gave the
45-year-old psychiatrist plenty to ponder and develop. Much of the
Dalai Lama's advice, Cutler said, boiled down to overcoming
negative states of mind such as anger, hatred and greed and
cultivating positive states like kindness and compassion.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama believes the underlying basic human nature is
gentle and kind, and that violence and aggression are superficial
characteristics that arise in response to various kinds of
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Cutler said he was especially challenged by the Dalai Lama's
belief that the purpose of life is to seek happiness. ``I found
that difficult because of my medical and psychiatric training. By
training a psychiatrist is meant to help a person become healthier
and happier. It's never stated that the purpose is to find
happiness. There's more of an emphasis on mental disorders and
negative states of mind and less emphasis on positive steps to
take.'' Cutler said before he left his psychiatric practice in 1993
to write the book, his encounters with the Dalai Lama had an impact
on his approach to patients. ``At the time I was practicing I had a
pretty orthodox, conventional psychiatric practice. But what I
found was how, as I implemented some of his principles, not so much
educating or instructing the patient in techniques for training the
mind or talking about Buddhist principles, but more from my own
side ... it changed the tone of the psychotherapy session so it was
more open and relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutler said he used the Dalai Lama's emphasis on developing
compassion and his techniques for establishing empathy, reminding
himself that he and his patients had a common human bond.
</P>
<P>
   If he does return to practice, Cutler said, he may work some of
the Dalai Lama's practices and techniques for dealing with anger,
antagonists, and enemies into therapy, depending on the patient and
his or her needs. He would do this, he said, without talking
specifically about Buddhism as a religion.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, he'll be writing another book for Riverhead,
publisher of ``The Art of Happiness.'' He will divide proceeds from
the first book with a trust for the Tibetan exile community.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
