<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ NATO warplanes hit fixed targets
and military units on the ground in Kosovo overnight despite bad
weather that hampered operations, officials at alliance
headquarters said today. All NATO aircraft flying night raids over
Yugoslavia Friday and early today returned to base safely, an
alliance officer said. Daylight operations were continuing Saturday
morning. NATO's supreme commander in Europe, U.S. Gen. Wesley Clark
traveled to the Balkans early today for talks with government
officials in Macedonia and Albania. Developing. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ MORINA BORDER POINT, Albania _ About 13,000
Kosovo refugees poured into Albania early today and thousands more
were on the move in Yugoslavia as Serb forces appeared to be making
a final push to clear Kosovo of its ethnic Albanian population. In
neighboring Macedonia, where at least 5,000 refugees crossed over
Friday, officials were bracing for an enormous influx in coming
days. Ron Redmont, a spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees, said more than 100,000 refugees were believed bound for
Macedonia after being driven from their homes in Kosovo.
(Kunstel/Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA _ SKOPJE, Macedonia _ U.S. Army Gen. Wesley
Clark, NATO's supreme commander, traveled here and to Albania for
talks with officials and visits to NATO troops Saturday. ``This is
not a campaign against the Serb people _ far from it,'' Clark said
after meeting with Macedonian Premier Ljubco Georgievski. ``But it
is a campaign against the policies which have caused the
humanitarian tragedy that is affecting this country.'' Meanwhile,
another 5,000 refugees crossed over into Macedonia Friday, and aid
officials were bracing for an enormous influx in coming days. The
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said more than 100,000 refugees
were believed bound for Macedonia after being driven from their
homes in Kosovo. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATO-SUMMIT _ WASHINGTON _ More than 40 heads of state from
across Europe and North America gather this week to mark the 50th
anniversary of NATO. But the mood of celebration is being undercut
by the difficult situation in Yugoslavia. NATO spent a half-century
preparing for the great war that never came. Now it's being tested
by a symptom of its own success. It was the Cold War defeat of the
old Soviet model, after all, that set in motion the collapse of
Yugoslavia. The job of picking up the pieces has fallen to NATO, in
the first combat mission in the history of the alliance, and very
possibly its last. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in International and Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-DATA _ A timeline of NATO history; NATO conflicts; U.S.
military alliances. (Cox News Service). 20.
