<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-850&AMP;AD     04-17 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVS CONTINUE `CLEANSING' CAMPAIGN DESPITE NATO ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO's air war of attrition with Yugoslavia
continued Saturday with attacks on tanks in Kosovo, but it could
not halt Yugoslav forces from driving tens of thousands more ethnic
Albanians out of the province.
</P>
<P>
   NATO command officers said that Yugoslav army and Serbian police
units were carrying out sweep operations all along southwestern
Kosovo near the border with Albania and Montenegro, burning and
wrecking villages and driving the inhabitants onto the roads to
flee for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather moved in over the area Friday night, once again
making it difficult for allied planes to do much about the Yugoslav
operations on the ground, allied officials said. But on Friday
afternoon they destroyed seven tanks from the air, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The ground forces successfully hit by the allies Friday appeared
to be miles away from the most intense Yugoslav operations along
the border. The allied attacks were concentrated instead near
Pristina, the provincial capital, and in the northern part of
Kosovo. The command did not say how many missions allied planes had
flown.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the allied command, Brig. Gen. Giuseppe Marani,
said that allied planes had also bombed strategic targets,
including an ammunition plant, and British military officials in
London said that a Yugoslav army headquarters near Pristina, which
was helping to direct Yugoslav operations on the ground, had been
bombed.
</P>
<P>
   But as Marani said, ``For ethnic cleansing, you don't need a
very strong structure in terms of command and control.'' In other
words, the targets NATO was striking from high in the air might
slow down but could not stop the ongoing destruction and killing by
Yugoslav forces on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great deal of killing has taken place,'' the alliance's
spokesman, Jamie Shea, said. NATO on Saturday made public an aerial
photograph of what it said could be a mass burial site near the
village of Izbica with up to 150 graves.
</P>
<P>
   Shea and Marani offered no new information Saturday about
Yugoslav assertions that allied warplanes had killed scores of
fleeing Albanian civilians on the road between Djakovica and
Prizren on Wednesday afternoon. Foreign correspondents allowed to
go to the scene found debris from NATO ordnance near the wreckage
of civilian tractors and wagons, but all Marani would say was,
``Debris will be one element of our investigation, but debris can
be moved around.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that when NATO had figured out what had happened it
would make its findings known, but Marani said he could not say
whether allied planes had attacked the road on Wednesday. That day,
the command said it had carried out a strike on a military convoy
in the area.
</P>
<P>
   With ethnic Albanian refugees once again pouring across the
border from Kosovo into neighboring countries, Shea said that
Yugoslav authorities under President Slobodan Milosevic appeared to
be trying to empty the province of as many of its 1.8 million
ethnic Albanians as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has rejected NATO's demands to stop the expulsions,
accept a cease-fire and let international peacekeepers escort the
refugees back home, and Shea said that Yugoslavia rejected similar
demands by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received reports that up to 100,000 people may be
trying to reach the border at Morina,'' Shea said Saturday. Morina
is just inside Albania near the already overcrowded refugee camps
at Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Henderson, the British armed forces minister, said in
London that officials had received reports of 50,000 more refugees
on their way to Macedonia and 18,000 to Montenegro, on top of
560,000 driven out of Kosovo over the last month.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, said in a telephone
interview Saturday from Skopje, the capital of Macedonia, that the
bombing could still be going on in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic is losing,'' he said. ``If he does not
change his policies, we're going to destroy those things President
Slobodan Milosevic values.'' As he spoke, allied planes continued
systematically trying to destroy military and police headquarters,
bridges, anti-aircraft guns and missiles and Yugoslav air force
planes and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   But the allies are finding it hard to pick off the tanks and
armored vehicles the Yugoslavs are using to systematically destroy
ethnic Albanian villages and settlements and drive out their
inhabitants. The Yugoslav campaign began late last year and
increased after the allies began bombing on March 24 because
Milosevic rejected a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand, as has been described before, his
whole military structure has a great deal of redundancy,'' said a
British admiral, Sir Ean Garnett, at a British Defense Ministry
briefing in London.
</P>
<P>
   Another NATO military officer said the Yugoslav armed forces had
been structured over the last 50 years to be able to wage a long
war of resistance against foreign invasion, with vast underground
bunkers storing fuel, ammunition and weapons the allies may not yet
have even found, let alone destroyed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Henderson estimated that 1.1 million of the approximately 2
million people who were living in Kosovo at the last census in 1991
had fled since fighting flared up a year ago between the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army, which wants independence for the province,
and Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Clark went to the Balkans Saturday to talk with leaders in
Macedonia and Albania about the refugee situation and about the
more than 20,000 NATO troops that are, or soon will be, in both
those countries to help deal with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia has taken in 160,000 ethnic Albanian refugees in the
last month, and 12,000 NATO troops originally intended for a
peacekeeping mission to Kosovo have built refugee camps and tent
cities for the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Another 7,200 allied soldiers are on their way to Albania to do
the same there, and another 4,000 American troops are on their way
to the northern part of Albania to fly Apache anti-tank helicopters
into Kosovo to hunt down Yugoslav units. The helicopters will also
be protected by powerful surface-to-surface missile batteries based
in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian officials say their country cannot take in any more
Albanians, and a spokesman for the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees in Geneva said Saturday that if the flow continued, an
airlift to fly refugees elsewhere might have to be organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the numbers rising again, it will be extremely urgent to
get more sites or expand the ones we have, and perhaps also then to
fly more people out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another U.N. official in Kukes, Jacques Franquin, said Saturday
that 5,000 refugees had arrived across the Morini border checkpoint
since midnight amid a rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible, it's a big problem,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
