<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLEWOMEN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dole aims to be definitive candidate for women
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Embedded in Elizabeth Dole's quest for the
Republican presidential nomination is the idea that she can be all
things to all women.
</P>
<P>
   She is the sharp-as-tacks, Harvard-trained lawyer and Cabinet
secretary in two administrations whose credentials attract
professional women who have chafed at glass ceilings, pay inequity
and a host of gender-based workplace insults.
</P>
<P>
   She is the proper Southern lady, raised in Salisbury, N.C., in
the 1940s and '50s and a born-again Christian. ``She grew up
saying, 'Yes, ma'am' and 'No, sir.' She's a conservative Southern
woman. It's genuine,'' said Rep. Tillie Fowler (R-Fla.), a Dole
backer who was reared in Georgia in a similar environment.
</P>
<P>
   Her candidacy has elicited cheers even from Democratic women who
have no plans to vote for her. Some Republicans are ecstatic about
the 62-year-old former president of the Red Cross because they
believe she will erase Democrats' recent advantage among female
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that she talks about it and that women
react to it,'' said Ari Fleischer, the Dole campaign spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Fowler called Dole the ``Jesse Ventura of the 2000 election,'' a
reference to the governor of Minnesota who won election with an
unorthodox campaign that drew voters from across the political
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's ability to mount a broad appeal may be telling in states
that have open primaries, like Georgia, in which voters can choose
to participate in either the Democratic or Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   California, which awards all its delegates to the Republican
National Convention to the winner of the statewide vote, also
employs an open primary, although officials there are considering
other options for its March 7, 2000, presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls give Dole a solid advantage over Vice President Al
Gore among women, as well as an overall edge. By contrast, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, who also comfortably leads Gore in the polls,
runs slightly ahead of Gore among women, but has a 25-point margin
among men.
</P>
<P>
   But there is some question about how soon Dole will have to make
her positions known on an array of issues, before opponents try to
define her, according to their purposes, as either too moderate or
too conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Bebitch Jeffe, a California political science professor,
said Dole's advantage among women stems from the fact that voters
know so little about her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have never simply voted for women because of gender.
They're not likely to start now,'' Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, the former Christian Coalition executive who now
runs his own political consulting business out of Gwinnett County,
Ga., identified potential problems in Dole's one-size-fits-all
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There does seem to be this strategy of `we can close the
gender gap and oh, by the way, she's a Christian,''' Reed said.
``Sooner or later, you have to decide which one of those you will
try to do. If you do both, you'll do neither well.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed is not affiliated with any campaign at the moment, but is
expected to work for Bush once he formally announces his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the National Abortion Rights Action League and GOP
opponent Gary Bauer have attacked Dole's stance on abortion from
their respective views.
</P>
<P>
   NARAL television ads have sought to remind viewers that Dole and
Bush do not support abortion rights, while Bauer chided Dole for
her ``retreat'' on the abortion issue and pledged to press for a
constitutional ban on abortions.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter released by her campaign, Dole pronounced herself
``pro-life'' and in favor of an anti-abortion amendment to the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, ``it's not going to happen because the American
people do not support it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she added, Republican women who hold different views on
abortion should set an example. ``We should agree to respectfully
disagree,'' Dole wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Dole campaign is betting that her answer will satisfy
Republicans who back abortion rights, particularly in a campaign in
which the GOP is seeking to avoid a major battle over the divisive
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
