<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROOPER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Subtle yet powerful Holden first African-American to lead
Southern highway patrol
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C._The South's only black state highway patrol chief,
Col. Richard Holden, remembers the first ticket he ever wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers it not so much for the traffic offense, but for a
judge's encouragement to the 22-year-old North Carolina State
Highway Patrol trooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a lot of authority. Use it wisely,'' state District
Judge George Stuhl told Holden privately. ``But don't let anybody
else, regardless of who they are, make you afraid to do your job
and do what is right.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the North Carolina patrol's two black troopers in
1969, Holden knew the Fayetteville, N.C., judge was referring to
race, a highly charged issue in the aftermath of Martin Luther King
Jr.'s assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbing police images linger from that tumultuous era, of
Alabama state troopers wielding clubs and bullwhips against civil
rights marchers in the 1965 ``Bloody Sunday'' confrontation in
Selma, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an image that law was an instrument of the white
establishment, rather than an instrument of the type of justice
envisioned by the U.S. Constitution,'' said Blease Graham, a
political scientist and dean of the College of Criminal Justice at
the University of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, in a growing number of cities, African-Americans have
risen to top cop jobs. But Holden, 51, is the only black to command
a Southern state highway patrol, according to the National
Organization of Black Law Enforcement Executives in Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt praised Holden as a ``man of great
character and integrity'' after selecting the 29-year patrol
veteran in February over five other finalists.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, where the State Highway Patrol is politically
powerful and, in recent years, plagued by controversy, Holden is
grappling with accusations that black motorists are unfairly
targeted by troopers.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate last week accepted the House version of a bill
requiring an analysis of traffic stops by state law enforcement
agencies to see whether minority motorists are stopped more than
white drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is happening, we plan to put an end to it,'' Holden said
last week in an interview at his Raleigh office looking across a
grassy lawn at the state legislative building. ``I want to stop
people for the right reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden, who supports the legislation requiring state police to
keep statistics about the race, gender and age of motorists they
stop, isn't convinced that state troopers are targeting minority
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, he said, that patrol officers are pulling more
blacks in communities where African-Americans represent a larger
percentage of the population. ``I think we need to look and see,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicion is widespread enough that Holden, in a recent
visit to all of the state's eight patrol posts, raised the issue of
fairness to the patrol's supervisors and urged them to spread the
message among the 1,380-member patrol. He told them, ``We are not
going to tolerate anyone, whether it be driving or just in an
office setting, harassing anybody for any reason.''
</P>
<P>
   During much of Holden's career, the patrol was under a federal
court order to hire more African-Americans. The order was lifted
last year, and now about 15 percent of the agency's sworn personnel
are minorities. At an awards ceremony in Greensboro last month
honoring a retired patrolman for bravery, four African-Americans
were among the 22 troopers attending. Holden was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   He offered kind but brief remarks honoring retired Patrolman
George D. Steele, who in 1997 risked his life pulling a
tractor-trailer driver from his burning rig. After the ceremony,
Holden approached him and said quietly, ``God bless you.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden is low-key and forceful, a style that so far has garnered
him broad support in the legislature and among fellow troopers.
``It leaves you in a good state of mind to see an African-American
in such a high-ranking position,'' said Tim Whitaker, 35, a black
trooper. ``I feel it gives the agency more credibility.'' One of
nine children who grew up on a farm in rural Wake County, outside
of Raleigh, Holden said his parents instilled Christian values of
hard word, patience and fairness. His father, Willie, taught the
broader lesson in mundane tasks, such as milking Betsy, a cow that
liked to kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while you learned to do the kind of things that were
soothing to the cow,'' Holden said. ``You have to learn the kind of
things that make people kick, just like with that cow.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden attended segregated public schools and earned a
bachelor's degree in industrial technology from North Carolina A&AMP;T
State University.
</P>
<P>
   Holden said he did not support student rioting that followed
King's assassination in 1968. He believed in obeying the law and
took an interest in the state patrol after meeting a trooper who
assisted him with a college research paper. Urged by others,
including a brother, to become a trooper, Holden placed an
application in Raleigh. He completed Basic Patrol School in 1969
and was assigned to Fayetteville, where he moved with his new wife,
Sandra Paulette Daye Holden, now a schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   He climbed through the ranks, living in Raleigh and
Winston-Salem. From 1993 to 1997, he was director of internal
affairs, putting him in charge of investigating allegations against
troopers. The past two years, he supervised training,
communications, research and planning.
</P>
<P>
   Holden remembers an occasional racial slight early in his career
and name calling by white motorists who questioned his authority to
stop them. He also remembers suspicion among some African-Americans
that he might be part of ``the establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden said he always reminded himself, as he does now, ``What I
am doing has to do with safety. These vehicles don't pick out
somebody's color when they run into somebody.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
