<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-POLITICS-720&AMP;AD     04-17 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINDU-LED INDIAN GOVERNMENT FALLS BY MARGIN OF ONE VOTE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The Hindu nationalist-led government that
turned India into a declared nuclear power collapsed Saturday. It
lost a vote of confidence, 270-269, the narrowest parliamentary
defeat for a government in independent India's 51-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Congress Party, led by Sonia Gandhi, the
Italian-born widow of an assassinated prime minister, will now try
to cobble together a new government.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the vote, India's president accepted the
resignation of Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, leader of the
Bharatiya Janata Party, but asked him to stay on as a caretaker
while efforts to form a new government go forward.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Congress Party, which has dominated Indian
politics for most of the past half century, said they would
immediately begin talking to other political parties with the aim
of forming India's sixth national government in three years, a
period that has seen the rapid rise and fall of several unstable
coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   Gandhi, president of the Congress Party and heir to the
Nehru-Gandhi dynasty, greeted thousands of well-wishers at her
home. They showered her with red rose petals, garlanded her with
marigolds and danced on the tops of their cars.
</P>
<P>
   But Gandhi, who drew huge and ecstatic crowds when she
campaigned across India in the last election but who has drawn some
criticism for her foreign birth, made no comment about whether she
will seek to become the next prime minister. Several party leaders
credited her with rebuilding the party and said they hoped she
would head a new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the leadership of Soniaji, the shape and structure of
the alternative government will be decided in consultation with the
Congress Working Committee,'' said Congress Party spokesman Arjun
Singh.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive by the prospect of more political instability, the
Bombay stock exchange's index plunged 7 percent after the
confidence vote. It was unclear what impact the change of
government will have on the modest steps taken recently by India, a
nation of 980 million people, to open its economy to foreign
investment and to build better ties with Pakistan and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The past year marked the Hindu nationalists' first real taste of
power. For decades, they had been unable to challenge Congress'
dominance. And as champions of the idea that India was
fundamentally a Hindu nation and culture, they had been seen as
opposite to the country's secular traditions and dangerous to
religious minorities, particularly Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the party came under fire as attacks on India's small
Christian minority climbed. Those attacks, opposition leaders
charged, were incited by associates of the party. Congress Party
leaders contended that Bharatiya Janata failed to rein in allied
Hindu nationalist groups _ a charge the party denied.
</P>
<P>
   In laying out his government's record Saturday, Vajpayee, 72,
touted its decision to conduct nuclear tests in the Pokhran desert
and develop a full-fledged nuclear deterrent, as well as its
efforts to build closer ties with Pakistan. The tests last May
stirred international fears that India and Pakistan, which
responded with its own nuclear tests, would soon be engaged in a
dangerous arms race.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Vajpayee took a much-heralded bus trip to Lahore,
Pakistan, to meet with Pakistan's prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, and
to discuss the core issues that divide them. The two nations have
fought three wars since independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Pokhran tests and my bus trip to Lahore are two sides of
the same coin,'' Vajpayee said.
</P>
<P>
   His government has had a very rocky year in power. Its tenure
has been plagued by the threats of its largest coalition partner _
a party from the state of Tamil Nadu that has 18 votes and is led
by the flamboyant Jayalalitha Jayaram _ to quit the government.
This week, Jayalalitha went through with her threat, depriving the
government of its majority and forcing the confidence vote.
</P>
<P>
   And the political strength of the Bharatiya Janata Party, which
led the coalition, was badly eroded in state elections elections in
November. Voters turned on the party largely because of the soaring
prices of onions and other vegetables and a general sense that the
government had mismanaged the economy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The capital's political class _ or chatterati, as they call
themselves _ has not yet turned to post-mortems on the government,
or attempts to fathom the impact of its fall on the crucial
questions of governance. Rather, the hot topics Saturday were the
horse-trading and political intrigue that came with this test of
the government's majority.
</P>
<P>
   Politics here in the world's largest democracy is ``a game of
numbers,'' Vajpayee said in his address to Parliament Saturday. His
government believed Friday night that it had the votes to win.
</P>
<P>
   But it received several nasty surprises Saturday when members of
Parliament pushed the buttons on their electronic voting machines,
with the most devastating one delivered by a small party with a
grudge against Bharatiya Janata.
</P>
<P>
   Mayawati, who heads the Bahujan Samaj Party, which draws its
support from lower-caste people, had declared Friday on the floor
of Parliament that the five members she controlled would abstain,
rather than oppose the government. Bharatiya Janata leaders
rejoiced at the news.
</P>
<P>
   But her promise was a trick. Still furious about what she
believed was the Hindu nationalists' betrayal of her party in the
state of Uttar Pradesh in 1997, Mayawati _ who like many
lower-caste women goes by one name _ got her revenge by voting
against the government Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It was appropriately symbolic that a formerly lower-caste woman
should have dealt the blow that helped bring down the government.
It is in large part the upsurge in political participation by
restive lower and middle castes, as well as regional parties, that
has undone the dominance of Congress, once the umbrella party that
sheltered Brahmins and untouchables, Muslims and Hindus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vote has become an instrument in the hands of the poor,''
said Yogendra Yadav, a researcher at the Center for the Study of
Developing Societies. ``They realize this is a unique possession in
their hands. They prize it and they make it work to their advantage
to get things they would not get otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The government had only a year to try to build a record.
Vajpayee, who insisted his government had safeguarded people of all
faiths, said in interviews he gave after a year in office that the
precariousness of the coalition had made the job of governing very
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been trying to meet the challenges, but at almost every
step I have had to compromise,'' he told one journalist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
