<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     04-17 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WORDS FROM THE DEPTH OF HIS SERBIAN HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The best hour to call is 2 or 3 in the morning, New
York time. That is when his brothers return home from the air-raid
shelters in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's six hours' time difference,'' Bora Milutinovic said.
``They spend the night there.''
</P>
<P>
   He cannot reach his sister at all, up in the mountains of
Serbia, because the lines have been cut. However, he hears she is
all right, for now.
</P>
<P>
   When he is on the soccer field, he tries to put the fighting out
of his mind. If people ask, he deflects it in fragments of four
languages, but when his fear and anger come out, they are as clear
as a scream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry but I must ask the question,'' he said, this time
in French. ``You have politics, but you also have people. Everybody
thinks they're right, but I must ask why do you destroy a country?
In the cause of what?''
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the most recognizable Serbs in North America, and
he recognizes that being Serbian is not exactly fashionable at the
moment. NATO is bombing Belgrade and other Serbian sections of the
former Yugoslavia, amid evidence that genocide has been perpetrated
upon ethnic Albanians in the Kosovo region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for Albanians,'' Milutinovic said. ``I feel sorry
for all humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, he is a blithe citizen of the world, the Fifth Beatle,
Ringo in a trench coat. He is currently coaching the New York-New
Jersey MetroStars of Major League Soccer, who are having their best
start. The operative word is ``currently,'' because Bora gets
around. He is the only coach in the history of soccer to take four
national teams to the second round of the World Cup _ Mexico in
1986, Costa Rica in 1990, the United States in 1994 and Nigeria in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a Mexican passport,'' he said, ``but I am a Serb.''
</P>
<P>
   It works that way in this new world. People who thought they
were integrated North Americans suddenly realize they are more
Irish or Korean or Ghanaian or Chilean than they had imagined. The
bombing has blasted through Milutinovic's effervescent veneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played in Belgrade in May last year,'' he said, referring
to his Nigerian team. ``We lost, 3-0, to Yugoslavia. The city was
beautiful. Beautiful. Now I hear hospitals and schools are being
bombed. NATO says it only bombs military targets. How do you
separate? It is impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   He made his plea during a luncheon he suggested, deciding to
unburden himself last Thursday at Serafina, a restaurant on East
61st Street in Manhattan. The busboys from Latin America bustled
when they spotted Bora, and the management from Italy gave him a
corner table.
</P>
<P>
   We spoke French mostly, but when his stylish Mexican wife, Mari
Carmen _ whom he adoringly calls Pancho _ arrived, we switched to
Spanish and English, with key phrases in Italian. But the subject
was anything but normal, as an impassioned and probably typical
Serbian expatriate emerged.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke with emotion about his parents, saying they had died
from ``fighting fascism'' during World War II. Later he suggested
they had died from enfermedad, Spanish for infirmity. At any rate,
he evoked the era when Yugoslavia was a valued alternative to
Russian-based communism.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have big alliances,'' he said, ``but inside you have small
countries, very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   He drew diagrams on the paper tablecloth, arrows here, lines
there, but instead of his strikers infiltrating opposing defenses,
he was demonstrating the tensions of a shattered Yugoslavia _ the
Serbs, the Croats, the Bosnians, the Kosovar Albanians, moving this
way and that in a vicious pattern. He scribbled some numbers on the
tablecloth, ratios tilting from a Serbian majority to an Albanian
majority in the south. He did not deny that violence had taken
place, but maintained that much of the impetus came from Albanian
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do people not write that?'' he asked. ``Television can
lie.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the details, he suggested that President Clinton
had been too busy defending himself against impeachment over the
Lewinsky affair to be up to speed on Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, once NATO goes in there, they never go out,'' he
said. ``Bombing does not solve anything. It only kills more people.
Here you have India and Pakistan testing nuclear weapons. You do
not bomb them. People kill people in Africa. You do not bomb them.
You've got crazy generals all over the world. Here, one missile
goes off target, maybe it lands in Bulgaria. What about Russia? It
is dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic did not discuss the past political divisions in
Serbia, and he did not get into whether the Serbs have committed
atrocities. The bombing has united all Serbs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``American people are great,'' he said. ``I love being here;
nobody says anything to me. German people, I have many German
friends. Italy, the planes come from there; I love Italian
people.''
</P>
<P>
   As he departed, he chatted up his hosts, and scuttled down the
street with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to say, nous ne sommes pas barbares, we are not,
how you say it, barbarians,'' he said. ``Please, stop the
bombing.'' Soon he would be back at soccer practice, where all
languages speak only of goals, where there is no talk of bombing.
Other people's loved ones were struggling to stay alive to reach
the border of Albania. There was no point in Bora Milutinovic's
calling home at this hour. His loved ones were in the air-raid
shelter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
