<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE-RODMAN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lakers underestimated task of coping with Rodman's instability
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The risk of hiring Dennis Rodman as the savior of a
talented team with cohesion issues came to a harsh and inevitable
denouement. The Los Angeles Lakers took the calculated gamble that
Rodman's championship pedigree would permeate the team. Instead, he
infected it. That's what germs do.
</P>
<P>
   It took a while, but the Lakers finally realized that they were
better off without Rodman and cut him Thursday. It was a decision
made to stabilize a reeling club, but also to restore some dignity
to a franchise that bowed to the mindless antics of a caricature
out of desperation to win an NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman had been at his distracting worst, a virus that ate at
the core of vulnerable cells. The Lakers had no cure for his
devastation. They won 11 consecutive games after he was signed, but
split the next 12 games, which should never happen on a team with
so many skilled players. For them to be in fifth place in the
Western Conference with all their talent speaks for Rodman's
destructive power.
</P>
<P>
   He showed respect for no one. Not vice president Jerry West, not
first-year coach Kurt Rambis, not all-star center Shaquille O'Neal.
It got so bad that owner Jerry Buss _ who enjoyed the attention
Rodman brought as much as George Burns did cigars _ finally
realized Rodman had no respect for him, either. So, Buss gave West
the go-ahead to thrust Rodman into the guillotine.
</P>
<P>
   His lack of respect, however, did not stop there. Not even
himself did he respect. Any self-respecting man who was paid six
figures to play basketball would not abandon his team for a week or
refuse on four occasions to enter a game or repeatedly come late to
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Rodman's antics and disrespect of the Lakers and the
profession virtually was played out for all to see, as they were
featured on nationally televised games seven times this season.
Rest assured that much of the seven other Lakers appearances will
be spent examining the team's recovery from Rodmanitis.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers insist they didn't dump Rodman for his latest
misadventure, in which he showed up more than an hour late for
practice on Thursday. Fittingly, he searched aimlessly for his
socks and shoes as Rambis sent him on his way.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``a pattern of behavior'' that did in Rodman, the Lakers
said. The exact pattern of behavior that has, sadly, typified his
last several seasons in the NBA. As Kobe Bryant said, ``We knew
what we were getting into when we signed Dennis. We knew what kind
of guy he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. Rodman did not do anything that surprised anyone. He
was himself, sad as that may be. He had a prime opportunity to
distinguish himself as a championship cog. The Lakers had the
ingredients, what with inside-dominant O'Neal, the slashing Bryant,
perimeter marksman Glen Rice and a host of other pieces. All Rodman
had to do was show up on time, bring his enthusiasm to the game and
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he brought lunacy. He brought the team down. During a
27-point loss at Portland on Tuesday, he played just 13 minutes
because of an elbow injury that players questioned. That was his
last game with the Lakers and, almost certainly, his last NBA game
ever. Who'd risk poisoning their team on Rodmanitis now?
</P>
<P>
   With a chance to go out a champion in Hollywood, Rodman instead
went out ignobly, placed on the curb like so much litter. The
Lakers were not going to win a championship with him the way they
were going. At least they can seize some dignity in losing without
him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
