<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-QUAIL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State beginning project to revive quail population
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ People might have been skeptical when the restoration
of Georgia's deer herd began during the late 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   And some folks had to wonder if nearly extinct wild turkeys
really could be reintroduced in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing existed as public and derogatory as the ``Stuck Pig
Award'' that state Sen. Bill Stephens (R-Canton) recently gave to
the Georgia Department of Natural Resources for the $1 million
appropriation for the Bobwhite Quail Initiative that includes
$50,000 for wood duck boxes.
</P>
<P>
   If Stephens had given a ``Stuck Pig'' for deer or turkey
restoration funds, the senator might be embarrassed today.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen if he will regret ridiculing the Bobwhite
Quail Initiative, but the odds are more in the senator's favor on
this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is going to be manyfold greater than deer or
turkey,'' said Dan Forster of the Game Management Unit of the
Wildlife Resources Division of the state Department of Natural
Resources.
</P>
<P>
   To restore deer and turkey was challenging, but was a matter of
replenishing wildlife in existing habitat. Of the state's 37
million acres, 24 million are forested timberland, perfect for deer
and turkey, but far from ideal for quail.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring quail is a matter of finding or creating habitat for
existing game. ``Seed quail'' are available, Forster said, but
habitat is a finite resource that is shrinking daily.
</P>
<P>
   From 1966 to 1993, bobwhites declined 62 percent across the
Southeast. Quail-hunting trips in this region declined from
7,644,000 in 1970 to 2,693,500 in 1991. The numbers of quail
hunters in Georgia have decreased from 135,000 in 1962 to 42,000 in
1996. Bringing them back will be the toughest, most ambitious
undertaking in the history of the state's wildlife management.
</P>
<P>
   The total projected cost of some $40 million for the project is
daunting enough, but that could be the easy part compared with
persuading the farming community _ farmers and bankers, etc. _ to
change current agricultural practices, the source of most of the
decline.
</P>
<P>
   Farms are now managed to eliminate weedy, shrubby areas between
fields, along ditch banks, adjacent to hedgerows and in odd field
corners. Fields have increased in size and double cropping has
become a common practice, meaning that fields stay in production
most of the year and seldom are ``laid by,'' or allowed to become
weedy.
</P>
<P>
   Many fields of row crop, especially in the Piedmont region, have
been converted to pine plantations and exotic pasture grasses.
Prescribed burning no longer is used to manage mature, thinned pine
stands and woodlots between agricultural fields.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers have made those changes to grow cash crops and for
aesthetics. Farmers need to borrow money for seed and equipment and
for cash flow, and appraisers and bankers frown at weedy, shrubby
areas.
</P>
<P>
   To survive, quail need ``early succession habitat,'' which
consists of native grasses, legumes, forbs (herbaceous plants),
small shrubs and small trees in combination to form a mosaic that
satisfies the bobwhite quail's requirements throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   It might not look pretty, but it's the source of life for good
hunting and for prey for almost all other carnivores in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The initial study, with a $939,000 budget and staff of nine,
will cover three focus areas of about four counties each and will
work with landowners on how to manage for quail or encourage them
to use more quail-friendly agricultural procedures. More details
will be available before July 1, when funds for the project become
available.
</P>
<P>
   As daunting as the task appears, Forster has hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be 1.5 million acres planted in cotton this year.
That's more acreage than all of Georgia's Wildlife Management
Areas. If every cotton field had a 30-foot buffer around it
suitable for quail habitat _ the concept is staggering.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
