<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-BOSTON-WOMEN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Breaking Boston's barriers
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fatuma Roba, surprise 1996 Olympic gold medalist,
pocketed an appearance fee approaching $100,000 just to make the
trek here from her native Ethiopia. When she steps to the starting
line Monday for the Boston Marathon, the crowd will cheer and Roba
will be swiftly on her way.
</P>
<P>
   No race official, irate at the sight of a woman in the race,
will try to remove her bib number or attempt to yank her from the
course. Boston, after all, is home to Harvard and a bastion of
progressive thinkers, along with being the favorite stomping ground
of such champion marathoners as Joan Benoit Samuelson, Uta Pippig
and Ingrid Kristiansen.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't always been that way.
</P>
<P>
   While the Boston Marathon has been around for 103 years, women
didn't become approved for the race until 1972. That did not
prevent some intruders from sneaking in.
</P>
<P>
   Most memorable was Kathrine Switzer, then a Syracuse University
student, who was almost tackled by an official during the all-men's
1967 race.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer entered wearing bib number 261, which she gained
surreptitiously by applying under the name of K.V. Switzer. When
official John ``Jock'' Semple, who himself ran 19 Boston Marathons,
jumped from the press truck four miles into the race and tried to
rip the number from her sweatshirt, Switzer's boyfriend, a hammer
thrower who was competing, shoved him away _ in full,
camera-clicking view of the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing is, that photo is more popular than it's ever
been,'' Switzer, 52, said. ``The legend continues to grow. HBO did
a big documentary on women's sports, and a lot of it focused on
that incident, because it was so dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not me that is famous, but the photograph. It was a
picture that was on the front of the world's newspapers the next
morning. It polarized people. There was a whole group that had no
problem with women wanting to run 26 miles, while you had another
group that was outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Semple wrote years later in his autobiography that he wasn't out
to harm Switzer. ``I just wanted my number back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Switzer prevailed on both counts. She managed to keep her
number, and she finished the race unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As funny as the photo looks now, it was a traumatizing
incident,'' Switzer said. ``If you look at the guy's face, he was
out of control. I had never been shouted at like that by anybody,
not even by my father. I was terrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was right on the eve of the women's liberation movement,
but I was unaware of all that. I was a kid. I was in college. I
thought women barging into men-only bars was crazy. I never felt
discriminated against until that official tackled me. Then, it was
instant radicalization. It changed my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, when Boston officially welcomed female runners
into the fold, Switzer was back. Although never a winner in Boston,
she won the New York Marathon in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   But her name is forever tied to Boston, and the incident endures
as one of the defining moments in women's running. She used it as a
springboard to help start the Avon running program for women and
still serves as program director. The television networks have
called on her as a marathon analyst, and this year she'll be
announcing her 21st Boston race on a local station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed incredibly since the 1970s and '80s, when we were
all feisty and trying to prove ourselves,'' she said. ``Now,
running has evolved into a lifestyle. It's the whole acceptance
thing. It's no longer unusual to see a woman out running in a pair
of shorts.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it out of the ordinary to see elite runners like Roba,
running for a top prize of $80,000 _ the same as for the men of
Boston. In fact, prize money in Boston is split equally between men
and women.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
