<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-VIOLENCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPARATISTS ATTACKED BY MILITIAS IN TIMOR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Militant supporters of the government
unleashed an orgy of attacks Saturday against supposed separatists
in the capital of East Timor, leaving more than 30 people dead,
scores injured, and homes and cars burned, diplomats and human
rights workers said.
</P>
<P>
   The violence, which erupted after a parade by pro-Indonesian
militia supporters, was the worst in the provincial capital, Dili,
since 1991, when Indonesian troops shot and killed more than 100
people.
</P>
<P>
   Among those killed Saturday was the adopted teen-age son of
Manuel Carrascalao, a leading pro-independence activist from one of
East Timor's most prominent families.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the violence followed a speech given this morning
by Eurico Gutteres, head of a paramilitary group, to a rally of
supporters outside the governor's office on the Dili seafront.
</P>
<P>
   ``I command all pro-integration militia to conduct a cleansing
of all those who have betrayed integration,'' Gutteres said.
``Capture and kill them, if you need.''
</P>
<P>
   They said civilians were then rounded up by militia members and
forced to attend the rally, while carloads of paramilitary members
drove around town firing in the air and attacking the homes of
known and suspected independence supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Those attending the rally included the East Timor governor,
Abilio Soares, and the province's army and police commanders.
Diplomats said other senior Indonesian military commanders were
also in Dili.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists and human rights officials in Dili said members of
the Indonesian military were seen actively cooperating with the
paramilitary members, waving them on and providing food and water.
</P>
<P>
   The violence casts fresh doubt on a U.N.-supervised vote on
self-determination for East Timor that is scheduled for July. It
also appeared timed to derail talks scheduled in New York this week
between Portugal and Indonesia to discuss a U.N.-sponsored meeting
on autonomy for the province.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 militiamen attacked the home of Carrascalao, the
independence leader, where some 150 refugees _ earlier victims of
paramilitary violence _ had sought shelter. They fired shotgun
blasts and smashed down doors to enter the house.
</P>
<P>
   Two journalists from Agence-France Presse who were at the scene
said the refugees were lying on the floor crying and pleading for
their lives. Both journalists were beaten with rifles and taken
back to a nearby hotel while the attack continued.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, the offices of a local newspaper, Suara Timor
Timur, were gutted by a hand grenade blast. Human rights officials
said a young man was lying dead outside the Resende hotel, while an
unknown number of people were killed and wounded in a suburb,
Metiaut.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon some 30 civilian casualties had been brought to
a small clinic operated by an American, Dan Murphy. Others were
taken to the city's understaffed general hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the Foundation for Legal and Human Rights was
evacuated after being attacked by militiamen armed with guns and
machetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At its height 3,000 to 7,000 militia paraded around the city
displaying their homemade weapons,'' the human rights group
reported by e-mail. ``They divided themselves to the east and west
of Dili and began terrorizing civilians with machetes and by
burning homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats said they believe the paramilitary violence had
been allowed to take place with the cooperation of senior
Indonesian military commanders opposed to an independent East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week the East Timorese independence leader, Xanana
Gusmao, under house arrest in Jakarta, declared that his supporters
had the right to bear arms for self-protection from the
paramilitary members.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners in Jakarta interpreted the call as a declaration of
war.
</P>
</TEXT>
