<HEADLINE>
THREE WOMEN WAIT ANXIOUSLY FOR THEIR SPACECRAFT TO REACH MARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sarah A. Gavit is leading an invasion of Mars. Built under her
direction are two craft now speeding toward a December rendezvous
with the red planet to help see if it harbors life.
</P>
<P>
   Her top aides are also women and, like her, edgy. They are all
pioneers pushing back frontiers of inquiry, technology and gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really out on a limb,'' the 37-year-old Ms. Gavit said.
This is probably the most anxious time, because there is little to
do but wait until December, hoping the risky technical gamble will
pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Never before in NASA's 40-year history, officials say, have
women held all the top posts _ project manager, scientist and
engineer _ in any space mission. And this one is tough. The craft,
which set off from a launching pad in Florida last January, are
meant to set planetary exploration on a bold new course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary,'' said Suzanne E. Smrekar, 37, the lead scientist.
``I really believe it's going to work. But even in a mission that
isn't high-risk, there are risks. In this whole business, you're
never sure of the outcome until it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has come a
long way since the right-stuff days when the top people tended to
be male, white, former military and macho. Now female astronauts
are routine, and the space agency prides itself on the women in its
ranks of experts and officials.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no women have led a planetary exploration until now,
making it a milestone for them.
</P>
<P>
   The women's team of experts at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in
Pasadena, Calif., designed and built the two intricate spacecraft.
Each is about the size of a grapefruit but they are heavy with
circuits and high-tech components, and built to slam into Mars at
high speed and penetrate at least three feet into its surface.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to study the rocky composition of the soil and look
for signs of water, which is considered a key to life but appears
scarce on the desert-like surface of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   No planetary probe has ever before crash-landed and radioed
signals back to Earth. Ms. Gavit, the project manager, said finding
a way to accomplish that goal took every ounce of skill and
creativity the team could muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the technology is new,'' she said. ``A couple things
were off the shelf. Everything else had to be invented, and some of
it is pretty radical.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's size peaked at 55 men and women. The project costs
$29.2 million, a pittance in a field where spacecraft have run $1
billion or more. The effort epitomizes NASA's new philosophy of
smaller, cheaper, faster and better, making the job even harder.
</P>
<P>
   Kari A. Lewis, 25, the project's chief engineer, said much of
the assembly work was done under microscopes. ``You can't see the
wiring with the naked eye,'' she said. ``It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The three women have kept a low profile. They rejected the idea
of a Jet Propulsion Laboratory news release on their role, fearing
that it would be dismissed as a publicity stunt. But interviews
were allowed for this article and for the May issue of Working
Woman, which goes on sale on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the two firsts _ the new character of a NASA
exploratory team and the challenging new goal _ are seen as linked.
In hiring for the project, the women say, NASA officials seemed to
be eager for experts less vested in the status quo and more willing
to take risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have a higher probability of getting into these roles,''
said Dr. Smrekar, the chief scientist. ``I didn't have the burden
of lots of experience on lots of past projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gavit said youthfulness was probably a more important
factor. ``They didn't want people with the old ways of thinking
because they knew it was a really challenging mission,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The team's composition also had an element of chance. Ms. Lewis
became chief engineer last June when her boss, a man, went into
private business, giving her the lead just as the project reached
its hardest phase, building the tiny craft and finding ways to make
nebulous plans come to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we're women hasn't made a difference,'' she
said. ``It's not an issue here. But it's good that young girls see
that engineering and technical fields are wide open to women.
That's the good thing about saying it's a woman-led team.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's tiny spacecraft, dubbed microprobes, are hitching a
ride to Mars aboard a larger mission known as Mars Polar Lander. In
December, as the large craft nears the planet, the microprobes ,
which are enclosed in so-called aeroshells that shatter on impact,
will fly off and crash-land at more than 400 miles an hour. The
bigger spacecraft will follow, firing rockets to slow its descent
to a soft landing.
</P>
<P>
   For the microprobes, the degree of risk depends on whether the
impact site turns out to be sand dunes, polar ice or unforgiving
solid rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got two tries,'' Ms. Gavit said. ``The whole idea
ultimately is to put eight or 10 of them on spaceships, so if you
lost a couple, it wouldn't be a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   If the microprobes work, the effort will pave the way for new
studies of Mars and other planets and planetary moons.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the December mission fails, Ms. Gavit said, the idea
is so sweet technically that it will flourish in time. Already, she
added, the team's innovations have spread to other projects,
showing the merits of pushing back all kinds of frontiers,
including those of gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have really added to the workplace because we do come at
things from a different angle,'' she said. ``For the same reason
that cultural diversity works, gender diversity is wonderful, too,
especially when you're trying to do something creative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
