<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FINE LINES FOR ETHICS IN SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ ``Medicine is just about life and death,''
said the graybeard Welsh philosopher Andrew Edgar last weekend.
``Sports is more important than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Take doing no harm, for example, certainly an ethical principle
in medicine, but not always one in sports. Can we chastise Mike
Tyson for biting Evander Holyfield's ear, asked Edgar, when both
men were trying to hurt each other in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   The current interest in sports ethics may have to do with the
general crisis in ethics (the ethics of business and politics are
better subjects for Comedy Central than for the academy, and
medical ethics is mired in end-of-life issues) as well as with the
current interest in sports, where moral imperatives and right
versus wrong seem to have no place on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement at a Brown University symposium on
ethics and sports, Edgar, director of the Center for Applied Ethics
at the University of Wales, promised his listeners that they would
find out just ``how difficult and irreconcilable the problems
are.'' Over two days, an impressive roster of panelists seemed to
agree only that politics, power, race, gender, class, disability
and sexual preference were the prisms through which sports could be
understood.
</P>
<P>
   The most personal and moving statement came from Richard
Hoffman, a 50-year-old poet and novelist, who had been raped at 10
by his soccer coach. In his 1995 memoir, ``Half the House''
(Harcourt Brace), Hoffman named the ``predatory coach,'' who had
first used heterosexual pornography to entrap him in a web of shame
and guilt.
</P>
<P>
   After the book's publication, according to Hoffman, he received
hundreds of calls from men who had never before spoken about being
sodomized by their coaches. Many had been raped by the same youth
coach who raped Hoffman. The coach was subsequently arrested and
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman offered specific advice and a program to counteract the
sexual violence that he sees as part of the ``curriculum of
boyhood,'' and thus of sports. But there is also a more systemic
violence, he said, which was put in place by that so-called
greatest generation, which returned from World War II with a
``combat mentality''; the militarism of modern American sports,
such as the authoritarianism of the coach, the insistence on
obedience, and the ``willful confusion of opponents and enemy'' are
among its legacies.
</P>
<P>
   In an even larger and more metaphorical context, Hoffman offered
his own ``Big Coach'' theory, finding the root of all sports ethics
in the Bible. Abraham, after all, was ready to sacrifice Isaac, as
we continue to sacrifice our children to the gods of games.
</P>
<P>
   In other sports news, fans, Richard Lapchick, founder of the
Center for the Study of Sport in Society, reviewed his group's
``racial report cards,'' again finding discouraging statistics on
the representation of blacks in coaching and administration. Eli
Abarbanel-Wolff, a Brown undergraduate who lost fine motor control
of his left arm and leg during heart surgery at 2, discussed
discrimination in sports against the disabled. He has played on the
U.S. National Disabled Soccer team and envisions a disabled
movement in sports on the model of the women's movement.
</P>
<P>
   One notable, and model, activist, Mariah Burton-Nelson, a former
college and pro basketball player and author most recently of
``Embracing Victory'' (Morrow), described a vision of competition
in which athletes ``seek together'' rather than do battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men,'' she said, ``are in danger of thinking winning is
everything while women think winning is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederic Reamer, a professor of social work at Rhode Island
College, led a series of lively panels that managed never to answer
such ethical questions as, Where does the responsibility begin in
the case of a basketball star who, under pressure not to let down
her team, plagiarizes a paper? And, What is the individual
responsibility of a linebacker sent in by his coach to knock out
the opposing quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   William Reynolds, a Providence Journal sports columnist and
author of a memoir, ``Glory Days,'' pointed out that the current
mantra ``Play hard'' contains the implicit ``Go get him.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference was created by Arlene Gorton, a recently retired
professor of physical education and associate athletic director at
Brown. It was not without its own ironies, underscoring Edgar's
premise of ``difficult and irreconcilable.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's record of Title IX compliance led to a bitterly divisive
and expensive lawsuit. Its new president, E. Gordon Gee, was also
president of Ohio State, Colorado and West Virginia, where, as he
enjoys recounting, he entertained prospective donors in his
football box. In his welcoming statement, he told the conference
that he was ``finally making more than the football coach.''
</P>
<P>
   One participant was Larry Farmer, the former UCLA basketball
player and coach and currently head coach at Loyola University in
Chicago. While here, he lobbied unsuccessfully for the head
coaching job at the University of Rhode Island, where he had been
an assistant. He was not pressed on the ethics of leaving a class
of recruits behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
