</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COLORADO, 3 JUDGES RULE ON PENALTY IN MURDER CASE  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., Neb.)  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Three judges in Colorado made history last week in the
state's first case in which a panel of judges, rather than a jury,
decided whether a convicted murderer should be sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   The state law transferring death penalty decisions from a jury
to a panel of judges was enacted in 1995, but its first test did
not come until last week. Criticism of the system mounted as the
panel neared its decision, and one judge who was not on the panel
resigned over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This removes the process from the conscience of the community
and makes it a dry legal process,'' said Richard Dieter, director
of the Death Penalty Information Center in Washington, which has
been critical of the way the death penalty is applied. ``The death
penalty is unique and is supposed to represent the will of the
people and this evolving standard of decency. Although the jury may
not be the perfect instrument, it is the traditional one.''
</P>
<P>
   In this first case, the judges unanimously concluded on Friday
that a life sentence was appropriate for Robert Riggan, citing in
part the reluctance of the jury to find that the murder was
intentional or premeditated.
</P>
<P>
   Riggan, 39, was found guilty last fall of first-degree felony
murder for raping and killing a 22-year-old Denver prostitute in
1997. Riggan has maintained that he is innocent and that the woman
injured herself trying to jump out of his vehicle. He has said he
would rather die than spend the rest of his life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cohen, a Denver lawyer and legal analyst, agrees with the
decision in the Riggan case, but not with how it was reached. ``I
think this was a just result but a terrible procedure,'' he said.
``It is likely to skew the process much more in favor of death
verdicts,'' as judges who are elected might be susceptible to the
wishes of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it seems to me that if juries wanted more death
verdicts,'' Cohen said, ``they would've voted for more.''
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty law in Colorado was backed by prosecutors who
had become frustrated with juries that would not impose capital
punishment and who did not believe juries should be given the death
penalty decision. The three-judge panel in each case is to be led
by the trial judge, with the other judges appointed by the Chief
Justice of the Colorado Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judges have to be concerned their decision will not be about
life or death, but about whether they will be retained as a judge
or not,'' said David Kaplan, a lawyer who represents a murderer
whose fate will be decided by a three-judge panel in May. ``And now
when you have people of conscience dissatisfied with the process
and leaving the bench, you have a bench with those who are greater
advocates for the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado law was modeled on a law in Nebraska, the only
other state to use the judicial panel method. Seven other states
let a judge determine the sentence in a capital case.
</P>
<P>
   There are four people on death row in Colorado. At least five
more death penalty cases will be decided by three-judge panels in
the state this year, and prosecutors in four cases scheduled to
come to trial this year have said that they would seek the death
penalty. Prosecutors say that this is an effect of coincidence and
the deliberate nature of the legal system rather than the new law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, these cases wended their way through the
system,'' said Ray Slaughter, executive director of the Colorado
District Attorneys' Council, ``and we are very circumspect in the
way we change and go forward on cases of this magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kaplan says most of the current cases were filed as death
penalty cases after the new law.
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter defends the law as ``constitutionally correct and
rational.''
</P>
<P>
   But one Colorado judge, Michael J. Heydt, found the law so
problematic that he resigned, effective just one week before he was
to sit on a three-judge panel in early June.
</P>
<P>
   Heydt, a judge for 12 years, described the law as ``manifestly
unworkable'' in his resignation letter and listed three reasons he
would not sit on a panel: a lack of data, time and experience with
a case, a desire to preside over an entire case before deciding a
person's fate and the problem of working with only a ``paper
record.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not wish to participate in a death penalty process,''
Heydt wrote in his resignation letter to the Colorado Supreme
Court, ``unless I believe that it is one that I can live with not
only as a judge but also as a human being.''
</P>
</TEXT>
