<HEADLINE>
YOUNG TEAM AND FEW FANS FOR WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In New York, New York, the Bronx is up and the Battery is down.
But in Chicago, the Cubs are up, and the White Sox are so far down
they are practically invisible. Their fans may be invisible before
long. The White Sox did not have many for their first series of the
season, and the outlook is bleak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be very satisfied if we hit what we did last year, a
million four, a million five, with the young kids,'' Ron Schueler,
the general manager, said. Is there a danger of drawing fewer fans?
``Yeah, if we don't get off to a good start. In Chicago, you better
be playing good by the time school lets out. They want to win on
the South Side. You don't have to win on the other side of town.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of fans the White Sox attract this season is relevant
because, Schueler said, the club relied on the view of fans in
choosing to start over with young players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kind of dictated this is the direction they wanted us to
go,'' he said. ``We had a lot of study groups, went to a lot of big
firms to find out exactly what our plans were. They wanted a
different type team. They wanted guys who would hustle, who would
get dirty, come to play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   So the White Sox let Albert Belle and Robin Ventura exit as free
agents, leaving Frank Thomas the only established and proven hitter
in their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robin's a great player, but he's quiet, no holler stuff,''
Schueler said. ``Albert just turned off everything. He wouldn't
talk to the kids, was rude to them, so that wasn't a fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Thomas, who will be 31 next month, the White Sox
field a team of players in their 20s, the youngest 21. Except for
Thomas, the basic starting batting order (eight players) has a
total of 12 years of major-league experience.
</P>
<P>
   An average crowd of 16,218, lowest in the American League,
watched these youngsters play their first three home games. That's
about the same average the White Sox attracted for their
season-opening series last year. They finished the season with an
average of 17,609 and a total attendance of 1,391,146, third lowest
in the league and lowest at Comiskey Park in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Lee MacPhail, when he was AL president, always said the league
needed a strong Chicago franchise. This version does not meet that
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Some people blame 8-year-old Comiskey Park, the only new park
that has not lured fans. Others blame Jerry Reinsdorf, the team's
chairman. Some fans seemed to be turned off by Reinsdorf's militant
stance during the 1994-95 labor dispute. Then there certainly
appeared to be a backlash to his decision to trade three pitchers
at the trading deadline two years ago when the White Sox were only
three and a half games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   That trade, on the other hand, gave the team its current
shortstop, Mike Caruso, and closer, Bob Howry.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout last winter, speculation had the White Sox trading
Thomas to shed the last of their big salaries. But Thomas remains
the core of the lineup, and Schueler said he expects him to stay
there. To trade Thomas, the general manager said, ``they'd have to
overwhelm me, and I don't see that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   How does Thomas feel about that status?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is home for me,'' he said. ``I'm going to make the best
of the situation regardless of what we've got to deal with. I plan
on spending the rest of my career here.''
</P>
<P>
   And until some of the younger players can develop into lusty
hitters, Thomas said he does not mind being naked in the lineup,
even though he is coming back from the worst of his eight full
seasons in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine,'' he said. ``I can handle it. I'm looking forward
to a big year. That's my goal; that's my plan. I have a role here
now. It's not a selfish Frank Thomas anymore. I'm the protector in
the lineup. I'm going to have to protect the guy who's swinging the
bat well. That will be my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   How about someone protecting him in the lineup? ``I'm not
worried about me,'' he said. ``I don't need any protection.''
</P>
<P>
   He has certainly not needed any so far. In Chicago's first nine
games, Thomas collected 15 hits in 29 at-bats for a league-leading
.517 average. He hit two home runs and drove in seven runs. Last
year he batted .265, his first sub-.300 performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think about it anymore,'' he said of last year.
``It was one of those growing years. I had marital problems.
Everything went wrong. It was a stressful year. I wasn't playing
well; I wasn't doing well off the field. It was a roller coaster
last year. The game was not as much fun. Now I'm back having fun
and having fun with this young team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Enjoying Home-Run Tear
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bell allowed himself a moment of fantasy. ``If the season
stopped today,'' he said before Friday night's games, a smile in
his voice, ``I'd be the home run champ.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks' second baseman indeed was the
major-league home-run leader, his five home runs putting him one
ahead of several players, including Mark McGwire, who last year hit
50 more home runs than Bell. With five in 10 games, Bell is 16
games ahead of his 1998 pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good spring training,'' the 33-year-old Bell said.
``But if I had to predict what would happen the first couple weeks
of the season, I would have had a real rough time because we were
facing tough pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks played their first 10 games against Los Angeles
and Atlanta. ``To have five home runs against the Dodger pitchers
is not the norm,'' said Bell, who hit his home runs against Kevin
Brown, Mel Rojas, Ismael Valdes (two) and Carlos Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, helping the Diamondbacks to three consecutive victories
over the Dodgers, whacked four of those home runs last week, which
was a ding dong of a week for all of baseball's Bells. Besides
Jay's four, David Bell of Seattle hit three and Derek Bell of
Houston hit his first of the season. Then there was a variation on
the theme: Albert Belle of Baltimore slugged a pair of home runs
against Roger Clemens of the Yankees on Thursday night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Strides of the Shortstops
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez is envious of his best friend, but he begrudges
Derek Jeter nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Derek has reached the pinnacle,'' Rodriguez, the
Seattle Mariners' injured star shortstop, said. ``He's certainly
reached the highest standpoint you can reach from a winning
standpoint. Two out of three years is pretty tough to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   But his fellow shortstop can get better as a hitter, just as he
and Nomar Garciaparra of Boston, the other super young shortstop,
can, Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an offensive standpoint, I think we can all get much
better,'' he remarked. ``Derek has made the most remarkable strides
out of all three of us. I think Derek has a good work ethic. He's
in a good environment to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter is off to a remarkable start, leading the league in
slugging, total bases and extra-base hits going into the weekend,
an unusual position for a shortstop. Albert Belle led the league in
those three categories last season. But nothing the Yankees'
youngest regular does surprises Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides being my best friend, he's one of the biggest
competitors I've ever met in my life,'' said the currently disabled
Rodriguez. ``We always talk about ways to get better. He's always
thinking of how he's going to get better. He's always asking me
questions. He's relentless. He's going to keep getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken Showing Weaknesses
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken's performance at Yankee Stadium last week did nothing
to discourage growing speculation that his career could be over
sooner than expected. The fading Baltimore star had difficulty
hitting and fielding as his batting average fell to .174, and his
number of errors rose to five in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken did have a rough ending to spring training with the death
of his father and a tough start to the season with a back ailment,
but his early play lent credence to the view of a former teammate
that once his incredible consecutive-games streak ended, Ripken
could lose his focus and determination.
</P>
<P>
   Indicative of the doubt about his hitting prowess was the
sacrifice bunt he executed in the third inning of the third game of
the Yankee series with the Orioles behind, 5-4. The first two
batters in the inning singled, and instead of swinging away and
trying to drive in one or both, Ripken sacrificed them to third and
second. The next batter was Charles Johnson, a .234 career hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken left New York needing 118 hits (it was 122 when the
season began) to reach 3,000. In 17 seasons, his lowest hit total
was 140, and that was in the strike-shortened 1994 season. But he
could very well fail to get to 3,000 this season because the time
may soon come when the Orioles decide they have to give Willis
Otanez, a rookie, a chance to show what he can do at third. Otanez,
in fact, played Friday night in Toronto as Ripken was benched.
</P>
<P>
   If that time comes, Ray Miller may not be the manager who makes
the decision. Even though Miller was not responsible for putting
together the Orioles' ill-conceived collection of players, he
figures to be the first person to take the blame for the team's
failure on the field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
