<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: CADE McNOWN, THE RUNT WHO WOULD BE FAVRE  
(jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cade McNown is the runt of the litter. Not that strong an arm.
Not that tall. Not that quick. At least according to most scouting
reports. That's why this 22-year-old left-hander was the fifth
quarterback selected in Saturday's National Football League draft,
behind Tim Couch, Donovan McNabb, Akili Smith and Daunte Culpepper.
The Bears took McNown with the 12th selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a lot of scouts miss the forest for the trees,'' McNown
was saying. ``They worry about a guy having one more mile per hour
on his arm, or about one guy running the 40 in 4.6, another guy in
4.57. But one scout told me I had a stronger arm than two of the
guys who are here.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown didn't identify those two quarterbacks, but by ``here,''
he meant two of the four higher-rated quarterbacks waiting with him
backstage in the Theater at Madison Square Garden for their names
and teams to be announced by Commissioner Paul Tagliabue shortly
after the draft began. McNown assumed he would be the last of the
five.
</P>
<P>
   ``But ultimately,'' he said, ``you're going to be judged on
production. Accurate passes. Moving the team. Winning games.
Winning championships.''
</P>
<P>
   McNown's production at UCLA was impressive. He led the Bruins to
a 10-2 record and the Rose Bowl last season; they scored at least
40 points in seven games. Over his Pac-10 career, his 11,285 yards
of total offense ranked first, his 10,708 passing yards ranked
second and his 68 touchdown passes ranked third.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not as if he were really a runt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Im 6 feet 7/8 of an inch, so I say I'm 6-1,'' he said. ``I
weigh between 210 and 215.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Couch is 6-4 and 227, McNabb 6-2 and 226, Smith 6-2
and 221 and Culpepper 6-4 and 252.
</P>
<P>
   Not that McNown cares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be 4 feet 3 inches; then I could throw under the
pass rushers,'' he joked. ``Hey, I wouldn't change my height for
anything. Most great quarterbacks, there's something quirky about
them. I'm just looking forward to the challenge. It's the next
step.''
</P>
<P>
   As a left-handed passer, McNown has created comparisons to Steve
Young and Mark Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young runs the same offense with the 49ers that I ran at
UCLA,'' McNown said, ``but he may do things way different. I was a
big Joe Montana fan. And I've gotten to know Troy Aikman pretty
well.''
</P>
<P>
   When he smiles, McNown has that same mischief in his eyes that
Brett Favre does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way Favre plays,'' he said of the Packers' All-Pro.
``If a linebacker is coming, he'll try to run over him. He likes to
get his nose into it. I do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What McNown is saying is that, at heart, Favre is a football
player, not just a quarterback, and so is he.
</P>
<P>
   At the NFL scouting combine in Indianapolis in February, not
many quarterbacks were willing to be timed in the 40-yard dash.
McNown ran for the stopwatches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my nature,'' he said. ``I love to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   As a youngster, he competed at almost every position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was big in the fifth grade, so they put me at offensive
guard and defensive lineman,'' he recalled. ``Then I went to being
a linebacker and a fullback, then a running back and an outside
linebacker, then a quarterback and a free safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to create a family crest as a sixth grader in Hollister,
Calif., the red-haired McNown drew a cross with a football and a
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   When his parents divorced, he moved with his mother to West
Linn, Ore., to be near his older brother, Jeff Jr. During his only
year at West Linn High, he was both a quarterback and a free safety
before enrolling at UCLA, where he was a history major.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an ancient language,'' he has said with a wink, ``McNown
meant football.''
</P>
<P>
   And as soon as he arrives at training camp, McNown will mean
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody is ahead of me, I'll just keep pushing,'' he said
firmly but quietly. ``When I get the opportunity, I'll make that
guy a Wally Pipp.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows baseball history, too. Wally Pipp was the Yankee first
baseman who never got his job back after Lou Gehrig was installed.
</P>
<P>
   Cade McNown also won't be afraid to speak up in an NFL huddle,
even as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   After Terry Donohue resigned as the UCLA coach after the 1995
season, the Bruins' hierarchy sought Gary Barnett, then at
Northwestern, and Rick Neuheisel, then at Colorado, but both
spurned the job.
</P>
<P>
   McNown, then 18, told Pete Dalis, the UCLA athletic director,
that Bob Toledo, then the offensive coordinator, deserved the job.
Toledo got it.
</P>
<P>
   And when Cade McNown, the runt of the quarterback litter, was
asked before the draft to assess his NFL potential as if he were an
NFL scout, he spoke up, quickly and defiantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say, `Get him.''' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
