<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-BOSTON-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LYNN JENNINGS, THIS TIME IT'S FOR REAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Lynn Jennings' memory plays tricks.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers back to 1975, when she was in the ninth grade and
watched on television as Bill Rodgers stopped twice to tie his
shoelaces and still won the Boston Marathon. But she says she
remembers little about 1978 when, as a 17-year-old high school
senior, she ran her first Boston Marathon _ unofficially, because
no one under 18 was supposed to run _ and was the third woman to
cross the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, running officially, she has become one of the
world's premier distance runners. In 1990, 1991 and 1992, she won
three consecutive world cross-country championships. In 1992, she
won an Olympic bronze medal at 10,000 meters. She has won 39 U.S.
championships and holds six American records.
</P>
<P>
   But she has never officially run a marathon. That will change
Monday when, at 38, the pride of Newmarket, N.H., will run in the
103rd annual Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Fatuma Roba of Ethiopia, who has won the women's race here the
last two years in 2 minutes 26 minutes 33 seconds and then 2:23:21,
is favored again. Her rivals include Franca Fiacconi of Italy, who
won last year's New York City Marathon; Colleen De Reuck of South
Africa, Anuta Catuna of Romania and Catherine Ndereba of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings seems likely to run in the 2:20s. She says only that
she wants to run 2:42, the automatic qualifying time for next
year's U.S. Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my publicly stated goal,'' Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   And her private goal?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's private,'' she said. ``Besides, John and I haven't had
our summit meeting yet. We will on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   John Babbington has been her coach much of the time since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a lawyer,'' she said. ``He went to Harvard. I went to
Princeton. These are long, detailed sessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings has not always listened. In 1978, she wanted to run in
this most hallowed of all marathons. Babbington said she was too
young, and besides, the minimum age was 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I ran,'' she said, ``because John told me not to. It was
typical 17-year-old rationale.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle Barron, who was 30, won in 2:44:52. Jennings finished
third in about 2:46 _ she received no official time _ but don't ask
her about that race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember nothing,'' she said. ``I have complete amnesia.
There's no psychological insight or Freudian reason. I just can't
recall. I've run a lot of races in the intervening 21 years. And as
Shakespeare said, `What's past is prologue.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings said she did not swear off the marathon after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I just got sidetracked by all the other things I could
do running,'' she said. ``The marathon has been lurking in the back
of my mind, but the timing never seemed right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a reason to move up, and I don't now. It would be
a mistake to think I'm no longer a track runner. I've done
everything else, and now I'm going to do something else. I am an
experienced runner, not an experienced marathoner.''
</P>
<P>
   No American woman has won here since Lisa Larsen Weidenbach in
1985, no American man since Greg Meyer in 1983. Jennings says she
feels no pressure because she does not consider herself a
contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running my own race,'' she said. ``I think I'll be in the
pack. I'm comfortable with the course. I know every inch of it. I
know the towns. I've done all the work necessary. I'm ready to put
that work to use. I would like to have a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Her preparation has been exemplary. She trained nearby during a
relatively mild New England winter. She did nine or 10 20-mile
training runs. On March 31, she finished behind seven men in a
half-marathon in New Bedford, Mass., in the good time of 1:11:41.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I would be on a couch prone after a 20-mile
training run,'' she said. ``I wasn't. After the last one, I took my
dog on a four-mile walk.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows the knowledgeable crowd will be cheering for her, but
she is quick to say: ``Boston is an egalitarian town. People here
cheer for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   She was going to run here last year, then backed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't injured,'' she said. ``It was not so much my training
as my mental discipline. It was like the difference between reading
and studying. Last year, I was reading. Now I'm cracking the books.
I feel robust, optimistic, eager. It's going to be a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun? Marathon runners seldom use that word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's fun,'' she said. ``I'm at ease. I don't run scared.
I don't get nervous. I'm an emotional runner. I get adrenaline.
I've been in this situation in the world championships and
Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, running seems to be as rewarding as ever. Would
she be as happy with life without running?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not if I can help it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
