<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2597 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-COMMISSIONE     04-17 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-COMMISSIONER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYPD COMMISSIONER, UNDER FIRE, DEFENDS HIS CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This story subs for HOSPITAL-ROOMS on Page One of Sunday's
metro edition.) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 BY DAN BARRY AND MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For three years now, Police Commissioner Howard Safir
has dutifully taken his place behind Mayor Rudolph Giuliani at news
conferences, his hands folded, his face set in inscrutability. It
is the enduring image of a friendship forged by time shared in
federal service, one in which roles are understood and discretion
is a given.
</P>
<P>
   But now Safir suddenly finds himself front and center _ and
under attack.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fatal police shooting of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed
African immigrant, in February, his department has been accused of
being insensitive to black and Hispanic residents, sometimes to the
point of brutality. Some of his recent actions have prompted
questions about his judgment and inquiries into his ethics. Then,
last week, the dominant police union cast a vote of no confidence
in his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout it all _ even as his own job approval ratings plummet
_ Giuliani has steadfastly supported the friend he lured into city
service, a man he described in an interview last week as honest,
straightforward and ``a very regular guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Howard Safir known to the mayor is not the Howard Safir
revealed to the city. What the public sees, often through the prism
of the press, is a tall, jaw-jutting symbol of federal arrogance, a
man not at peace with microphones and not inclined to provide basic
public information. He is so reserved that some police officers are
unaware of his background as a federal agent and dismiss him as a
former fire commissioner _ in other words, an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   This is not how Safir sees himself.
</P>
<P>
   In an extensive interview on Friday, he talked of his long
career as a federal law enforcement agent who worked on several
high-profile cases. He also defended the professional and personal
decisions he has made and criticized the press for unfair coverage
of him.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is he as reserved as he often appears. For one thing, he
considered his experiences in law enforcement so exciting that he
once unsuccessfully shopped around a book proposal and even toyed
with plans to help create a fictional television series.
</P>
<P>
   For another, he is a self-confessed ``Parrot Head,'' a member of
the corps of Hawaiian-shirted, margarita-drinking fans of singer
Jimmy Buffett. ``I have every single one of his albums,'' he said.
``I know the words to every song. And in fact, when I go to the
concerts I sing every one of his songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir, 57, who grew up in the Bronx, argued that his public
persona belies his private, good-humored self.
</P>
<P>
   ``I unfortunately am stuck with a face that has a down-turned
mouth,'' he said. ``When my face is not animated _ when I'm just
sitting somewhere _ I look like I'm mad. But I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   The job, by nature, does not lend itself to humor. ``In a way,
it's very difficult to project when you're talking about homicides,
rapes, explosions. It's very difficult for that image to come
across,'' Safir said. ``I was just talking to a friend of mine who
said: `How come they don't really know who you are?'''
</P>
<P>
   Before choosing to stand in the shadow of Giuliani, Safir had
already lived a life of adventure, intrigue and some acclaim. After
working as an undercover agent for the federal agency that would
become the Drug Enforcement Administration, he moved on to the U.S.
Marshals Service, where he made a name for himself tracking down
fugitives and reviving the service's troubled witness-protection
program.
</P>
<P>
   Among his cases was Christopher John Boyce, the ``falcon'' of
``The Falcon and the Snowman'' fame, a convicted Soviet spy who had
escaped from a federal prison in Lompoc, Calif. After a lengthy
investigation, Safir recalled, Boyce was captured in Washington
state as he was about to board a private plane bound for the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christopher Boyce was the spy who cost the United States the
most money in history,'' Safir said. ``He gave the Russians all of
the codes to our spy satellites, which meant that all of our spy
satellites had to be retooled, which cost billions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1980s, Safir's successes and administrative
abilities had caught the attention of Giuliani, who was also then
in Washington, as the third-highest-ranking official in the Justice
Department. ``The Marshals Service had changed from being a
semi-political operation to a very, very excellent law enforcement
organization,'' the mayor recalled. ``Much of that was due to
Howard's work.''
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship was strong enough by 1984 that Safir called
on Giuliani to testify on his behalf in a lawsuit in which he had
accused Geraldo Rivera of slandering him in a television report
about the witness-protection program. That lawsuit was later
settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani returned to New York to become the U.S. Attorney
for the Southern District, he and Safir continued to work together,
further strengthening their friendship.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, however, both men had left the federal
government. Giuliani was planning a second run for mayor, while
Safir was overseeing a private security business that until
recently was run by his wife, Carol, and his son, Adam.
</P>
<P>
   Public records show that he and his wife, who is a real estate
agent and investor, own 10 pieces of property with a combined worth
of between $500,000 and $1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Safir was also trying to sell his story, and one such attempt
resulted in a lawsuit. Dan E. Moldea, a freelance writer, was
awarded $17,500 in 1995 after accusing Safir of hiring him to work
on a book without revealing that he already had unsuccessfully
sought a publisher.
</P>
<P>
   A book proposal in the court files opens with a dramatic,
first-person account of one of Safir's adventures: an episode in
which he is inside a church crowded with dignitaries that has just
received a bomb threat. It reads, in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a small bead of sweat begin to form on my forehead as I
whispered to Mickey, `Have you swept the place?' He replied: `Dogs
and a complete physical search.' I looked at him and said, `That's
why I get the big bucks, we'll sweat it out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Safir joined the Giuliani administration in 1994 as fire
commissioner. In 1996, when the mayor forced the resignation of
Police Commissioner William J. Bratton, known almost as much for
his love of the limelight as for his successful innovations in
fighting crime, he selected Safir to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main reasons I selected him was that I knew he had
this ability to have tremendous command and organization of
facts,'' the mayor said, ``of how to analyze problems and to come
up with solutions, and to make good personnel choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three years, Safir generally presented himself as
the un-Bratton _ tight-lipped, often hostile to the press, not one
to take Bratton's place at late-night sessions at Elaine's.
Although he was often portrayed as Giuliani's marionette,
administration officials say that Safir feels comfortable enough to
challenge the mayor on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard is not afraid to tell the mayor what he thinks and to
disagree with him,'' said Peter Powers, a former deputy mayor. ``He
follows the rule that most people follow: You disagree in private,
you don't disagree in public.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani agreed. ``It's a professional relationship, but it's
also a personal relationship,'' he said. ``Howard disagrees with me
fairly often enough, and has, at times, been able to talk me out of
things that he thought were the wrong approach.''
</P>
<P>
   During his three-year tenure, Safir has frequently been
dismissed as a caretaker for crime-reducing policies instituted by
Bratton and has drawn criticism for several administrative miscues,
including a proposal to have a New York City Police Department
presence in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   But Safir maintained that he would be remembered for a number of
programs: the city's expanded anti-drug initiatives, the
installation of security cameras in city housing projects and his
call for taking DNA samples from everyone who is arrested. Most
important, the crime rate has fallen even more sharply under Safir
than it did under Bratton.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the strong Giuliani-Safir relationship is being
tested.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting death of Diallo, who was black, by four white
police officers renewed charges that police officers mistreat black
and Hispanic residents in ways ranging from discourtesy to civil
rights violations to brutality. It also aimed the spotlight on
Safir because the officers belonged to the Street Crime Unit, an
aggressive squad whose success in making gun arrests had led the
commissioner to triple its size and, some say, dilute its
precision.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to the case snowballed, as protesters rallied
outside Police Headquarters, the four officers were indicted on
murder charges and federal and state officials began investigations
into Police Department practices. The mayor and Safir at first
resisted calls for reform, but in recent weeks have met with
community groups and have begun to announce a series of modest
changes in police policy.
</P>
<P>
   But the spotlight on Safir has lingered. In the midst of the
outcry over the Diallo shooting, he and his wife flew to Los
Angeles for the Academy Awards on a private jet as guests of a
corporate executive whom the commissioner describes as a friend.
Images of Safir at the ceremony, in a tuxedo and mingling with
celebrities, caught some City Council members by surprise: They had
been told he would probably miss a hearing on the Diallo case the
next morning because of a ``scheduling conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   With news of his California trip causing a stir in New York,
Safir caught a red-eye flight back to the city in time to attend
the hearing. It did not help matters that the Giuliani
administration had criticized his predecessor, Bratton, for
accepting similar trips. Safir's trip has sparked two ethics
inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Then came news that Safir had dispatched two detectives to the
home of a Queens woman who had given a false name after her car
rear-ended one being driven by his wife. The accident came to light
after a lawsuit naming the Safirs as plaintiffs was filed in
Manhattan Supreme Court; it alleged that the Queens woman was
intoxicated and that Safir had lost the ``consortium'' of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, reports surfaced that eight police detectives had been
assigned to the January wedding of the police commissioner's
daughter, an FBI agent, and had assisted in chauffeuring guests.
</P>
<P>
   Public Advocate Mark Green has called for Safir's resignation,
and the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, in a no-confidence
vote, has demanded his suspension.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani said that the criticism is a result of a
``pile-on'' attack by a press in mid-frenzy. ``Are there times when
I would do something differently, or when he would do something
differently? Of course,'' the mayor said. ``But I think he has
excellent judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the police commissioner defiantly defended his
handling of the car accident and the wedding as appropriate, even
necessary, for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my wife had this accident, a woman ran into the back of
her car and lied'' about her name, he said. ``Anybody in law
enforcement knows that this is a great technique for finding out
people's addresses, for finding out who people are. When we found
out that this woman lied, I wanted to find out who she was, to see
if she was a threat to me or my family. And once we found out who
she was, that was the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He also insisted that the lawsuit in his name was filed without
his knowledge and he has since fired the lawyer. While the matter
of loss of consortium was raised in the lawsuit, he called the
press' coverage of that detail a ``cheap shot.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his night at the Oscars, Safir shared some remorse _ but
not much.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight, would I go to the Oscars?'' he said. ``Probably
not, but only because, in hindsight, I know what the media has made
of it. But do I believe that I did something improper in going to
the Oscars? I don't believe I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be easy to be contrite and say, `I did something
terrible,' '' he added. ``I don't believe I did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
