<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALENDAR CHANGES MAY AVOID BURNOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this time of year, National Football League general managers
and coaches get to the office at 6 a.m. and leave well after the
sun comes down. And for the coaches, that kind of schedule is
nothing new. Whether it is this weekend's draft, or the scouting
combine, or coaching in the Pro Bowl, five hours of shut-eye is
sleeping in to the average coach. Vacations? What are those?
</P>
<P>
   Never before have pro football coaches had so little downtime, a
situation created by free agency. After the Super Bowl comes the
Pro Bowl in Hawaii, an assignment you would think coaches would
love. But Jets Coach Bill Parcells skipped the Pro Bowl this year,
citing his health. The common perception among coaches was that
Parcells simply did not want to go because he was tired from a long
season.
</P>
<P>
   After the Pro Bowl comes the deadline to designate franchise and
transition players. Then comes the free-agent signing period. Then
the trading period begins, and the scouting combine in Indianapolis
follows. And it is only February.
</P>
<P>
   There are owners' meetings in March, the restricted free-agency
period, the draft in April, more meetings in May. In June, head
coaches start to put together their plans for training camp in
July. After camp comes the season, and then it starts all over
again.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches are extremely well paid, with some, like Parcells,
making millions of dollars a year. So no one should cry for them.
But it is has become clear to members of the league's competition
committee that a break must be built into the system, or the league
will lose coaches to burnout. Last year, Miami Coach Jimmy Johnson
almost quit, citing the pressures of the game and how it had taken
over his life.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many so-called old-school coaches, like Johnson,
Parcells, Mike Ditka of New Orleans and Jim Mora of Indianapolis,
have complained in recent years about how coaches no longer have
any chance to have a life. It would not be surprising if those four
_ especially Parcells _ retired from coaching at the end of next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is much, much more tough for coaches now than it ever
was,'' Rich McKay, general manager of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers,
said. ``The off-season is gone. You're constantly on the job. The
pressure to win is constant.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition committee, of which McKay is a member, is
considering making significant changes to the NFL calendar. The
league wants to move the start of free agency from February to
sometime in mid-March, McKay said. The idea is to make February a
down month, so coaches can take vacations and spend more time with
their families.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has already spoken to the players' union about the
proposed changes, and there is agreement. The change could be
implemented in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   McKay was asked if he would ever coach. ``I might try it
someday,'' he said, ``but under the conditions that coaches work
now, I don't know how long I would last.''
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay Drafts Well
</P>
<P>
   A number of teams have drafted extremely well during the '90s,
the Pittsburgh Steelers and Green Bay Packers among them. But the
Tampa Bay Buccaneers has arguably drafted as well as any of them,
thanks to Rich McKay, one of the more talented _ and underrated _
general managers in the game.
</P>
<P>
   McKay was officially named general manager of the Buccaneers in
1994, but had really been doing the job beginning one year earlier.
Under McKay, who has emerged as one of the best talent evaluators
in football, the team has gone from the Yuccaneers to one of the
top franchises in the league.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1998 Pro Bowl, the Buccaneers were the only team
represented by at least one player from each of their drafts from
1993 to 1997: safety John Lynch (1993), quarterback Trent Dilfer
(1994), linebacker Derrick Brooks and defensive lineman Warren Sapp
(1995), fullback Mike Alstott (1996) and running back Warrick Dunn
(1997). In the 1996 draft, the Buccaneers got four starters:
Alstott, cornerback Donnie Abraham, tackle Jason Odom and defensive
end Regan Upshaw.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 25 players drafted by McKay since 1993 are still on the
roster. That's a pretty good track record.
</P>
<P>
   McKay knew when he took the job that changes had to be made in
the way Tampa Bay drafted. So the first thing McKay did was sit
down with Buccaneer scouts and others to ask what they thought was
wrong. ``The feelings were pretty unanimous about what we needed to
fix,'' McKay said.
</P>
<P>
   McKay felt that the organization was putting too much emphasis
on potential and not enough on what a player did on the field. In
other words, McKay wanted to pay less attention to stopwatches and
shuttle runs in postseason workouts, and more to performance in
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not had to dip that much into free agency because
we've drafted well, and that has helped the franchise,'' McKay
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
