<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, April 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a very chilly start with pockets of early morning frost,
abundant sunshine will cover the southeastern states on Sunday as
high pressure builds across the Gulf of Mexico. Despite the potency
of the midspring sun, afternoon temperatures will average 5 to 10
degrees cooler than normal across the region with daytime readings
generally in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, residual moisture trailing a cold front will
bring clouds and scattered showers to extreme southern Florida on
Sunday morning. Drier breezes from the northwest, however, will
promote clearing skies over northern and central sections of the
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Stubborn low, gray clouds will obscure the sun throughout the
Great Lakes and portions of the interior Northeast. Most of the day
will be dry, though spotty light showers will occur at times,
especially over southern Michigan, Ohio and western Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, the air will likely be sufficiently cool to
produce a few flurries over the Green and White mountains of New
England. Winds from the northwest drying on descent from the
Appalachians will cause clouds to crumble east of the mountains,
where intervals of sunshine and milder conditions will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Dry weather will rule the western states on Sunday as a large
high-pressure system persists. Patchy clouds, however, will cover
the sky at times across the Pacific Northwest and northern Rockies.
Meanwhile, abundant sunshine will promote record warmth in parts of
Southern California and deserts of the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Frost Above Freezing
</P>
<P>
   Frost can cover the ground when the official temperature is
above 32 degrees. Early Saturday, a late frost was noted in
portions of Texas and the interior Southeast as the mercury hovered
above freezing. Official thermometers are placed 5 feet above the
ground. On a clear, calm night, the air at the ground cools rapidly
as it loses heat to space. As the night goes on, the layer of cold
air gets deeper, but the coldest and densest air hugs the ground.
The difference between the ground temperature and the official
temperature can be more than 5 degrees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
