<HEADLINE>
BLEAK FORECAST FOR A MATCHING FUND 
NATIONAL PARTY RULES? FORGET ABOUT THEM 
REPUBLICANS DECIDE TO IGNORE DAVID DUKE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., La.)   (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More bad news from the tax man for those who would be president.
</P>
<P>
   The federal fund that matches cash raised by candidates running
in primaries and caucuses _ dollar for dollar per contributor, up
to $250 _ is running out of money.
</P>
<P>
   The problem?
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, as citizen dissatisfaction with the political
system has spread, fewer and fewer taxpayers have been checking the
box on the tax form that authorizes the IRS to shift $3 of their
tax payments to the matching-funds pool. Making things worse, at
the same time that the checkoff rate has been falling, to 10
percent this year from almost 30 percent in 1976, the demand for
matching money has been steadily growing as candidates have been
forced to raise ever more cash to meet the ever-escalating cost of
running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Come Election 2000, the demand for matching funds could be the
greatest ever, given that more than a dozen people are talking
about running.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials of the Federal Election Commission, which
administers the matching money, when the initial requests for
Election 2000 come in next Jan. 1, they are likely to total $65
million or more unless the current field of hopefuls shrinks. But
at that point, the commission projects, there will be no more than
$20 million in the pot. And on top of that, the commission projects
that candidates will file for $35 million more in matching cash
before the primary and caucus season ends.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   The checkoff will produce more than $20 million this year for
distribution in Election 2000. In fact, the take may be as much as
$70 million. But at least $50 million of that must be set aside up
front to help finance national nominating conventions and the fall
race that follows.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we'll have left _ the $20 million _ will be all that
candidates get initially for the primaries and caucuses,'' said Ian
Stirton, a commission spokesman. ``They'll still be entitled to the
full $65 million that they've requested, but we'll just have to
make it up with late payments drawn from tax checkoffs in later
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The late payments may be but a small inconvenience for
candidates able to raise a lot of money on their own, like Vice
President Al Gore, currently the leading Democrat, and Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, currently the leading Republican. But most other
candidates will probably be left scrambling at a time when they
need every possible dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The Election 2000 primary and caucus schedule is the most
``front-loaded'' ever, with the most important contests scheduled
in February and early March.
</P>
<P>
   Some candidates will most likely take out loans, putting their
government IOU up as collateral. But there will be plenty of
interest to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels in South Carolina
</P>
<P>
   The way Democratic leaders in South Carolina figured it, the
Republicans, already on a roll in the state, would get a free
publicity ride if they were the only party on the presidential
primary ballot next Feb. 26. So when the state Democratic executive
committee met on Tuesday, it voted unanimously to hold the South
Carolina Democratic primary on that date, too.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody pointed out that under rules set by the Democratic
National Committee, all state parties, with the traditional
exception of New Hampshire and Iowa, are forbidden to hold either a
presidential primary or caucus before the first Tuesday in March.
But the South Carolinians decided to ignore that prohibition on the
ground that their struggling party needs all the help it can get.
Besides, it was argued, everybody else seems to be joining the rush
to the front end of the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to go our own way,'' said Dick Harpootlian, the
party's outspoken chairman, adding that in his judgment the
national party had almost totally ignored the needs and problems of
South Carolina Democrats in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC is not ignoring Tuesday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   It has sent word to Harpootlian that if the primary is not reset
to conform with national party rules, 25 percent of the state's
delegates to the national convention will not be seated, including
Harpootlian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Party rules are very clear,'' Peter Kauffmann, a spokesman for
the national committee, said on Thursday. ``We're intent on having
a balanced primary and caucus schedule. But we're also willing to
work with them, to compromise. Perhaps they could make the Feb. 26
vote nothing but a beauty contest and then reschedule an event,
within our rules, at which they would actually take an official
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Harpootlian seems little interested in a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being disconnected from the national party isn't all that
bad,'' he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans Duke It Out
</P>
<P>
   Ever since former Rep. Robert Livingston of Louisiana's 1st
Congressional District resigned, opening the way for a special
election on May 1 to choose a successor, there has been little
doubt that the winner almost certainly will be a Republican, like
Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   But which Republican?
</P>
<P>
   There are seven running, among them David Treen, a former
governor and member of Congress; Monica Monica, a wealthy eye
doctor with an eye-catching name; and David Vitter, a state
representative.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is David Duke, a former state representative but more
famously _ some would say infamously _ a former Ku Klux Klan
leader.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Republican leaders in Louisiana, and also in
Washington, have worried that in a contest crowded with nine
candidates (there are also two Democrats running), no candidate
would emerge as a clean winner, with more than 50 percent of the
vote. That would mean a runoff, and Republican leaders fear that
given the particular kind of appeal that Duke has in a Deep South
district, he just might make that runoff.
</P>
<P>
   After that, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Rather than face that question, Republican leaders, especially
those running the National Republican Congressional Committee, have
been exploring the idea of abandoning the party's usual policy of
remaining neutral in contests involving more than one Republican.
They commissioned a poll to determine who might be the best bet,
who might head off Duke by winning outright on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   The precise results of the poll have not been made public. But
Rep. Jim McCrery of Shreveport, a committee member, said Treen, Ms.
Monica and Vitter all ran well, especially Treen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's moot,'' McCrery added, ``because David Duke ran
even worse than the Democrats. We'd do better to worry about them.
We don't have to get into this. Duke's not a player. Let the field
fight it out and go on to a runoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke's response?
</P>
<P>
   His polls have him on top.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
