<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GRETZKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE GREAT GRETZKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Sunday, April 18:
</P>
<P>
   Just as the name Michael Jordan registered with those who pay no
attention to basketball, so Wayne Gretzky infiltrated the
consciousness of a much larger group of Americans who care little
for professional hockey. Athletes cannot do that unless they are
transcendently good. Gretzky was that good, over a 21-year career
that began in Edmonton, Alberta, and will end with one last
appearance in a New York Rangers uniform at Madison Square Garden
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers tell only part of the story. He holds the record for
points scored with 2,856, including an astounding 1,962 assists, a
testament to his uncanny ability to find the open man and make the
perfect pass. He was voted hockey's most valuable player nine times
and led the Edmonton Oilers to four Stanley Cups. Traded to Los
Angeles in 1988, he is seen as a kind of Johnny Appleseed of the
sport, spreading what was essentially a Canadian game to America's
Sun Belt.
</P>
<P>
   But what truly set Gretzky apart from most hockey players was
his awareness. In a game known for strength and speed, Gretzky was
neither strong nor particularly fast. He was small and slender _
floating, as Jordan did, almost above the game, knowing at any
given moment where the puck and the players were on the swirling
ice around him and sensing, intuitively, where they would be a
moment hence. Most hockey fans go to hockey games to root for their
home team, and a few go to watch the fights. But some went just to
watch Gretzky, who played a game all his own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1558EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-EASTNOTES18-C     04-17 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-EASTNOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Riley: Wilkens' record is secure
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pat Riley, 54, said catching up to 61-year-old Lenny
Wilkens' all-time record for coaching victories ``is not a goal. If
I decide to coach another 10 years, I guarantee you Lenny Wilkens
will still be coaching. I see him winning 50 games a year for the
next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't catch him,'' Riley said after winning his 939th last
week. ``I will probably retire before he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley's winning percentage (.700) is second among coaches who
worked at least 400 games behind Phil Jackson's .738. The Heat
coach has moved into third place on the all-time victory list,
trailing only Bill Fitch (944) and Wilkens (1,144) through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only joy I take in that is I never thought this would
happen to me,'' Riley said. ``I was hired as an interim coach, and
I thought it would be short-lived. I never thought I would be more
than four or five years in it, and here I am 17 years later. Being
in the company of guys I really admire _ (Jack) Ramsay, Fitch,
(Dick) Motta, (Red) Auerbach. It's great company to be in, and I'm
flattered I could stay around this long.''
</P>
<P>
   Knicks' hefty payroll
</P>
<P>
   According to the New York Times, the Knicks' $68.6 million
payroll is the highest by far in the NBA, with Portland second at
$53 million and Indiana next at $51 million. Madison Square Garden
president Dave Checketts denied there were problems between club
president Ernie Grunfeld and coach Jeff Van Gundy, but it's clear
the payroll will weigh heavily in the evaluation of Grunfeld after
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what we've invested, the results have been
disappointing,'' Checketts said. ``When the Knicks were in the NBA
Finals, we were at $26 million on our payroll. So, yes, we've spent
a lot. I understand that. It hasn't worked out, and the
responsibility comes back to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacers getting serious
</P>
<P>
   They've eliminated the theatrics in Indiana, vowing it's time
for business.
</P>
<P>
   That dance routine the Pacers do at introductions is history.
Mark Pope's ritual encouraging offbeat talks to the team are over.
</P>
<P>
   Pregame huddles are limited to pertinent matters only, with
everybody on court exactly 18 minutes before tip-off.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Jackson says, ``We pretty much took away our privilege of
doing things with flair. That has nothing to do with winning or
losing, but that's something that was a privilege because we were
an elite team. We've gotten away from playing like that, so until
we show we're there again, we've put it on ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Strickland cautions Marbury
</P>
<P>
   Rod Strickland, a former Knicks point guard, didn't disagree
when Stephon Marbury said the Knicks will never win with Chris
Childs and Charlie Ward on point. But the Wizards' Strickland
warned Marbury that it might not be wise to disrespect other NBA
players that way. ``Young guys speak their mind, but we're men
first,'' Strickland said. ``I respect everybody in this league. I
respect the fact that they got in this league. You have to be good
to be here. But for me, it's an issue of how we relate to each
other, man to man.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
