<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marbury the Mouth
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It apparently wasn't enough for Stephon Marbury to
force a trade from a franchise on the rise and later claim ``it
wasn't God's will.'' Neither was it enough that he called Minnesota
coach Flip Saunders to tell him he wanted to go back to the
Timberwolves from New Jersey. Nor was it enough that he admitted he
couldn't play on the same team with friend Kevin Garnett because
Garnett's contract is worth $50 million more. No, Marbury has more
mouthing to do.
</P>
<P>
   He chose moments after his team was trashed by New York last
week, when he was held to eight points and committed eight
turnovers against Charlie Ward and Chris Childs, to talk trash
about the Knicks guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still need a point guard,'' Marbury said. ``They'll never
win no championship with them two guys. They'll never, ever win.
You can put that on your back page if you want to. It's just not
gonna happen. They're just not the guys you need to win a
championship. They might not even make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Childs appropriately responded: ``Until you win a
championship, and prove you're playing the game for love and not
for money, you shouldn't be making comments like that. The person
who is defeated should admit it and go on. The guy is a talented
player, but when you speak like that, you should go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Marbury's Nets went to pathetic Denver and
were crushed by 23 points.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK OUT, DIKEMBE
</P>
<P>
   Chris Childs will have revenge on his mind when he returns in 10
days with the Knicks to face the Hawks. Dikembe Mutombo knocked out
a tooth, cutting Childs' mouth with an elbow nine days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see next time we play him,'' Childs said. ``Hopefully,
it's not a game we need to get into the playoffs, because I'm gonna
get him back. I might not be able to reach him in his mouth, but
I'm gonna get him back.''
</P>
<P>
   ENOUGH'S ENOUGH, BOO BIRDS
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' Antoine Walker was 3-for-12 in a loss to the Hawks
on Wednesday, and he got booed for every false move. The Boston
fans have put so much energy in belittling their own player that
they hardly provide a home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans have got to cut Antoine a break,'' coach Rick Pitino
said. ``He's played terrific basketball the last three weeks, and
every time they start booing, he starts pressing. He missed a shot
from the free-throw line and they were all over him. It's totally
unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Walker: ``I guess I'm not a person or a player the fans
want. I enjoy playing here, but for it to continue throughout the
season, I guess it's not going to get any better. I don't know what
to do at this point. I guess I'm not playing to their standards.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If our fans could give it to the opposing team
rather than us, maybe things would change. Last year, this was a
tough place for opposing teams to play. This year, it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan scored more than 49 points all by himself 37
times in his career. He scored 60 or more five times, 40 or more
197 times. So, he was bound to have much to say to his old Chicago
teammates, who scored just 49 points against Miami recently.
</P>
<P>
   But Ron Harper wanted to wait on that.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't check my message, but I ain't calling Michael,'' said
Harper, a friend of the retired legend. ''Maybe I will this week,
but not yet. I can just imagine him using one of his favorite
quotes: `Forty nine points? I could do that all by myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To Utah's Karl Malone. His style may be annoying and borderline
dirty, and his arrogance and quickness to shoot off the mouth are
annoying. But the Wailman has been great in pulling the Jazz past
Portland for the best record in the league. He continues to play as
he has for the last five years _ hard, tough and effectively.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To Dennis Rodman. Can one player be so destructive to a team?
It's likely not. Los Angeles brought him in for stability and all
he did was tear the team down. Here's to the Lakers for dumping
him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
