<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-WESTNOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. coaching snub still rankles Sloan
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After holding his tongue for months, Jerry Sloan
finally admitted his disappointment over not being named U.S. coach
for the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is: What did I do wrong? I'm a competitive person.
I don't mind criticism. Did I do something wrong? I'd like to know.
I thought I did it right,'' said Sloan, who worked as Lenny
Wilkens' top assistant in 1996. Sloan believed he was next in line
after Wilkens went from top assistant to Chuck Daly in 1992 to the
head coaching job four years later. However, USA Basketball gave
the job to Rudy Tomjanovich, who finished third with a collection
of CBA players in the 1998 world championships, which were
boycotted by NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an inconsistency here. Jerry should have been a lock
for that job,'' Jazz president Frank Layden said.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley barks at refs
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley had fun with the referees Monday night after
Houston's victory over Minnesota. ``The officiating was terrible,''
Barkley said. ``We had two blind mice. They let them get in the
game. (The T-Wolves had) seven players on the court at all times
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's explanation: ``It's tax season. The refs are nervous.
... The IRS didn't come to me. They said I don't make enough to
check me.''
</P>
<P>
   The league didn't come to him, either, though Barkley made
similar comments in a postgame TNT interview and the Timberwolves
also complained about referee Jack Nies' crew. The nose-breaker
</P>
<P>
   Spurs forward Malik Rose fractured teammate Will Perdue's nose
in a win over Houston with an inadvertent forearm. Rose also broke
reserve Brandon Williams' nose in training camp. ``Go check Malik's
belt,'' Perdue said after his fourth career fracture. ``I think he
has a couple of notches in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Webber working out
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are more than happy with Chris Webber. ``His attitude
has been unbelievable,'' Kings vice-president Geoff Petrie said.
``From day one, Chris has been terrific with our coaching staff,
the people in the office, the community, his teammates. He came in
here totally committed to the team, and I think along the way he
was surprised by the talent we have here. Vlade (Divac) is better
than he thought. He loves playing with Jason (Williams).''
</P>
<P>
   Woeful Nellie
</P>
<P>
   Once regarded as an innovator bordering on genius, Don Nelson
has never recovered from his sudden resignation in New York and his
public feud with Webber when both were in Oakland. Now, Nelson is
apologizing for repeated failures in Dallas and vowing to retire as
coach after next season, provided owner Ross Perot Jr. and club
president Terdema Ussery allow him to stay that long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take full responsibility for how the team is playing,''
Nelson said, with the Mavericks doomed to their ninth straight
losing season. ``I'm very disappointed with myself for how this
season is ending up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson reiterated that next season, his 22nd as an NBA coach,
will be his last. ``I'm going to retire from coaching for good,''
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
