<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BAMA-QB18-COX     04-17 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAMA-QB18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tide quarterback race begins
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ Charlie Stubbs put the pictures on his office
wall as a reminder to all who entered: It means something to play
quarterback at Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Bart Starr, Joe Namath, Ken Stabler, Steve Sloan, Scott Hunter
and Walter Lewis are but a few of the legends on the wall of the
Crimson Tide quarterbacks coach. Beside the pictures is a solitary
frame surrounding the words: ``Who's Next?''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Crimson Tide fans want to know as Alabama concludes
spring practice today and looks toward the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike DuBose won't call it a quarterback controversy. He
prefers to call it a ``competition'' at a program that hopes to
rejoin college football's elite. Alabama, 7-5 last season, hasn't
won an SEC championship since 1992, when it also won the school's
12th national title. That's a long dry spell for the SEC's most
successful franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get the type of competition at each position that we've
got at the quarterback position, then we'll contend again for that
13th national championship,'' DuBose said.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback debate _ Andrew Zow or Tyler Watts _ will be the
thing that keeps the talk shows humming throughout the state during
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Zow, a sophomore from Lake Butler, Fla., is No. 1 for now. As a
redshirt freshman, he was inserted into the fourth game against
Florida when the offense was struggling behind starter J.D.
Phillips. Zow moved the ball against a very good defense, and
Alabama came close to knocking off the Gators before finally losing
16-10. He started the rest of the season and finished with 1,969
yards passing and 11 touchdowns, a school record for a freshman
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Zow would have gotten an opportunity earlier in the 1998 season,
but he never really excelled in practice. Chalk up another lesson
for a young head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned last season that you can't really judge a
quarterback strictly by what he does in practice,'' DuBose said.
``He has to be a guy who can make plays when there are 80,000
people in the seats. Andrew is a guy who proved he could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, DuBose and Stubbs both said last week that
Watts will get significant playing time in the Crimson Tide's first
few games, starting with the opener at Vanderbilt on Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really never knew what Andrew could do before we put him in
a game,'' Stubbs said. ``We have to find a way to play Tyler so we
really can get a sense of who's further ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Manning at Tennessee was one of the few quarterbacks to
have entered college with more fanfare and hype than Watts. A
SuperPrep All-American, Watts threw for 2,485 yards and 20
touchdowns as a senior at Pelham (Ala.) High School. Upon signing
with Alabama, he was hailed by some as the savior of a program that
was trying desperately to move its offense into the modern age.
Some even predicted that Watts would become the starter immediately
and help the Tide compete for the SEC championship.
</P>
<P>
   But Watts never got on the field as a freshman, taking a
redshirt year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know now that it was the best thing that could happen to
me,'' said Watts. ``When you first come to a place like Alabama,
you get humbled real quick. Then after a while, people accept you,
and you can just relax and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Zow entered the spring with the attitude that the job was his to
lose. He now has seven starts under his belt in Stubbs'
sophisticated passing offense, and his arm is a little stronger
than Watts'. He accepts the fact that Watts will get some playing
time and welcomes the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyler makes me a better player,'' said Zow, who completed 55.9
percent of his passes last season. ``He's a great competitor, and I
have to raise the level of my play to stay up with him.'' ``There
is no friction between us,'' Watts said. ``We share ideas all the
time. We may be competing, but the ultimate goal is to make the
team better. If we can learn from each other, it helps the team.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to have that attitude in the spring, before the
games begin. Stubbs wants to make sure the two still work well
together after the fans start fueling the controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing you have to do is communicate and let both of
them know everything that's going on,'' Stubbs said. ``Unless it's
something personal, I will always have them both in the room when
the position is being discussed. Even if it's going to bother one
of them, you've got to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I coach a tough position,'' Stubbs said. ``You can't run a
happiness camp. We're going to make decisions, and there are times
when we are going to get criticized. It comes with the job.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
