<HEADER>
A2610 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FEATURE-GRETZKY18     04-17 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEATURE-GRETZKY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gretzky going out on top
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The exit will not be Jordan-esque. If Wayne Gretzky
scores the winning goal in his career finale today, his final NHL
point will be in an otherwise meaningless regular-season game, not
a championship. The New York Rangers aren't the best NHL team. Only
the Islanders enable them to be New York's best.
</P>
<P>
   But the retirements of Gretzky and Michael Jordan do have one
thing in common: Both came at the right time. Jordan had achieved
every conceivable goal and left on top. Gretzky embraced thoughts
of another Stanley Cup, but didn't let his ego cloud the reality
that it wasn't going to be.
</P>
<P>
   Playing in New York was agreeable to Gretzky, but playing for an
organization that broke a promise and changed paths wasn't. The
Rangers signed him as a free agent in 1996 with the understanding
they would do everything possible to win a Cup while he was there.
In his first season, they went to the conference finals. But after
the playoffs, the team let Mark Messier, the team leader and
Gretzky's close friend, sign with Vancouver as a free agent. In
ensuing months, general manager Neil Smith started to rebuild with
youth _ which may seem logical, but it wasn't the program Gretzky
signed on with.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are now an odd mix of inexperienced players and
expensive oldies and will miss the playoffs for the second
consecutive season. There were suggestions, mostly by the Canadian
media, that Gretzky should be traded to Toronto, where he could
close his career with a contending team a mere skip from his
hometown of Brantford, Ontario. But Gretzky didn't want to change
addresses again and give the impression he was leaving the Rangers
merely because he didn't get his way (which happened in Los
Angeles).
</P>
<P>
   NHL commissioner Gary Bettman would have preferred a more
glorious exit, which is one reason the league was scrambling to
make today's ceremonies special _ a decorated distraction from the
game's lack of ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to this: There will be no farewell tour next season,
something the low-key Gretzky never embraced. But the NHL should do
something to honor a player whom most consider the greatest ever,
something beyond retiring his No. 99 jersey.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Bettman announced a new trophy to be given to the
goal-scoring champ will be named for Hall of Famer Maurice
``Rocket'' Richard, the NHL's first 50-goal scorer. Hockey has a
history of honoring its heroes. The league should waste no time
creating an honor for Gretzky or renaming a current one _ be it the
Most Valuable Player (Hart Memorial Trophy), scoring (Art Ross
Trophy) or for sportsmanship and career dedication to hockey
(Masterton Memorial Trophy).
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's on-ice accomplishments _ 61 league records, 10 scoring
titles, nine MVPs, two playoff MVPs, four Stanley Cup rings, etc. _
pale in comparison only with what he achieved off of it. If not for
him, hockey would have remained a Northern pastime and Southern
obscurity. He said he never thought of himself as the game's
leading ambassador, but acknowledges, ``I just happen to fall into
that category.''
</P>
<P>
   When Edmonton dealt Gretzky to Los Angeles in 1988, hockey
boomed in the shadow of Hollywood and franchises sprouted in San
Jose and Anaheim, Calif., Phoenix and Dallas, Miami and Tampa,
Fla., Raleigh, N.C., and Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers fans can pout about not getting a chance to watch
Gretzky perform next season. Or they can realize that without him
the Thrashers likely wouldn't even exist. ``He is the best thing to
ever happen to hockey,'' Philadelphia general manager Bob Clarke
said. ``There's always going to be those who argue (Gordie) Howe or
(Bobby) Orr (was better). But there's no doubt over who has done
more for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Dafoe, the Boston goalie and a former teammate of
Gretzky's in Los Angeles, said this week by phone, ``I think he's
worthy of some type of award being named after him. He's had one
accomplishment after another. There's Mr. Hockey, Gordie Howe. But
Wayne Gretzky has surpassed everybody in bringing hockey to the
point it's at now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows that better than Les Jackson. He went from working
for an NHL team in Dallas to one in Atlanta as the Thrashers'
assistant general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's left us with 21 years of highlights,'' Jackson said.
``They should give him whatever he wants. They should name a trophy
after him. Heck, they should name the league after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky is not about to make any such suggestions. He only knows
it was time for him to leave. And Jordan?
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally,'' Gretzky said, ``I thought Jordan should've kept
playing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
