</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fans heap scorn on Isles owner
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was not a festive atmosphere for the New York
Islanders on Fan Appreciation Night. The Isles were smacked by
Carolina 6-1 in their final home game of the season, leaving them
with the second-worst home record (11-23-7) in franchise history.
Fans not only booed and yelled the usual soft-core obscenities,
they targeted maligned owner Howard Milstein with such choice signs
as ``Milstein: The NFL Wanted You About As Much As We Did.'' The
reference was to Milstein withdrawing his $800 million bid for the
Washington Redskins after it became clear that NFL owners were
going to reject his second attempt to join their fraternity. He
lost out earlier in an attempt to land the Cleveland Browns
franchise. With all of those nine-digit bids, Isles fans wonder why
he can't throw another $10 million into the payroll for players and
a decent coach. Milstein's one-year ownership has been disastrous,
from the time he claimed that Nassau County Coliseum was unsafe
because the scoreboard might fall on the players. NHL Gary Bettman
would have preferred that the NFL accept Milstein's bid for the
Redskins, because it might have expedited his move out of hockey.
While pursuing the Skins, Milstein sold 45 percent of the Isles to
his brother. It is assumed that Milstein eventually will sell; his
father, millionaire Paul Milstein, didn't want his son to buy the
team in the first place. But finding a buyer might not be easy.
Finding a buyer willing to keep the team on Long Island could be
even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Flying low
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the probable loss of Eric Lindros for the
playoffs, Philadelphia will be without Mark Recchi for the start of
the postseason and has an ailing John LeClair. Recchi suffered his
second concussion in three weeks, and it is evident that he came
back prematurely from his first one. A physician also thinks that
Recchi has a degenerative condition in his neck. LeClair has been
undergoing treatment for a bad back but will play. The Flyers' best
hope is that they finish the season the No. 6 seed, pitting them
against somewhat overrated No. 3 Carolina. Lindros, LeClair and
Recchi have combined for 98 goals and 138 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers general manager Don Waddell has been named vice
chairman and assistant general manager for USA Hockey for the
upcoming World Championships and will help select players from the
NHL's nonplayoff teams. . . . Isles general manager Mike Milbury
has had preliminary talks with interim coach Bill Stewart about a
contract extension. But uncertain ownership makes both of their
jobs uncertain. There is speculation that the team might pursue
former Islander Butch Goring, who has been coaching the IHL's Utah
Grizzlies and last year rejected an offer from Anaheim. . . .
Despite projected losses of $20 million, Caps owner Abe Pollin has
cut ticket prices for next season. . . . Buffalo's Joe Juneau
hasn't solved Buffalo's scoring problems. He has netted just one
goal since being acquired from Washington at the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
