<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers: The search begins
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the Thrashers' coaching picture is any clearer
today than it was several weeks ago, it's only because of the
number of potential candidates who have been eliminated. General
manager Don Waddell's first coaching hire will not be:
</P>
<P>
   _ Marc Crawford, who got fidgety in a TV booth and leaped into
the ulcer-inducing position of coach of the Vancouver Canucks. They
will finish with their second-worst record in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   _ Larry Robinson, who is expected to lose his job in Los Angeles
and has shown neither the patience nor the motivational abilities
necessary to be a coach of any team _ let alone an expansion club
in search of an identity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jacques Lemaire, who despite his denials appears likely to end
up with the general manager job in Montreal and, besides, preaches
a defensive style that, while successful, is in conflict with
Waddell's preference to attack.
</P>
<P>
   Even Waddell doesn't know who the Thrashers' coach will be. He
said he probably won't start interviewing until after he returns
from the World Championships, May 1-17 in Norway.
</P>
<P>
   But Waddell will begin background checks on potential candidates
as early as this week, perhaps including preliminary telephone
contact. Waddell previously confirmed that former Buffalo coach Ted
Nolan is one candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the preliminary list might be Montreal assistant coach
Dave King. King fills Waddell's spoken prerequisite of having head
coaching experience _ three seasons in Calgary that include two
firsts and one second-place finish _ and isn't quite in the retread
category. He was head coach of the 1992 silver medal-winning
Canadian Olympic team and has a reputation for being a good
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell said he probably will make preliminary checks on ``nine
or 10 guys'' but have face-to-face interviews with only ``three or
four.'' Even if he started the interviews in mid to late May, that
small a field would give him plenty of time to have a coach in
place before the Thrashers' expansion and amateur drafts, June 25
and 26, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get back from the World Championships, once I start the
interviews I expect things to move very quickly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he has made it clear that he doesn't feel any sense of
urgency with any potential head coach, as evidenced by not
immediately pursuing Crawford before this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say it's wide open,'' Waddell said. ``In my
mind, that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   SNEAK PEAK
</P>
<P>
   Statistics from some of the league's top NHL backup goalies,
most of whom will be left unprotected for the Thrashers in the
expansion draft (Anaheim, Los Angeles, Montreal, Nashville, the New
York Rangers and New Jersey are exempt from losing a goalie):
</P>
<P>
   Player _ Team _ Record _ GAA _ Save Pct.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Turek _ Dallas _ 16-3-3 _ 2.08 _ .915
</P>
<P>
   Steve Shields _ San Jose _ 15-11-7 _ 2.20 _ .922
</P>
<P>
   Norm Maracle _ Detroit _ 6-5-2 _ 2.27 _ .918
</P>
<P>
   Fred Brathwaite _ Calgary _ 11-8-7 _ 2.43 _ .915
</P>
<P>
   Damian Rhodes _ Ottawa _ 22-13-6 _ 2.46 _ .905
</P>
<P>
   Rick Tabaracci _ Washington _ 4-12-3 _ 2.51 _ .906
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hextall _ Philadelphia _ 10-7-4 _ 2.53 _ .888
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Tallas _ Boston _ 7-6-2 _ 2.59 _ .900
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Shtalenkov _ Edm./Pho. _ 13-19-4 _ 2.62 _ .898
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Kidd _ Carolina _ 7-10-5 _ 2.74 _ .903
</P>
