<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lacroix works wonders for Avs
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Few NHL general managers were under as much scrutiny
as Colorado's Pierre Lacroix entering the season. Lacroix played a
significant role in the departure of former Stanley Cup-winning
coach Marc Crawford and there were questions about player chemistry
on the team's roster. But the Avalanche will enter the playoffs as
one of the three most likely teams to win the title, with Dallas
and Detroit being the others. The team has played well under Bob
Hartley, Lacroix's no-name replacement for Crawford. Off the ice,
Lacroix has settled the team's two biggest potential personnel
losses, signing would-be free agents Patrick Roy and Peter
Forsberg. Both signed lucrative deals but probably could have
netted more on the open market. Forsberg, only 25 and arguably the
league's best player, acknowledged as much after agreeing to $30
million over three seasons, including a $3.5 million signing bonus.
``Maybe I could've gotten an offer,'' he said, ``but I didn't see
any reason why I should wait until after the season. I wanted to
stay here, and that's what we were working for the entire time.''
With Lacroix earlier extending the deals of Sandis Ozolinsh and
Adam Foote, the Avs' payroll will top $40 million next season. That
doesn't include the recently acquired Theo Fleury, who will test
the market. Lacroix said the team is ``building a relationship''
with Fleury. So far, all of his relationships have gone well.
</P>
<P>
   Reason to howl
</P>
<P>
   Remember that trend of declining suspensions handed out by NHL
police chief Colin Campbell? Scratch that. Campbell dealt out seven
suspensions totaling 15 games and $214,751 in lost salary in the
first two weeks of April. And that was before Dallas' 6-foot-5
Derian Hatcher went airborne to drive an elbow into the jaw of
Phoenix forward Jeremy Roenick. The play got Hatcher suspended for
seven games _ the longest penalty in league history _ but cost the
Coyotes much more. Roenick's jaw was dislocated and fractured in
three places, and he is out for the playoffs. Further, Hatcher
can't use the ``It was an accident'' defense. He had vowed before
the game that the Stars would get retribution for a boarding
penalty by Roenick on Mike Modano that opened a seven-stitch gash
near Modano's eye. The difference is that Modano didn't miss any
games. Coyotes center Keith Tkachuk said, ``We lose a guy who's
been our leading scorer and best centerman all year to a piece of
dung like Hatcher. It was a premeditated incident.'' This was
actually the second time Hatcher ended Roenick's season. His
knee-on-knee check in 1995 also knocked Roenick, then with Chicago,
out for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's most likely downfall in the playoffs will be its power
play. Even before Roenick's injury, the Coyotes' 11.4 success rate
ranked 26th out of 27 teams, and they had scored just three goals
in their last 40 power play attempts. ... San Jose goalie Mike
Vernon wasn't bitter, at least not publicly, about the possibility
that Steve Shields had stolen the starting playoff job from him,
based on Shield's recent 9-0-2 run. ``It's hard to break up
something that's working,'' Vernon said. ``Steve has been
sensational. He's been a big reason why we're successful.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
