A2614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIKE-HINCAPIE-525&AMP;ADD     04-17 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-HINCAPIE-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING DOWNTIME PEDALING IN A 5-DAY RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ After three highly successful weeks of racing his
bicycle over the roads of Italy, Belgium and France, George
Hincapie is getting a chance to enjoy what he calls downtime. For a
while, there will be no more battling the wind, rain and
cobblestones, not to mention 180 or so rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Hincapie, though, won't be sitting near the sea in Spain, where
he lives during the long season, or watching television at home in
Charlotte, N.C., or even visiting his family in the borough of
Queens, N.Y., where he grew up. By downtime he means a five-day
race in Spain for his U.S. Postal Service team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be so nice to be in a race where you're not fighting for
position every moment of the day,'' he said in an interview before
the Tour of Aragon began last Wednesday. ``I won't have any
pressure there. If I don't want to go to my limit in a climb, I'll
just go easy; not easy, but find a good group where I'm not killing
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   That relatively soft life contrasts with his springtime campaign
in the World Cup of prestigious one-day races, where Hincapie, the
American national champion, posted some of the best results of his
career. He was ninth in Milan-San Remo, 21st in the Tour of
Flanders and fourth in Paris-Roubaix, adding up to 10th place
overall in the World Cup standings.
</P>
<P>
   Competition continues Sunday with the Liege-Bastogne-Liege
classic in Belgium, but Hincapie will skip it, returning to the
circuit in the Amstel Gold Race next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Few riders participate in the Liege race after taking a pounding
the Sunday before on the cobblestones of Paris-Roubaix. In
addition, Hincapie raced on the Wednesday between Flanders, on
April 4, and Paris-Roubaix, finishing fourth in the Ghent-Wevelgem
semiclassic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those World Cup races are so stressful,'' he said. ``People
who are your friends, you don't even talk to them in those races.
Maybe you say hello, but hardly ever in the pack is there talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always battling for position. I mean always. If it's
not a climb coming up, it's windy. The first attacks come early,
and then it's boom, boom, boom, boom. In Spain, the races are hard,
of course, but you always get your downtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning 26 late in June, Hincapie is in his sixth season as a
professional after dominating races as an amateur in the United
States. His progress has been steady and, as he nears a racer's
peak years, he has become more powerful and higher placed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every year I'm getting stronger,'' he agreed. ``Also,
I've been happy with my form the last couple of weeks. I could have
had even better results if a few little things had happened
differently. Like in Milan-San Remo, it was just a matter of
positioning. I had a very strong finish, right after the line I was
third instead of ninth on the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing that helps is that the teams have really been
working for me,'' he continued. ``It's nice in the first 100, 150
kilometers when the team is looking out for me. I never had that
before, a rider whose only job is to keep me out of trouble.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In other years he was that rider. Previously Hincapie built to a
peak for the Tour de France in July and the World Cup classics that
follow it, but this year his program was reshaped to emphasize the
spring races.
</P>
<P>
   After the Amstel race, he will return to the United States for a
three-week break, return to Europe for a couple of races and then
start preparing to defend his national championship in Philadelphia
early in June.
</P>
<P>
   That red, white and blue jersey with the white stars means a lot
to Hincapie, who thought he won it in 1997 and then learned he had
been disqualified because of actions by team officials. Last year
he won the jersey and kept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the winter, when I'm just out training, it's so
important for me to be wearing the jersey,'' he said. ``I try to do
well in big races wearing it. I've always wanted to wear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another jersey he covets is the yellow one that the Tour de
France leader wears. Hincapie came within two seconds of earning
the jersey in the last Tour, but admits that his future is more in
the one-day classics than in three-week stage races.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next couple of years he can become one of the best
classics riders,'' said Fred Mengoni, who has sponsored the G.S.
Mengoni racing team in New York City for 25 years and who helped
guide Greg LeMond, Mike McCarthy and Hincapie. ``He's developing
the strength. What he needs now is the confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Hincapie agreed that confidence was vital and said he was
working on it. ``I definitely gained confidence this spring,'' he
said. ``If you go into a race thinking, `This is not my style, this
is not my thing,' you're already 50 percent less than the other
riders. If you come in, `I think I can win this,' that does a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, after his breakthrough spring, he's beginning to think ``I
can win this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
