<HEADER>
A2615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRETZKY-RANGERS-ART-N     04-17 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRETZKY-RANGERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY ISN'T THE ONLY RANGER REACHING THE END OF THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(Eds: Subs for HKN-GRETZKY-APPRECIATION) 
(See also HKN-GRETZKY-PRACTICE, HKO-OTHER GRETZKY) 
(rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wayne Gretzky probably won't be the only New York
Ranger playing his final home game at Madison Square Garden Sunday
when the regular season concludes against the Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   Mediocre teams that miss the playoffs for two consecutive
seasons, even with respectable improvement, rarely stay intact.
</P>
<P>
   As Gretzky ends his 20-season career in the NHL, his Rangers
bring a 33-37-11 record into the nationally televised farewell to
the Great One. Their 77 points, up from 68 last season, would
qualify for the postseason in the Western Conference. But the East
has fewer great teams and more good ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is very obvious what we need,'' said John Muckler,
finishing his first full season as coach. ``We need help behind the
blue line. We need help up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in the season, when Gretzky missed 12 games with an injury,
the Rangers went 6-3-3 and seemed poised to earn one of the eight
conference berths. ``With Wayne coming back, I thought that would
put the icing on the cake,'' Muckler said. ``We just didn't get the
job done.''
</P>
<P>
   So the next job will be to lure more first-line forwards and top
defensemen. The quick fix could be through free agents. The easiest
to recruit, for a wealthy team such as the Rangers, are
unrestricted veterans over age 31 who have played out their
contracts. ``The Rangers have a lot of resources to do these
things,'' Muckler said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for them, the most attractive free agent in a
shallow market this summer is Brian Leetch, their captain and
attacking defenseman. With only 12 goals, Leetch is almost certain
to finish with the lowest total of any full season in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Possible factors for his drop in production include the awkward
compatibility between his style and Gretzky's, something Leetch
cited last season; the limitations on his mobility under Muckler's
system, something Muckler denies; or the gradual erosion that comes
from 12 seasons, several serious injuries and too many playing
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The team lost toughness with Jeff Beukeboom's career-threatening
concussion and Ulf Samuelsson's trade to Detroit. Alexander
Karpovtsev was traded to Toronto for Mathieu Schneider, a deal that
probably helped both teams. Younger players like Rumun Ndur, Chris
Tamer and Richard Brennan showed potential and limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Among forwards, Petr Nedved became the first-line center after a
trade from Pittsburgh for Alexsei Kovalev, another deal that helped
both teams. Nedved scored 20 goals but took a beating and left the
lineup three weeks ago after a serious rib injury.
</P>
<P>
   Asking him to do two jobs _ center a scoring line and check the
other team's top line _ is a sure way to burn him out. When Gretzky
was injured, young centers Marc Savard and Manny Malhotra played
more minutes and showed encouraging moments of creativity and
speed. But neither has yet proven he is ready to sustain the energy
for 20 minutes of playing time per game over an 82-game season.
</P>
<P>
   On the wings, Adam Graves, healthy again, revived his career
with 38 goals, excelling at even strength, on the power play and
killing penalties while earning a multiyear contract. But he is 31,
and it is fair to wonder how many more injury-free seasons of high
productivity he has.
</P>
<P>
   John MacLean, signed as a free agent last summer, has 28 goals
and consistently gave full effort, but sometimes looked weary as a
34-year-old veteran of 16 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Stevens, has 23 goals and played more strong games than
some thought possible. But he is 34 and might soon decorate an
expansion team's roster.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Harvey, a 24-year-old right wing, added spirit, but missed
half the season with injuries, a major concern. Niklas Sundstrom
has 13 goals, down from 19 last season and 24 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Sundstrom, an excellent checker, is one of few Rangers who would
draw value in the trade market. Another possibility is one of the
goalies. Mike Richter, the veteran, had a good season, and Dan
Cloutier, the rookie, showed promise. But Neil Smith, the general
manager, always says it is difficult to trade goalies.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Smith has seemed increasingly irritable and is
drawing more criticism than ever before, not all of it fair. On the
dais at Gretzky's news conference on Friday, while others looked
sad, Smith seemed to frown and scowl.
</P>
<P>
   Even the television executives and basketball bosses who run the
Garden know that Muckler and several of Smith's top aides have
succeeded elsewhere as general managers. Like many of his players,
Smith's future in New York could be decided by moves made in the
next few months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
