<SLUG> BC-HKO-OTHER-GRETZKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER GRETZKY WAITS FOR HIS BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANDREW BLUTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A familiar name graces the back of the sweater worn by
the speedy center for the Wolves, this city's independent
minor-league hockey team. He can play behind the net, pass with
deadly accuracy, and coaches say he sees the ice almost as well as
the man who shares his last name.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Gretzky is accustomed to being told he is almost as good
as his older brother, Wayne. And like any other aspiring hockey
player, he thinks ``not quite as good as Wayne Gretzky'' is a nice
compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will ever be as good as Wayne,'' Brent said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as the hockey world was held captive while Wayne
pondered retirement, Brent quietly went about his usual anonymous
role. As a midseason addition to the Wolves, he has helped the
defending International Hockey League champions to another
regular-season division title and, unlike Wayne, is readying for
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Brent said Wayne didn't discuss his retirement with him. He had
hoped his brother would play another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's another reason for me to read the sports page,'' Brent
said. ``I'm always hoping for him to break another record or do
something else on the ice. And I'm not just saying that because
he's my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent is the youngest of five children, three of whom pursued
the sport that their father, Walter, loved and coached. Eleven
years younger than Wayne, Brent was only 2 when his brother left
home in Brantford, Ontario, to play junior hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, I'd watch Wayne on TV and then go out
to the rink and try out some of his moves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was on that backyard skating rink, built by Walter Gretzky,
where the brothers honed their skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys used to want to skate all the time, and if I took
them to a park it was just too cold,'' said Walter, who worked for
the local phone company in Canada. ``I built that rink for
self-preservation. People always say, `Wow you built a rink so
Wayne and the boys could skate.' No. It was for me. It was so I
wouldn't freeze to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent said, ``Everything my brothers and I learned about hockey,
we learned from our dad. People ask me all the time what I learned
from Wayne. We don't talk hockey, but he did teach me how to play
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he is still relentlessly compared to Wayne, Brent said
he felt fortunate that his brother Keith came along first. It was
Keith who absorbed the nickname the Other One. Brent is merely the
Little One.
</P>
<P>
   Brent also attributes much of his recent success and return to
North American hockey to Keith. After several years floating
between minor-league teams, Brent decided in 1997 to play in
Europe. He spent a season in Austria, and after a contract dispute,
thought his playing days might be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   But Keith, who was a career minor-leaguer himself and is now a
minor-league coach for the Asheville (N.C.) Smoke, gave his little
brother a chance. Brent credits Keith with re-energizing his
offensive game and his mental approach to hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Europe, he spent parts of three seasons in
the Tampa Bay Lightning organization and was called up to the NHL
for a total of 13 games. One of those was against the Los Angeles
Kings _ whose starting center was Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he won every faceoff we had,'' Brent said. ``Finally
the last one, he let me win, and the crowd started cheering.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Gretzky added: ``I thought I was going to have go down
there and referee the game myself. The two can't play a game of
cards without fighting about something.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent calls that game the best experience of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hadn't hit me until right before the game,'' he said. ``I
was walking out of the tunnel and my knees were shaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 27, Brent acknowledges his chances of making the NHL again
decrease every year, but he says he is playing the best hockey of
his career and is still optimistic. Others agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely got NHL ability,'' said his coach, John
Anderson. ``He needs a team to come along that is willing to let
him showcase his abilities, because he's definitely got them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
