<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SAMPRAS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK INJURY PREVENTS SAMPRAS FROM PREPARING EARLY ON CLAY
</HEADLINE>
   (lh) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARCELONA, Spain _ The man voted the greatest tennis player in
the last quarter-century by a panel of experts has yet to reach a
final in 1999. And Pete Sampras, because of a back injury suffered
earlier this week, won't be reaching one any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   After earnestly and eagerly deciding to start his clay-court
campaign early by accepting a wild card into the Open Seat Godo in
Barcelona, he left here on Wednesday without playing a singles
match after withdrawing because of a lower back injury.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras felt his back tighten during a doubles match on Tuesday
night, and despite a hot bath and a long massage, he awoke very
stiff in the morning, the muscles surrounding his sacroiliac joint
in spasm. By Wednesday afternoon, he was sitting in a crowded
interview room wearing the slightly self-conscious expression that
he often reserves for bad days at the office.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a number of those this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a setback, no question,'' said Sampras, who blamed
himself for not warming up properly. ``Having not played many
tournaments and not played great this year, it's disappointing. But
I'm not sitting here panicked about everything. There's a lot of
tennis still to be played this year.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the ATP trainer Per Bastholt, Sampras will not be
playing or practicing for five or six days, at least. He has
already decided to withdraw from next week's Monte Carlo event, and
unless he changes plans, his next tournament will be the Italian
Open in Rome from May 10 to 16. Instead of getting onto European
red clay early in an attempt to prepare for the French Open (the
only Grand Slam event he has not won) Sampras will again get onto
it late. The French Open starts eight days after the Italian Open
ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the way I wanted to start off my clay-court
season: with an injury,'' he said. ``But sometimes you have to
listen to your body and be smart about it.''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing No. 1 in the ranking for a record sixth
consecutive year, Sampras skipped the year's first Grand Slam, the
Australian Open, to rest his weary mind and body. ``At the end of
last year, I was miserable,'' he said. ``But I felt this was really
the only chance for me to break this record, and I put so much
pressure on myself that I wasn't eating well or sleeping well.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he returned to the tour in February, his results hardly
have been reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the reason is that he's been putting too much pressure
on himself,'' said his coach, Paul Annacone. ``Missing Australia
for the first time was a change of routine for him.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first tournament, Sampras defaulted from the semifinals
in San Jose, Calif., with a sprained ankle. He was beaten in the
second round in Scottsdale, Ariz., by Jan-Michael Gambill; by Felix
Mantilla in his opening match at Indian Wells, Calif., and, more
understandably, by Richard Krajicek in the quarterfinals at Key
Biscayne, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I needed the break,'' Sampras said. ``I felt like
the pace I was going the last couple years, I was burning that
candle pretty quickly, and after stressing over whether I should go
to Australia, I decided not to and then told myself that I had my
break and was ready to go. But then all of a sudden it starts all
over again: not getting the results you want. I was putting in the
time and training in January, but it's not easy. And you know the
next couple of years are going to be interesting for me. They
really are.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Interesting because Sampras is not at all certain that he wants
to continue playing in enough tournaments to remain in contention
for No. 1. Under the new ranking system that will start in January,
top players will be penalized if they don't compete in the four
Grand Slam events and the ATP Tour's top nine events, now known as
the Super 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if I'm willing to play every Super 9 event,'' he
said. ``The next few years, I really want to have a schedule where
I play when and where I want to play and not where I'm forced to
play. Last year, I felt I had to play those tournaments at the end
of the year to finish No. 1, but now that I got the record, is that
what's going to keep me driving and working hard?
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean I've analyzed this. When you have a lot of time off,
you sit and think about your career and what I went through at the
end of last year. How happy was I going through this? I'm not
fighting for my life out there. I'm trying to achieve a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite appearances to the contrary, Sampras said one of his
goals is to return to Davis Cup. Though he declined to play last
year or in this month's first round against Britain, he said he had
kept track of his former teammates' 3-2 victory in Britain while
training on clay in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a bit of it, and it was a hell of an effort by the whole
team,'' he said. ``When you hear about the matches and how exciting
they were, there's a part of you that thinks twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the captain, Tom Gullikson, he added: ``I know Tom
has his team set for the next round, or at least that's what I've
heard. I have no problem with that. Those guys made the commitment,
and they get the first shot, but my Davis Cup career is not over.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, it is the French Open that matters most, and
though his chances grow slimmer by the season on his least favorite
surface, he and Annacone have decided that his best chance is to
attack the net with great regularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I realized I need to come in more,'' he said. ``I
don't need to do it to the same extreme as Pat Rafter. I need to
use what I have, the whole arsenal I have in my game. But these
clay-courters don't like guys chipping and charging and serving and
volleying. And it's something I'm just going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   To do it at Roland Garros he will need to be very healthy, and
his lower back problems are not new. Last fall during his stressful
and successful effort to maintain his virtual edge, he had spasms
with some frequency, and despite efforts to improve his strength in
the off-season, he experienced more discomfort in Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a lower back injury keeps coming up like this, you can
never be sure it won't happen again,'' Bastholt said. ``Pete will
now have to be very careful about warming up and stretching out
before he goes out to play any match.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
