<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN MAN, 21, IS DEAD AFTER SHOOTING IN A THEATER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 21-year-old Brooklyn man who dreamed of rapping his
way to a better future died five hours after he was shot in the
back at a Flatbush movie theater during a Friday night screening of
the film ``Life.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim, Jumaane Cox, was one of three men wounded shortly
after 10 p.m. at the Kenmore Quad Theater. Cox died of his wounds
at the hospital shortly after 4 a.m., the police said. They
described him as a bystander to an argument between two rival
gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dispute over seating,'' said Detective George Nagy, a
police department spokesman, adding that the shooter also had been
angered by noisy patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Batiste and Nigel Ramirez, both 19 and from Flatbush, were
also shot in the dispute, he said. Both were listed in stable
condition at Kings County Hospital Center Saturday afternoon, with
Batiste suffering a single gunshot wound to the back and Ramirez
with three gunshot wounds to the torso.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said that the department had
suspects, but declined to reveal details because the shooting
remains under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Cox had been sitting to the right of the shooting with his niece
and a friend. ``Everything happened all of a sudden,'' said his
niece, Shamika Page, 19. ``We weren't even five minutes into the
movie when I heard the shots, and we hit the deck. I thought he was
fine and was already out when I got to the street. I didn't even
know that I had crawled over him, that he was the one on the floor
who had been shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox's mother arrived at the theater a few minutes after
receiving a call from Ms. Page telling her what had happened. When
she got there, her son was still lying inside the theater,
conscious but unable to speak and without any signs of a wound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed with him, and tried to talk to him,'' Ms. Page said,
speaking on the phone from the Cox family apartment. ``Then when
they turned him over there was this tiny hole, no bigger than a
dime on his back.''
</P>
<P>
   Weeping, she added: ``That little hole, that tiny thing, it
killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other family members said that it had been uncertain on Friday
night whether Cox was actually going to attend the movie. Although
he had been eagerly awaiting the release of the prison comedy,
starring Eddie Murphy and Martin Lawrence, his brother Kevin said
in an interview that he had urged Cox to go to another theater
because of the gang activity around the Kenmore. He said the
theater is covered with gang graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated calls to the theater seeking comment went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Better known in local rap circles as Wax, Cox had begun to shop
his first demo tape, family members said. They added that he was
also an accomplished artist who spent hours each day drawing
super-heroes inspired by his love of Spider-Man and designing logos
for businesses, including the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had recently passed a test to become a track cleaner
for New York City Transit, Mrs. Cox said, he retained dreams of
making it big in the music world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wanted to do anything to make it out of here, and he
was always talking about rapping,'' said his mother, a nurse's
assistant. ``He always said he was going to make money, buy cars
and houses, get me a place to stay and take care of me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't a troublesome kid, someone who stayed out late or
got involved with the bad people,'' she said, drifting off into
tears. ``I just can't believe this is happening. I'm just so sad,
and I don't understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
