<HEADLINE>
SILAS MAY HAVE FOUND A BIG ALLY IN JORDAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Jordan and George Shinn, owner of the Charlotte Hornets,
are moving closer to a partnership that would result in Jordan's
owning 50 percent of the team, a first for a former National
Basketball Association player.
</P>
<P>
   An official of another Eastern Conference team said Jordan and
Shinn met last week and are merely working out details of what each
one's role in the organization would be.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Shinn have tentatively worked out an arrangement in
which both would have veto power over major decisions. And both
would be consulted on every matter pertaining to the team, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ownership structure may not be final until after
this season, the Hornets' interim head coach, Paul Silas, may not
have to worry about his future.
</P>
<P>
   Despite speculation that the former Bulls coach Phil Jackson
would supplant Silas after this season, Jordan has apparently
agreed with Shinn that Silas, a longtime assistant, should be kept
as head coach if Charlotte continues on its current pace.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night's 95-94 victory in Milwaukee, the Hornets had
won six straight under Silas and were 14-9 since Dave Cowens
resigned on March 8. Part of the resurgence can be attributed to
Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell. Obtained for Glen Rice from the
Lakers last month, the two have been consistently good _ a
description seldom applied to Campbell's game before. That Silas
has been able to coax energy and effort out of the formerly
lethargic Campbell is a testament to his ability.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets entered the weekend two and a half games out of the
eighth and final Eastern Conference playoff spot, with a Band-Aid
lineup that was missing Derrick Coleman and Anthony Mason. They
have beaten New York, Orlando and Utah under Silas, whose
reputation among players is golden.
</P>
<P>
   Even notoriously unhappy players like Coleman, who has four
years left on his contract, and Mason, who has three seasons left,
count Silas as one of the few authority figures in the game to whom
they actually listen. Silas coached Mason on the Knicks on Pat
Riley's staff and worked with Coleman on the Nets as part of Chuck
Daly's and Butch Beard's staffs.
</P>
<P>
   With the conference up for grabs for the next several years, the
possibilities in Charlotte are tantalizing. If Coleman drops 30
pounds, if Mason returns healed from a torn biceps, if Campbell and
Jones keep fitting in, and if point guard David Wesley thinks pass
instead of shoot first, that team is a bona fide contender. And
Jordan as owner would not hurt the team's marketing possibilities,
either.
</P>
<P>
   If Silas is given a longterm deal, it will send a message that
NBA coaches are not necessarily saviors, and that longevity and
loyalty mean something. And it would be one of the few times in
recent years when a black coach inherited a promising situation.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year alone, Silas has been interviewed for positions
in Seattle, Chicago and Sacramento and come up empty. His only
previous head coaching job was essentially a no-win situation,
overseeing the San Diego Clippers in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   With the dismissal of Bernie Bickerstaff two weeks ago in
Washington, Silas is one of four black head coaches in the league.
He joins Alvin Gentry in Detroit, Butch Carter in Toronto and Lenny
Wilkens in Atlanta. It's no secret that many in the black coaching
fraternity wonder why their peers often inherit underachieving
teams doomed for the draft lottery, never to resurface as head
coaches again.
</P>
<P>
   From Beard with the Nets to Jim Cleamons in Dallas to Eddie
Jordan in Sacramento, the list goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, in this type of situation, you get passed and passed
over, and you wonder if it's ever going to happen,'' Silas said
last week. ``You interview several times, and you end up getting
beat out by a recycled coach with a pretty good record. It's the
nature of our business. About the only way a longtime assistant
gets a head coaching job is when he becomes an interim coach after
a firing and turns the situation around.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time NBA owners begin promoting loyal souls again.
That's how Jackson and Rudy Tomjanovich, among others, got started.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to keep your nose clean, you try to do the right
things, you try to learn your craft, and you're constantly missing
out,'' Silas said. ``Fairly or unfairly, it wears on you after a
while.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many Stops on Coaching Carousel
</P>
<P>
   Paul Silas may be safe, but the other interim head coaches are
beginning to emerge as clear long shots.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Rambis, who replaced Del Harris, may have only a month left
to blend all that Lakers ego and talent into a contender, a
gargantuan task that Harris could not accomplish in four and a half
seasons. His authority undermined by Dennis Rodman for the last two
months, Rambis' only hope may be getting the Lakers back to the
Western Conference finals. And even that may not be enough to
guarantee security.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson is an obvious candidate, but don't discount Dave
Cowens.
</P>
<P>
   Because Bernie Bickerstaff was fired so late in the season in
Washington, Jim Brovelli was given an impossible job. If Silas does
not re-sign in Charlotte, look for Wes Unseld to give him serious
consideration for the Wizards job. Gar Heard has also been
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Don Casey, meanwhile, was looking like a sure bet to take over
the Nets on a permanent basis. But Stephon Marbury and his fragile
friends fell apart against the Knicks and on the West Coast this
past week, dousing some of those hopes, although the Nets blew out
Seattle Friday night to go 8-11 under Casey.
</P>
<P>
   At 61, he is more contemporary than most of his peers, able to
get through to his players with biting sarcasm and humor instead of
challenging their manhood. Like Silas, he is another career
assistant who understands the old Chuck Daly credo: In the NBA,
your players allow you to coach them.
</P>
<P>
   Don't Rule Out Rodman Return
</P>
<P>
   Don't cry for Dennis Rodman, who was released by the Lakers on
Thursday, because he became more of a hindrance than a help.
Because Rodman was released after the first week of March, he is
not eligible for a playoff roster this season, but even though he
is 37 there are plenty of desperate franchises who may give him a
job next season.
</P>
<P>
   A few places Rodman could still play:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: The Sonics need an ornery rebounder. Plus, Rodman is a
good friend of Pearl Jam's Eddie Vedder. Having been tattooed and
pierced more than most of Grunge America, Rodman would go over big
in the smoky clubs and latte hangouts.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: The Pistons, the team Rodman began his career with, are
soft in the middle, too. And imagine the tearful homecoming when he
sees his former club.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill: ``Welcome back, Dennis. Look, there's your old
locker.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman: ``You guys still practice?''
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI: Even though Rodman has said, ``Not even Pat Riley can
control my demons,'' the Heat needs another solid veteran for the
playoffs. Believing he can motivate any human being to fit in with
the franchise, Riley would accept Rodman with the proviso that he
be on time, work hard and not detract from the team concept. From
his South Beach cabana, though, Rodman would label the conditions
completely unacceptable.
</P>
</TEXT>
