<SLUG> BC-NY-GOTTI-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOTTI BELIEVED TO BE USING BROTHER TO CLING TO POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With his son and reputed successor about to follow
him into federal prison, John Gotti is trying to cling to the reins
of the Gambino crime family through his brother Peter, Mafia
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Gotti, 59, a former New York City Department of Sanitation
employee, has been identified by the FBI as a capo, or captain, in
the Gambino family. He is said to run a crew from the Bergin Hunt
and Fish Club in South Ozone Park, Queens, which was once the
headquarters for his brother.
</P>
<P>
   As a close relative, Peter Gotti is allowed to meet with his
brother, and investigators believe that these visits will enable
John Gotti, who is serving a life sentence, to maintain a pipeline
to the Gambino family.
</P>
<P>
   J. Bruce Mouw, a former FBI agent who was in charge of the
agency's Gambino family investigations from 1980 until his
retirement last year, described Peter Gotti ``as not exactly a
Rhodes scholar nor particularly aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But just by the process of elimination he is actively running
the family now,'' Mouw said. ``Does he have the capabilities?
Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts, current and former federal and state investigators,
say that John Gotti, 58, is determined to remain the Gambino boss
despite the recent guilty plea by his son, John A. Gotti, to
racketeering and tax evasion charges and the difficulty of
communicating his wishes from a prison where he is locked in a cell
for 23 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   The incentives for Gotti are strong, the investigators say: As
long as he remains boss, he or his relatives are entitled to a
share of the family's illicit profits.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state law-enforcement agencies estimate that in the
early 1990s the Gambino family reaped about $100 million a year
from gambling, loan-sharking, gasoline tax frauds, and labor
rackets and extortion in the construction and garbage carting
industries. The loot, the experts say, has been sharply cut by a
government crackdown against the family.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the younger Gotti, 35, admitted his guilt in a
plea bargain, he claimed that legal battles with the government had
virtually impoverished him. But federal and state agents say he has
squirreled away millions of dollars that agents have been unable to
trace.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was imprisoned in 1992 at the federal penitentiary in
Marion, Ill., the elder Gotti has relayed directions mainly through
meetings at the prison with his son, law-enforcement officials say.
Although all of Gotti's prison visits are recorded on video and
audio tape, federal prosecutors contend that he and his son,
reportedly the acting Gambino boss, discussed Mafia matters in
code.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a control freak,'' Mouw said of the elder Gotti. ``He
just wants to maintain control through his son or his brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Schiliro, the head of the FBI in the New York area, said
John J. Gotti remained the Gambino family's paramount leader. ``We
still carry him as the boss,'' Schiliro said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   After the conviction of the younger Gotti, Schiliro said it was
too early to determine the new composition of the hierarchy that
will supervise the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dust has not settled, and they are still in flux, but
Peter Gotti is a front-runner,'' Schiliro added.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cutler, a lawyer for the Gotti brothers, denied that Peter
Gotti was an organized crime figure, pointing out that he was
acquitted, in 1991, of the only racketeering charge brought against
him. ``He is a devoted brother,'' Cutler said of Peter Gotti.
``These unsupported allegations are an unholy obsession by law
enforcement with anyone who has the name Gotti.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Gambino family, based in the New York City area, is the
nation's second-largest and second-most-powerful Mafia group, with
about 200 soldiers and several thousand associates who work for the
gang, according to the FBI. Many of the soldiers, however, are
elderly or imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Mouw said John Gotti might seek to deter rivals by
re-establishing a committee of Gambino members loyal to him to
oversee the family's day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   While imprisoned for the last seven years, Gotti has left vacant
the family's other high-ranking posts of underboss and consigliere,
investigators said. ``The last thing Gotti wants is a permanent
underboss or consigliere who can slowly take over the family,''
Mouw said. ``If he tries to run the family through a committee he
will appoint his own people from the loyal palace guard, and if he
doesn't like anyone he will throw him off the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   But, at best, Mouw added, Gotti only has superficial authority
and must depend on loyalists to carry out his policies and to
resolve issues that cannot await instructions from him.
</P>
<P>
   Most investigators maintain that Gotti also wants to exercise
control to ensure that his relatives, known as the Gotti faction in
the crime family, get shares of illicit profits that generally flow
to a Mafia boss. In addition to his son and his brother Peter,
law-enforcement officials say two other relatives are Gambino
soldiers: another brother, Richard, 56, and a son-in-law, Carmine
Agnello, 37, the husband of Gotti's daughter, Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   Before John A. Gotti, who is known as Junior, pleaded guilty to
federal charges on April 5, he claimed that he had difficulties
providing for his wife and four children because the government had
seized many of his assets and because of the expense of a $10
million bond to stay free while awaiting a trial.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators doubt the claim of poverty. Mouw said that
John Gotti received millions of dollars a year from Gambino family
rackets since 1986, when they say he became the Gambino boss. Since
1992, Mouw asserted, the son has been collecting payoffs for his
father and for himself.
</P>
<P>
   In a plea deal with federal prosecutors for a reduced prison
sentence of about five to seven years, the younger Gotti agreed to
pay a fine of $1 million and to forfeit $358,000 in cash that was
found in a safe in his office in Queens. He also must forfeit homes
and property in Pennsylvania and Sullivan County, N.Y., but he has
been allowed to keep a $700,000 home in Mill Neck, N.Y., and a
$300,000 home in East Massapequa, N.Y., both on Long Island. He is
to be sentenced July 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tens of millions of dollars stashed away,'' Mouw
said. ``Where is it? If we knew we'd seize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Shargel, a lawyer for John A. Gotti, said: ``It's very
easy for federal agents to say that Gotti has a lot of money. All
the evidence we have points to the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro of the FBI declined to say if agents were trying to
locate cash they believe has been hidden by the Gottis. ``Certainly
the financial resources of the Gambino family are extensive,''
Schiliro noted. ``All I can say about searches is that our
investigation into the Gambino family's activities is continuing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
