<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKING QUARTERBACKS AS EASY AS 1-2-3: COUCH, MCNABB AND SMITH
</HEADLINE>
   (lh) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few quarterbacks have faced the microscopic scrutiny Kentucky's
Tim Couch underwent this month, on everything from the way he
selected an agent to how he held the football.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, the Cleveland Browns had their doubts about
selecting him with the No. 1 pick in the draft _ the first in their
reborn franchise's history. But Cleveland's thinking changed after
Couch performed so well in a recent workout. Following that
performance, Browns officials began talking of how Couch reminded
them of Joe Montana, who many of them knew first-hand from their
days with the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that Couch could lead their franchise for the next 10
years, the Browns came to terms with him several hours before the
draft on a seven-year, $48 million contract that includes a $12.2
million signing bonus, the largest ever given to a rookie. By the
time the clock started for the Browns to make their selection,
their choice was the worst-kept secret in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After Couch, two more quarterbacks were selected, the first time
that has happened since 1971. Choosing second, the Philadelphia
Eagles selected Donovan McNabb of Syracuse and the Cincinnati
Bengals then picked Akili Smith of Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the biggest shock of the day. Indianapolis, long
thought to be interested in Ricky Williams, the Heisman
Trophy-winning running back from Texas, or Champ Bailey, the
cornerback from Georgia, instead chose Miami running back Edgerrin
James, whose stock rose dramatically in recent weeks. While the
Colts say the reason they went with James was simply because they
had him rated higher, it is hard to believe that the conservative
Colts coach, Jim Mora, wasn't bothered by Williams's dreadlocks and
pierced tongue.
</P>
<P>
   James going before Williams led to one of those awkward moments
that seems to have become commonplace in the draft. Williams
thought he was going to the Colts and, with cameras focused on him,
expressed shock when his name was not called.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts' decision immediately led to the first of several
blockbuster trades that will be remembered for years and could
change the course of franchises.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Coach Mike Ditka had pledged that he would pay
almost any cost to get Williams, and the price he paid was indeed
steep. Once the Colts passed on Williams, Ditka got on the phone
with Washington and offered all of his picks from this year's draft
_ from the first, third, fourth, fifth, sixth and seventh rounds _
and a first- and third-round choice next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins took Ditka's charitable offer, moving from fifth
overall to the Saints' spot at 12, and the Saints selected
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected Indianapolis to take me, so I was surprised,''
Williams said. ``But I'm glad I'm going to a place where I'm
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Williams concerned about the pressure that will be on his
shoulders, the way the blockbuster trade Dallas made with Minnesota
more than 10 years ago followed Herschel Walker around for the rest
of his career?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too worried,'' Williams said, ``I'm just going to go
out and play football.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Washington made a trade of its own. The Redskins took some
of their new picks from New Orleans and combined them with a few of
their own to switch places with Chicago and move up to No. 7 to
select Georgia's Champ Bailey, probably the best athlete in the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins, like the Saints, gave up a lot to get Bailey.
Washington gave Chicago the Saints' first- and third-round picks,
then their own fourth and fifth-round selections from this draft
and a third-round selection from next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears used their choice to try to address their quarterback
problem, drafting Cade McNown of UCLA. He was the fifth quarterback
taken in the first 12 choices, coming one after the Minnesota
Vikings had drafted Daunte Culpepper of Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did quarterbacks dominate the draft, it was heavily
oriented toward offensive players.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, who just acquired running back Marshall Faulk from
Indianapolis, added a wide receiver for their anemic offense,
choosing Torry Holt of North Carolina State. Then, one pick after
Washington chose Bailey, Arizona selected another wide receiver,
David Boston of Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore then selected Chris McAlister, another cornerback. No
other defensive players were taken until Tampa Bay used the No. 15
pick to choose Louisiana State University lineman Anthony
McFarland, the latest a defensive lineman has been selected in the
first round in more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, the Giants, drafting 19th, chose the Notre Dame
offensive tackle Luke Petitgout, a 6-5, 315 pound player.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the quarterbacks who were the focus of the first
round. The last time quarterbacks went 1-2-3 was in 1971 when the
New England Patriots drafted Jim Plunkett, the New Orleans Saints
chose Archie Manning and the Houston Oilers selected Dan Pastorini.
</P>
<P>
   Some NFL personnel men felt that Cleveland's at times public
hesitation over Couch was an effort to gain an upper hand in
negotiations. Others felt that the Browns were genuinely puzzled
about whom to take, their top three choices being Smith, Williams
and Couch.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what sealed the Browns on Couch was that second
workout. In it, Couch showed accuracy and confidence that wasn't on
display in his first workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That workout pushed us over the top,'' said Carmen Policy, the
former San Francisco executive who is now president of the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland officials had contacted the agents for all three
players, but in the last 48 hours the Browns had concentrated their
efforts on Couch. Talks between the Browns and Couch's agent, Tom
Condon, heated up beginning around 9 p.m. on Friday and did not
conclude until around 3 on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not tolerate any disruption of his focus,'' said
Policy when asked why it was so important to sign Couch early. ``We
needed our leader signed early and we wanted that to send a message
to anyone who was going to be part of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch was glad to have it over with.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a great moment,'' he said. ``I can't tell you how
happy I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
