<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO REAL FOOTBALL, DRAFTEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Pa., Ill., La., Ind.)  (With FBN-DRAFT, FBN-DRAFT-NOTEBOOK, FBN-DRAFT-JETS, FBN-GIANTS,
FBN-ANDERSON) 
(mk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Usually, the top players and their families arrive
for the National Football League draft full of hope and optimism
and leave with even more. Often the day is one of smiles all
around, an oozy feeling of warmth among the families after an
exhausting process that finally leads to a new address along with
new riches. Instant peace.
</P>
<P>
   But after the draft Saturday at Madison Square Garden, most of
the draftees present felt as if they had just survived a big
squeeze. A sticky shakedown.
</P>
<P>
   Twist me, use me. Rip me up.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they dealt with it. Off they flew to their new teams and
new cities. But already, they had learned a valuable lesson in how,
as pros, to keep both eyes open both inside the locker room and
out. To expect even more scrutiny on the way to making their own
way.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the six players present _ Tim Couch, Donovan McNabb,
Akili Smith, Ricky Williams, Daunte Culpepper and Cade McNown _
experienced the shakedown.
</P>
<P>
   Couch was the draft's first selection. But it happened after the
Browns all but forced the quarterback to sign a contract before he
was picked.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb went next to Philadelphia, and some Eagles fans present
at Madison Square Garden booed him immediately. Some reporters
asked him if he really deserved to be selected so high and if he
expected to be a ``project'' at quarterback for at least three or
four years.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was the No. 3 pick, to Cincinnati. He and his agent, Leigh
Steinberg, said the Browns strung both agent and quarterback along
the night before and the morning of the draft, using them as
leverage in the Browns' negotiations with Couch.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the Heisman Trophy-winning, record-setting running
back, was snubbed by the Colts at the No. 4 slot (they selected a
back, Edgerrin James, widely considered less talented than
Williams). Williams went to the Saints at No. 5. And then Williams
watched as his agent, Leland Hardy of No Limit Sports Management,
the company founded by the rapper Master P., was grilled about his
ability to negotiate NFL contracts. The innuendo was that Williams
had fallen to No. 5 because of his agent.
</P>
<P>
   It was thought that Culpepper would be picked as high as No. 7;
he slipped to No. 11 at quarterback and still is being questioned
about coming from a small school, Central Florida. McNown has
already been through the fires, having in the last few months
answered an assortment of questions about gambling ties that proved
unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   Relief!
</P>
<P>
   It is over now. And, then again, it just begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was anxious for this to happen, and I felt I could be the
best quarterback in the draft all along,'' said Couch, who for the
last month had been reported to be a toss-up choice along with
Smith. That was what the Browns said. Was it a ploy all along to
ensure Couch would sign before the draft?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not looking for the better deal,'' said Al Lerner, the
Browns owner. ``We were looking for certainty. I had said that if
our first pick was a contract holdout for 20 minutes, that would be
too long. We didn't want an 11th-hour idea to come up in
negotiations with new demands we had never seen. No new wrinkles.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Couch is signed, and Steinberg feels used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland called us last night and talked contract
parameters,'' Steinberg said. ``And then they called back about
11:15 last night and said negotiations were done for the night. I
asked them if it was done for the Couch team. They said yes and all
along Couch people were there in front of them when the phone call
was being made. It was an emotional roller-coaster for the Smith
family. They kept telling them Akili really had a chance to be
their pick and all we asked (of) them (was) to be was honest. Akili
will handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch and Smith are once again linked, in the same state and
same division. They will play each other twice a year in the
American Football Conference Central division. Cleveland vs.
Cincinnati. Couch vs. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Tim,'' said Smith, ``but I also see a rivalry being
born. I don't know if he sees it that way, but I do. I'm looking
forward to playing Cleveland for a number of years. For one of us,
Cleveland or me, this is going to be a constant reminder on who
missed what.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb said Syracuse had not won in the years before he arrived,
but that that changed afterward. He said the same would happen in
Philadelphia. Culpepper said he was nervous as the clock slipped
by, that he thought he might go anywhere from No. 2 to No. 20 as
time passed. Like McNabb in Philadelphia, McNown looks to a future
in Chicago to change recent losing attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, however, experienced the day's most startling
shakedown. And so did his managing team. The look in his eye,
however, hinted that he knew what to do. Likely, the others do,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of set back a little bit, kind of thrown off when
they took Edgerrin,'' Williams said. ``I don't know if it's because
of my agents or my braids or style or what. I feel very much today
like me and my team are sacrificial lambs. It's new for people, my
look, me having a black management team that falls under the
business of a megastar rapper. But I am not worried about it. The
Saints gave up a lot to get me, and now I'll go to a place where
they will use me. And time tells the story. We all just go from
here, and we get the last word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
