<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS DRAFT NOTRE DAME'S PETITGOUT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Mich., Wis.)   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ When it was the Giants' turn to announce
their first-round choice in Saturday's National Football League
college draft, the Giants took less than a New York minute.
</P>
<P>
   The selection process was speedy, and the selection was a
surprise. Luke Petitgout, a 6-foot-5{-inch, 315-pound tackle from
Notre Dame who was not rated a first-round pick by most who
evaluated the draft, became the Giants' choice with the 19th pick
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Giants Coach Jim Fassel announced minutes after the selection
that Petitgout would begin competing for the starting left guard's
job. Greg Bishop, the team's starter at left guard the last two
seasons, signed a free agent contract with the Atlanta Falcons this
winter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 22-year-old Petitgout's versatility and foot speed
that made him the Giants' choice over tackles L.J. Shelton of
Eastern Michigan and Aaron Gibson of Wisconsin, who were considered
the most sought after offensive linemen after John Tait of Brigham
Young, who was taken by Kansas City with the 14th pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected you to be shocked,'' Giants General Manager Ernie
Accorsi told reporters after Petitgout was drafted. ``But he was
the highest rated lineman and the highest rated player remaining on
our board.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Petitgout also reveals Fassel's expanded
influence on the drafting process. Fassel prefers quick offensive
linemen rather than mammoth ones. He values agility over brawn.
</P>
<P>
   Petitgout's selection also gives the Giants some flexibility
should they have trouble signing left tackle Roman Oben to a
long-term contract this year. Oben is scheduled to become an
unrestricted free agent after the 1999 season. Petitgout's
abilities at left tackle were prominently mentioned Saturday by
both Accorsi and Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   If Petitgout has trouble moving to guard, which is generally
regarded as an easier position to learn and play in most NFL
offenses, then the Giants might consider moving right tackle Scott
Gragg to guard and letting Petitgout play right tackle. They did
not pursue Bishop in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Things started to fall into place for the Giants as the
Pittsburgh Steelers and other teams picking ahead of the Giants
went for players at positions other than the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers in particular were expected to take an offensive
lineman, but they instead selected Louisiana State wide receiver
Troy Edwards with the 13th pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs then took Tait, which was hardly a surprise since
Tait was considered the class of this year's group of offensive
lineman.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Seahawks traded their first-round pick, the 17th
overall, to the New England Patriots, who used that spot to take
Boston College center Damien Woody. This also didn't hurt the
Giants, who were seeking a tackle/guard rather than a center, a
position at which Brian Williams is making a comeback from an eye
injury and the third-year center Derek Engler also returns.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that the Giants were then deciding between Shelton
and Gibson. ``We would have been perfectly happy with either of
those two,'' Accorsi said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants moved fast on Petitgout instead. Why did their
selection take so little time?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a conviction on the player we were picking,'' Accorsi
said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   There were other first-round developments that will affect the
Giants, most notably the choice of Ohio State wide receiver David
Boston by the Arizona Cardinals. The Cardinals are a rising force
in the National Football Conference East, and talented Cardinals
quarterback Jake Plummer now has a big, physical, game-breaking
receiver to extend the field and improve what already is a quality
offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Redskins, meanwhile, added a player in the first
round that Giants fans may come to know all too well. Georgia
cornerback Champ Bailey has been compared to Deion Sanders, who has
terrorized Giants quarterbacks across several seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
