<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT NOTEBOOK: TOP CHOICES OFTEN DON'T FINISH FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
  (With FBN-DRAFT, FBN-DRAFT-JETS, FBN-GIANTS, FBN-ANDERSON,
FBN-NOTEBOOK) 
(mk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So what playing position do the majority of National
Football League teams favor as the overall first pick of the draft?
</P>
<P>
   Tim Couch's selection Saturday by the born-again Cleveland
Browns made him the fourth quarterback of the decade to go first.
There has been only one running back chosen No. 1. There were two
defensive tackles and one wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, in the first 10 drafts starting in 1936, only one
quarterback _ Angelo Bertelli of Notre Dame _ was the top pick. But
after World War II and the importance of the T-formation, the
quarterback began to make his way to the top. Being picked first,
at any position, hardly guarantees a championship, however.
</P>
<P>
   Only one overall top choice of the '90s, Dallas defensive tackle
Russell Maryland (1991), has been on a Super Bowl winner. Indeed,
only one top choice in the 1980s, the Cowboys' Troy Aikman, has
been a part of that team's development into a Super Bowl champion.
John Elway was the league's top pick in 1983, but that was with
Baltimore, for whom he refused to play and was traded.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed Results
</P>
<P>
   The Browns are in their glory, for now, with the expensive
acquisition of Tim Couch. But first-year teams, given the overall
top pick, have had mixed results with that choice. Here is how the
most recent expansion teams fared:
</P>
<P>
   _ Carolina, 1995: Traded its overall top pick to Cincinnati,
which chose Ki-Jana Carter, the Penn State running back whose
career has failed to live up to his high selection, at least in
part because of injuries. (Carolina went fifth, taking quarterback
Kerry Collins of Penn State, who is now with his third team, the
New York Giants.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Tampa Bay, 1976: Picked Lee Roy Selmon, defensive end from
Oklahoma, who produced a Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta, 1966 (NFL): Picked Tommy Nobis, Texas linebacker, who
went on to distinguished career.
</P>
<P>
   _ Miami, 1966 (American Football League): Picked Jim Grabowski,
an Illinois running back, who signed with the NFL's Packers.
</P>
<P>
   The Parcells Plan
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were twiddling their thumbs for more than five hours
Saturday because their first choice was the 57th pick of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   They have had mixed success in coach Bill Parcells' first two
Jets drafts, in which Dick Haley played the lead role in organizing
the selections. Of their 23 picks, 14 remain with the club. One is
a starter on offense _ last year's fourth-round pick, tackle Jason
Fabini of Cincinnati _ and one is a starter on defense _ lineman
Jason Ferguson of Georgia, the last pick of the Jets' 1997 draft.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also Leon Johnson, one of the best third-down backs
and kick returners in recent Jets history, as well as Dedric Ward,
the deep-threat receiver and kick returner.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker James Farrior, Parcells' first pick in his first
draft in 1997, was demoted to the second string last year. So was
free safety Kevin Williams, who began last season as a rookie
starter and now will try to convert to cornerback. Still, both
could develop into valuable players over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Two players who missed last year with injuries will get serious
opportunities this summer: linebacker Casey Dailey and defensive
lineman Terry Day. Doug Karczewski, a rookie guard last season, may
also be given a shot at starting.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Jets' success in drafting, Parcells said,
somewhat defensively, ``Look around and tell me what other people
have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Ward have been impact players, and the 14 who remain
from the Parcells drafts are his kind of people, which by any
yardstick has to be an improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Classes
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of this year's quarterback class _ the first
three choices were quarterbacks, something that hadn't happened
since 1971, when Jim Plunkett (Patriots), Archie Manning (Saints)
and Dan Pastorini (Oilers) were selected.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers compare the depth of this year's crop to the 1983
group, which will probably produce three Hall of Famers: John
Elway, Dan Marino and Jim Kelly. That collection also included
three others who went in the first round: Tony Eason, Ken O'Brien
and Todd Blackledge. Who remembers the order they went in, though?
</P>
<P>
   1. Elway (Colts, traded to Denver).
</P>
<P>
   2. Blackledge (Kansas City).
</P>
<P>
   3. Eason (New England).
</P>
<P>
   4. Kelly (Buffalo, elected to go to the U.S. Football League).
</P>
<P>
   5. O'Brien (Jets).
</P>
<P>
   6. Marino (Miami).
</P>
<P>
   According to Charley Casserly, the Redskins' general manager,
``The class of '71 was far better.''
</P>
<P>
   Phifer in the Big City
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Roman Phifer met with Jets fans Saturday, and he came
away impressed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the newest Jets, Phifer joined the club as a free agent
after playing for the perpetually troubled St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised by how excited they were,'' said Phifer, who
was at the Official All-Star Cafe on Broadway for the Jets'
open-house draft party. ``It's a big change coming from St. Louis.
The fans were around the block.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
