<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: A BOOMING ECONOMY THAT CONFUSES THE FED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's boom time in America. The U.S. economy is acting as if it
just got a new wind, and growth _ which virtually every forecaster
was sure would slow this year _ seems to be accelerating.
Unemployment is low and so is inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The seers at the Federal Reserve Board are as puzzled as the
rest of us. ``Recent performance is both better than expected and
better than most of us thought the structure of the economy would
allow,'' said Laurence Meyer, a Fed governor, in a speech last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The new belief in the vibrancy of the American economy was
visible in the stock market last week as investors moved money out
of Internet wonders and into companies that actually make stuff.
America Online stock fell 13 percent while Caterpillar soared 30
percent. You would think this economic recovery was just starting,
rather than in its ninth year. Recessions, investors think, are for
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   It was only last fall that there was a consensus that it was
just a matter of time until the world's economic illness infected
America. There were signs that it had already started, as
manufacturing companies reported falling profits and exports
declined.
</P>
<P>
   It now looks as if the contagion went the other way. Brazil's
recession is less serious than was expected and Asia is recovering.
American manufacturers report that exports are picking up.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, American consumers have decided to spend more than
ever. ``The things that were strong last year have not missed a
beat,'' said Robert Barbera, the chief economist of Hoenig &AMP; Co.
Retail sales are up 6 percent over last year, after adjusting for
inflation. That is a pace that is unprecedented except when the
country is coming out of a recession. The last time we saw such
growth was in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   All this suggests that confidence is about as high as it has
ever been. Investors believe there will be no recession, and
consumers have no fears that their incomes will fall.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it seems clear that the Fed overdid it last fall,
when it cut interest rates three times in an effort to stave off
world recession and moderate the expected slowing in this country.
Instead, it fostered a boom that may be unsustainable and could
bring on inflation. It also provided the liquidity needed to push
the Dow Jones industrial average up 39 percent since August.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is whether the Fed will reverse course and
start to tighten. If it does, that would certainly put upward
pressure on interest rates, and it might dampen both the stock
market and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The answer probably depends on what conclusions the Fed members
reach about why the economy has been so strong. If they still
believe in conventional forecasting, they probably will tighten. In
the past, unemployment rates this low and consumption this strong
were deemed sure signs of incipient inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But the old economic indicators do not seem to be working the
way they once did, a fact that is reflected in the poor forecasting
record of the Fed and most other economists. The Fed members wonder
whether much of this can be explained by a surge in
computer-related productivity, and whether weakness in the rest of
the world is keeping a cap on American wages even when jobs are
plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Most on Wall Street think the Fed is not likely to act soon.
``The days of pre-emptive tightening are over,'' says Barbera,
predicting that action will be delayed until inflation is clearly
on the rise. Similarly, Stephen Roach, the chief economist at
Morgan Stanley, thinks the Fed should raise rates to at least
partly offset last fall's cuts, but says it appears that such a
move will come later rather than sooner.
</P>
<P>
   But the bet here is that the Fed will act sooner than most
people think. Meyer, the Fed governor, said last week that a rate
increase might be appropriate if the economy continued to grow
rapidly, even if inflation did not rise immediately. If that was a
hint, it was one that Wall Street was not in a mood to hear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
