<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-PARADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS HAIL UCONN AT PARADE HONORING TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Tens of thousands of faithful fans took to the
chilly streets here Saturday for a parade saluting the University
of Connecticut men's basketball team, which won this year's
national championship after years of late-season heartbreaks.
</P>
<P>
   The UConn players donned T-shirts declaring ``Mission
Accomplished'' for the team's victory lap through the Connecticut
capital on a flatbed towed by a tractor-trailer, which drove slowly
enough for the state's heroes to dispense autographs and low-fives.
Three eighth-grade girls from Bristol vied for blown kisses by
wearing Husky boxer shorts and a basketball net on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The mushers from the Connecticut Valley Siberian Husky Club
delighted children with a sled towed by white huskies, just like
the UConn mascot. Rambunctious spectators showered the team and
coach Jim Calhoun with Silly String, and signs proclaimed ``The
Year of the Dog'' and ``Coach Calhoun for President.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the parade, cheers turned to shrieks when,
police said, an exuberant child darted into the street and was hit
by a police motorcycle. The parade halted briefly but resumed after
the girl was taken to Hartford Hospital, where she was listed in
stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   Fans had arrived as early as 5:30 a.m. for the 11 a.m. March of
Champions, which Hartford officials billed as the city's biggest
event since the celebration of the end of World War II in 1945. The
mayor's office estimated that 250,000 turned out to honor the team,
which had made it to the Sweet 16 of the NCAA finals seven times in
10 years, but until this year had never cracked the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through all the Huskies' bad times _ these are the good
times,'' said Marilyn D'Andrea, 58, an order-entry worker from
Wallingford. ``We need more good things in the world, and
especially in Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of a compact state and the lack of any major
league team has made UConn basketball a unifying obsession for
Connecticut. Gov. John Rowland, who strolled the
one-and-a-half-mile route in a Husky sweatshirt and khakis, said:
``The excitement and the pride and the community spirit that we
have now, it's very infectious. I hope it lasts a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, Patty Rowland, added, ``We want to know where
all these people were in January, at the inaugural parade.''
</P>
<P>
   A bit of a shadow had been cast over the festivities when Khalid
El-Amin, the star point guard, was charged Tuesday with marijuana
possession after being stopped for running a red light in Hartford.
El-Amin went to court two days later, accepting a sentence that
requires him to perform six hours of community service and give
antidrug speeches at three middle schools.
</P>
<P>
   One vendor tried to capitalize on the arrest by selling
Cat-in-the-Hat-style hats festooned with marijuana leaves.
Saturday's crowd was in a forgiving mood, however, and most
spectators said El-Amin, 19, had simply made a youthful mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Suzy Bronson, 37, had brought along a Sports Illustrated
commemorative issue, ``Top Dogs,'' with El-Amin on the cover, in
hopes of snagging an autograph. ``The cops should have just slapped
him on the head and let him go,'' she said, in a sentiment that was
echoed by many.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants and bars in the downtown area, which is usually
deserted during the day on weekends, opened for the occasion. A
popular bar with no name, known to locals as ``No Name,'' warmed up
fans with drinks called Lucky Dog (tequila and tonic) and Husky
Blue (schnapps, Sprite and a blue liqueur).
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour parade and a rally that followed at the Capitol,
including presentation of the Waterford crystal trophy, were
carried live on four Connecticut television stations. At 11:30 a.m.
on Sunday, WFSB Channel 3, the CBS station, is to replay UConn's
77-74 upset of Duke in the championship on March 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may have shocked the world, but you did not shock all of
your fans here back in the state,'' Rowland said at the ceremony.
After El-Amin was introduced, he grinned as he acknowledged a
second round of applause that amounted to a supportive curtain
call.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers had planned for 40 parade units, but that quickly
grew to 70, and 30 or so others were turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Several bands boomed from flatbed trucks, including one with a
name that would have been sure to provoke raspberries in this
crowd: Duke and the Esoterics. For the day, the band playfully
crossed out the ``Duke'' on its banner and became ``Hugh Cohn and
the Esoterics.''
</P>
<P>
   The day brought out all of the state's political royalty, with
the exception of the lieutenant governor, M. Jodi Rell, who kept
her months-old promise to throw out the first ball for the Wilton,
Conn., Little League.
</P>
<P>
   The Husky triumph seemed to inspire long-suffering fans
everywhere. At the turn onto Jewell Street, a bedsheet decorated
with blue paw prints proclaimed, ``Dreams Do Come True.'' Someone
had added, ``Go Red Sox.''
</P>
</TEXT>
