<SLUG> BC-NJ-COL-ATHEISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ATHEISTS LAND WHERE FAITH HAS TIDY ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRANFORD, N.J. _ The priests, the pastors and the rabbis of the
Cranford Clergy Council were having their usual Monday morning
breakfast meeting at the Family Diner on North Avenue the other day
when one of them asked, ``Did you see where the atheists have moved
to town?'' and someone else said, ``Well, we've got to find out
where they are and invite them to our Monday meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   As he recalls the moment, the Rev. George Freyberger of Calvary
Lutheran laughs so hard that the conversation starts to run off
track and into a bog of speculation about the nature of unbelief _
isn't it a kind of belief? _ and away from the news.
</P>
<P>
   That news, as everyone in town has heard by now, is that
American Atheists Inc., slayers of prayer in school and strict
constructionists of the establishment clause of the First
Amendment, have indeed moved from Austin, Texas, to a new national
headquarters in this pleasant inner suburb of Elizabeth, the better
to fight against Americans' tendency to mix government with
religion.
</P>
<P>
   They won't have to look far. As in a lot of other places,
Cranford's houses of worship are up to their rafters in government
business. Members of the clergy council rotate saying opening
prayers at the Cranford Town Council meetings, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Local observances of Thanksgiving, Martin Luther King Jr. Day
and Yom ha-Shoah, the Holocaust Remembrance Day, are suffused with
elements of church and state, with the clergy praying and
sermonizing and elected officials reading proclamations and
memorializing.
</P>
<P>
   And when Union County Social Services takes in a homeless
family, where do they turn? Among their options are the 12 Cranford
houses of worship that rotate duties as shelters, each serving
about a month, for families in distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 37 years as a pastor, I have never found a community where
the houses of worship and the pastors and rabbis work so closely
together with each other and with the government for the good of
the community,'' Freyberger said.
</P>
<P>
   So with church and state happily coexisting, the reaction to the
newcomers down around Walnut Street and South Avenue, where
Cranford is rebuilding its downtown, was pretty much a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're very interested in us,'' said Benjamin
Hardin, a dry-cleaning materials distributor who was catching the
train to New York. ``I'm a little surprised they came here instead
of the city, but it's a free country.''
</P>
<P>
   Cranford has about 25,000 residents and was famous in the 1920s
as ``The Venice of New Jersey,'' for the way the Rahway River
meanders through town. These days it is a bedroom community for
commuters to New York City and the ring of office parks built along
the rail lines to the city.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Ron Barrier, the atheists' spokesman, the
organization chose Cranford for the same reasons hundreds of other
office-based concerns have moved to the area _ it was pretty and
clean, close to New York but without New York prices. ``Anybody
who's involved in a cause has to be situated in the New York
City-Washington, D.C., corridor,'' he said. ``This is the
communications center of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The atheists held the ribbon-cutting of their new headquarters _
on Christiani Street _ just two weeks ago, and the silence that
followed the news was another reason the nonbelievers came here,
Barrier said. ``In Texas, we used to get hate mail and hate calls
all the time, but we haven't had any here and we don't expect
any,'' he said, adding, ``This is a more enlightened part of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   John Laezza, the Cranford town manager, made pretty much the
same point. ``It's not like they came in here with banners flying
saying they were going to save the world,'' he said. ``When people
read it in the paper we got some calls along the lines of `Did we
know this was happening?' and some wanted to know if we could stop
it. But people are basically saying it's a free country and they
don't need our permission to move in.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the two sides remain in the wary watching stage of
new-neighborness. ``I just hope they're a tax-paying entity and
aren't going to file for a tax exemption,'' Laezza said.
</P>
</TEXT>
