<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VANSAUN-PROFILE-N     04-17 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VANSAUN-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMERICAN'S ODYSSEY TRYING TO MAKE IT IN THE WORLD'S GAME'S U.S.
LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The soccer career of Jesse Van Saun has been anything but dull.
From leading the St. John's program to the 1996 NCAA championship
to undergoing surgery for a serious injury two years later, Van
Saun has experienced the heights and depths of his chosen sport.
</P>
<P>
   And through it all, he has maintained a level head that has
helped him home in on a professional career in Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Van Saun's soccer odyssey began when he was 4 years old and his
parents registered him in a league for 6 and 7 year olds. The
precocious Van Saun excelled against the older players, but he
still could not get peers interested in his passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something comes naturally, you should try to excel at
it,'' said Van Saun, 22, a native of Hillsdale, N.J. ``It was tough
for a while when I was growing up because my friends really weren't
interested in the game, but I love to play so it didn't matter. It
never crossed my mind to ever give the game of soccer up.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even when he was cut at age 16 from the New Jersey state
team by coach Dave Masur. ``It was a difficult process,'' Masur
said in his own defense, ``evaluating all of the players in such a
short period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``As it turned out, I may have overlooked Jesse when I made the
cuts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The coach would have another chance to evaluate Van Saun, and
this time Masur did not let the youngster get away.
</P>
<P>
   Masur became the head coach at St. John's in 1991, and he
offered Van Saun, an attacking midfielder for Pascack Valley High
School, a partial athletic scholarship for the fall of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later on,'' Masur said, ``I said to Jesse, `Why didn't you try
out for the state team?' He said, `Because you cut me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Van Saun, who describes Masur as precise and a perfectionist,
credits the Red Storm coach with helping develop his skills as a
player, focusing on discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Masur's method involved visualization. Before each game,
the coach would ask the players to close their eyes and clear their
heads. He would then tell them to see themselves performing well
the next day during the game.
</P>
<P>
   The St. John's players began to believe in themselves and, long
story short, improved so much that they won the national
championship in 1996. The soccer team did what the school's proud
and renowned basketball program had never done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public reaction,'' Van Saun said, ``was incredibly
positive. You could immediately tell the difference in the way we
were perceived. The students at the school knew we were good
before, but they had never come out to support us until '96. The
community around the campus also embraced us after we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Having helped to win a national title in his sophomore year, a
dream season in which he led the Red Storm in scoring with 16 goals
and was named the most valuable player of the championship game,
Van Saun found his own act a tough one to follow. As a junior, he
scored only five goals and St. John's made a disappointing
second-round exit from the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 39 goals and 25 assists in four years for St.
John's, Van Saun left school a few credits short of graduation and
decided to turn pro. He entered the MLS draft and was selected by
the New England Revolution in the second round in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had thought I would be drafted by the MetroStars, because it
was close to home,'' Van Saun said. ``But the New England
organization was unbelievable. Robert and Jonathan Kraft give the
players a lot of attention and the fans in the area really
supported us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts are the team's owner-investors, and also own the New
England Patriots of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Van Saun appeared in only five games in his first year with the
Revolution, playing a total of 117 minutes, and was hampered
throughout the season by a severe groin injury. Last December, Van
Saun underwent surgery as doctors cut into his abdomen to release
tension on his pelvic area.
</P>
<P>
   He worked back into game shape for the 1999 season, but did not
play in New England's first two games and was released on April 7.
Five days later, he got a call from Bob Bradley, coach of the MLS
defending champion Chicago Fire. Bradley, the former coach at
Princeton, knew Van Saun from the schoolboy's playing days in New
Jersey. Last Monday, Van Saun was claimed on waivers by Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse needs experience, he has to grow on the job,'' Bradley
said of the 5-foot-9-inch, 160-pound scorer and playmaker. ``We are
always trying to put together a good roster with young players. We
think Jesse is that kind of player and that he will develop and
improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Saun was thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Bradley told me that the organization is looking to gather
young, talented players,'' Van Saun said. ``They want to see what I
can do. There are no guarantees, but I heard great things about
Chicago and I am looking for a new start. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
