<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FED-CUP-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DOESN'T MISS DAVENPORT AS RUBIN TOPS MAJOLI IN FED CUP
OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Chanda Rubin, the designated replacement player
at this replacement site at Raleigh Racquet Club stepped in for the
injured Lindsay Davenport admirably Saturday and pulled off an
arduous 7-6 (7-5), 4-6, 10-8 Fed Cup victory against Croatia's top
player, Iva Majoli.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin's perseverance against the erratic Majoli, who hasn't won
a title since her breakthrough at the 1997 French Open, gave the
United States a 1-0 lead in the weekend's best-of-five-match series
against Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans win, their next opponent will be the winner of
Spain-Italy. After the two singles matches Saturday in Reggio
Calabria, Italy, the two countries are tied, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   After being broken three times as she served for the victory at
5-4, 6-5, and 7-6, Rubin fell behind by 8-7 when Majoli ended a
five-game-long streak of broken service games by holding with a
backhand winner. More poised as the pursuer than the front-runner,
Rubin held for 8-8, and broke for 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she only had to hang tough on serve to convert this epic
match into a point for her nation. And finally, when she
desperately needed to, Rubin got herself to double match point with
an ace and ended things on her second match point when Majoli
netted a tired forehand 2 hours 46 minutes after the struggle
began.
</P>
<P>
   Right from the first set, the players battled a chilly,
skirt-blowing breeze that stole their shots and stirred up the
clammy green clay underfoot.
</P>
<P>
   They traded breaks in the fifth and sixth games, with Rubin
surrendering her serve with a netted backhand but breaking straight
back with a crisp cross-court forehand. The pair battled into a tie
breaker, where they stayed on serve until Majoli suddenly succumbed
to the tension and double faulted to give Rubin a set point at 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin thought she had converted the set with an ace, but the
serve was called a let and had to be replayed. Rubin finally
captured the set in the tie breaker by blasting in another first
serve and following it with an untouchable down-the-line forehand.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first player to falter in the second set was Rubin, who fell
behind, 4-2, when she belted a backhand out of bounds at break
point. But just as she had in the opening set, she broke back
immediately. In trouble again on her next service game, Rubin
fended off four break points, the last with an ace, before finally
holding serve to level the set at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   But Majoli evened the match by breaking Rubin in the 10th game,
this time with a forehand that clipped the net and dropped over for
a winner to send them to a third and deciding set.
</P>
<P>
   Majoli, such a mainstay for the Croatian squad that its captain,
Vjeran Friscic, allowed her to show up for duty three days late on
Thursday, hasn't won a tournament title since she trounced Martina
Hingis, 6-4, 6-2, in the final of the 1997 French Open.
</P>
<P>
   Seeded ninth there, at 19, Majoli became the lowest-seeded Slam
champion in the Open era. Majoli's first and only Grand Slam title
sent her ranking soaring to fourth in the world, but her dry spell
in the ensuing two seasons has caused her to plummet to No. 32, a
position far inferior to her talent.
</P>
<P>
   Like the 23nd-ranked Rubin, who once reached a career high of
sixth, Majoli, just 21, finds herself in the strange position of
trying to fight her way back to the stature she enjoyed while still
a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   But at least in Fed Cup, Majoli has been a reliable performer:
her 14-6 singles record is the reason Croatia managed to improve
itself into the elite World Group this year after defeating Japan
and the Netherlands in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin learned Wednesday night that she would be standing in for
Davenport, a role she also assumed in 1995 against Spain. Davenport
was unable to launch her two-handed backhand with any semblance of
authority due to tendinitis that set in after she sprained her left
wrist three weeks ago at Key Biscayne and informed team captain
Billie Jean King that she was unfit for singles duty. Rubin, with
her 2-2 Fed Cup singles record and 2-2 record against Majoli, was
the obvious replacement.
</P>
<P>
   This year has brought encouraging results for Rubin, whose
recovery from the wrist problem that required major surgery and
ruined her Olympic chances in 1996 has been maddeningly slow.
</P>
<P>
   She won her second career title at Hobart, Australia, in
January, and in March at Indian Wells, she reached the semifinals
by upsetting top-ranked Martina Hingis. According to King, who had
selected Rubin for that 1996 Olympic squad, the Lafayette, La.,
native is playing the most promising tennis of her career and is
the reason there was no panic in the American camp after it lost
Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   King had a similar comment to make about this round's Fed Cup
anchorwoman, the Yugoslav-born Monica Seles, who became available
once the round was relocated from Zagreb to Raleigh and assumed the
head role for singles and doubles upon Davenport's withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's getting better and better,'' King said, she's back in a
big way.''
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's second singles match, Seles faced the 70th-ranked
Silvja Talaja. The two have never played each other, but they did
have one thing in common, unblemished Fed Cup records: Seles is
8-0, Talaja 5-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
