<SLUG> BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEENS PROSECUTOR TO SEEK DEATH PENALTY FOR ACCUSED KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Queens district attorney, Richard Brown, has
decided to seek the death penalty for a man charged with killing
two people in separate robberies last year.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who describes himself as an opponent of capital
punishment, said he reached his decision after a ``painstakingly
thorough review of all of the facts and circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the third time prosecutors in Queens have sought the death
penalty since capital punishment was revived in New York state in
1995. Since then, only two defendants statewide have been sentenced
to death, and both are appealing the decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Steven Smelefsky, 34, of Ridgewood, Queens, is
charged with first-degree murder in the slayings of two Queens
residents during robberies with different accomplices. Both
accomplices have been charged with second-degree murder, which is
not a capital offense in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that after reviewing his office's findings, materials
presented by lawyers for Smelefsky and meetings with the victims'
families, he concluded that ``a sentence of death would be
justified if the defendant were convicted.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first case, Smelefsky waited for a 92-year-old neighbor
in the garage of their building at 1724 Gates Ave., and attacked
him when he got out of his car. Authorities said Smelefsky then
bound the victim, Louis Thumudo, and threw him into the trunk of
his car.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said that with his accomplice, Rubin Ortega, 44,
Smelefsky drove to Stroud Township in Pennsylvania and dumped
Thumudo by the side of the road. His body was found on May 18.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, authorities said, Smelefsky and an
accomplice went to the Rego Park, Queens, home of a friend,
44-year-old George Capobianco, on July 31. The authorities said
that Smelefsky and the accomplice, Keith Knoesel, 29, hit
Capobianco with a bottle and stabbed him.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several days, according to the indictment, they
returned to Capobianco's house to steal his property, and were
arrested getting into his car.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers from the capital defender's office in Manhattan, who are
representing Smelefsky, said they were ``deeply disappointed'' with
Brown's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case does not fit into the extremely narrow range of
cases where a jury should be asked to decide if the penalty of
death is warranted,'' they said. ``In short, Steve Smelefsky is not
among the worst of the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City prosecutors who oppose the death penalty have had
to resist intense political pressure to seek it.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Manhattan district attorney, Robert Morgenthau, nor
the Bronx district attorney, Robert Johnson, have ever brought a
death penalty case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
