<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-SOLO-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAILING SOLO ROUND THE WORLD, AN AMERICAN IN DISTRESS DISCOVERS
MANY FRIENDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Calif., Uruguay, Argentina, Great Britain, France,
Russia)   By SUSAN B. ADAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neither wind nor rain nor broken mast will keep the American
solo sailor Brad Van Liew from the completion of his appointed
round. Or so it appears.
</P>
<P>
   Van Liew's odyssey in the Around Alone yacht race _ his first
solo circumnavigation _ seemed over as recently as last Sunday,
when he despondently reported that his 50-foot yacht Balance Bar
had been dismasted in a fierce squall and 10-to-15-foot seas less
than 90 miles out of Punta del Este, Uruguay. Van Liew and the
eight other solo sailors in the fleet were one day out of port en
route to Charleston, S.C., on the fourth and final leg of the
27,000-mile voyage that began last September.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Van Liew, a 31-year-old Californian who is the
youngest competitor in the race and the only American, limped back
to Punta del Este under jury rig, his team and other supporters
were rallying to his side. His wife, Meaghan, and the rest of his
team returned to the Uruguayan port to spearhead a fund-raising
effort with local volunteers; fellow sailors offered encouragement
and equipment; Hall Spars/Argentina said it could build a
replacement aluminum mast in 30 hours, and the Balance Bar Co., Van
Liew's sponsor based in Carpinteria, Calif., said it would match
every dollar raised by his ground crew to pay for the repairs and
new gear.
</P>
<P>
   Van Liew said Thursday that he hoped to be back in the race by
Saturday. ``I feel absolutely awesome,'' Van Liew said. ``It feels
like the world has picked me up by the scruff of my neck and said,
`You will not stop here.'''
</P>
<P>
   The bond that develops between sailors in an event like the
Around Alone can make for extraordinary displays of sportsmanship,
and his peers rallied around Van Liew in his distress. When they
heard of the dismasting, Jean-Pierre Mouligne, the current overall
leader of Class II for 40-to-50-foot yachts, immediately diverted
to assist, as did Mike Garside on Magellan Alpha.
</P>
<P>
   Van Liew and Garside, who had battled each other for second
place in Class II for the better part of three legs, had struck up
a friendship, talking almost daily and encouraging each other as
they competed. By the end of Leg 3, less than 10 hours separated
the pair. When he heard of Van Liew's misfortune from race
headquarters, Garside was devastated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like crying,'' the 54-year-old British sailor wrote in
an e-mail posted on the Around Alone Web site. ``The message was
bald enough. It simply said that Balance Bar had been dismasted and
that my young friend Brad was cutting away the fallen spars.''
</P>
<P>
   Garside said he felt better when Van Liew ``e-mailed to say he
was well on his way back to Punta under jury rig.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had more offers of help than he could possibly need and he
felt sure something would turn up for the good,'' Garside wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In one of those offers, Marc Thiercelin, the Frenchman now in
second place in Class I for 60-foot boats, pledged a mast and a
full set of sails to his stricken fleetmate. Before the start of
Leg 4, Thiercelin had received a new carbon fiber mast, but his
temporary aluminum replacement mast was too large for the 50-foot
Balance Bar. Thiercelin's sails would do, however, and they were
being cut down and resewn to fit Van Liew's smaller rig.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the water at the front of the fleet, Giovanni
Soldini and Thiercelin, the two sailors left in Class I, were
leading the race to Charleston. Soldini aboard Fila led Thiercelin
on Somewhere by some 20 miles with about 4,700 miles to go before
the finish. Through Friday, the two were making their way up the
coast of South America with Soldini following a course as close to
the shore as winds allowed and Thiercelin much farther east. Both
looked as if they would stay just ahead of a fierce southern cold
front that was predicted to move through the rest of the fleet this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Some 40 miles behind Thiercelin, Garside was leading Class II
yachts, followed by Mouligne (Cray Valley); Viktor Yazykov (Wind of
Change Russia); Neal Petersen (No Barriers); Minori Saito
(Shuten-dohji II), and Neil Hunter (Paladin II).
</P>
<P>
   The wind from the cold front will push the Class II yachts
forward, but they will also run into the Brazilian Current and be
subject to ``really awful sailing conditions,'' according to Ken
Campbell of Commanders' Weather. By contrast, Fila and Somewhere
will beat into brisk northerly headwinds of 25 knots.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
