<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2662 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-POLL-0418-COX     04-17 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-POLL-0418-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLL: GORE IMAGE WILTING UNDER WEIGHT OF CLINTON SCANDALS
 &HT;    Moving in both (w) Washington and (p) Politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Al Gore's campaign for president is starting to
feel Bill Clinton's pain -- that is, the fallout from the Clinton
administration scandals is beginning to contribute to the vice
president's declining favorability ratings, according to a new Pew
Research Center poll.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three out of four Americans polled by the center agreed
with the statement that they are ``tired of all the problems
associated with the Clinton administration'' -- a clear indication
that Gore is vulnerable to Republican suggestions that it is simply
``time for a change'' in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is ``clearly hurt by weariness with problems of the Clinton
administration,'' said Andrew Kohut, the director of the research
center and its chief pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, for the first time since September 1997, when
allegations of wrongdoing in the vice president's reelection
fundraising activities first surfaced, Gore's favorability ratings
have slipped below 50 percent in the Pew poll, which was released
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 47 percent of the public holds a favorable opinion of
Gore, significantly below the 58 percent favorable rating he
registered just before the Republican-led Congress began its
impeachment proceedings against President Clinton late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the new poll suggests that Gore has some personal
image problems -- that is, a sizeable number of Americans simply
don't like the vice president, or rather, the caricature that Gore
himself has helped to promote: boring, dull, stiff.
</P>
<P>
   Only 19 percent of voters used positive words to describe Gore
in the latest Pew poll, compared to 32 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And nearly a quarter of those polled used mocking words such as
``wimp'' or ``wooden'' to describe Gore. When voters volunteer such
negative terms to describe Gore, ``it may be their way of saying
they just don't like Al Gore,'' said Kohut.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, then, the task in seeking the Democratic Party's 2000
presidential nomination is to reintroduce himself to the American
people -- perhaps even, after having spent half of his 50 years in
public life, to reinvent himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it has to do with the fact that he is vice president
and the vice presidency usually is a shadow role,'' said Gore
campaign spokesman Roger Salazar. ``And it's hard for a vice
president to define himself, but that's what we're fixing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans like Gore better than Clinton as a person, but
not by an overwhelming margin in the latest Pew poll, given Gore's
``Boy Scout'' image. Fifty-two percent agreed with the statement,
``I like Al Gore better as a person than Bill Clinton.''
Thirty-five percent disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Americans don't see Gore as more caring than Clinton. Only 34
percent agreed with the statement, ``Al Gore cares more than Bill
Clinton about people like me.'' Fifty percent disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is no Bill Clinton,'' said Darrell West, a political
scientist at Brown University. ``The vice president lacks the
president's personal charisma and ability to connect to voters.''
And while he is seen as more ethical than Clinton, Gore ``is having
problems controlling his own destiny,'' West added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's problem is not with Democrats, however. Seventy-one
percent hold a favorable opinion of him. And in the current
one-on-one scrimmage with NBA Hall of Famer Bill Bradley, the vice
president is the overwhelming favorite to win the party's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's problem is with the American public at large,
specifically, independent and female voters and his fellow baby
boomers, as reflected in the Pew poll's latest theoretical match-up
of Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the frontrunner for the
Republican 2000 presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In this poll, taken in the last week of March, Gore trails Bush
41-54 percent, a much wider margin than in January, when he trailed
the Texas governor 44-50 percent. Gore leads Bush only among
non-whites, senior citizens and urban dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, the gender gap that helped fuel Clinton's
reelection in 1996 is helping Gore only at the margins. Women
prefer Bush over Gore by a margin of 52-42 percent. Men choose Bush
by a wider margin, 57-40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew Center's analysis of its polling data noted, however,
that Gore ``might take some comfort'' in the fact that early
presidential trial heat polls have a notoriously poor track record.
Not since 1967 have polls taken in the first quarter of the year
preceding a presidential election accurately forecast the winner.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1995, the latest example, then-Senate Majority
Leader Bob Dole led Clinton by 6 percentage points in the polls,
but lost the election 49 percent to 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was conducted by telephone March 24-30. It involved a
national sample of 1,786 adults 18 years of age or older. The
margin of error was 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
