<P>
   MEXICO-TRAFFICKER _ JUAREZ, Mexico _ It's a familiar tale in
Mexico by now. Small town boy becomes cop, turns corrupt and gets
into drug trafficking. The difference this time is that this former
police officer is an American citizen, Gilberto Salinas, aka
Gilberto Garza Garcia or ``Whitie Gil,'' who went from being a cop
in South Texas to marijuana smuggler to key figure in the Juarez
cartel, one of Mexico's most notorious cocaine-smuggling rings.
Salinas is jailed in Mexico now on money laundering and drug
smuggling charges. He is also wanted in Texas and Atlanta on drug
trafficking, and authorities in McAllen, Texas would like to
question him about the killing of a doctor there. (Ferriss, Cox
News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CRANE-RESCUE _ Reader on the events that unfolded Monday that
lead to the dramatic meeting of crane operator Ivers Sims, Atlanta
firefighter Matt Moseley and a DNR helicopter pilot 220 feet above
the rolling Fulton Bag and Cotton Mill fire in Atlanta. Following
each of the individuals involved _ Moseley, Sims and the pilot.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 60. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   DISABILITIES-CASE _ In a case that advocates for persons with
mental and physical disabilities are calling their ``Brown v. Board
of Education,'' the U.S. Supreme Court on April 21 will hear
arguments as to whether Georgia must pay for transferring disabled
patients out of state-run institutions if they can do better in a
more integrated facility, such as a group home. In December, the
U.S. Supreme Court agreed to hear the case when 26 states, led by
Florida, petitioned the high court to overrule a ruling against
Georgia by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. Since
then, however, disability advocacy groups have stormed state
attorneys general offices (with protestors being arrested in some
states) and successfully persuaded 18 of these 26 states to tell
the Supreme Court they've changed their minds. The lawsuit, filed
by two Atlanta-area women who resided at the Georgia Regional
Mental Hospital on Panthersville Road claims the Americans With
Disabilities Act allow disabled people to move into more integrated
settings if they are able, instead of being warehoused in state
institutions. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   KEEN _ Jerry Keen gave up his job at state chairman of the
Christian Coalition to work for a man who once publicly mocked
Christian conservatives. Keen, along with a handful of other former
coalition leaders, works for Steve Forbes, who is trying to make
himself the choice of conservative GOP primary voters. We spend
some time with Keen and profile this little-known, but influential
Georgian. (Sherman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TROOPER _ RALEIGH, N.C. _ C. Richard Holden, North Carolina's
first black commander of the Highway Patrol, takes charge amid
allegations and a legislative inquiry into whether troopers are
more likely to pull black drivers on North Carolina's roads. A
profile of Holden, a 29-year veteran of the state Patrol. (Burritt,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FUNERAL-INVESTIGATION _ WICHITA FALLS _Tres Hood was a popular
Wichita Falls television news anchor when he died of cancer at the
age of 31 last summer. Hood stayed on the air until shortly before
his death, delivering the evening news with a sunken face and
thinning hair. More than 1,400 people attended his funeral, where
he was eulogized as a professional who demonstrated how to live and
die with dignity. But what happened to Hood after his death robbed
him of all the dignity he stood for, his family says. The funeral
home allegedly botched Hood's embalming. The funeral home, owned by
industry giant Service Corporation International of Houston, denies
responsibility. Hood's family complained to the Texas Funeral
Service Commission, a state agency whose future is up in the air
because of turmoil that has erupted since it began investigating
the embalming practices of SCI. Lawmakers may abolish the agency,
which has been beset with funeral industry conflicts of interest, a
backlog of complaints and investigations, and allegations of
political pressure to drop the nearly $450,000 in fines it has
proposed against SCI. But Hood's family worries that Texas may lose
sight of consumers and what needs to be done to regulate a funeral
industry that could continue to bury its mistakes rather than
correct them. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   AIRFORCE _ In a ceremony that has national significance, the
U.S. Secretary of the Air Force and Sen. Hutchison will be in town
to give Mayor Kirk Watson and the City of Austin the deed to the
former Bergstrom Air Force Base, soon to be known almost
exclusively as Austin-Bergstrom International Airport. The
transformation from Air Force base to civilian airport is being
touted by Defense Department officials as evidence that there are
economic possibilities for former military sites. (Hiott, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GORE-POLL _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore's campaign for
president is showing signs of the American public's weariness with
the Clinton administration's scandals, according to a Pew Research
Center poll. Gore also is having problems with his personal image _
only 52 percent like him better than Bill Clinton. (Shepard, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: To move in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Once again, Congress has played a
passive role as U.S. troops entered combat abroad. As members
ponder billions in extra funding for the Kosovo operation, a look
at the forces that have led Congress to cede war-making initiative
to the president. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   DOLEWOMEN _ How likely is it that independent and Democratic
women would vote for Elizabeth Dole in open primary states like
Georgia and California? The answer could hold the key to her
chances to become the GOP nominee for president. Dole so far has
said little about her positions on a wide range of issues, but in
Georgia, she has attracted the support of some prominent
conservative women, including DeKalb Commissioner Elaine Boyer and
state Rep. Renee Untermayer. As her positions become known, can she
attract both moderates and conservatives? (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-ARCHIVES _ WASHINGTON _ America's treasured national
documents, including the Declaration of Independence and the
Constitution, are being bathed in a greenhouse gas. And that's
good. National Aeronautics and Space Administration chemists
recently used a laser-based instrument to determine that airtight
cases containing the two documents and the Bill of Rights have not
leaked. The laser's brief trip to the world of priceless historical
documents was an example of a growing trend among museum curators
and archivists to use Space Age technologies to deal with age-old
problems. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
