<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-UTILITIES-800&AMP;ADD-     04-17 1344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UTILITIES-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE INDUSTRY DEREGULATION, UTILITIES AVOIDING NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Mass., R.I., Pa., N.J.)  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For years, officials here and in other state
capitals have hailed competition as a way to lower electricity
bills, and New York is one of just five states that have actually
begun letting some customers choose their supplier of power.
</P>
<P>
   But the price framework the Pataki administration has created
provides very little room for competition, less than in almost any
other state that has begun the process. Customers are learning that
they cannot find a price much lower, or even slightly lower, than
the one being offered by their old, familiar utilities.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, most of the nation's major energy retailers have
stayed out of New York, although they are competing aggressively
for customers in several other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not about to jump into the New York market and lose
money,'' said Howard Fromer, director of government affairs in New
York for Enron Corp. of Houston. ``I can't believe any outside
marketer is making money in the New York market.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some officials at the Public Service Commission, the state
agency that regulates utilities, concede privately that there is
far less competition than they had hoped for. It was the
commission, whose members are appointed by Gov. George Pataki, that
designed the system for competition.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission's chairwoman, Maureen Helmer, said that while
New York might have less robust competition than some states have
now, it has laid the groundwork for more competition in the future.
``I think when you look in one or two years, you're going to see a
very different picture,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   New York has some of the highest electricity rates in the
country, about 50 percent above the national average. Business
groups say that makes the state less competitive economically, and
they have long pushed for a freer energy market.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, too, have high hopes for competition. They
predict that companies marketing ``green power,'' power generated
by the cleanest sources, will find ready takers even if the
companies charge a little more for electricity, a theory borne out
in other states. Power plants, particularly older ones burning coal
and oil, are a major source of air pollution and acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to realize that the choice of an energy
provider is the single most important environmental decision they
can make,'' said Ralph Kavanagh, energy program co-director for the
Natural Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   But if the rate structure does not leave room for the biggest
energy marketers to turn a profit in New York, smaller companies
offering green power say they stand even less of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York's setup is just not supportive of competition,'' said
Julie Blunden, vice president of Green Mountain Energy of South
Burlington, Vt., a leading seller of green power that has shunned
New York. ``We don't market ourselves as being cheaper, but price
competition helps us because it means people are out shopping for a
new supplier.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials and analysts say they believe that New York's
regulators wanted to shield the state's seven established regional
utilities, including Consolidated Edison, from the pressures of
competition. But some also contend that in making trade-offs, the
Public Service Commission believed that it had no choice but to
restrict competition.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a five-year transition from the traditional
monopolies to a competitive market, New York's utilities are being
radically reorganized. They are selling their power plants and each
one is splitting into two companies, one to own and maintain the
transmission and distribution system, and the other to sell power
to consumers. The commission was never sure that it had the legal
authority to order such changes _ the utilities threatened to tie
the state up in litigation for years if it tried _ so it negotiated
the transition with the utilities, reaching agreements with them in
1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Pataki administration was determined to
begin the process with across-the-board rate reductions, which
turned out to be 10 percent in Con Edison's territory and less in
other parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get the utilities to agree to restructuring and rate cuts,
they settled for less competition than they might have gotten,''
said Larry Shapiro, staff attorney at the New York Public Interest
Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Helmer said New York has been more aggressive than other
states in getting utilities to sell their power plants. That, she
said, will mean vigorous wholesale competition among power
producers, which will eventually translate into retail competition
and lower prices. The result, she said, will be ``more sustainable
benefits for New Yorkers than they may get in other states.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Advocates of competition laud the sale of the power plants, but
they say the price structure the state set still poses a long-term
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Competition in New York began last year in Con Edison's
territory, New York City and Westchester County, where about
one-fifth of the market has been opened up to competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers snapped up that power as soon as it was available, but
it is unclear how much real competition that reflects. Retailers
were able to offer only a very small savings over Con Edison's
rates, based mostly on a tax loophole that the administration has
warned it will close this year. And many of the consumers who took
advantage of the competition did not sign up with an outside
retailer, but with Con Edison's own new, competitive subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Even after states introduce competition, the old utilities still
hold monopoly control of the system that distributes power and
delivers it to homes and businesses. So a portion of every
customer's bill will continue to go to the utility, even if the
customer buys electricity elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly subjective process, state regulators look at the
old, monopoly-style utility bill and decide which charges represent
those services the utilities will continue to provide and which
reflect the actual price of electricity. The electricity portion of
the bill is known as a ``shopping credit'' or a ``back-out rate,''
meaning that consumers can stay with the utility, for now, at that
price, or shop for a better deal.
</P>
<P>
   The lower the shopping credit, the higher the guaranteed revenue
for the established utility, and the harder it becomes for any
company to undercut the utility's price.
</P>
<P>
   Among four of the five states where competition has begun _ New
York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania and Rhode Island _ as well as a
few others that have set their price structures but have not yet
ushered in competition, New York allows the least room for
competition by setting the lowest shopping credits. The fifth
state, California, is an anomaly in that regulators did not set
specific shopping credits, letting them fluctuate instead, and its
system effectively leaves even less of a margin for competition
than New York's does.
</P>
<P>
   The rate structure the Public Service Commission created for Con
Edison allows a shopping credit averaging about 3.5 cents a
kilowatt-hour out of a total bill of about 15 cents per
kilowatt-hour, though both figures can vary widely. The credits are
smaller, often less than 3 cents, for customers of upstate
utilities like Niagara Mohawk Power Corp.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, most residents and businesses in Pennsylvania
have shopping credits of 4 to 5 cents per kilowatt-hour; the
credits are scheduled to rise over the next few years until the
average is above 5 cents. New Jersey, which is scheduled to begin
some competition on June 1, has decided on a framework with
shopping credits generally above 5 cents. In Rhode Island and
Massachusetts, the average shopping credit is about 3.5 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
