<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT OF NOWHERE, A BIG SCORE FOR NETS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was like a gift from above, one night of nearly
perfect basketball for a team that has experienced a season filled
with hardship in the form of injuries, embarrassment and poor play.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, in their finest performance of the year, closed their
disappointing West Coast trip Friday night with a dominating 121-91
victory over the talented Seattle SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everything went right for the crestfallen Nets, who will
try to maintain their momentum at home on Sunday against the
Philadelphia 76ers. They outrebounded the taller Sonics by 48-35,
shot 51.1 percent, hit more than half of their shots for the first
time this season, made a season-best nine 3-pointers and matched
the NBA's mark for points in a regulation game this season.
</P>
<P>
   That the showing came on the back of a three-game losing streak,
which included humiliating defeats against the dismal Los Angeles
Clippers and the Denver Nuggets, made it all the more astounding.
Even the Nets (11-28) did not know exactly what to make of their
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a crazy year,'' said Keith Van Horn, who was one of
six Nets to score in double figures with 16 points. ``I don't
understand any of this. It makes you wonder what could've been.
It's kind of strange.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory should not be blown out of proportion, as Seattle
(19-20) is no longer the perennial Western Conference contender it
once was. And the Sonics were playing their third game in three
nights and coming off an emotional overtime victory in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who improved to 8-11 under the interim head coach Don
Casey, capitalized on the Sonics' weariness with the type of
tenacious defense that led them to five victories in six games
earlier this month. They double-teamed in the post to hold
Seattle's starting frontline to 16 points, played the passing lanes
well to make 12 steals and banged the Sonics to cut off their paths
to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   The gritty defense was pleasant to the eyes of the Nets'
coaching staff, which had watched its team play soft in allowing
229 points over the previous two games.
</P>
<P>
   When Scott Burrell drew a charging foul on John Crotty early in
the fourth quarter, Nets assistant Eddie Jordan jumped from his
seat to praise Burrell and pump his fist. It was only the fourth
charging foul the Nets have taken in the last 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't contained people,'' said Jordan, explaining the
Nets' defensive demise during the three losses. ``People were
driving right by us and getting anywhere on the floor they wanted
to. Our reputation was being built on making steals, so we got into
this gambling, reaching thing. We weren't using our bodies to get
in front of people and when somebody drove the middle, we were just
reaching instead of coming all the way over and taking a charge.
Good defensive teams step in and take charges.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' defense led to fast-break opportunities and propelled
them toward their offensive explosion. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
