<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHOOLS-REAL-3TAKE     04-17 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PRIVATE SCHOOLS, INGENUITY IS KEY TO EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHEN A. KLIMENT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The battle of Waterloo may have been won on the
playing fields of Eton, but for the private schools of New York
City it is the battle to find even a postage-stamp-size site for
baseball and tennis, or Latin and math, that has led to a range of
resourceful tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Suburban campus-type schools can make inroads into vacant land,
but for urban schools the options are limited. They can build
upward _ a choice limited by zoning. They can dig down _ an
expensive, unsettling step that several have nonetheless taken as a
last resort. Or they can subdivide existing space, a dismal step
that can often produce a rabbit warren of tight, listless rooms
that Dr. Noam Shudofsky, administrator of the Ramaz School, calls
``sardine-can status.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, in rare cases, they can buy real estate within walking
distance of the main building, then gut and rebuild or raze and
build, creating a sort of instant campus.
</P>
<P>
   Several private schools that have recently completed expansion
projects took distinct approaches to dealing with their space
problems. St. Aloysius School on West 132nd Street in Harlem
stretched its zoning-permitted expansion to the limit by
encroaching on its schoolyard to gain extra space for its library
and computer facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramaz School, anxious to consolidate its middle school,
managed with great dexterity to acquire a nearby site from the York
Preparatory School, in a creative exchange of sites that landed
York on the West Side and gave Ramaz an extended East Side urban
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to create for its girls an oasis in gritty, noisy New York
City, the Chapin School ended up using space over part of its
building for a large but cozy two-story learning and research
center, atop which is a new gymnasium along with a black-box
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Friends Seminary, which had enjoyed a single-building campus
since 1860, ventured across 15th Street to convert, in a gesture of
brightness and hope, the dark former art deco German Masonic temple
into a bright, high-tech, environmentally ``green'' math and
science center.
</P>
<P>
   Like other private schools, Trinity School was built in stages,
in its case on a constricted site that runs almost the full length
of West 91st Street between Columbus and Amsterdam avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Resolved to unify its middle school, which had been scattered
throughout an elegant brownstone structure and a corner concrete
fortress built in the 1960s, and in dire need of up-to-date gym
space, Trinity School razed the old story-and-a-half gym on its
midblock 130-foot site and replaced it with a carefully scaled
four-story glass and brick building.
</P>
<P>
   The new structure, designed by the architects Buttrick White &AMP;
Burtis, houses the new middle school classrooms on two of the
floors, and two 100-foot-long gymnasiums, one above the classroom
floors, the other below ground, on the other two floors, for a
total of some 43,000 square feet. The $8 million cost also covers
about 14,000 square feet of renovation in adjacent buildings.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy. To make room for the downstairs gym, Trinity had
to dig down 30 feet, 15 of them through rock. In the upper gym, to
make sure that bouncing balls and running feet didn't upset classes
beneath, a floating double floor was put in, with the upper floor
isolated from the lower by a system of spring mounts.
</P>
<P>
   The big worry in any addition or renovation is the risk of
losing the physical features that say ``school.'' Trinity's
headmaster, Henry Moses, frets over saving this element, which he
calls ``schoolness.'' At Trinity, on the side facing the playing
field _ an acre of Astroturf atop the roof of a parking garage _
the architects deftly hid the air-conditioning equipment behind a
new clock tower.
</P>
<P>
   The sleek tower houses a bell that once graced the parish house
of St. Agnes Chapel, which had formerly occupied the very site of
the new middle school. By a curious odyssey, the bell had migrated
to Trinity Church in Cornwall Bridge, Conn., only to return in 1998
to its first site.
</P>
<P>
   Like Trinity, the Ramaz School focused on a middle school _
grades five to eight _ when it embarked on its current building
program. Ramaz has had its high school in a metal-clad building on
East 78th Street since 1980 _ on the site of the now-defunct Finch
College _ and its lower school on East 85th Street. Grades five and
six were in the lower school, seven and eight in the upper school.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how it came to build a six-story building on 85th
Street between Lexington and Park avenues has as much to do with
real-estate resourcefulness as with architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The 85th Street site had been owned by York Preparatory School,
which was looking in vain for bigger quarters. Ramaz, determined to
keep its middle school students in the neighborhood, offered to buy
the York Prep buildings for $6 million, a sum that York, a
for-profit school, turned down because of the huge threatened tax
bite.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Born, a Ramaz board member who is a New York hotel
owner, developer and operator, then came into the picture,
Shudofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Born's idea was to buy a suitable building for York, then
exchange it for York's 85th Street building. Under a section of the
Internal Revenue Code that allows like-kind exchanges, such a
maneuver would avoid a tax. Born found a site for York Prep on West
68th Street and bought it. York liked it, the exchange was made,
the old York complex was torn down, and work began on the new Ramaz
middle school.
</P>
<P>
   Designing and building the school on the former York Prep site,
augmented by an adjoining brownstone, has been anything but
straightforward, although the project is on track for a fall 1999
opening. Ramaz at first wanted to build a bridge to connect the new
site with the lower school almost directly across the street, but
the plan didn't work because East 85th Street is an east-west fire
street and cannot be obstructed. The idea of a tunnel was
eliminated because of the spaghettilike infrastructure of pipes and
cables.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest part, according to the architect, Robert Immerman
of Horowitz/Immerman Architects, has been ``fitting the school's
requirements into a medium-sized space.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The midblock zoning regulations are very strict,'' Immerman
said, ``which means we don't have the luxury of high ceilings and
two-story, double-height spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   To fit the school's 60,000 square feet into the envelope allowed
by zoning requirements, it chose an option also used by Trinity, to
dig down. Ramaz ended up excavating three stories to accommodate
the gym, locker room, mail room and music studio, all of which
could prosper without daylight.
</P>
<P>
   The $30 million construction cost, which does not include
furnishings or retrofitting existing space, was borne by a
fund-raising campaign among members of the modern Orthodox Jewish
community that includes outlying areas of the New York region, as
well as the 1,000 families of the Orthodox Congregation Kehilath
Jeshurun, with which Ramaz is affiliated.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
