<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2674 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISABILITIES-CASE18-C     04-17 1663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABILITIES-CASE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patients stage showdown over rights of disabled
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As a mental health patient at Georgia Regional
Hospital, Elaine Wilson wanted out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt trapped, I felt like I was in a little box,'' said
Wilson, 47, who is mildly mentally disabled and has a personality
disorder. ``You couldn't do anything there but sleep or eat or
smoke. That's all you could do.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Wilson joined a lawsuit filed by fellow patient Lois
Curtis, who is also mildly mentally disabled and has been diagnosed
with schizophrenia. Curtis, 31, was institutionalized for three
years at Georgia Regional before Atlanta Legal Aid lawyers filed
suit on her behalf in federal court in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson now lives in College Park with a roommate; Curtis lives
in a group home in Decatur. Although the women have been released
from the mental health hospital in DeKalb County, their lawsuit has
made its way to the U.S. Supreme Court, which will consider the two
women's claims on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The case focuses on the Americans with Disabilities Act. Signed
into law in 1990, it calls for greatly increased access to public
and private facilities and programs for individuals with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The high court will decide whether the ADA requires states to
pay for the placement of mentally disabled patients such as Curtis
and Wilson in community settings when doctors say they are ready to
be removed from institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The case brought by Wilson and Curtis, known in the lawsuit only
by their initials, E.W. and L.C., is being closely watched by the
country's well-organized disability rights organizations. The
groups have staged protests nationwide, calling the lawsuit a
symbolic civil rights case that follows decades of government
segregation of disabled people in mental health institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To people with disabilities, this case is as significant as
Brown vs. Board of Education was to people of color,'' said Mark
Johnson, advocacy coordinator for the Shepherd Center in Atlanta,
referring to the landmark U.S. Supreme Court ruling on school
integration. ``When the ADA was passed, it was a mandate for
integration. Now we've got our state challenging our right to
integration.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Olmstead, director of Georgia's Department of Human
Resources, fears the case will lead to the wholesale release of the
state's mentally retarded patients into places where many cannot
receive proper care.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has been steadily removing its mental health patients
from institutions over the past several years, Olmstead said. Since
1996, he noted, the DHR has closed three mental health institutions
and funneled $83 million toward services in community settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to avoid making mistakes that have been made in the
past with the release of mental health patients, many of whom wound
up living under bridges, homeless or in jails,'' he said. ``You
need to have adequate resources to care for them after their
release. I just think you can do this without a court order.''
</P>
<P>
   Olmstead has not been immune from the protests. He returned home
from work this month to find wheelchair tracks all over his front
yard and placards posted in his lawn. The Macon chapter of ADAPT, a
disability rights group, had held a protest at his house earlier
that day.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Jamieson, an Atlanta Legal Aid lawyer, said the ADA allows
the integration of disabled individuals into the community only
when their doctors say they are ready to go and only when their
release will not fundamentally alter the state's ability to
administer its mental health care programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case forces us to focus on what we've allowed states to
do for generations,'' Jamieson said. ``They've said they'll treat
these people, but only if they're put aside in a big building and
left there. Now the ADA mandates that people with disabilities get
to decide if they want to live a reasonably normal life in a
community setting.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Jamieson's arguments have prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Marvin Shoob in Atlanta first ruled in her
favor, and, a year ago, so did a three-judge panel on the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the denial of community placements to individuals
with disabilities such as L.C. and E.W. is precisely the kind of
segregation that Congress sought to eliminate,'' Judge Rosemary
Barkett wrote in a unanimous opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But 26 states joined Georgia in its appeal to the U.S. Supreme
Court, and in December the high court decided to hear the case.
That decision _ coupled with the 26-state petition _ was tantamount
to throwing down the gauntlet to the country's disabilities rights
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few months, advocacy groups have exerted enormous
political pressure on state governors and attorneys general, urging
them to withdraw from the Supreme Court petition.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning reversal, 19 of the 26 states did, telling the
U.S. Supreme Court they no longer supported Georgia's position.
</P>
<P>
   Disabilities rights groups have deluged state offices with
letters and e-mails, staged protests and news conferences. In
Texas, 17 activists were arrested at the governor's mansion while
urging Gov. George W. Bush to remove his state from the petition.
Although Bush refused to budge, his brother, Gov. Jeb Bush of
Florida, later withdrew that state's support.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, only eight states remained on the petition.
Eddie Roland, director of the DHR's mental health division, wrote
to them, imploring them to hang on.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt, you and your public officials are being pressured to
withdraw your state's support,'' he wrote. ``I am writing to urge
you to stay with us.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, South Carolina notified the Supreme Court that
it, too, was withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   The legal issue for the court to consider Wednesday is the
language in Title II of the ADA, which says ``no qualified
individual with a disability shall, by reason of his disability, be
excluded from participation in or be denied the benefits of the
services, programs or activities of a public entity or be subjected
to discrimination by any such entity.'' The court must also
consider ADA regulations that require the services to be
administered ``in the most integrated setting appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   In its briefs to the Supreme Court, Georgia argues that the ADA
provides disabled people access to activities that only nondisabled
people engage in. Ramps must be constructed so wheelchair-bound
individuals can have equal access to public facilities such as
museums, according to the state's arguments. But the ADA should not
apply to mental health patients seeking state treatment in a
group-home setting because those facilities have only disabled
people in them _ and for that reason, there is no discrimination
when such care isn't provided, the state said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Gottesman, who will argue the case on behalf of Atlanta
Legal Aid, said Congress never intended the ADA to be interpreted
so narrowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the statute is to enable the disabled to be
integrated into the community,'' he said. ``Obviously, if you're
locked up in a mental institution, that's impossible. ... It's like
saying to AIDS patients, `If you want medical treatment paid for by
the state, we'll provide it, but you have to agree to live in a
prison to get it.'''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Olmstead, the former mayor of Macon who was
appointed to head the DHR in 1994, said he finds the criticisms of
his agency ``kind of insulting.'' He said he fully supports moving
disabled patients out of state hospitals and into the community,
but only when adequate planning and services are in place.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, the DHR has moved 450 people from mental retardation
institutions into the community, he said. ``That's something they
don't speak about.''
</P>
<P>
   Olmstead added that 1,900 mentally retarded individuals _ many
living with aging parents who can no longer provide for them _ are
on a waiting list to receive state services. If the state is
required by the courts to move patients in institutions into group
homes, it may create further delays for people on the waiting
lists, Olmstead said.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 3,000 people housed in the state's eight mental
health institutions. About 1,200 of these individuals are
psychiatric patients who reside there only for brief periods. About
220 are forensics patients, such as those charged with crimes. The
rest are mental health patients, as were Wilson and Curtis.
</P>
<P>
   Gottesman, a Georgetown University Law Center professor, said it
costs less money to treat mentally disabled people in the
community, compared to an institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is overwhelming in that regard,'' he said. ``It's
politics that explains the states' resistance. It's a combination
of the employees in these institutions don't want to lose their
jobs, the admnistrators don't want to lose their kingdoms, and
there are still lots of folks out in the community who are happy
with continuing to lock these people up and keep them out of
sight.''
</P>
<P>
   During her stay at Georgia Regional, Curtis sat in a day room
for hours at a time and smoked up to three packs of cigarettes a
day. Since her release, she has stopped smoking and takes six
classes a day at a habilitation center.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really blooms at art,'' said Sandra Fields, director of
the Foundation of Exceptional Achievers center. ``She's happy,
she's content, she's expressing herself more and making more of her
own choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson recalled times at the hospital when she was bound to a
wheelchair by a bedsheet because she was over-medicated. Since her
release, Wilson said, she has taken up ceramics, crocheting and
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I have accomplished a lot since I've been out,'' she
said. ``It feels great to do all those things that I want to do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHOOLS-REAL-2NDTA     04-17 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: is affiliated.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A special problem faced the 98-year-old Chapin, an all-girl
kindergarten through high school on East End Avenue at 84th Street,
across from Carl Schurz Park. Last September Chapin completed an
extensive library, gymnasium, and black-box theater over an
existing gym.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying challenge, said Sandra Theunick, the head of the
school, was not so much growing enrollment _ from 573 in 1992 to
619 today _ as a concern that the quality of school life was in
danger of getting lost in the effort to reconcile the technical
demands of modern education with Chapin's goal of small classes and
informal settings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed space for the girls for reflective thought,'' said
Ms. Theunick, ``spaces where they'd be more able to learn to
communicate one on one.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Butler, a partner in the architectural firm Butler
Rogers Baskett, which designed the addition, said the new
construction was ``a wonderful opportunity to rationalize the
internal organization and create new spaces that would serve the
faculty and students well into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was a two-and-a-half-story addition with 22,000
square feet of new space at the geometric center of the school, as
well as 26,000 square feet of renovations elsewhere in the
building.
</P>
<P>
   Most in sync with Chapin's goals is the library, known as the
Annenberg Center for Learning and Research. It's a two-story
spread, amply studded with small group-study rooms, plus warm brown
alcoves with carrels, tables and huge comfortable armchairs,
suitable for quiet study, reading and informal talk. The center
provides just the sort of haven Ms. Theunick seeks as a foil to the
toughness of the city. Large windows flood the space with natural
light.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into the library is a large multimedia classroom equipped
to handle everything from lectures to video presentations and
conferencing. And for fitness, there's a well-equipped gymnasium,
adjoined by a 72-seat theater. The entire design is topped by a
sloping roof of gray metal and a row of matching air exhausts.
</P>
<P>
   A renovated ground-floor dining room big enough to feed 750
students and staff in 90 minutes for breakfast and lunch was part
of the renovation, completed last October. There is even a space
where kindergartners can take a 30-minute nap, as specified under
state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The $16 million construction budget, which includes renovation
of existing space plus money for maintenance, was met in part by
funds from a successful $25 million capital campaign. The Walter
Annenberg Foundation, no doubt motivated by the presence on campus
of an Annenberg granddaughter, with other relatives as alumnae,
gave $6 million for the library.
</P>
<P>
   Friends Seminary, a 570-student coed school whose enrollment has
nearly doubled since 1950, has had a single-site campus since 1860.
It sits on a block between East 15th and 16th streets and faces
tree-lined Stuyvesant Square, the sort of fresh-air amenity popular
with city schools hungry for open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, pressed for space, committed to reducing class size,
eager to strengthen its math and science instruction, and having
exhausted possibilities of expanding within its site, resolved to
cross the street, thereby creating the first unconnected campus in
its history. ``We're very tightly packed,'' said Richard Eldridge,
the principal.
</P>
<P>
   Looking around for feasible, affordable space, Friends Seminary
viewed some 15 sites, including banks, clubs and a Salvation Army
home. In the end, it bought a five-story-plus-basement structure on
the south side of East 15th Street for some $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The structure had been built in 1880 and renovated in 1936 into
a stylistic mix of Greek Doric and art deco by its occupants, who
were members of a group of Masonic lodges. The building was known
as the German Masonic Temple. During its 1936 remodeling the
structure lost nearly all its daylight; the front windows were
pared down and rear windows covered entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The resolve to cross 15th Street was unsettling to teachers and
administrators, some of whom felt the move would be divisive. They
saw themselves as a single-school community where children in
kindergarten could have contact with 12th-graders, and they didn't
want to lose that.
</P>
<P>
   The solution was to save the casual contacts among grades in the
old building, and to use the annex to beef up math and science and
add a black-box theater and seminar rooms. The 16,000-square-foot
annex adds about 25 percent to Friends' original space.
Construction cost came to $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation was radical. First, said its architect, Ross
Anderson of Anderson Architects, ``We had to let in the light.''
The building had functioned as a dark place of secretive ceremonies
and rituals. ``Our challenge was to convert it to light,'' he said.
So the stairway was moved to the center, freeing up outside walls
for windows to light the classrooms. Each floor has a piazza, an
irregular open place where students, as in Chapin's library, can
casually meet.
</P>
<P>
   The annex ended up a cheerful, funky place, with walls at odd
angles, and plenty of industrial materials such as diamond plate
sheet steel and fiber-reinforced cement board walls with intricate
arithmetical incisions that change from floor to floor. The
architects retained some of the Masonic symbols on the facade, half
concealed by panels of green frosted glass.
</P>
<P>
   The annex went ``green'' with a vengeance. Old wooden joists
were removed, but not discarded, during demolition, to be reused on
other construction projects. Materials were chosen for their
healthy qualities _ low v.o.c. (volatile organic compound) paints
were used because they release fewer toxic compounds as they dry.
</P>
<P>
   Materials were also chosen for their environmental properties.
Anderson asked suppliers about possible pollution occurring during
each material's mining and manufacture, how durable it was and how
easily recycled. Glass was chosen that has reduced heating and
cooling loads, and lights are set to turn off in any room that no
one is using. Students and teachers may open windows.
</P>
<P>
   Friends paid for the Annex construction in two ways, Eldridge
said. A $7 million capital fund-raising campaign has yielded $5.3
million so far. Some of this paid for a part of the construction.
</P>
<P>
   The balance of construction cost came from bonds issued by the
Industrial Development Authority, a New York state agency empowered
to issue tax-exempt Civic Facility bonds to nonprofit institutions,
typically at a 6.125 percent interest rate, rising to 7.0 percent,
a point or two below commercial rates.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds are sold as a package to investors. They are used by
independent schools, such as Friends and Trinity, which typically
create a sinking fund to pay off the bonds over 10, 20 or 30 years,
according to Fred Calder, executive director of the New York State
Association of Independent Schools.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
