<HEADER>
A2675 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLARK-0418-COX     04-17 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLARK-0418-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIR ATTACKS CONTINUE AS CLARK EXPLORES POSSIBILITIES ON THE
GROUND
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0418.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ NATO's relentless air assault on Yugoslavia
continued Saturday as the alliance's top military leader visited
Macedonia and Albania in an effort to seek support for deploying
more U.S. combat forces in the region, possibly including ground
troops for action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's supreme allied commander,
made his first visit to the Balkans since the start of the bombing
campaign last month in an apparent effort to sound out political
and military leaders about an escalation of NATO operations on
Yugoslavia's southern flank.
</P>
<P>
   His surprise trip came a day after the Clinton administration
formally acknowledged it was considering a limited ground-forces
operation into Kosovo as one of three options in the next phase of
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Clark won assurances from Macedonian leaders that 4,000 more
troops could be added to the 12,000-troop NATO contingent already
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, Clark indicated that NATO's newly established
airbase would soon be handling a rapid influx of U.S. troops and
equipment for an American strike force, as well as more NATO troops
devoted to helping Albanian and international humanitarian agencies
cope with the influx of more than 300,000 refugees into the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The Rinas Air Field ``is probably going to be one of the busiest
spots in Europe for the next several days,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after meeting with Macedonian officials in Skopje,
Clark vowed to crush Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
military capability. He called NATO's continuing air war ``a
campaign against the policies which have caused the humanitarian
tragedy that is affecting this country.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent wave of new refugees has pushed the total number of
Kosovar Albanians seeking refuge in Macedonia to nearly 130,000.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces appear to be making a final push to empty Kosovo of
ethnic Albanians. Some 25,000 refugees, lashed by rain and high
winds, arrived in Albania and Macedonia Saturday and as many as
100,000 more are expected in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather over the area Friday night hampered air operations
and again made it difficult for NATO planes to target Serb forces
in the southern Kosovo region where refugees are being driven from
the province, NATO officials said. However, by mid-day Saturday,
the weather had improved significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NATO on Saturday revealed what it said was further
evidence of atrocities by Serb forces in Kosovo, disclosing aerial
photos of what it claimed may be up to 150 fresh graves near the
Kosovo town of Izbica.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that there is mounting evidence of detentions,
summary executions and mass graves,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea
told reporters at NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that based on refugee accounts, about 3,200 ethnic
Albanians had been slain by Serbs in the province in the past
several weeks. He said the figures could not be verified.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced Friday that NATO is considering three
possible scenarios to rescue ethnic Albanians trapped inside
Kosovo, which has been ravaged by Yugoslav forces and Serbian
paramilitary gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is a plan to send NATO combat troops across
Yugoslavia's southern border to carve out a corridor of territory
the alliance would control. The other options are air drops of food
and medical supplies and the insertion of humanitarian aid groups
under NATO protection.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials stressed that the corridor plan is merely
under consideration and spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon called the
option ``unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clark held his consultations in Macedonia and Albania, a
senior Yugoslav commander told Serb reporters that NATO would
suffer heavy losses if it launched a ground invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia is ``preparing for an all-out war,'' said Gen.
Nebojsa Pavkovic, chief of the army's third division, based in
southern Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In case of an intervention on the ground in Kosovo, NATO would
face 150,000 armed men,'' Pavkovic said. ``Even if every third
bullet (these men) fired hits a target, it will be a price the
aggressor will have to pay for coming into our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's trip to the region seemed aimed at gauging reaction in
Albania and Macedonia to the plans under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   He hinted that the initial goal of American Apache attack
helicopters and artillery units being deployed in Albania may be a
limited one: clearing out a zone along Albania's northern border
with Kosovo of Serbian gunners and infiltrators who have been
raiding and shooting mortar shells into Albania for the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to do everything we can to stabilize the
situation here in Albania,'' Clark said. ``We are very concerned
about the situation in the north, where Serb aggression against
this country is increasingly evident, with artillery being fired
across the border and infantry forays and other things. That has to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian leaders gave Clark assurances that the contingent of
12,000 NATO troops currently in Macedonia could be increased by
4,000 in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Cox Newspapers after his meeting with
Clark, Prime Minister Ljubco Georgievski said Clark did not
formally request that Macedonia allow a NATO invasion force to be
based in the country.
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops initially came to Macedonia last fall as a
contingency force to extract international truce monitors in Kosovo
if needed. A United Nations force has been in the country since the
early 1990s, created to ensure that the Balkans conflict did not
spill across the border into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Georgievski suggested that Macedonia would consider a NATO
request to serve as a staging area for offensive troops if it
received a fast-track application to become a member of the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very good if Macedonia becomes part of NATO,
because then the obligations of Macedonia toward NATO would be
different. The security and long-range consequences would be
different,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, NATO has more than 650 aircraft committed to its air war
against Yugoslavia, which began March 24. More than 22,500 NATO
ground troops are posted near Kosovo's borders or scheduled to
arrive over the next week or so.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
