<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHOOLS-REAL-3RDTA     04-17 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-REAL-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Independent Schools.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With far skimpier resources but no less urgent space problems,
St. Aloysius School is a 330-student pre-kindergarten through
eighth grade co-ed school at 223 West 132nd Street. Enrollment has
more than tripled in the last three years, largely because of the
efforts of its principal, Laurel Senger.
</P>
<P>
   The school, which the Jesuit Province of New York operates for
the Roman Catholic Archdiocese, occupies a nondescript brick
structure in the middle of a long block of distinguished
brownstones. It is two houses away from the ornate, neo-Italian
Gothic church dedicated to the same saint.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by its strong-minded principal, who taught elementary
school in Vermont and worked at Covenant House before joining St.
Aloysius in 1990, the school took some of the pressure off when it
expanded into its courtyard with a 4,500-square-foot building
completed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Its architect, Michael Doyle of Acheson Thornton Doyle, said he
was able to squeeze two stories into the 22-foot above-ground limit
by excavating enough for the lower story to count as a cellar,
which doesn't count toward the overall zoned height. The students
benefited most from a new library, an 11-terminal computer room and
a roof garden used for teaching. The cost was $1 million _ a high
figure necessitated in part by the small landlocked site and a tiny
7-foot access alley, making for a difficult construction job.
</P>
<P>
   Its annual tuition is $1,600, about 10 percent of the fees
charged by richer schools such as Trinity and Chapin, and St.
Aloysius had to work hard to finance the recent addition. Seventeen
individuals and foundations ended up paying the bills. Operating
costs have come from the Archdiocese and the Jesuit Province, but
the school is under pressure to obtain more independent financing
or face closing. A capital campaign to raise $4 million to $5
million is pending.
</P>
<P>
   In a city like New York, the options to grow that are open to
private schools are limited. The Buckley School on East 73rd Street
bought an adjacent brownstone for expansion, but on finding that
the floors didn't match, ended up gutting the interior and
rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   Collegiate School, on 78th Street off West End Avenue, retained
an architect, David Helpern, who managed deftly to fill in the
narrow alley between its two main buildings. The alley had been
used for play space. The new infill building provided room for an
expanded gymnasium, an art studio and a new kindergarten, but above
all it integrated the two buildings horizontally _ all without
requiring a zoning variance.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill School is negotiating to sell its current East 95th
Street building, and is under contract to buy the five-story
Madison Square Boys and Girls Club at Second Avenue and 29th
Street, with a September 2000 planned move-in date, according to
Kristine Baxter, the head of school. Churchill has hired Paul Segal
Associates Architects to renovate the building, adding two stories,
to accommodate the school's expansion to include grades nine
through 12.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding in dribs and drabs doesn't pay, said Calder, the
executive director of the independent schools association. In 1990
Ramaz considered a modest 11,000-square-foot addition over its
present 78th Street structure. But the work would have cost $5
million, and code problems were awesome. ``So we discarded it,''
said Shudofsky. A little can be worse than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   With a spacious campus built around a large green, Horace Mann
School in the Riverdale section of the Bronx has managed to avoid
many of the pressures facing schools in more built-up areas of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Horace Mann is set to expand this fall into two new buildings on
its Riverdale campus designed by the firm of Gruzen Samton. A
horseshoe-shaped structure with 21 classrooms will be neighbor to a
pie-shaped arts and dining center with a 225-seat concert hall
overlooking Van Cortlandt Park. A major renovation of Horace Mann's
1910 high school building is to get under way in 2000, says Dr.
Eileen Mullady, the head of school.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line facing private schools' boards and
administrators that with annual tuition pushing through the $20,000
level, parents are looking for more than simply getting sons and
daughters into Mount Holyoke or Yale. They are after value _
congenial environments, small classes, well-equipped resource
centers, individual-centered athletic programs _ and expect the
schools to provide such amenities.
</P>
<P>
   And a nice modern new building creates a challenge for teachers
and principals. As Ms. Theunick of Chapin said, ``We now have to
live up to the opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
