<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CONGRESSIONAL-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EARLY START TO BATTLE FOR PIVOTAL HOUSE SEAT IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ The moment Rush Holt, a Democrat, had broken
the Republicans' grip on the 12th Congressional District last
November, both political parties decided that central New Jersey
would be a major battle zone in the fight for control of the U.S.
House of Representatives in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But few could have imagined then that the skirmishing would
start so soon.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a second former Republican congressman stepped
forward as a potential challenger to Holt. And before the day
ended, the national congressional committees of the two parties had
already issued statements pummeling each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all seems a bit premature,'' said a slightly bewildered
Holt, whose 105th day in office was Thursday. ``I'm not prepared to
engage in a partisan campaign for re-election only three months
after I was sworn in.''
</P>
<P>
   The traditional start of the all-out campaigning for
congressional seats is still about eight months off, after the
November elections. But last week provided a preview of the kind of
seat-by-seat fight that each side intends to wage next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 12th District is very high on our target list,'' said
Terry Nelson, the political director of the National Republican
Congressional Committee, on Friday. ``We think Rush Holt is
vulnerable on the demographics of the district. This is a
Republican seat by any measure, and we should be able to get it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson conceded that recapturing the district would not be
easy. ``I think the Democrats know it is not a seat they should
have,'' he said, ``but they are going to do everything they can to
keep it in their column.''
</P>
<P>
   The district stretches from the green lawns of Princeton
University near its southern boundaries to the foothills of
Bedminster in the north, and despite the ideological and geographic
landscapes it covers, it could always be counted on to vote
Republican in House races _ that is, until last November.
</P>
<P>
   Holt's victory and a sprinkling of other upsets across the
nation helped the Democrats reduce the Republican majority's margin
to six seats in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the margin is only six seats, every seat is vitally
important,'' said David Plouffe, the executive director of the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee. ``This is a swing
seat, and so we will watch this race very closely, as will the
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   With at least three candidates who have held the 12th District
job in the last five years vying to return to it, voters are going
to need a score card to follow next year's race.
</P>
<P>
   There is Holt, 50, a physicist from Princeton. He was declared
the loser on election night, only to see that call reversed when
election officials discovered late in the evening that they had
transposed results from a heavily Democratic precinct and given a
huge advantage to his Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, so far, is Richard A. Zimmer, who
represented the district for three terms before he gave up the seat
in 1996 to run for the Senate. Zimmer lost in a bare-knuckled
contest to Rep. Robert G. Torricelli, a Democrat whose campaign was
managed by Plouffe.
</P>
<P>
   Standing between Zimmer and the House nomination is Michael
Pappas, who succeeded him. Pappas lost to Holt last November but
promptly announced that he would be a candidate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   A primary match-up between Zimmer, who calls himself a social
moderate and fiscal conservative, and Pappas, a hard-core
conservative, sets up a proxy fight between two ideological wings
of the party. ``The presence of both Dick and myself in this race
will offer voters a clear choice between our two different visions
of government and where the Republican Party is headed,'' Pappas
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas said he had the backing of David Norcross, the Republican
national committeeman from New Jersey, a grass-roots organization,
and support that was ``second to none.'' Pappas also noted that
Zimmer, who had amassed at least 64 percent of the vote in each of
his three races for the House, received only 50.8 percent of the
vote in the 12th District ``in his first race against a
well-funded, formidable Democrat'' _ Torricelli.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNERAL-INVESTIGATION     04-17 2371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNERAL-INVESTIGATION18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newscaster's death raises questions about funeral homes'
influence on regulatory rulings
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Everyone in town knew that Jefferson
Frank ``Tres'' Hood III was dying _ and that he was too young to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Hood was a TV star in this North Texas city, a homegrown news
anchor with a soft touch for storytelling. When the story affected
him, though, he wouldn't tell it. Colon cancer was killing Hood at
age 31, but he ignored the gaunt face in the mirror and anchored
the news on the local CBS affiliate until he couldn't get out of
bed anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 1,400 people attended Hood's funeral last July. Within
months, the death of this beloved local celebrity would become
entangled in one of the nastiest government messes in Texas: how to
regulate the state's multimillion-dollar funeral industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hood's family claims the funeral home botched his embalming.
Fluid leakage caused the wooden casket to break, and a maroon
liquid leaked from his marble crypt and puddled on the mausoleum
floor. The family paid nearly $7,000 to have the crypt cleaned and
Hood's remains put in a new copper casket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my son was violated terribly,'' said Gayle
Johnson, Hood's mother. ``I want justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The family filed a consumer complaint with the Texas Funeral
Service Commission. But chaos over funeral regulation in Texas
delayed the investigation and raised questions about the influence
of funeral home companies in state regulatory decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Hood was embalmed by the world's biggest funeral home company,
Service Corporation International of Houston. The company's
embalming practices have been under investigation by Texas for more
than a year. Regulators have recommended a record fine of nearly
$450,000 for alleged violations. SCI is fighting back, and the
controversy has exposed the agency's lackluster record of enforcing
the law and added to internal strife and staff turnover.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy involves campaign contributions to Gov. George
W. Bush, whistleblowers who allege government corruption and a
mistrust that runs so deep that the agency's acting director often
uses fluorescent-orange tape to secure his office door when he's
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of Texas are simply not being served in an
acceptable manner,'' said state Rep. Jim Pitts (R-Waxahachie), who
is leading a move in the Texas Legislature to dismantle or
reconfigure the state funeral agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a consistent concern that this agency may be
hampered in its effectiveness due to the strong industry
representation on the board,'' he said. ``The Texas Funeral Service
Commission does not exist to serve the industry; it is there to
serve the public.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas House of Representatives voted last week to kill the
agency's $500,000 annual funding beginning in September. But Pitts
and others said the vote was mostly symbolic and that they plan to
restructure the agency to reduce funeral industry influence that
has left Texas with lax enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral agency has been in turmoil for a year.
</P>
<P>
   The commission challenged SCI's embalming practices in 1998,
finding that the company used an unlicensed, in-house company to
embalm bodies in the Dallas-Fort Worth area and allowed
unsupervised apprentices to embalm bodies. The commission
recommended a fine of nearly $450,000. In February, however, the
commission decided to re-evaluate its investigation after questions
were raised by the governor and state lawmakers who received
campaign contributions from SCI's political action committee. If
the commission's internal review of its SCI investigation finds
that its staff overstepped their authority, the whole matter could
be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Two key agency employees have been fired, and both are suing to
be reinstated. Executive director Eliza May was fired in February
after the board said it lost confidence in her ability to manage
the agency. Her lawsuit alleges she was fired for complaining that
SCI held improper influence over the commission's work and that
Bush's staff tried to pressure her to end the investigation into
SCI's embalming practices. Bush, she pointed out, received $35,000
in campaign contributions from SCI's PAC between 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Cole Reed, the agency's only investigator at the time, was fired
in January for alleged insubordination. His lawsuit alleges that he
was fired after he contacted Bush's office to complain that May had
instructed him to go to the Texas Ethics Commission to research
campaign contributions by SCI's PAC. Reed was the funeral agency's
representative at the disentombment of Hood's body in Wichita Falls
in December. After Reed was fired, the Hood case stalled. Another
investigator has since been hired. The governor's office has
allowed SCI to have two of its executives on the agency's
nine-member governing board since February even though Texas law
prohibits such dominance by one company. Last week, Bush named a
replacement for one of the SCI commissioners, but the new appointee
cannot serve until the Senate confirms the nomination. That is not
expected to happen until next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Funeral Service Commission has a backlog of about 50
complaints, including the one filed by Hood's family last year. The
agency received 167 complaints last year, most of which are
generated by staff inspectors who uncover alleged violations during
routine inspections or are filed by consumers concerned about
overpricing.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints about botched embalmings are not common, said David
Richards, general counsel at the funeral agency.
</P>
<P>
   Hood's family had planned to hold an open-casket visitation at
SCI-owned Hampton Vaughan funeral home the night before the
newscaster's funeral. But when they saw Hood's embalmed body, they
had to change plans. Fluid leaked from Hood's eyes and mouth, and
his face was so distorted that his 18-year-old brother became
hysterical and fled the room. ``My husband said, `It looks like a
rookie did it,' '' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The worst was yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks of his July 27, 1998, funeral, Hood's $4,495
mahogany casket began to leak. An odor developed. Soon, Johnson
found swarms of gnats when she visited her son's tomb.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral home officials urged Hood's family to put a strong
deodorant in the mausoleum because a mouse might have died in the
walls, then suggested the family should have the local cemetery
monument company bleach the crypt and reseal it if necessary,
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   By November, Johnson had made arrangements to have Hood's body
disentombed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you've got to take care of it whether they're going
to help you or not,'' Johnson said. ``I know my son's soul is not
in there, but his earthly remains are. It was not the kind of
dignity that he deserves. No one does.''
</P>
<P>
   SCI general counsel James Shelger declined to comment on the
case except to say, ``We want to resolve this family's concerns
privately.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hood's family, an SCI funeral home official said
the embalming was difficult because the body had been autopsied.
Johnson said she had requested an autopsy because she suspected her
son had received incompetent medical care.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the funeral commission, Hood's uncle, Bill
Walker, said a funeral home officer ``told me that because a wooden
casket was used that leakage of fluid from the vault was possible
and that they had no control over that.''
</P>
<P>
   After arranging to have the crypt opened, Johnson's lawyer filed
a complaint against Hampton Vaughan with the funeral commission,
along with a request that the state send a representative to the
disentombing Dec. 1. SCI officials declined to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since this is a private family mausoleum in a city cemetery, I
am of the opinion responsibility lies with the family and the City
of Wichita Falls,'' SCI's area manager wrote in a Nov. 24 letter to
Lancaster Memorials, the company that would be opening the crypt.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 a.m. Dec. 1, Hood's casket was removed from the crypt and
several local funeral experts helped clean up the seeping liquid.
But when they attempted to lift the casket back into the crypt, the
bottom split.
</P>
<P>
   The disentombment cost Hood's family $5,070 for a replacement
casket and transfer of the body and $1,900 to have the monument
company open the crypt and reseal it. The original funeral handled
by SCI had cost $8,229, including the mahogany casket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shouldn't happen to anybody,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   State lawmakers say they want to protect consumers from
incompetent or dishonest funeral companies. But one of the two
funeral bills that have been filed was written by a lobbyist paid
by SCI and would curtail the commission's regulatory powers. The
other bill would kill the agency and require the Texas Department
of Health to regulate funeral homes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers say they expect the final legislation will be
somewhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   At a March hearing, the House Appropriations Committee
criticized the agency's lackluster performance. Statistics
collected by lawmakers show the 10-employee agency has fallen
behind in completing investigations, imposing penalties and taking
disciplinary action _ even though the number of complaints has not
increased substantially. The agency is taking half a year to
resolve a complaint, twice as long asagency standards. Complaints
are backlogged, and last year the agency imposed 14 fines for
violations of Texas funeral law, compared to 92 fines in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral commission officials attribute the problems to high
staff turnover, inexperienced staff and vague and contradictory
funeral service rules.
</P>
<P>
   After the committee brought the problems to light, the full
House passed a budget that included no money for the funeral
commission. But lawmakers said they did it to send a message and
that they would rather revamp the commission. To do that, they plan
to take the SCI-drafted bill and make it more responsive to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   As written, the SCI bill would limit funeral commission fines to
$10,000 per complaint. It would limit the agency's executive
director from issuing subpoenas for funeral company documents
without a commission order, which May did last year in
investigating 23 SCI homes. It also would prohibit an agency
employee from simultaneously serving as an officer of a state
political party, a provision prompted by May's role as treasurer of
the Texas Democratic Party last year. And, the bill would prohibit
the public from seeing information that state inspectors compile
when they investigate a complaint against a funeral home, even
after the case is closed. Similar inspection reports for nursing
homes, state psychiatric hospitals and other facilities are open
while an investigation occurs. Inspection reports of day care
centers under investigation are made public after the investigation
is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Marchant (R-Coppell), who received a $5,000 campaign
donation from SCI's PAC last October, introduced the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing sinister about it,'' he said. ``It was mainly
a shot across the bow to say something's really wrong here, and we
really need to do something. There is a lot of chaos over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, lawmakers were negotiating how to make the bill more
consumer-friendly. One compromise would change the makeup of the
commission so there are fewer members from the industry. Now, the
commission has five public members and four funeral industry
members. The proposal is to have a six-member board, with four
public members and two industry representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also are discussing a proposal to prevent the
commission from disclosing any proposed fines against a funeral
home until they become final. Such a provision would have kept
secret the proposed $450,000 fine against SCI.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Richards, who took over day-to-day operations of the
funeral commission after May was fired Feb. 8, is generating
controversy of his own. The commission awarded Richards a $20,000
pay raise, from $40,000 to $60,000, and Pitts and other lawmakers
quickly criticized the increase. May was paid $43,000. Richards,
the agency's general counsel,points out that his new salary is
within the state pay scale allowed for agency attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Richards said he is working on the review of the funeral
agency's 1998 investigation of SCI's embalming practices and hopes
to have it completed in time for the commission's next meeting, on
May 27. The board also plans to take up the complaint about Hood's
embalming at the same meeting.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that has not changed under Richards' leadership is a
problem with security fears. When May was executive director, she
hired a private security guard because of an attempted break-in and
a death threat from a disgruntled former SCI apprentice embalmer.
May also was concerned about a private investigator hired for a
short time by SCI to dig into her personal background. Now, when
Richards is out of town, he usually tapes his door shut with orange
tape so he can tell if anyone enters his office, where sensitive
investigative files and working papers are kept.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been entries into the office that have been
unauthorized,'' he said of the unusual security measure.
</P>
<P>
   None of the controversies engulfing the funeral agency gives any
comfort to Tres Hood's family. They fear their complaint against
Hampton Vaughan could fall through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned they're going to minimize and negate our
complaints in some way because of the conflicts of interest,'' said
John Horany, a Dallas lawyer who represents Hood's family. ``They
may put it on slo-mo and wait until there is no more funeral
commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitts, the Waxahachie lawmaker, vows the Legislature will do
something to protect consumers like the Hood family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be assured that the state will be looking over the
shoulder of this industry when we're finished,'' he said. ``It's
just been a circus, and we need to restore the public confidence in
this agency. We're going to abolish it and start one over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
