<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTERY-FIGHT18-COX     04-17 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-FIGHT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waffle House waitress sued for big helping of lottery pie
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND BAY, Ala. _ Tonda Dickerson's days of serving $1.98
breakfasts at the Waffle House are over. She quit her waitress job
March 7 after seemingly becoming a millionaire thanks to a Florida
Lotto ticket she received from one of her regulars.
</P>
<P>
   She wants a Camaro to replace her stolen one so she can quit
driving her mother's Chrysler LeBaron. She's looking at plans for a
two-story brick house that will replace her trailer and wants to
provide college tuition for her child and nieces and nephews.
</P>
<P>
   But what Dickerson wants most, she says, is the good name of her
family restored. That may not come, if at all, until after a
verdict in a civil trial that starts Monday in Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Three Waffle House waitresses and a shift manager claim
Dickerson was part of a pool that agreed to share winnings from
lottery tickets they received from Edward Seward Jr., a regular
customer who had been giving waitresses Florida Lotto tickets for
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When Dickerson refused to sign a settlement giving away 70
percent of a jackpot stake worth $10 million, she was hit with a
civil lawsuit. The complaint contends Dickerson and her family
conspired to shut out the other waitresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never an agreement,'' Dickerson, 28, said at the
kitchen table of her dad's house, eating a Mrs. Smith's French silk
chocolate pie.
</P>
<P>
   But attorney Stephen E. Clements, who represents the other
waitresses, said the verbal agreement to share jackpots was
discussed whenever Seward came to the Waffle House.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the point,'' Clements said. ``It was discussed all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Favors Alabama game
</P>
<P>
   With Alabama residents scheduled to vote on their own lottery
this fall, Dickerson says she's a bad barometer of how others might
vote. She rarely watches the news or picks up a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything doing with politics, from the president on down, it's
so confusing, so unimportant to me,'' said Dickerson, who for a
while pursued a physical therapy degree at the University of South
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, she favors an Alabama lottery. ``It would
give someone else a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson said she's heard rumors she's divorcing her husband of
seven months, James, because they're squabbling about the money.
And they're sure they're being watched by private detectives trying
to turn up anything that can be used against them in court.
</P>
<P>
   She chuckles. He's defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're smearing her name from here to Atlanta,'' James
Dickerson said. ``Just like taking a garbage truck and just dumping
it out in someone's yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson and other Waffle House waitresses began crossing paths
with Seward around January. Seward, 41, a former seafood cook and
restaurant manager, suffered a stroke three years ago. His sister
lives near the Waffle House in Grand Bay so he frequently stops to
eat and socialize.
</P>
<P>
   After getting to know the morning shift, Seward started handing
out Florida Lotto tickets. Friends said he usually bought them at a
Groovin' Noovin' convenience store just across the Florida line
near Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like he was trying to build up these friendships, and
then in return for the friendships he would kind of like reward you
with these tickets,'' Dickerson said.
</P>
<P>
   On March 7, the day after the drawing for a $20 million Florida
Lotto jackpot, Seward handed Dickerson a ticket in a sealed
Groovin' Noovin' envelope. Written across the top were the winning
numbers: 3-4-7-36-39-40. One ticket was sold in Stuart, Fla. Seward
bought the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he really did want them to divide it,'' said Emma
Seward, Edward Seward's aunt. He also wanted a new truck from the
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Clements said Seward will testify to both verbal agreements at
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next time,'' Emma Seward told her nephew, ``give it to your
aunt. I'd share it with you.''
</P>
<P>
   A family trip to Florida
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson hasn't talked to Seward since she struck it rich. She
initially led the other waitresses to believe she might have bought
the winning ticket from a local resident who often sells Florida
lottery tickets. She started the talk, she said, to throw people
off track so she could thank Seward for the winning ticket.
Dickerson said she wants to reward Seward but hasn't figured out
what to give him yet.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson says she regrets the ruse, which is mentioned
prominently in the suit against her.
</P>
<P>
   Four days after Seward gave the ticket away, Dickerson and her
husband, father and mother drove to Tallahassee to claim the prize:
$10 million divided by 30 annual payments, about $216,000 a year
after taxes. They formed a corporation, 9 Mill Inc., named for
their $9 million share. After last-minute sales were counted, their
stake grew by $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want everybody just to take a lump sum and spend
their money and 20 years from now everybody be broke,'' said
Dickerson, who slept with the ticket in a Ziploc bag before she
filed her claim.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a problem. A Mobile attorney had called Florida
Lotto officials, saying his clients were in a pool with Dickerson
and that she fled so she wouldn't have to share.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we conspired that,'' said Dickerson's father, Bobby Reece,
``she could have took off Sunday night and been there waiting
Monday morning and cashed that thing in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be irresponsible for us to pay the winner without
having this resolved,'' said Ed George, director of communications
for the Florida lottery. ``Any information we have puts the burden
on us to get some facts to see if it's a real person with a real
claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rags-to-riches story either way. I'm surprised one of
the TV networks hasn't approached us yet. Or at the very least
`Oprah.'''
</P>
<P>
   For now, everyone will have to settle for Court TV, which will
tape the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
