<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2688 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAS-OUT-2ndTAKE-LADN &LR;      04-17 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-OUT-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
  
Los Angeles: 99.8 cents 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   California, where heavy demand and extra environmental
regulations make gas especially expensive, has experienced the
sharpest rise. Premium prices are flirting with the $2 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Comforted slightly by Attorney General Bill Lockyer's pledge
last week to investigate whether oil companies are gouging
motorists at the pump, Mayes said it is ``time to make a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Schlichting, a spokesman for the California Energy
Commission, said he supported the goals of The Great American Gas
Out, but warned the action could actually have a detrimental
effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could raise prices,'' Schlichting said. ``The whole concept
is don't buy gas on April 30, but buy as much as you want on the
29th and the day after the boycott. There could be an artificial
shortage on the day of the boycott that could raise prices. The
Great American Gas Out only shifts the buying time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could hold it for a week, maybe then it would have some
power. A much better idea would be to for everyone to car pool. A
car pool would create a significant fall in the amount of gas
purchased. Or do like I did this morning and ride your bike to
work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Schlichting, prices likely will drop soon. The
expected fall in prices would be mostly due to recent reports that
supplies are much larger than expected despite a vows by overseas
oil producers to cut back on shipments, and two notable refinery
fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get angry for that day and protest, but maybe you can
take that energy and get even for a long time,'' said Bill
VanAmburg, a spokesman for Calstart of Pasadena, a transportation
technologies consortium that develops and promotes alternative
fuels.
</P>
<P>
   Hybrid vehicles that rely on electricity and gas already are
affordable and will only get cheaper in the next year, VanAmburg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Honda's electric car, the VV, is available in a few major
markets and will debut across the country this fall. The car, which
looks similar to the company's Civic coupe, relies on both an
electric motor and a gas engine and gets about 70 miles per gallon.
Unlike its predecessors, the VV retails for under $20,000,
VanAmburg said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn has been leasing similar electric-powered vehicles to
drivers since 1997, and General Motors, Toyota, Ford and Chrysler
all plan to have either electric or natural gas vehicles ready for
sale within the next year, VanAmburg said.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred recharging stations for electric vehicles and
about 80 natural gas stations already exist throughout Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas sells for about 75 cents per gallon; electric cars
can be recharged for about 40 percent of the cost of an equivalent
gallon of gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of a Great American Gas Out maybe it should be the
Great American Gas Alternative,'' VanAmburg said. ``There are lots
of technologies out there that are starting to come into their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
