u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-1STLD-     04-17 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVS CONTINUE `CLEANSING' CAMPAIGN DESPITE NATO ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for major rewrite with new reporting. In 2nd graf, note
change to ``Macedonia'' from original ``Montenegro.'')  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians poured
out of Kosovo on Saturday, driven from their homeland despite
NATO's continuing air war of attrition with Yugoslavia and what the
alliance called successful attacks on Yugoslav tanks.
</P>
<P>
   NATO command officers said that Yugoslav army and Serb police
units were carrying out sweep operations all over southern Kosovo
near the border with Albania and Macedonia, burning and wrecking
villages and driving the inhabitants onto the roads to flee for
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   At least 13,000 ethnic Albanians streamed into Albania
overnight, relief officials said, while another 7,000 arrived in
Macedonia, where the defense minister was quoted as saying he would
not permit new camps to be built for them and urged foreign
countries to airlift them from the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   There was a hint of movement on the diplomatic front, too.
Former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin of Russia, appointed last
Wednesday as his country's special envoy in talks on the Yugoslav
crisis, will present President Boris Yeltsin with proposals on
Monday to resolve the conflict, Russian news agencies said.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin was quoted as saying that resolving the conflict
would be a difficult process but that he was ready next week to
start foreign trips to try to achieve a diplomatic breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin has held meetings with Western diplomats and
Russian experts, and has said that Russia should keep a cool head
with NATO despite its anger over the bombings of fellow Slav
Orthodox Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather moved in over the southern Balkans overnight, once
again making it difficult for allied planes to do much about the
Yugoslav operations on the ground, allied officials said. But on
Friday afternoon they destroyed seven tanks from the air.
</P>
<P>
   The ground forces successfully hit by the allies Friday appeared
to be miles away from the most intense Yugoslav operations along
the border. The allied attacks were concentrated instead near
Pristina, the provincial capital, and in the northern part of
Kosovo. The command did not say how many missions allied planes had
flown.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the allied command, Brig. Gen. Giuseppe Marani,
said that allied planes had also bombed strategic targets,
including an ammunition plant, and British military officials in
London said that a Yugoslav army headquarters near Pristina, which
was helping to direct the operations on the ground, had been
bombed.
</P>
<P>
   But as Marani said, ``for ethnic cleansing, you don't need a
very strong structure in terms of command and control.'' In other
words, the targets NATO was striking from high in the air might
slow down but could not stop the destruction and killing by
Yugoslav forces on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great deal of killing has taken place,'' the alliance's
spokesman, Jamie Shea, said. NATO on Saturday made public an aerial
photograph of what it said could be a mass burial site near the
village of Izbica with up to 150 graves.
</P>
<P>
   Shea and Marani offered no new information Saturday about
Yugoslav assertions that allied warplanes had killed scores of
fleeing Albanian civilians on the road between Djakovica and
Prizren on Wednesday afternoon. Foreign correspondents allowed to
go to the scene found debris from NATO ordnance near the wreckage
of civilian tractors and wagons, but all Marani would say was,
``Debris will be one element of our investigation, but debris can
be moved around.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that when NATO had figured out what happened it would
make its findings known, but Marani said he could not say whether
allied planes had attacked the road on Wednesday. That day, the
command said it had carried out a strike on a military convoy in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon on Saturday, a spokesman for the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, Capt. Steve Pietropaoli, said the pilot of an American F-16
whose taped interview was released last week after the incident had
attacked a military, not a civilian, vehicle. Pentagon officials
expressed concern that the aviator was being unfairly blamed for
the civilian deaths.
</P>
<P>
   In view of the new flow of refugees, Shea said that Yugoslav
authorities under President Slobodan Milosevic appeared to be
trying to empty the province of as many of its 1.8 million ethnic
Albanians as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has rejected NATO's demands to stop the expulsions _
initially an enormous exodus, then more intermittent as the
Yugoslavs alternately opened and closed their borders _ accept a
cease-fire, and let international peacekeepers escort the refugees
back home. Shea said that Yugoslavia rejected similar demands by
the U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received reports that up to 100,000 people may be
trying to reach the border at Morina,'' Shea said Saturday. Morina
is just inside Albania, near the already overcrowded refugee camps
at Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Henderson, the British armed forces minister, said in
London that officials had received reports of 50,000 more refugees
on their way to Macedonia and 18,000 to Montenegro, on top of
560,000 driven out over the last month.
</P>
<P>
   In comments published in Macedonian newspapers Saturday, the
Macedonian defense minister, Nikola Kljusev, said his government
had rejected a request from the U.N. refugee agency and NATO to
build new camps in his country. ``It's possible to expand existing
camps,'' he was quoted as saying. ``But new refugees must
definitely go to third countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, with a large ethnic Albanian minority, is worried
that a huge influx of ethnic Albanians will destabilize its own
delicate politics.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.N. high commissioner for refugees in
Geneva said Saturday that if the flow continued, an airlift to fly
refugees elsewhere might have to be organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the numbers rising again, it will be extremely urgent to
get more sites or expand the ones we have, and perhaps also then to
fly more people out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While 7,000 refugees arrived in Macedonia, about 1,000 more were
turned back at the border by Serb security forces, who continued
their erratic pattern of behavior about when and whether to let
Kosovo's Albanians flee, refugees who made it across the frontier
said. Relief officials expressed hope that those 1,000 people would
make it across later.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, said in a telephone
interview Saturday from Skopje, the capital of Macedonia, that the
bombing could still be going on in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic is losing,'' he said. ``If he does not
change his policies, we're going to destroy those things President
Slobodan Milosevic values.'' As he spoke, allied planes continued
systematically trying to destroy military and police headquarters,
bridges, anti-aircraft guns and missiles and Yugoslav air force
planes and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   But the allies are finding it hard to pick off the tanks and
armored vehicles the Yugoslavs are using to systematically destroy
ethnic Albanian villages and settlements and drive out their
inhabitants. The Yugoslav campaign began late last year and
increased after the allies began bombing on March 24 because
President Milosevic rejected a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand, as has been described before, his
whole military structure has a great deal of redundancy,'' said a
British admiral, Sir Ean Garnett, at a British Defense Ministry
briefing in London.
</P>
<P>
   Another NATO military officer said that the Yugoslav armed
forces had been structured over the last 50 years to be able to
wage a long war of resistance against foreign invasion, with vast
underground bunkers storing fuel, ammunition and weapons the allies
may not yet have even found, let alone destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson estimated that 1.1 million of the approximately 2
million people who were living in Kosovo at the last census in 1991
had fled since fighting flared up a year ago between the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army, which wants independence for the province,
and Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Clark went to the Balkans Saturday to talk with leaders in
Macedonia and Albania about the refugee situation and about the
more than 20,000 NATO troops that are, or soon will be, in both
those countries to help deal with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia has taken in 160,000 ethnic Albanian refugees in the
last month, and 12,000 NATO troops originally intended for a
peacekeeping mission to Kosovo have built refugee camps and tent
cities for the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Another 7,200 allied soldiers are on their way to Albania to do
the same there, and another 4,000 American troops are on their way
to the northern part of the country to fly Apache anti-tank
helicopters into Kosovo to hunt down Yugoslav units.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
