<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Milestone start a nice surprise
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Ernie Irvan makes his 300th career start in
a Winston Cup race in today's Goody's Body Pain 500 at Martinsville
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   There are 16 Winston Cup regulars who have more career starts
but few have endured the pit falls Irvan has faced.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan, 40, stared at death nearly five years ago, and has
battled a reputation of being reckless .
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been as low as you can get,'' Irvan said. ``I've been as
high as you can get. I've been a lot in the middle. ...''
</P>
<P>
   In his second season of driving the No. 36 Pontiac of MB2
Motorsports, a team owned by University of Georgia graduates Read
Morton, Nelson Bowers and Tom Beard, Irvan is 23rd in points after
seven races, trailing leader Jeff Burton by 389.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a surprise to many drivers that Irvan is still alive
to make the milestone start.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was wild on the track and he was taking a lot of chances
and putting a lot of people in jeopardy,'' veteran Darrell Waltrip
said. ``He was going to get somebody hurt. That's what we were all
worried about. You hate to see a talented driver go out and do
things that jeopardize him and everybody else. It doesn't have to
be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan's reckless driving finally caught up to him in 1991, his
fifth season on the circuit. He caused an accident at Darlington,
in which Neil Bonnett suffered head injuries. A month later at
Talladega, Kyle Petty broke his leg in a wreck that was blamed on
Irvan.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Waltrip and Richard Petty sat Irvan down at
Talladega, telling him he had to temper his aggression and
apologize to the other drivers. Waltrip said Irvan immediately
reacted by ``sticking his chin out'' and saying, `That's the way
Dale Earnhardt does it.' I told him we don't need another Dale
Earnhardt,'' Waltrip said.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, though, Irvan asked if he could apologize at
the drivers' meeting before the Winston 500 in May 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one turning point in your career that makes a
difference, I think that really made a difference,'' Irvan said.
``Not because of what I said, but because of my attitude and what I
changed about myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darrell Waltrip said, `You're as good a race car driver that
has ever stepped into Winston Cup racing, but if you don't
straighten up, you're going to get kicked out, not from Winston
Cup, but you're going to get kicked out because nobody is going to
like you and nobody is going to associate with you.' There's no
doubt those guys knew what they were talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   If Irvan didn't earn the respect of his competitors then, he
undoubtedly did after he was nearly killed in an accident at
Michigan Speedway in August 1994. Irvan was given only a 10 percent
chance of surviving, but, miraculously, he returned to racing after
14 grueling months of rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   And nearly four years later, he's still climbing back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm kind of like coming back again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
