A2695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES18-CO     04-17 0337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New pit road to play major role in race
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Winston Cup veteran Darrell Waltrip says you
better be careful what you ask for.
</P>
<P>
   For years, NASCAR drivers implored Martinsville Speedway to
reconfigure its pit road. The track finally obliged this year,
switching from pit roads on the front and back straightaways to
one, long continuous one. Drivers complained that cars pitting on
the backstretch had barely any shot at winning a race.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip and others believe the new pit road could play a major
role in today's Goody's Body Pain 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be careful what you pray for sometimes,'' said
Waltrip, second only to Richard Petty with 11 career victories at
Martinsville. ``We've all been praying for one pit road here and
we've got it. Now we've got to help them make it as good as it can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers have complained that the .526-mile oval is too
short to accommodate a 35-mph speed limit on pit road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pit road is going to kill you, period, on a green-flag
stop,'' said Kyle Petty, who will start 10th. ``Look at the race
track. It's a half-mile track. We can get around here in 20
seconds. It takes you 44 seconds to go down pit road at 35 mph.
That's two laps you've (lost) already during a green-flag stop.''
</P>
<P>
   B. Jones goes home
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup rookie Buckshot Jones of Tucker, Ga., was one of
three drivers who failed to qualify for today's race. It's Jones'
third DNQ of the season, and snapped his string of five starts in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Also failing to qualify were veteran Morgan Sheppard in owner
Junie Donlavey's No. 90 Ford and Dave Marcis in the No. 71 Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Around the tracks
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott and his brother, engine builder Ernie Elliott,
declined comment on Saturday's report that McDonald's was
considering pulling its sponsorship from the No. 94 Ford team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
