<HEADER>
A2708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT     04-17 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTO FULL UPDATE  
 (SK) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/17/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- April 17, 1999 -- ABUSE-IMMIGRANTS-WIVES-2,
4-17 -- The abusive husband of this 26-year-old Dominican woman
threatened her because he was a legal resident and she was not.
``He would say that because he is legal, he has more rights in this
country than I do,'' she says. Advocates for issues involving
immigrants say spousal abuse has long been one of the most critical
problems endured by women who do not have legal residency in the
United States but are married to someone who does. (Joyce
Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ANN ARBOR, Mich. -- April 17, 1999 --
ABUSE-IMMIGRANTS-WIVES-1, 4-17 -- Leslye Orloff, the national
policy director for Ayuda, a group supporting battered immigrants.
Ms. Orloff says that many of the women fear that if they leave the
United States, they will be exposed to suits claiming custody of
their children, many of whom were born in the U.S. ``They know that
they are going to be forced to make an impossible choice to either
leave the country to get their green card, and risk extreme danger
for themselves and their children,'' she says. (Peter Yates/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 17, 1999 -- NY-POLICE-COMMISSIONER,
4-17 -- For three years now, New York City Police Commissioner
Howard Safir has dutifully taken his place behind Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani at news conferences, his hands folded, his face set in
inscrutability. It is an enduring image of a friendship forged by
time shared in federal service, one in which roles are understood
and discretion is a given. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 17, 1999 -- HKN-GRETZKY-RANGERS-2,
4-17 -- Wayne Gretzky posing for one of his final pictures in a
hockey uniform on Saturday, one day before he ends his 20-season
career in the NHL. Gretzky's Rangers play against the Pittsburgh
Penguins at Madison Square Garden on Sunday afternoon. (Nicole
Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- April 17, 1999 -- HKN-GRETZKY-RANGERS-1, 4-17
-- As Wayne Gretzky ends his 20-season career in the NHL, when his
Rangers play against the Pittsburgh Penguins at Madison Square
Garden on Sunday afternoon, Gretzky chooses to retire with the same
grace and creativity that led him to spread his sports' popularity
past the borders of his native Canada. Having shattered nearly
every offensive record, the great one always managed to keep his
ego in perspective, and control it as he did his stick. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) DENVER -- April 17, 1999 -- FLYING-UPSIDE-DOWN, 4-17 -- A
flight operations intern, Eric Gancarz, left, of United Airlines,
watches as Capt. John C. Penney, in a Boeing 747-400 simulator,
explains how a pilot would recover control of an airliner that was
rolling or diving. During three days of annual retraining, Capt.
John C. Penney drills crews on what to do if something throws the
plane out of kilter. ``It's not show-boating or hot-dogging,'' says
Penney, a former fighter pilot. ``It's an eye-opening exercise.''
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BEIJING -- April 17, 1999 -- CHINA-STREET-MARKETS, 4-17
-- At the Dragon Temple market, Yang Zhuju, 36, right, sits next to
the rubble of her stall. Like the man next to her, she repairs
shoes. Ms. Yang moved to Beijing a decade ago from a village in
southern China. By demolishing street markets, the local government
hopes it can drive rural migrants back home. ``How can they get rid
of us? What we do benefits the everyday life of Beijing
residents,'' says Ms. Yang. (Erik Eckholm/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- April 17, 1999 -- UNEARTHED-BORDELLO, 4-17
-- The towering stone memorial for Mary Ann Hall, a determined
woman who built and managed one of this city's finest 19th-century
bordellos, stands just down the way from a phalanx of smaller
stones of departed lawmakers in the once-rural Congressional
Cemetery. Archaeologists have found no mention of Mary Ann Hall in
history books, but have uncovered bureaucratic records of her
bordello in the federal census. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) COLTON, Calif. -- April 17, 1999 -- HOSPITAL-ROOMS, 4-17
-- Thelma Waln, 64, recovering from hip surgery at the new
Arrowhead Regional Medical Center, likes her private room complete
with bathroom and television. Private rooms in hospitals were once
for only those affluent patients willing to pay extra. Now a
growing number of hospitals are eliminating shared rooms and
offering all patients -- Medicare and Medicaid, rich and indigent
-- their own rooms, often at no extra charge. ``This is going to
lead to malingering,'' says Mrs. Waln. (Edward Carreon/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- April 17, 1999 -- AIDS-TEEN-SURVIVORS-1, 4-17
-- Renell Grant, 49, is one of thousands of parents across the
country facing an unexpected challenge -- the three children she
adopted as HIV-infected babies in the 1980s are now thriving into
their teens. About 40 percent of infected children are cared for by
someone other than their biological parents. ``We were told that
these kids might die at any time and to be strong, give them a life
and make them comfortable,'' says Ms. Grant. (Nicole Bengiveno/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PASADENA, Calif. -- April 17, 1999 -- NASA-WOMEN, 4-17 --
Kari A. Lewis, 25, left, chief mission engineer, Sarah A. Gavit,
37, project manager, and Suzanne E. Smrekar, 37, lead scientist, a
women's team of experts at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory, head a
Mars mission. The team designed and built the two intricate
spacecraft. Each is about the size of a grapefruit to study the
rocky composition of the soil and look for signs of water, which is
considered a key to life but appears scarce on the desert-like
surface of Mars. (Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SKULL VALLEY GOSHUTE RESERVATION, Utah -- April 17, 1999
-- NUCLEAR-WASTE-FIGHT-2, 4-17 -- A sign near the reservation of
the tiny Skull Valley Band of the Goshute Tribe in Utah prohibiting
high level nuclear waste in the area. The Skull Valley Band has
signed a 50-year lease with eight electric companies to store bury
high-level nuclear waste on its reservation. The state fears that
once the waste gets here, it will never go away. (George Frey/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SKULL VALLEY GOSHUTE RESERVATION, Utah -- April 17, 1999
-- NUCLEAR-WASTE-FIGHT-1, 4-17 -- The chairman of the tiny Skull
Valley Band of the Goshute Tribe in Utah, Leon D. Bear, says making
the reservation a nuclear waste deposit could bring back tribe
members. The Skull Valley Band has signed a 50-year lease with
eight electric companies to store bury high-level nuclear waste on
its reservation. ``It's because of the economics, that's why people
left,'' says Bear. (George Frey/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
