<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-COLLEGES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC AMONG WOMEN'S ROWING POWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A trivia question: Which school is the reigning
national champion in women's four-rowing?
</P>
<P>
   East Coast colleges come to mind: Princeton, Boston College,
Dartmouth. But the answer is USC.
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense to Trojans coach George Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an outdoor sport, and this is the best weather for
outdoor sports,'' he said. ``Why should someone in Boston be better
than us?''
</P>
<P>
   Rowing's not just for East Coast colleges anymore. Washington is
ranked first nationally according to U.S Rowing. USC is fifth, and
Gonzaga is a West Coast Conference power, having won each of the
first two WCC titles.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA has designated women's rowing as an emerging sport,
freeing up scholarship money (USC has 20 scholarships). The West
Coast Conference has its championships today in Folsom, Calif. At
the same time and place, USC is competing in the California State
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have had rowing as a club sport since the late
1970s. Its importance to intercollegiate athletic programs is
increasing because schools now need more female athletes to achieve
gender equity.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins equates rowing's rise to that of women's volleyball
about 15 years ago. Back then, the best teams were in California.
Now, ``Nebraska is as good as Stanford,'' he said. ``Florida State
is as good as USC or UCLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Ott, the WCC assistant commissioner, said rowing is a
metaphor for life: You can only go forward by looking back.
</P>
<P>
   You also can come to the school, hook up with the program and
row your way to a scholarship. That's what USC's Annelisa Gross,
Kasey Ryan and Rebecca Moneymaker did, and they became three-fifths
of the winning women's fours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large numbers of women want to be involved,'' Ott said. ``It's
growing out here.''
</P>
<P>
   No problem: USC lost the Mountain Pacific Sports Federation
women's water polo title to Cal last week. But coach Jovan Vavic
said it means nothing in the Trojans' plan to win the national
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of the MPSF is to get an MPSF winner,'' Vavic said.
``It also counts for our national seeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans next compete in the West Regionals at USC next week.
No matter what, the Trojans likely will be seeded no lower than
fourth at the NCAA tournament in Davis next month.
</P>
<P>
   Commitment: USC's volleyball team signed 6-foot-8 outside hitter
Marcus Gilmour, an All-Southern Section Division III second-team
pick who helped Santa Ynez High reach the section final. He also
helped his Junior Olympic team finish ninth.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA notes: The gymnastics team qualified for next week's NCAA
championships by winning last week's regional. The Bruins earned
the second seed in the 12-team nationals that start Thursday in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Six teams compete in two separate preliminary sessions, with the
top three from each session advancing to the final. UCLA has a
favorable draw, going against Alabama, Stanford, West Virginia,
Arizona State and Louisiana State. The odds are good, coach Valerie
Kondos said, that the team will make the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time since '89, we have the talent,'' Kondos
said. ``We don't need another team to fall. If we hit, we'll win.
In '97, if Georgia would've hit, we wouldn't have won.''
</P>
<P>
   Only four schools have ever won the national gymnastics title:
Utah, Alabama, UCLA (1997) and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Heidi Moneymaker is defending her NCAA uneven bars title.
Moneymaker is one of only four Bruins to have won an individual
title, but none won on the bars. She said tendinitis in her right
shoulder will make it difficult. She's more confident in the vault.
</P>
<P>
   _Swimmer Keiko Price was named to the Pacific-10 All-Academic
first team. Gymnast Susie Erickson made the second team.
</P>
<P>
   _The school is celebrating its 25th anniversary of women's
athletics with a gala dinner May 1 at the Beverly Hilton. Many of
the top UCLA athletes _ Ann Meyers Drysdale, Dot Richardson, Evelyn
Ashford, Lisa Fernandez, Jackie Joyner Kersee and Gail Devers _ are
expected to attend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
