<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hudek glad to join Braves, leave Reds
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ John Hudek, the newest member of the bullpen, acquired
from Cincinnati in the Mark Wohlers trade, is both eager to join
the perennial playoff-contending Braves as well as to leave the
Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh thrilled, thrilled to death,'' Hudek said was his reaction
to Friday's news. ``There have been rumors years before that I was
asked to come here and now that's it's come true (my wife and I)
are just thrilled to death. That's why I got on the plane (Friday)
when they told me to get here for last night's game.''
</P>
<P>
   As for leaving the Reds, he said: ``I was glad to get out of the
Cincinnati scene, not as much for the players as I was upper
management.''
</P>
<P>
   That was before Hudek heard Jim Bowden's comments in Saturday
morning papers, which were: ``I call this an `AON' deal _ all or
nothing,'' Bowden said. ``Mark Wohlers has a tremendous upside.
He's possibly one of the most dominant closers of the '90s. And if
we can't get him over the Steve Blass disease, we haven't lost
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudek's response to that?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Bowden for you,'' Hudek said. ``I'll leave it at
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudek is a hard-throwing reliever who has been up and down in
stints with the Astros, Mets and Reds in the last four seasons.
Hudek, who came back from 1996 rib extraction surgery _ the same
that Braves reliever Mike Cather had last summer _ characterized
his career as roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   Hudek is on the upswing now, coming off a career year with the
Mets and then the Reds, setting personal marks in appearances (58),
innings pitched (64), wins (5) and strikeouts (68) but also walks,
something that has hampered him throughout his career.
</P>
<P>
   His role with the Braves is yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Injury Update
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko was back swinging the bat against soft toss and took
some light batting practice on Saturday. For the first time since
he pulled his hamstring Wednesday night in Philadelphia, Klesko was
able to stretch his leg. ... Reliever Mike Remlinger is set to come
off the disabled list today. He's been on the 15-day DL with a
pulled lat muscle in his back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
