</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS BEAT YANKS, 3-1  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Yankees of 1999 will help define the greatness of
the 1998 Yankees before this summer is over. These Yankees are
exceptional, with deep starting pitching and an even more explosive
Derek Jeter and a hungry Roger Clemens. They will win many games,
and they are the favorite to win the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But the '99 Yankees have already showed themselves capable of
slumps, the physical and mental slides and the periodic loss of
concentration that even the best teams inevitably experience over
the course of a 162-game season _ every team, of course, except the
'98 Yankees, who competed with intense concentration in almost
every game.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 Yankees played poorly again Saturday in their third
consecutive defeat, a 3-1 loss to Detroit that was twice delayed by
rain. A poor decision by the reliever Jeff Nelson led to a throwing
error and cost the Yankees the lead in the bottom of the seventh
inning. And for the third straight game, the Yankees made two
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte, making his first start after beginning the season
on the disabled list, pitched six shutout innings, throwing
impressively, but when it was over, Pettitte spoke quietly in a
sullen Yankee clubhouse. Paul O'Neill, who made the final out with
the tying runners on base, slumped in front of his locker, stared
off into nowhere, arms crossed, his leg propped on another chair.
The Yankees are not accustomed to playing this way, squandering
scoring chances and giving away runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a better club than that,'' said Don Zimmer, the Yankees'
interim manager, who on Friday referred to the team's recent play
as shabby. Hopefully, Zimmer said, ``we'll get our act together
tomorrow and play like we're capable of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Zimmer's 51st year in baseball. He has seen great teams
slump, and bad teams experience winning streaks. ``You can say
things like that happen,'' Zimmer said.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the '98 Yankees were so exceptional: things like that
did not happen to them. They lost games, sometimes two or three at
a time, but as Manager Joe Torre noted, he had never seen a team
maintain such a high degree of concentration for so long. The '98
Yankees were relentless, holding a lead in 48 consecutive games, a
streak that lasted from June to August.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 Yankees (7-4) are a great team. They are not the '98
Yankees, they most likely will not win 114 games in the regular
season and will avoid the comparisons. ``It's our job to try to
stay away from those comparisons,'' pitcher David Cone said. ``To
me, that would be a big mistake, to entertain those comparisons.
It's a different year.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Cone acknowledged, the comparisons will be made all
year. The '98 Yankees ran the bases aggressively in the first half
of the season, setting a tone they maintained all season. They
swiped 23 bases in the first 11 games of '98, everybody from Jeter
to O'Neill to Darryl Strawberry looking to run; the '99 Yankees
have five stolen bases in the first 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch ran aggressively Saturday, and it cost them. The
Yankees assumed a 1-0 lead in the third inning, when Joe Girardi
rolled a double down the first-base line and scored on Knoblauch's
single.
</P>
<P>
   But then Knoblauch made the Yankees' first mistake of the day:
Jeter pulled a single to left, and Knoblauch churned around third,
challenging the strong throwing arm of Detroit left fielder Juan
Encarnacion _ and Knoblauch was cut down when Encarnacion made a
perfect throw. With nobody out and O'Neill, Bernie Williams and
Tino Martinez due to bat, it was a questionable decision that
loomed after the Yankees failed to score any more runs in the
rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cardinal rule in baseball that you don't get called out
at third base or home plate on the first out of an inning,'' said
Zimmer, who then recalled the times when he coached third when he
had violated that rule. ``Knoblauch thought he could make it,''
Zimmer added, with a shrug, ``but he didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who scored one run in Friday's loss to Detroit,
were 1 for 7 with runners in scoring position in the first six
innings. They had runners at first and third and two out in the
seventh when rain stopped the game for the second time. After a
delay of 1 hour 4 minutes, the game resumed with Jeter batting
against the hard-throwing Matt Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter coaxed a walk, loading the bases for O'Neill, and it
figured Detroit Manager Larry Parrish would call on a left-hander
to face O'Neill. But Parrish stuck with Anderson, based on a
scouting report that showed O'Neill batted .067 on high fastballs
last year _ and Anderson throws a very hard and high fastball.
O'Neill struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson relieved for the Yankees in the bottom of the seventh,
and with one out, Damion Easley hit a chopper down the third-base
line. Nelson charged the ball, telling himself over and over, throw
to first, throw to first. He picked it up, turned _ just as Easley
neared first _ and fired the ball away and into the vast foul
territory along the right-field line. Easley ended up at third on
the play, and later Nelson said the ball had slipped out of his
hand. ``But I should've eaten it,'' Nelson said, meaning he should
not have thrown the ball at all.
</P>
<P>
   Encarnacion singled home the tying run, and stole second and
third _ a problem that has plagued the Yankees this season _ and
scored the go-ahead run when the pinch-hitter Brad Ausmus singled
over a drawn-in infield.
</P>
<P>
   Even in beating Baltimore last Tuesday and Wednesday, the
Yankees did not play their usual brand of baseball. They are
slumping, and will break out of the slump. ``We'll be all right,''
Zimmer said the other day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
