u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT &LR;      04-17 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT EXPOS, 3-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the 35th anniversary of the first game played at
Shea Stadium, the Mets managed a 3-2 victory over the Montreal
Expos Saturday. The victory relied on a formula the Mets often won
with last season before Mike Piazza arrived _ good starting
pitching supported by maximum offensive efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had just six hits Saturday, but their lineup was
depleted with Piazza (sprained knee ligament) on the disabled list
and Rickey Henderson (tight hamstring) and Robin Ventura (sore
foot) out of the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   As for the starting pitcher, however, not many could have
foreseen Bobby Jones opening the season like this. He performed
Saturday much as he did two seasons ago, when he opened with a 12-3
record and was selected to play in the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   In his third start of the season, the 29-year-old right-hander
survived a shaky first three innings to retire 14 of the last 15
batters he faced. Jones, who struggled to a 9-9 record last season,
is now 3-0 with a 1.29 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt confident, as I did my first two starts,'' he
said. ``I was throwing every one of my pitches for strikes. And
when I can do that, those are the times I can be effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones threw 82 strikes in 121 pitches. And with much help from a
big, lollipop curve ball, he scattered seven hits in his seven
innings, allowing only two runs, in the second inning, while
walking none and striking out six.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Franco, enjoying a rare start at third base, tied the game
for Jones with a two-run double off Carl Pavano in the bottom of
the third. The Mets manufactured the winning run in the fifth when
Roger Cedeno doubled, Edgardo Alfonzo grounded to the right side,
John Olerud walked and Bobby Bonilla hit a run-scoring fielder's
choice. Olerud's hard slide was the key ingredient, breaking up a
potential inning-ending double play and allowing the winning run to
score.
</P>
<P>
   That offense was enough for Jones, after Armando Benitez pitched
a dominating eighth and John Franco came on to pitch a scoreless
ninth for his fourth save in as many opportunities this season.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ended a two-game losing skid for the Mets (8-4) and
enabled them to retake first place in the National League East from
the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   It still did not seem good enough, however, for some of the
announced 34,784 in attendance _ many of whom could not decide
whether to cheer or boo Bonilla and Franco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not dictating or concerned with what the crowd does,''
Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``They have their own minds and they
can do what they want to do. But when someone is doing the b-o-o-o
thing with their mouth, it's a whole lot louder than 10 people
clapping.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, who ran out the fielder's choice play with a partial
ligament tear in his right knee, said: ``It's New York, man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
