<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2721 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONCORD-HISTORY-BOS &LR;      04-17 1523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCORD-HISTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ALLURE OF CONCORD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ They started coming here in the 1790s.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders realized while George Washington was still president
that something extraordinary had occurred at Concord's North Bridge
on April 19, 1775, and they wanted to see the site for themselves.
They have never stopped coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter always knew when the tourists arrived because
their pocketbooks matched their shoes,'' recalls Barbara Powell,
director of the Concord Free Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   The look is back. It's showtime once again in Concord.
</P>
<P>
   The bunting is up at the Colonial Inn, the front door repainted
at the North Bridge Visitor Center. Saturday, the Redcoats and the
Minute Men engaged in faux warfare along Battle Road, and some of
them danced the night away at the annual Patriots Ball. Monday
morning, a tattoo of musket fire breaks the dawn at the North
Bridge, followed by the requisite pancake breakfast at the Knights
of Columbus building and the town parade.
</P>
<P>
   This is distilled Yankee tradition at its purest.
</P>
<P>
   No other town in the country of comparable size can match
Concord's river of history, which began at the Puritan headwaters
and coursed through turbulent eddies of revolution and dreamy pools
of transcendentalism from the early 1600s to the Civil War. Since
then, the community has made an uncommon effort to memorialize its
past. Few other places have been as aware of their history as has
this town of 15,328.
</P>
<P>
   But managing history is harder than it looks, particularly when
there is so much to handle. Concord is no Potemkin village. Unlike
Colonial Williamsburg, the historic recreation in Virginia,
families here log onto the Internet while living in houses that are
two centuries old. It gets tricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``People along Battle Road say that tourists peer in their
windows thinking their houses are museums,'' says Sally Schnitzer,
chairwoman of the Board of Selectmen, about the stretch of highway
between Concord and Lexington, where the bloodiest fighting of
April 19 took place. Adds David Hackett Fischer, author of ``Paul
Revere's Ride,'' ``Concord has always been very mixed feelings
about tourists. They are proud of their history but don't want to
be overrun.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is that historic turf is a sensitive subject in these
parts, honed to a fine edge by the inherent weirdness of smalltown
politics and the relentless pressure from developers to build on
the town's dwindling stock of open land as homes skyrocket into
seven figures.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the current contretemps between the Orchard
House, home of the Alcotts and a National Historic Landmark since
1963, and its neighbors. Last week, its board of directors closed
on a house across the street to alleviate structural problems and
severe shortage of space in the Alcott home.
</P>
<P>
   But the board did not inform any of the Orchard House neighbors
of the acquisition, which began more than a month ago. Bad idea.
Signs now dot the front yards of the homes in the area reading,
``This Is A Residential Neighborhood'' and ``No No Orchard House
Annex.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bronson Alcott would have never behaved to his neighbors this
way,'' says Lee Bagley, who lives with her family across from
Orchard House. ``We already tolerate a lot with tourists, but this
is just intrusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Stunned by the firestorm, Christopher Davies, the board chairman
of Orchard House, vows to find a compromise. ``We're very anxious
to work things out with our neighbors,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And relations between the Historic District Commission, which
rules on all new construction in historic areas, and the Board of
Selectmen are a tad frosty these days because the commission keeps
rejecting projects proposed by the selectmen, such as an
air-conditioning system in the Town House, Concord's old town hall.
Then too, there is a byzantine warrant on the Town Meeting agenda
this month that conceivably could lead to the abolition of the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, history.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, though, the degree of comity over the
years within the community over its history has been remarkable,
and Concord has managed its extraordinary patrimony with care. ``It
does an excellent job,'' says Fischer, who teaches history at
Brandeis. There are, to be sure, a few altercations at the moment,
but Schnitzer is unfazed. ``This is what real life is all about,''
she says. ``There has been a flurry this year, but it comes and
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   To understand Concord's approach to its past is to know its
congenital reticence. `` `Don't mess with it too much' is how
Concord has handled it,'' explains Powell. ``Everyone relaxes until
something comes up and then you have a polarizing controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   Concordians, after all, have always been an independent lot.
This explains why there is no Concord Historical Society. Instead,
there exists a dizzying array of groups devoted to the different
strains of its story spanning three centuries. The closest thing to
an umbrella structure is the Concord Historical Collaborative, a
loose confederation linking the directors of the various historic
organizations. It is not listed in the telephone book, and no one
is sure when it started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talked to everybody and then someone finally put a
name on it,'' says Nancy Nelson, superintendent of the Minute Man
National Historical Park.
</P>
<P>
   The collaborative effort was overdue for a town with such a
breathtaking patrimony, anchored by two superb institutions, the
private Concord Museum, and the public Concord Free Public Library.
``They have the documents and we have the artifacts,'' says Desiree
Caldwell, the museum director.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just for starters. Other private outfits include the
Thoreau Society, the Thoreau Institute (whose headquarters are over
the Lincoln line), Walden Woods (a project of the institute), the
Louisa May Alcott Memorial Association, the Ralph Waldo Emerson
Memorial Association, and the Old Manse, the Emerson ancestral
home.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the library, the town fields the Thoreau
birthplace and Sleepy Hollow Cemetery, where Thoreau, Emerson, the
Alcotts, and Hawthorne are buried.
</P>
<P>
   The US government boasts the historical park stretching into
Lexington, the Great Meadows National Wildlife Refuge, and The
Wayside, home at various points to Alcotts and Nathaniel Hawthorne.
The Commonwealth of Massachusetts claims Walden Pond State
Reservation, which includes the site of Thoreau's iconic cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Phew.
</P>
<P>
   The very richness of this historic stew invites controversy over
the best way to digest it. Exhibit A is the imbroglio over the
visitor's center, a spirited slugfest that has kept things
interesting for years. The selectmen twice have tried
unsuccessfully to gain Historic District Commission approval for a
plan to turn a garage in an open field near the center of town into
a visitors center to replace the current one across the street,
which resembles an off-season roadside blueberry stand.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, tourists are basically on their own now when they
hit town. ``You see the first person walking on Lexington Road and
ask where to begin,'' Powell says.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes would be minimal, supporters maintain.
Besides, something is needed. More than a million people visit
Concord each year and they lack a coherent way to plan their day.
More important, they need restrooms. There are none now at the
current site, and history without toilets is a tall order for a
family of four.
</P>
<P>
   This fight is deadly serious to some. ``There is an
extraordinary rift in the town over this,'' says Chris Rinaldo,
cochair of the Concord Historic Commission, who opposes the plan.
``The site is one of the last remaining pieces of open land near
the center of town.'' Adds John Althouse, Historic District
Commission secretary, ``Selectmen want to take a 1950s Cape garage
and dress it up with colonial accoutrements and say it is
appropriate for a meadow.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lull in combat now, and the two sides should reach a
compromise. But when? ``That is the great question,'' says
Selectman Arthur Fulman, who supports the proposal. ``I hope it
gets settled in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   The tourists are oblivious to such internal fissures in the
town's facade. Their inexorable tide has led to the creation of a
cadre of 73 licensed town guides, most of whom work with the
Chamber of Commerce. The mere idea of licensed guides would have
appalled Concordians a few decades ago. But gone are the days of
creative history. ``My daughter used to give tours at the Orchard
House,'' says Powell. ``She made a lot of it up as she went.'' No
more.
</P>
<P>
   The latest ripple was the appearance last month of a tourist
trolley plying the literary trail of homes of famous authors from
Boston through Cambridge to Concord. It will be a weekly fixture in
town for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Most residents take its arrival in stride. Outsiders, after all,
have been showing up for a couple of centuries. So what's another
trolley?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
