<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-FIGHTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO COMMANDER WARNS ON SPREAD OF WAR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ As fighting proceeded along the
Albanian-Yugoslav frontier, NATO Commander Wesley K. Clark Saturday
expressed his greatest concerns yet that the conflict may intensify
beyond Yugoslavia's borders. He warned Slobodan Milosevic, the
Yugoslav president, that NATO is ``going to do everything it can''
to contain Yugoslav aggression.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, leaders of the Kosovo Liberation Army
turned over a captured Serb soldier to NATO troops. A Pentagon
spokesman said he was ``not optimistic'' that the captured Serb
could be swapped for three US soldiers who were taken as prisoners
of war on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army's of the Serb soldier to NATO
reflected increasing collaboration between the guerrilla force and
the Western alliance, which had shied away from supporting the
organization because of its terrorist tactics and its goal of
independence for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group said they have shared reconnaissance photos
with NATO to help its bombing campaign against Serb troops, and
NATO leaders have admitted that they are in touch with at least one
rebel leader, although they have not said NATO is providing the
Kosovo force directly with arms.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army is openly recruiting in NATO
countries, which apparently have not restricted the flow of new
guerrillas to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, NATO's supreme allied commander, said the alliance is
committed to securing the border with the northern part of Albania,
which is peppered with Kosovo Liberation Army training camps, and
which, in recent days, has come under heavy fire from Serb forces
on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned about the situation in the north, where
Serb agression is increasingly evident, with artillery being fired
across the border and infantry forays'' into Albania, Clark said
after meeting with officials here Saturday. ``That has to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   There were also these developments Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   --New questions surrounded the admission last week that a NATO
plane had accidentally struck a civilian convoy and killed some
refugees. When NATO confirmed that one of its pilots had
accidentally hit civillians, the military alliance also released an
audio tape from an F-16 pilot in which a bombing run was described.
The tape was reported to have been made by the pilot who had
launched the bomb that killed the civilians. But Pentagon officials
said Saturday that the tape had come from a pilot who had correctly
executed a strike on a Serbian military convoy.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO officials said that the Serbs had stepped up their
campaign of ``ethnic cleansing.'' One report said that 3,200 ethnic
Albanians had been killed. More than 100,000 refugees are believed
to be heading toward the Kosovo border, seeking shelter in one of
the crowded frontier refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   --A NATO spokesman said that aerial photos showed what appeared
to be mass graves. One photo showed that as many as 150 people
appeared to have been buried at a grave site in Izbica, according
to Brigadier General Guisseppe Marani, a NATO spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In Tirana, the Albanian capital, NATO forces prepared for the
arrival of 24 Apache helicopters, as US Army soldiers amassed in a
camp inside the Tirana airport, where they are setting up
logistical support for the low-flying craft.
</P>
<P>
   Clark indicated that the operation in Albania will intensify in
the next few days, while pointing out the increased Army presence
in the military camps at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Several US senators also visited the military base Saturday,
meeting with US troops. Senator Ted Stevens, Republican of Alaska,
addressed concerns about the wait for the arrival of the Apaches,
which are supposed to begin flying to Tirana Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had to ``make sure that they have the total
support before they go into combat activity,'' Stevens said,
expressing his commitment to the operation. ``As long as we are
doing it, we've got to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joseph R. Biden Jr., Democrat of Delaware, urged
Congress to approve emergency funding for US troops. ``The bottom
line here is, the mission has to prevail,'' Biden said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bujar Bukoshi, a former leader of the Kosovo regional
government that signed the Rambouillet, France, peace accord in
February, said for the first time that he did not expect Kosovo to
remain part of Yugoslavia. He said the peace deal is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We signed for peace and we got a genocide,'' Bukoshi said
during a visit to a refugee camp in Tirana. ``The only alternative
now is to stop the Serbian fascism. Almost anything should be
allowed to stop the genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he now supported the Kosovo Liberation Army,
Bukoshi, in a departure from his previous statements, said, ``Of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, meanwhile, the citizenry tried to go on with life
as normally as possible, with joggers taking part in a three-mile
``fun run'' through the city streets.
</P>
<P>
   Anne E. Kornblut reported from Tirana, Albania, and Michael
Kranish from Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
