<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKIES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rockies rock Rocker
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Tom Glavine and the Braves had the Rockies right where
they wanted them, down 4-2 in the bottom of the ninth inning at
Coors Field. But John Rocker didn't do his part, blowing his first
save opportunity of the year by allowing three runs as the Braves
fell 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Echevarria, the 25th man on the Rockies 25-man roster,
came through with a bases-loaded single to tie the game at 4 and
bring up Darryl Hamilton, who won it on a flair to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confused really at the bottom line,'' Rocker said
afterward. ``That's the best stuff I've ever had. I haven't given
up three runs in an inning in probably a year and a half. ...
You're either the hero or the goat. ... I don't know. Stuff
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker got one out before walking Todd Helton. He then gave up a
single to Mike Lansing who was able to turn on a 100-mph fastball.
Rocker then walked Kirt Manwaring to load the bases. He had
Echivarria 2-2 and late on his fastball but hung him a slider which
Echivarria fired into left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk guys in the ninth inning, you're going to get beat,
simple as that,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``We played a
terrific ballgame. We played flawless until that inning. You don't
see many real good games like that here. Usually something happens.
It did, in the ninth inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The blown save spoiled the first win opportunity for Tom
Glavine, who was fighting back from his worst start since 1990 at
0-2. Glavine found his form in the most unlikeliest of places _
Coors Field. But Glavine feels a lot more comfortable here than
most. He's thrown two of the seven shutouts in the stadium's
five-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine scattered seven hits on Saturday, allowing only two
runs, striking out five and walking one. lowered his ERA from 7.11
to 5.49.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's frustrating,'' Glavine said of the no-decision.
``I guess there's nothing you can do about it. I'm more
disappointed that we lost the game as a team. No question it would
have been nice to get the first win under my belt and get going. I
felt good about what I did today. I hope it's something I can build
on.''
</P>
<P>
   With he and Rockies ace Darryl Kile swapping turns on the mound
Saturday afternoon, the game was much less about rocket shots and
tons of runs and more about about ground balls and manufacturing a
few runs.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss, the former Rockie, worked his way on base with a 3-2
double to right field to lead off the seventh inning, moved to
third on a Tom Glavine bunt and scored on an Otis Nixon flyball.
That put the Braves up 3-2 in the last inning they would have to
contend with Kile.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan jumped on Rockies reliever Jerry DiPoto his third
pitch into the game with a rocket shot to left field for his third
home run of the year putting the Braves up 4-2 in the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
