<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons feel lucky to grab Kerney
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves wasn't doing cartwheels at 5
p.m. Saturday, but if he weren't 54 years old with double-digit
surgeries to his credit, he might have tried.
</P>
<P>
   After Atlanta selected Virginia defensive end Patrick Kerney in
the first round of the NFL draft, Reeves and team officials were
quite pleased they were able to get a player projected by many to
go much earlier in the round.
</P>
<P>
   Kerney, a 6-foot-5, 270-pounder who blossomed during the past
two seasons, had 15 sacks as a senior, eight as a junior and 31
tackles for a loss in his past two seasons with the Cavaliers.
</P>
<P>
   About 75 minutes later, the Falcons traded their first-round
pick for the 2000 draft in exchange for Baltimore's second-round
pick.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, which did not have a second-round pick of its own then
used the 42nd pick overall to select Mississippi State tight end
Reggie Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-4, 253-pound Kelly caught just 12 passes for 140 yards and
a touchdown last fall in his only season as a full-time starter. He
did, however, have 54 knockdown blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Kerney addresses an immediate need. Starters Chuck Smith and
Lester Archambeau are the only ends on the roster who have played
in an NFL game, and both have contracts that expire after next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great motor; he really brings it on every play,''
Reeves said. ``And he's a great kid with a frame to get bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really impressed with Coach Reeves, and (defensive line
coach Bill) Kollar,'' said Kerney. ``It was nerve-wracking waiting
so long, but it's great to go to a team that is coming off a Super
Bowl. I hope to be able to compete to start right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who had the third-to-last selection in the third
and final round Saturday, also have six selections in the final
four rounds today. They also are expected to announce that they
have reached agreement with a veteran defensive lineman, likely
former Vikings defensive end Derrick Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
