<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-INVESTORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT TIPS GEARED TO BLACKS USEFUL FOR ALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- As a former personal finance editor for Black
Enterprise magazine, Juliette Fairley received many letters asking
for help on how to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing a need for basic investment education, she wrote a book
filled with money tips from the leading financial experts in the
African-American community.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, the advice in her ``Money Talks: Black Finance
Experts Talk to You About Money,'' is applicable to anyone --
regardless of race or gender -- who is new to the market. That is,
stop spending money on unnecessary luxuries and start investing
money in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing our children a disservice if we don't leave them
with an inheritance,'' Fairley said. ``We (also) want to have a
good retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Fairley has a unique view of Wall Street. In addition to her
work at Black Entertainment magazine, she's a personal finance
correspondent for a weekly business show on Black Entertainment
Network. She has contributed to the New York Times and USA Today.
Fluent in French, she was a news anchor for Agence Internationale
D'Image Televisee in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Fairley said in a recent interview that the African-American
community is not widely benefiting from a strong stock market as
much as other investors across America. While there are certainly
affluent and successful African-Americans on Wall Street, many
people in the community still are novice investors, if they're
investing at all.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit is a lower income base, she said, and lack of
experience and knowledge about the markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans don't make as much money,'' Fairley said.
When they have savings, ``they've worked so hard to get it, they
don't want to lose it. They see (the stock market) as gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   While growth in median income for African-Americans -- up 4.3
percent from 1995 to 1997 after adjusting for inflation -- rose
higher than the 1.9 percent for the general population,
African-American household income still lags behind all other
groups, according to the U.S. Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The median household income for African-Americans was $25,050,
compared with $45,249 for Asian-Americans and Pacific Islanders,
$38,972 for whites and $26,628 for Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   A smaller income is one reason fewer African-Americans own
securities.
</P>
<P>
   About 6 percent of African-Americans own market assets compared
with 20 percent of whites, said Deardra Green-Campbell, president
of D. Campbell &AMP; Co. Inc., an investment education and information
organization in Atlanta that publishes a Web site aimed at
African-Americans at www.investedmagazine.com.
</P>
<P>
   Among households earning $50,000 or more, slightly more than
half of blacks own securities, compared with 81 percent of whites,
Green-Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the income and experience disparity, investing is
possible, Fairley points out in her book, and necessary. Fairley's
book lays out simple first steps for readers to take -- really,
tips that can be used by any novice investor.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to do is control spending and save more.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Fairley decried name-brand shopping, saying it's a
habit that's quite costly. And she pointed out that frequent trips
to the beauty salon can add up to a lot of money not saved.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other recommendations made by financial advisers in
Fairley's book:
</P>
<P>
   Track expenditures to find wasteful spending. That $2.50 latte
each workday costs $50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Save 10 percent to 15 percent of wages, or at least $50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Put savings in a mutual fund, where it should appreciate in
value.
</P>
<P>
   Set financial goals -- whether it's for a new car, trip to
Hawaii or cushier retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Become familiar with the investment world. Read financial
publications, watch CNBC or other business news shows, and scour
the Internet for information.
</P>
<P>
   After starting an investment program, let it grow.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
