r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      04-17 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASINOS HAVE NOT BEEN THE OGRES MANY PREDICTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City made national headlines Thursday for its enlightened
business climate, in which health-care insurance is more readily
available for small-company workers than it is in many other U.S.
metro areas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit for this situation, according to The Wall
Street Journal Page 1 story, should go to the riverboat casinos.
When the gaming industry arrived here, it apparently raised the
benefits bar a couple of notches by providing health-care coverage.
Many small firms had no choice but to follow suit to survive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This helped to encourage the Greater Kansas City Chamber of
Commerce to find a way to help these small firms. The article
praised chamber President Pete Levi for teaming up with Blue Cross
and Blue Shield of Kansas City several years ago to devise an
affordable health-care coverage plan that pooled the risk of many
small businesses into one program. It's called ChamberCHOICE and
covers nearly 12,000 employees and their families at more than
3,000 businesses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the gaming palaces arrived in Kansas City, opponents
refused to acknowledge that they would be responsible for any
positive economic contributions. There were warnings instead that
the cost of dealing with increased social pathology would more than
offset any economic benefit created by riverboats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, the dire consequences haven't materialized.
Meantime, the boats not only have created thousands of good-paying
jobs, but also, as it apparently turns out, helped enhance the
fortunes of other local workers as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the overall benefit of the casinos themselves, a
scientifically rigorous analysis of the gaming industry supports
the view that both casinos and greyhound racing are indeed spurs to
economic growth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Douglas M. Walker of Georgia College &AMP; State University and John
D. Jackson of Auburn University set out to explore two aspects of
the issue. One was whether legalized gambling generated economic
growth and, if so, was the result dependent on out-of-town
business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Their analysis was published in the fall '98 issue of The Review
of Regional Studies, which is the official journal of the Southern
Regional Science Association. As a scientific exercise, their
approach depends so heavily on quantitative models and the
resulting math as to be incomprehensible to anyone untrained in
these methods. This precision, however, is what distinguishes it
from most other efforts to probe the economic merit of the gaming
business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When all the pertinent numbers were run, the two economists
concluded that both casino and greyhound racing operations create
economic growth. Moreover, they found that ``exports,'' or outsider
patronage, weren't crucial to achieving such growth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What aroused their interest, they said, was the thesis of
legendary economist Joseph Schumpeter, who posited in the '30s that
providing a new good for consumers spurs economic growth. They
wanted to see if Schumpeter's thesis applied to areas involved in
the relatively recent legalized gambling boom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Walker-Jackson research and what's happening in Kansas City
are both valuable additions to the debate over the economic value
of legalized gaming. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
