<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRAUD-POHL18-COX     04-17 2842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAUD-POHL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fraud suit says Pohl cheated his investors
 &HT;    By Dylan Rivera
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Bill Pohl, whose land holdings will help define
the future of the U.S. 183 corridor, amassed at least $18 million
through fraudulent land deals that exploited his partners' trust in
him, according to a lawsuit in state district court.
</P>
<P>
   Using European corporations to conceal profits, the lawsuit
charges, Pohl and his associates bought land, then sold it to
investors they had solicited at prices marked up by 21 percent to
359 percent without disclosing the profit to theinvestors. Pohl,
who has been involved in about 105 limited partnerships since 1974,
created and continues to manage the five identified in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Because 985 acres acquired by the partnerships were overpriced,
the lawsuit says, citing previously confidential sales prices, the
partnerships have been unable to sell the tracts, even during the
land boom of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Pohl says he provided investors information required by law. A
small group of frustrated investors filed the suit, Pohl says, and
it has no merit.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter mailed to his partners in April 1998, Pohl
vigorously denied the allegations, saying that a plaintiff's lawyer
had mischaracterized the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer ``has taken isolated accounting entries and removed
them from context to create allegations and accusations that are
false,'' Pohl said in the letter, which was filed as evidence in
the suit. ``His letters would lead you to believe that Gary Brown
and I have stolen from the partnerships. This is absolutely false.
Not only have we not stolen from the partnerships, we have never
deceived anyone.'' Pohl's partnershipscontrol about 5,000 acres _14
times the size of Zilker Park _ worth hundreds of millions of
dollars, giving them enormous influence over the growth of
Northwest Austin and southwest Williamson County. Pohl and his
associates also are major contributors to the elected officials who
decide when and where to build roads and extend water and sewer
service that make development possible. ``They are unbelievable,''
said Kent Taylor, a real estate agent who handles commercial land
in southern Williamson County. ``They are the major land player in
the area.'' The Bill Pohl story is about money, land and politics.
His successes and failures parallel those of the entire real estate
community, which dominated Austin's business and political scene
until high-tech entrepreneurs recently joined the party. For 25
years, Pohl has bet his and his partners' money on the power of
suburban housing prices and schools to draw the middle class and
its employers to the edge of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit names Pohl as well as Pohl, Brown &AMP; Associates Inc.,
the real estate company he runs with Gary F. Brown, and several of
Pohl's partners and associates. Eleven investors, mostly from the
Austin area, filed the suit in July 1997. Since then 23 more, most
of them Belgian, have joined. The suit now involves 16 partnerships
that own 1,987 acres, almost all in Williamson County.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs describe Pohl, Brown in the lawsuit as a company
``adrift without any ethical moorings,'' where profits are for
insiders, creditors are shown false data and investors are
deceived. As the suit heads toward a hearing, Pohl, Brown officials
are continuing to negotiate to sell land _ 640 acres at first, with
more possible _ in Northwest Austin and Cedar Park to PacTen
Partners,a California company.
</P>
<P>
   While Pohl is best-known for trying to bring a Double-A baseball
team to Cedar Park and for buying the 446-acre, state-owned Hog
Farm tract last year after a zoning fight with Austin, his main
business for 25 years has been real estate brokerage and investing.
</P>
<P>
   Pohl, who grew up in Austin, has persuaded about 1,200 American
and European investors to give him tens of millions of dollars for
land purchases in the Austin area and, more recently, near Dallas
and Houston, and in Florida and California. Pohl tells investors to
expect three to five times their money back and says his
partnerships usually hold land three to five years before selling,
according tothe lawsuit and confidential offering memorandums
distributed to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Pohl, Brown gathers investors into limited partnerships _ groups
of people who pool their money to share ownership of a business or
property. Limited partnerships give investors confidentiality and
shield them from personal liability for claims against the
business, said Brian Rider, a professor who teaches law and real
estate at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And in Texas and California, unlike in most states, limited
partnerships don't have to pay franchise taxes, which corporations
and companies pay annually, Rider said. The Legislature has decided
not to tax limited partnerships because many small, family-owned
businesses use that structure, Rider said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loophole has been created for nothing that has to do with
. . . real estate,'' Rider said. ``But the real estate people are
using it.'' At least 19 of Pohl's partnerships have been through
bankruptcy. Others had land foreclosed on for not making payments,
and some were sued on allegations they failed to pay taxes or repay
loans worth millions of dollars, according to court records. The
State Securities Board gathers complaints and pursues cases of
securities fraud, including allegations such as those in the suit,
some of which would be felonies if prosecutors proved them in
criminal court. But filing a civil suit is often the quickest and
surest remedy for investors, said David Weaver, general counsel for
the securities board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always advise people when they do file complaints with us
that they should also seek private counsel, because the likelihood
of their recovering from our actions is just not that great,''
Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   The board's 28-person enforcement division is in charge of
investigating and enforcing securities violations by the more than
100,000 securities agents in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A question of disclosure
</P>
<P>
   The people suing Pohl, Brown say that in a series of deals,
company officials negotiated land buys and organized limited
partnerships to make the purchases. Investors understood that Pohl
would take a standard broker's commission on that deal and even
share some of the money with other investors. Then Pohl, Brown
officials or companies controlled by Pohl, Brown bought the land
first and sold it to the partnerships without telling investors of
the intermediate deals, the plaintiffs say. Failure to disclose the
``flips,'' which made Pohl, Brown millions of dollars, breached the
company's legal responsibilities to its investors, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Farmer, an investor and longtime friend of Pohl, was an
investor in Carolville Ltd., one of the partnerships at issue in
the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Pohl drove Farmer out to look at the land, on Brushy Creek Road
where Parmer Lane now intersects it, in 1989. ``It was raw land,
agricultural land, covered with cactus and live oak trees and some
cedars,'' Farmer saidin an interview last fall. Noting the
continued lack of activity there, he said it looked ``just like it
looks today, pretty much.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer put up the $85,000 earnest money on a contract to buy the
525 acres.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo to Farmer discussing the deal a few years later, Pohl
said that company officials spent about two years in ``tough
contract negotiations'' to buy the land from former Texas Attorney
General Will Wilson and Ann Seaman, whose family sold the land to
liquidate a family trust.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for Pohl, Brown &AMP; Brown Inc. _ a previous name for
Pohl, Brown &AMP; Associates Inc. _ told Farmer that Carolville would
buy the land for about $9,000 an acre,Farmer said in a sworn
statement. Since Texas was in a recession and land was selling
cheaply, especially in the Austin area, Farmer said he assumed the
partnership was buying land for a good price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it would be one of those things that we would
buy today and six months later sell for four times what we put into
it, but I thought over five to seven years it would be a good
investment,'' Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   What Farmer and other plaintiffs testified they didn't know was
that on June 20, 1989, just before Carolville bought the land,
Garry C. Brown _ who no longer is with the company _ bought it, as
a trustee, for less than $7,500 per acre, according to deed records
collected as part of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In records filed from 12:39 p.m. to 12:41 p.m. on June 27, 1989,
Garry C. Brown bought the 525 acres for about $3,743,000 and sold
it to the partnership for $4,698,750.
</P>
<P>
   Pohl said in an interview this month that almost all the
$955,000 price increase in Carolville was used to pay commissions
to Europeans who helped find investors for the partnership. Pohl,
Brown officials also got a commission of about 6 percent of the
purchase price from Wilson and Seaman, which is standard and was
disclosed to investors, Pohl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The balance went to the people who raised the money in
Europe,'' who wanted the deal structured in two parts, Pohl said.
European agents demand more than the 6 percent commissions that are
standard in the United States, Pohl said. ``You have to pay an
outrageous commission to attract it. It's just that simple,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer said the intermediate sale, which the lawsuit says he
didn't discover until after the suit was filed in 1997, infuriated
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have never done another deal with him if I'd known
Carolville was bought for $3.7 million and he told everyone $4.7
million,'' Farmer said last fall. ``I would have never done another
deal with the guy at all, and I would have gotten out immediately,
and I would have taken action against him then.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm outraged with it,'' Farmer said. ``I think it's the most
asinine thing I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Pohl said that Farmer knew of the intermediate transaction and
had received commissions himself for recruiting other people _ his
daughter, mother and some friends _ to invest, knowing the land
price was going to increase to pay European commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit now becomes part of Farmer's legacy. He killed
himself in January, after about 10 years of battling multiple
sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Alleged markups
</P>
<P>
   Carolville was not the only, and it was far from the largest,
deal in which Pohl and his associates made millions off their
partners by inflating the price of land, according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Nine other deals for 460 acres included hidden markups of $17
million, plaintiffs allege. In those sales, Pohl used third parties
he controlled to make the profits, the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   Documents in the suit show that two European corporations _
Madron Investments Ltd., incorporated in Gibraltar, and F.F.U.
Ltd., incorporated in Jersey, Channel Islands _ sold land to Pohl,
Brown partnerships for millions of dollars more than the
corporations had paid for the land. None of the markups was
disclosed, and the money was returned to Pohl and other defendants,
the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   While Pohl denies being an owner of either Madron or F.F.U., the
plaintiffs say he runs both companies and essentially used them as
checking accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In one of those deals, the plaintiffs say, Madron made $10
million, and $6.6 million ended up in Pohl, Brown's pocket later
that year.
</P>
<P>
   Madron bought 148.29 acres surrounding Lakeline Mall for $4.8
million on March 27, 1995, and sold the land to two Pohl, Brown
partnerships about 10 days later for $15 million, according to
settlement statements filed in the lawsuit and Williamson County
deed records.
</P>
<P>
   Financial statements for both corporations show that from April
to December 1995, after selling to the Pohl, Brown partnerships,
Madron paid F.F.U. $7.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   For the same period, F.F.U. paid Pohl, Brown $6.5 million and
paid thousands of dollars directly to Pohl and Brown and other
employees of the company as commissions, financial records for
F.F.U. show.
</P>
<P>
   Pohl said most of the $10 million markup went to reimburse
Madron for payments it had made to settle back taxes. The markup
also covered other expenses, including commissions for European
agents and Pohl, Brown officials, Pohl said. He structured the sale
to pass through the European companies to protect his investors'
assets from possible seizure by the local governments owed the back
taxes, Pohl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took all the cost for those parcels, plus commissions to
Europe, 6 percent for us, and that's how you get'' the price paid
by the partnerships, Pohl said.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs say Madron profited from buying and selling land
to Pohl, Brown partnerships and shared those profits with Pohl and
other defendants who helped set up the deals.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs say that Pohl controls Madron and that Christian
Jean-Jacques Wanner is the key to understanding Pohl's relationship
to Madron.
</P>
<P>
   Wanner, a Swiss man who has done business with Pohl, Brown for
years, has signed deeds on behalf of Madron when the corporation
bought and sold hundreds of acres in Williamson County.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, Wanner met with Austin Mayor Kirk Watson to
discuss Madron's plans for the state-owned Hog Farm tract that
Madron had a contract to buy. And Fred C. Clark, an accountant who
does tax returns for Madron, said in a deposition that Wanner owns
Jawer Ltd., another foreign corporation. Jawer owns 99 percent of
Madron, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Wanner has sworn as part of the lawsuit that he is
not an ``officer, director or employee of any Texas business or any
business which owns property in Texas.'' He knows who owns Madron,
Wanner testified, but he won't identify them.
</P>
<P>
   According to Pohl and Wanner's testimony, Pohl advised Madron on
which tracts of land to buy and used F.F.U. Ltd. as a
``pass-through'' to pay commissions to Pohl, Brown &AMP; Associates and
other defendants. Pohl said the money needed to go through F.F.U.
for tax purposes, on Clark's advice. But Clark testified that he
didn't know why money flowed through F.F.U. Ltd. and that it made
no difference for tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Too much commission?
</P>
<P>
   In another land purchase, according to the suit, duplicate
records were used to hide commissions a partnership paid to Pohl
and his associates without investors' knowledge. Further, the
plaintiffs say, the commissions exceed industry standards. In
November 1992, a Pohl, Brown partnership called Par 620 Ltd. bought
11.132 acres at the northwest corner of Parmer Lane and RM 620 for
$5,536,440, according to closing statements.
</P>
<P>
   Two closing statements were written for the deal.
</P>
<P>
   One had two columns, ``buyer's transaction'' and ``seller's
transaction.'' The seller's column included $951,341.42 in
commissions, including $785,313.08 to Pohl, Brown and $52,666.67 to
W.B. Pohl and Associates Inc. The second statement listed only the
buyer's transaction. The commissions do not appear.
</P>
<P>
   The edited statement was distributed to limited partners, such
as Bruce Farmer's mother, Helen Farmer, and daughter, Sally Anne
Farmer, the suit says.
</P>
<P>
   Charles H. House, who handles Pohl, Brown's business in
California, testified that industry standards would dictatethat
commissions as high as 17 percent be disclosed to limited partners.
Real estate brokers in the Austin area say commissions can vary but
are usually from 6 percent to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   House, who finds investors for Pohl, Brown, said in a sworn
statement he ``didn't realize there were flips. . . . And I'm not
100 percent sure there are flips, but it appears that there are.''
Nevertheless, House said last week, he and his investors would
consider the issue moot if Pohl can close a sale to California
developer PacTen Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Pohl said he thinks the suit is motivated from frustration that
the partnerships' land hasn't sold more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not mad at them for filing a lawsuit,'' Pohl said. ``I
don't know if I could have invested with me at that time and the
results were delayed at that level, that I wouldn't have done
something out of frustration. And I hope it's just resolved through
land sales. That's happening now.''
</P>
<P>
   House said he believes Pohl's explanation that the price
increases paid for expenses and not, as plaintiffs allege, for
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Pohl didn't pocket all the money from the price
increases _ if the money went to pay for expenses, as Pohl and
House say _ the price increases are still fraudulent under the
plaintiff's theory of the case, because they were not disclosed to
the limited partners, said Jim Hemphill, an attorney for the
plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say, `I did mislead you, and I did deceive you, but I
still gave you a good deal, it just wasn't as good as I told you it
was,' well, when you're a partner, that's not acceptable conduct,''
Hemphill said. ``Just because you make money doesn't mean there
wasn't fraud or misrepresentation through deceit.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
