<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY'S BEHAVIOR COULD JEOPARDIZE HIS DEAL WITH YANKS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Even if Darryl Strawberry passes the drug test
administered to him in the aftermath of his arrest Wednesday for
cocaine possession and solicitation of prostitution, he is in
jeopardy of losing his $2.5-million deal with the Yankees.
Virtually his entire salary is tied into a consulting agreement
with the team, instead of being compensation for playing baseball,
and the consulting agreement hinges on a strict behavior clause.
</P>
<P>
   That clause, some baseball officials say, will give the Yankees
great latitude in determining whether they will sever their ties
with Strawberry, who was in contact with the team on Saturday for
the first time since his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   According to an official who has seen Strawberry's contract _ a
minor league deal _ the 37-year-old outfielder is to receive only a
nominal salary for playing baseball; some minor leaguers receive
less than $2,000 per month. The remainder, perhaps more than $2.4
million, is tied into a consulting arrangement with the Yankees,
and some baseball officials believe the Yankees could void the deal
solely on the solicitation charge.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Strawberry has many other hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   If either of the urine samples he gave last week tests positive
for cocaine, Strawberry would be subject to immediate suspension by
Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   If Strawberry, who faces a maximum of five years for possession
of cocaine and a maximum of 60 days for solicitation, arranges a
plea bargain on the cocaine charge, Major League Baseball would
view this as an admission, and Strawberry would be subject to
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   And if Strawberry is eventually convicted of solicitation, the
Yankees could void his contract on the clause contained within the
consulting arrangement _ or even on the basis of a behavior clause
within the standard minor league deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy has troubles on both counts,'' said another baseball
official.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, whose arraignment has not been scheduled, called
Yankees General Manager Brian Cashman on Saturday, his first
conversation with a club official after two days without
communication. Cashman would not reveal any specifics of their
conversation, although he did say that there are no plans to have
Strawberry continue his workouts at the team's minor league
facility in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
