<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air Force deeds Bergstrom to Austin as new airport site
 &HT;    By Debbie Hiott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With two simple signatures and a lot of ceremony
Saturday, Bergstrom Air Force Base, which once symbolized Austin's
protection from foreign threats, transformed officially into a hub
of commerce and travel.
</P>
<P>
   In one of several ceremonial milestones in the weeks ahead to
celebrate the opening of Austin-Bergstrom International Airport, F.
Whitten Peters, acting secretary of the Air Force, signed over the
deed to the former Air Force base, now airport site, to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``While that officially ends the presence of the Air Force on
this property, the influence on the community will endure for years
and generations to come,'' said Mayor Kirk Watson.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony was the first major event before the May 23 opening
of the new airport. Although the airport opening has been delayed
from May 2, grand opening celebrations continue as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Also Saturday, the city named one of the last remnants of the
Air Force base, the 12,250-foot west runway, after President Lyndon
B. Johnson, who used to fly in to the base on Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   The east runway will bear the name of former U.S. Congressman
Jake Pickle, who pushed for the new 9,000-foot runway to allow
simultaneous landings and takeoffs at Austin's new airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Johnson runway and the Pickle runway will be running
separate but parallel,'' said Pickle, who represented Austin in
Congress for 31 years. ``I take comfort in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickle also thanked Peters for signing over the deed for the
base and making the transfer official, pointing out ``you
understand, Mr. Secretary, I wasn't suspicious of the federal
government or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters, who is advocating for another round of national military
base closures, lauded the $690 million airport as one of the
country's most successful base conversions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is just a tremendous success,'' Peters said.
``It's a case study.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal and local officials have said they know of no larger
conversion from a military base to civilian airport in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   By using the former military base as a starting point in
building the new airport, city officials saved $200 million in
runway reuse and land costs.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison (R-Texas) said the city also
avoided what could have been a heavy economic blow to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many times I have seen that when a base closes, everything
comes down,'' she said. ``That didn't happen in Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Congressman Lloyd Doggett (D-Texas) said travelers will
know they are in Austin when they arrive at the new airport, which
will feature work and recorded music by local artists and artisans,
a live music stage and native plants in the landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Denver without the chewed up baggage,'' Doggett
said. ``It's unique to Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one other major reminder of the former Air Force base
besides the west runway will remain at the new airport. That's the
Bergstrom name, in honor of Capt. John August Earl Bergstrom, who
was the first soldier from Travis County to die in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   LaVerne Bergstrom-Jackson said Saturday the Bergstrom family was
honored to have the new airport named after her cousin, as it was
to have the base named after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the epitome of the soldier-citizen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Grand opening festivities continue Wednesday when President
Clinton, with U.S. Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater and
Federal Aviation Administration Chief Jane Garvey, arrive to
celebrate the airport opening. Gov. George W. Bush will join
Clinton at a small event at the airport Wednesday morning. Some
members of the public will be allowed to attend, but details of the
visit aren't expected to be made available until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
