<HEADER>
A2746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-1STLD-WRITE     04-17 1340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKING QUARTERBACKS AS EASY AS 1-2-3: COUCH, MCNABB, SMITH  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to expand by 300 words, and rewrite)   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few quarterbacks have undergone the kind of scrutiny Kentucky's
Tim Couch received this month, of everything from the way he
selected an agent to his grip on the football.
</P>
<P>
   Even the expansion Cleveland Browns, who selected Couch Saturday
with the No. 1 pick in the National Football League draft and the
first pick in the reborn franchise's history, had their doubts. But
Cleveland's thinking changed after Couch performed well in a recent
workout. After that performance, Browns officials, many of whom
worked for the San Francisco 49ers, spoke of how much Couch
reminded them of Joe Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling that Couch could lead their franchise for the next 10
years, the Browns came to terms with him several hours before the
draft on a seven-year, $48 million contract that includes a $12.2
million signing bonus, the largest ever given to a rookie. By the
time the draft began, Cleveland's choice was the worst-kept secret
in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a great moment,'' Couch said. ``I can't tell you
how happy I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland's selection of Couch was about the only thing that
went to form in a topsy-turvy, trade-crazy draft, one of the most
exciting in years. The most shocking moment came when the
Indianapolis Colts took Miami running back Edgerrin James over the
Heisman Trophy winner, Ricky Williams of Texas, with the fourth
pick.
</P>
<P>
   Two more quarterbacks were selected after Couch, making it the
first time since 1971 that quarterbacks were chosen 1-2-3 in the
draft. Philadelphia selected Donovan McNabb, the poised player from
Syracuse, and Cincinnati took Oregon's Akili Smith, whose strong
arm has reminded scouts of a young John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   The last quarterbacks to go in the top three were Jim Plunkett,
Archie Manning and Dan Pastorini.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big year for quarterbacks, as five were taken in the
top 12 picks. They included Daunte Culpepper of Central Florida,
who becomes the heir apparent to Randall Cunningham in Minnesota,
and Cade McNown of UCLA, who the Chicago Bears believe is a more
athletic Doug Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   Once the top three quarterbacks were gone, things began to get
strange. Indianapolis, long thought to be interested in Williams or
defensive back Champ Bailey of Georgia, shocked just about everyone
by taking James, a slick runner whose stock rose dramatically in
recent weeks. While the Colts said they simply had James rated
higher, it was hard to believe that Williams' braids and pierced
tongue did not bother the conservative coach of the Colts, Jim
Mora.
</P>
<P>
   James' being selected before Williams led to the sort of awkward
moment that seems to have become commonplace in the draft.
Williams, who thought he was going to the Colts, expressed utter
shock on camera when his name was not called.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts' decision led to several blockbuster trades that will
be remembered for years and could change the course of franchises.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Coach Mike Ditka had said he would get Williams at
any cost, and he paid a steep price. Once the Colts passed on
Williams, Ditka called the Washington Redskins and offered all of
his picks from this year's draft and two from next season _ the
Saints' picks in the first, third, fourth, fifth, sixth and seventh
rounds this year and first- and third-round picks in 2000. The
Redskins jumped at the deal, moving down from No. 5 to the Saints'
spot at 12 in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected Indianapolis to take me, so I was surprised,''
Williams. ``But I'm glad I'm going to a place where I'm wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was concerned about carrying an franchise on
his shoulders, Williams said: ``I'm not too worried. I'm just going
to go out and play football.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington then made another trade. Using some of their newly
acquired picks from the Saints, and combining them with a few of
their own, the Redskins switched places in the first round with
Chicago, moving back up to No. 7. That allowed the Redskins to get
the player they wanted the entire time in Bailey, probably the best
athlete in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins, like the Saints, gave up a lot. Washington gave
Chicago the Saints' first- and third-round picks and their own
fourth- and fifth-round selections from this draft, and a
third-round selection from next year. The Redskins are so confident
that Bailey will be able to start this season that Coach Norv
Turner announced that the 11-year veteran Cris Dishman would be
released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, there were six trades in the first round alone. Dallas,
for example, gave Seattle its pick at No. 22 as well as a
fifth-rounder to move up two spots to No. 20 and select North
Carolina defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban. The Cowboys wanted
defensive linemen, because they may lose tackle Leon Lett for all
of next year to a drug suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Miami was so unimpressed with the talent remaining at No. 24
that it traded out of the first round entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Teams did not just trade draft picks. St. Louis sent quarterback
Tony Banks, who has had a disappointing career, to Baltimore for a
fifth-round pick this year and a seventh-rounder in 2000.
Meanwhile, the Ravens traded the backup quarterback Eric Zeier to
Tampa Bay for a sixth-round pick. Zeier will put pressure on the
Tampa Bay starter, Trent Dilfer.
</P>
<P>
   There were other interesting twists to the draft beyond the
dealing inside the Garden. A small group of people protested
outside the arena, claiming that the NFL was racist because a black
quarterback had never been drafted with the first overall pick.
While that held true this year, the three black quarterbacks taken
in the first round of this draft _ McNabb, Smith and Culpepper _
equaled the total number of black passers ever taken in the first
round (Doug Williams in 1978, Andre Ware in 1990 and Steve McNair
in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dramatic falls in the draft was that of Andy
Katzenmoyer, the heralded linebacker from Ohio State, who dropped
to New England at No. 28. Team officials said privately that
Katzenmoyer, the Butkus award winner for best college linebacker,
was hurt most by a lack of foot speed. Teams also said that he was
not impressive in interviews. Ditka considered taking Katzenmoyer,
but shied away when Katzenmoyer told him that his favorite
linebacker was Brian Bosworth, a pro bust _ because he liked how
Bosworth ran out of the tunnel before games.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest curveball of the day was Cleveland's signing of
Couch before the draft began.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when it seemed the Browns might not choose
Couch because of questions about his arm strength and grip on the
ball (he held his index finger too high, causing the ball to
occasionally wobble).
</P>
<P>
   Some NFL personnel people felt that Cleveland's sometimes public
hesitation when it came to Couch was intended to give it an upper
hand in negotiations. Others felt that the Browns were genuinely
puzzled about whom to take, their top three choices being Smith,
Williams and Couch.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what sold the Browns on Couch was his second workout
for them. In it, Couch showed accuracy and confidence that had not
been on display in his first workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That workout pushed us over the top,'' said Carmen Policy, the
former San Francisco executive who is now president of the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland officials had contacted the agents for all three
players, but within the last 48 hours the Browns had concentrated
their efforts on Couch.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between the Browns and Couch's agent, Tom Condon, heated
up beginning around 9 p.m. on Friday and did not conclude until
around 3 on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not tolerate any disruption of his focus,'' said
Policy when asked why it was so important to sign Couch early. ``We
needed our leader signed early and we wanted that to send a message
to anyone who was going to be part of this team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
