<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHAIR-RIDDLE18-COX     04-17 2101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHAIR-RIDDLE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At heart of O'Hair case: Riddle of David Waters
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi and Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At 17, David Roland Waters and three friends
beat another youth to death for not letting them borrow his car.
</P>
<P>
   At 30, a year out of prison, Waters beat his mother with a
broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, 52, who once described his youth as uneventful and his
criminal record as ``my brush with the law years ago,'' is now
sitting in jail in San Marcos _ apparently the focus in the
disappearance and perhaps death of world-famous atheist Madalyn
O'Hair. O'Hair and two family members disappeared from Austin in
1995, just three months after Waters pleaded guilty to stealing
$54,415 from O'Hair's American Atheists.
</P>
<P>
   Waters stayed out of jail by agreeing to repay the money, and
later got the restitution reduced to $15,000 by giving police
evidence that he said would help them find the O'Hairs. ``The
police thought they were about to find them'' with Waters' help two
years ago, said Rosemary Lehmberg, first assistant in the Travis
County district attorney's office. ``It's our impression now that
he duped everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, although authorities have not charged him in the O'Hair
disappearance, his attorney Patrick Ganne says federal agents are
trying to tie his client to the suspected deaths of O'Hair, her
son, Jon Garth Murray, and the granddaughter she adopted as her
daughter, Robin Murray-O'Hair. Also missing: $500,000 in gold
coins.
</P>
<P>
   Even as investigators pore over Waters' criminal files in Travis
County and beyond, the question is: Could a high-school dropout who
spent more than a quarter of his life behind bars mastermind a
high-profile killing for a half-million dollars and the elaborate
plot to cover it up? If so, why would Waters, having lost his
longtime girlfriend and apparently living like a pauper, choose to
stay in Austin, writing a book about the O'Hairs' disappearance as
authorities closed in?
</P>
<P>
   Last month, seven-time felon Gary P. Karr, who once served time
with Waters, confessed to being an accomplice in multiple murders
in Texas, according to the FBI. Based on Karr's information,
federal agents searched a Hill Country ranch Easter weekend, but
turned up nothing, according to sources. Last month, federal agents
searched Waters' apartment and charged him with possession of
ammunition, a crime for a felon. When federal agents knocked on
Waters' apartment last month, he was on the verge of being evicted
for not paying rent. He had lost his longtime girlfriend to a
neighbor. He was riding the bus to his job at a pet shop because
his broken-down red Camaro wouldn't run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not appear to be the guy who made the big score,''
said David Travis, a former co-worker at American Atheists.
Besides, Travis said, ``You don't kill someone and write a book
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the line
</P>
<P>
   Waters' early crimes were more thoughtless acts than elaborate
schemes requiring smarts.
</P>
<P>
   A teen-ager always in trouble with the law, Waters was a regular
in the Illinois reform school system and a perpetual runaway. By
his midteens, Waters had been caught twice breaking the curfew in
Peoria, Ill., once for public drunkenness and once for burglarizing
a woman's house with four of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   One December night in 1964, Waters, 17, crossed from
misdemeanors to murder. He and three of his teen-age friends caught
a ride with 16-year-old David Gibbs, who wore Buddy Holly glasses
and a flattop haircut. The four soon got into an argument with
Gibbs, first about girls, then about borrowing his car. Then,
according to a 1964 article in the Peoria Journal-Star, the boys
pulled Gibbs from the driver's seat and a fight began. It spilled
over into the road, where the four-on-one beating turned bloody and
brutal. Waters and the other three took turns hitting Gibbs with a
club fashioned from a broken fence post, according to their
confessions. Police later found a blood trail leading across the
road and tattered pieces of Gibbs' plaid shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, who posed for a newspaper photo wearing the collar of
his jailhouse jumpsuit up and a cigarette dangling from his mouth,
was sentenced to 30 to 60 years in prison for the murder. He served
12 before being paroled.
</P>
<P>
   Just more than a year out of prison, Waters was convicted of his
second felony _ aggravated battery for attacking his mother with a
broomstick. He also urinated on her face. Waters spent another year
in jail.
</P>
<P>
   But, on Valentine's Day 1980, the man with the violent past
became a victim of random violence. His first wife, ``Mari'' Anne
Budde Waters, was murdered while visiting a friend in Danville,
Ill. Waters' wife and her friend, Cheryl Geld, had gone to a male
strip club. When Geld's boyfriend found out, he flew into a jealous
rage and stabbed them both to death. The killer is still on death
row.
</P>
<P>
   Waters later remarried, but the marriage lasted only two years
before the couple divorced, citing irreconcilable differences.
</P>
<P>
   World of Madalyn O'Hair
</P>
<P>
   Rootless, Waters moved from place to place and crossed paths
with the law again in 1985, when he forged a name to a $5,000
counterfeit check and was sentenced to four more years in prison.
After his release, Waters moved to Florida, where he was convicted
of driving under the influence.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Waters, looking for a fresh start, picked
out Austin from a tourism brochure.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1993 he answered a classified ad for a typesetter at
$7 an hour. The ad warned: ``Religious persons may feel
uncomfortable.'' He omitted his criminal record from the
application and was hired at the American Atheists' national
headquarters in Northeast Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Waters entered the world of Madalyn O'Hair, who by many accounts
was secretive, paranoid, short-tempered and always cursing. She
lived and worked with her son, Jon Murray, and granddaughter, Robin
Murray-O'Hair, whom she had adopted as her daughter. She trusted no
one else at the Austin headquarters. From that fenced office
building, the aging O'Hair oversaw a small work force of three to
seven people producing videos, magazines and newsletters and
soliciting money.
</P>
<P>
   Water's co-workers, Travis and Derek Nalls, describe the ex-con
as likable, hard-working, in love with his girlfriend but saying
nothing about his criminal past. In the next 14 months, Waters
worked his way up to office manager at a time the office was under
siege because of an ongoing legal battle in California.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair had tried to claim the estate of an eccentric millionaire
who had bought the atheist magazine The Truth Seeker. The estate
countersued, claiming the O'Hairs had conspired to steal millions
from the estate. When it looked as if they might lose, the O'Hairs
began hiding money, paintings and even the organization's
collection of books on atheism, according to former employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They even told us employees not to leave anything valuable in
our desks, because we might come to work someday and the doors
would be padlocked,'' Travis said.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this time, Waters contends, that Jon Murray induced
him to divert money from the atheist organization to the O'Hairs.
He said his cut was $15,000. In his unpublished manuscript, Waters
writes that the O'Hairs double-crossed him.
</P>
<P>
   While the O'Hairs were in San Diego fighting the lawsuit, Waters
wrote, he was stealing money from the atheist organization under
Jon Murray's orders. When the O'Hairs won a standoff in the
California trial, they returned to Austin and accused Waters of
theft. Waters was already gone, leaving behind a letter of
resignation. He later wrote that he went to California to visit a
sister. Within three weeks, however, he returned to Austin to turn
himself in.
</P>
<P>
   Travis said he was mystified by Waters' return: ``I think he did
it for his girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters faced up to 99 years in prison as an habitual criminal.
Citing his long, violent history, Travis County's pre-sentencing
investigators recommended imprisonment. Yet prosecutor Lehmberg
said O'Hair wanted Waters to repay the money instead of going to
prison. She said the O'Hairs also worried that a jury would be
biased against them because of their notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors offered Waters a deal: He pleaded guilty to theft
and the habitual criminal charge. He agreed to repay the $54,415
over 10 years. His sentence was deferred and he faced up to 99
years in prison if he did not keep his end of the deal, Lehmberg
said.
</P>
<P>
   Given Waters' history, Lehmberg said it was improbable he could
repay the money, but added: ``It's not uncommon with people, even
with violent backgrounds, to get deferred adjudication at the
victim's request.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, O'Hair feared Waters enough to request a restraining
order to keep him from her family, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after Waters pleaded guilty, the O'Hair family
disappeared from their Northwest Austin home. They left their
breakfast dishes, O'Hair's diabetic medication and three dogs. They
also left a note on the American Atheists' headquarters doors,
telling employees the office was closed because they were leaving
to deal with an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   In the next month, the O'Hairs stayed in touch by cell phone
from San Antonio. Someone purporting to be Jon Murray sold his
Mercedes at a motel parking lot. The buyer said the man who sold
him the car got into a pickup with two people he now recognizes as
Jon Murray and Robin Murray- O'Hair. A San Antonio jeweler
converted $500,000 into gold coins for Jon Murray, who came alone
to a San Antonio bank to claim the money. But he never returned for
$100,000 more in coins. Instead, on Sept. 29, Murray made his last
cell phone call. No one has claimed to have heard from the three
since.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance prompted some intense but brief media
speculation about whether the O'Hairs were victims of foul play or
had fled the country.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, along with other former O'Hair employees, began offering
opinions. Unlike the others, Waters claimed to have documents, such
as credit card receipts, that would lead the police to them. He
traded that information for prosecutors lowering his restitution to
$15,000. He also began a book.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1997, Waters called on Harry Preston, a
longtime writer of books, plays and scripts, living in Garland.
Over the course of a weekend, Waters told his story and showed
Preston an outline and his notes from documents he said he stole
from the atheist headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was charming, very pleasant and intelligent,'' Preston
said. ``Don't ever sell David Waters short. He's no dummy.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters was having trouble paying restitution for the theft from
the O'Hairs, risking prison. Yet he had a $2,500 money order from
Illinois _ Preston said he believed it was from Waters' brother _
for the first half of Preston's fee.
</P>
<P>
   Preston said he believed Waters had a simple motive for the
book: money. ``This woman had disappeared,'' Preston said. ``He
thinks he has the inside scoop, and he's thinking, 'Let's write a
book and make a million dollars.' '' Preston wrote a 217-page
manuscript, ``Good Gawd, Madalyn! The Not-So-Sudden Disappearance
of Madalyn Murray-O'Hair,'' but Waters ignored the author's demands
for the rest of his fee.
</P>
<P>
   A break
</P>
<P>
   By January 1999, Dallas investigators got a break in a murder
case. For three years, a corpse with its head and hands severed had
gone unidentified. It was found along the Trinity River in Dallas
County just three days after the O'Hairs were last heard from, but
there was no reason at the time to believe it was connected to
their disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Then, acting on a tip, authorities identified the corpse with a
DNA test as Danny Fry, a friend of Waters who was visiting him in
Austin at the time the O'Hairs disappeared. Authorities began
looking at Karr and Waters.
</P>
<P>
   After ignoring Preston's calls for about a year and half, Waters
suddenly phoned the author.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called a couple of months ago all sweetie-pie,'' Preston
said last week. ``He wanted me to pursue marketing the book. He
confessed to me he was broke and needed some money.''
</P>
<P>
   No publisher had expressed an interest, Preston said, until
after news of Waters' arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Preston said he is left wondering to what extent Waters was
involved. ``I'm in no position to accuse anyone,'' Preston said.
``But this new wrinkle may change the title to, `Who Murdered
Madalyn Murray O'Hair?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
