<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2758 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-O'HAIR-MYSTERY-2400(2     04-17 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-O'HAIR-MYSTERY-2400(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEADS RESURRECT MEMORIES OF O'HAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: stolen the money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The only facts that existed were damning,'' Zindler said.
``The theory that they were extorted and bumped off sounded like a
cheap dime store novel. Some turned against Madalyn, and
(newspaper) articles assumed the three of them were sunning
themselves on a tropical island.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Johnson, who replaced Jon Garth Murray as president of
American Atheists, said that at first, she never doubted that the
family would return. Even now, when Johnson knows they probably
won't, she refuses to give any substance to news accounts until
there is irrefutable evidence about their fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell me the latest nonsense,'' said Johnson, a New
Jersey mother of two who has spoken at the White House and appeared
before the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights on behalf of the atheist
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an atheist, so show me the evidence. People are always
coming up to me with suppositions and maybes. The worst thing is
not knowing. And what's really upsetting is that people inside and
out of the organization who thought the worst of the O'Hairs are
strangely silent right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Madalyn Murray O'Hair earned her spurs as an atheist during the
early 1960s when she campaigned relentlessly against school prayer.
Her case, Abington Township School District vs. Schempp, was one of
three involving school prayer heard by the Supreme Court in 1962
and '63, said Rob Boston of Americans United for the Separation of
Church and State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was personally courageous for her to take her case on,''
Boston said, ``but a myth grew up around her that she promoted,
that she single-handedly removed religion from public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Zindler said that after the Supreme Court ruled in favor of
O'Hair on June 17, 1963, she could no longer continue to live in
Baltimore with her two young sons. People picketed and harassed
O'Hair, Zindler said. There were acts of vandalism at her home,
including the crucifixion of a pet cat.
</P>
<P>
   He said O'Hair had confrontations with the police and suffered a
broken wrist. She decided to flee when she was charged with
assaulting 16 police officers.
</P>
<P>
   That began an odyssey that took O'Hair to Hawaii, Mexico and
finally to Texas. According to Zindler, Gov. John Connally decided
against extraditing her to Maryland after hearing about the assault
charges against her.
</P>
<P>
   Austin was a refuge for O'Hair. It was a growing university town
with a liberal reputation during the anti-war period of the 1960s
and early '70s. O'Hair conducted her religious war with zeal,
filing dozens of lawsuits in an attempt to remove references to God
in public places or from public documents.
</P>
<P>
   When she received a notice for jury duty, she ceremonially
burned the summons because jurors would have to take an oath under
God.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman was a pioneer,'' said American Atheists spokesman
Ron Barrier, host of The Atheist Viewpoint, a weekly cable
television program. ``What Madalyn accomplished was not banning God
or prayer, but making public schools a level playing field for all
children.''
</P>
<P>
   But O'Hair did not make these points in a cool and reasoned
manner. She could whip the masses into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Altoona, (Pa.) we had one of the first shock jock late
afternoon talk shows, and the host would have her on a lot,''
Boston said. ``People would call in and scream at her.''
</P>
<P>
   And O'Hair would scream back. ``She used vulgarity that you
couldn't imagine,'' Harrington said. ``She was filled with hatred.
The debates we had around the country were like pep rallies. I was
taking on the meanest woman in America, and you don't sit back and
be a gentleman with her. You launch combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus would have targeted her,'' Harrington said. ``It would
have been a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Zindler recalled the time O'Hair was giving a lecture at the
University of Texas at Austin and an incensed young woman shoved a
cream pie filled with needles and pins in her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she was personally afraid many times,'' said Ole
Anthony of the Trinity Foundation in Dallas, which monitors
television ministries and evangelists ``But she loved to play the
persecution card. She was always a victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony, who kept up a correspondence with O'Hair, said she knew
the Scriptures better than most preachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the core of her being I think she wanted to believe in
God,'' Anthony said. ``But she had so much bitterness about how the
Christian community treated her. She did everything she could to be
a thorn in the side of the faith community.''
</P>
<P>
   Time did not mellow her, although John Garth Murray and board
members began to play a more prominent role in American Atheists.
</P>
<P>
   For William Murray, who lost his mother, brother and biological
daughter, Robin Murray O'Hair, in the tragedy, time has not healed
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This family never goes away,'' said Murray, whose
organization, the Religious Freedom Coalition, is based in
Washngton, D.C. ``The best you can do is hope not to transfer this
dysfunctional behavior to your kids or grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where does it end for me? I would have to change my name and
open an ice cream stand in Key West, Florida. But the memories
never go away.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
