<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2759 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-O'HAIR-MYSTERY-2400(2     04-17 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-O'HAIR-MYSTERY-2400(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEADS RESURRECT MEMORIES OF O'HAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was a fiery leader with an acid tongue and an insatiable
appetite for the spotlight. Madalyn Murray O'Hair was a devout
atheist and outspoken advocate of the separation of church and
state who incited audiences during public debates by tearing pages
from the Bible and laughing as she tossed them into the air.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair founded American Atheists in 1963 and delighted in being
known as ``the most hated woman in America.'' She filed one of the
lawsuits that led to the U.S. Supreme Court's ban on prayer in
public schools, and she tried to have the words ``In God We Trust''
removed from U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
   So when O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and adopted daughter
Robin Murray O'Hair vanished from their Austin home in August of
1995, it created a mystery worthy of the X-Files.
</P>
<P>
   Some thought that the three had been kidnapped; others,
including some followers, thought that they absconded with the
atheist organization's trust fund. Knowing O'Hair, some suspected
an elaborate publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair was 76 years old and in failing health. Three dogs,
O'Hair's diabetes medication and unwashed breakfast dishes were
left behind in the house. Although there were no signs of forced
entry or a struggle, it did not look as if the family's departure
that morning was planned.
</P>
<P>
   Little progress was made on the case for 31/2 years. Then, late
last month, federal authorities arrested two felons on firearms
charges. One had previously worked for O'Hair, and the other
volunteered information about four homicides in Texas that may
finally provide clues to unraveling the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The latest twists put Madalyn Murray O'Hair back in the news and
inflamed passions among family, colleagues and foes reminiscent of
the days when she was at the forefront of the atheist movement.
</P>
<P>
   Her estranged son, William J. Murray, said the recent
developments were long overdue. He has blamed the Austin police for
dragging their feet, saying they resented his mother for her
constant criticism of the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she was brutal with everyone,'' said Murray, 52, who
rejected his mother's atheist beliefs and became a Christian. ``She
could buy a package of gum, and by the time she was done, the
teen-age clerk in the convenience store would feel like dirt. But
it doesn't mean you turn your back on a murder.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Austin Police Department said the case is
still open and the investigation continues. ``We've pursued every
lead that's come in,'' said public information officer Kevin
Buchman.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, more than a year ago, Murray began lobbying elected
leaders for help. He wrote and spoke to House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, Sen. Phil Gramm and Gov. George W. Bush. ``My letter to
Governor Bush said that it doesn't matter that these folks are
opposed to what you and I believe,'' Murray said. ``They should
have equal protection under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray credited Armey with prompting the Department of Justice
and the FBI to look deeper into the disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears likely that the the three were victims of foul
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought it was a prank and she was going after
attention,'' said the Rev. Bob Harrington, a 71-year-old minister
who traveled across the country with O'Hair during the mid-1970s in
a series of 38 raucous religious debates. They also appeared
together on the debut of the Phil Donohue Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept expecting to hear from her,'' said Harrington, who now
lives in Mansfield. ``I thought she must have gotten hemmed up in
some situation and didn't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I found out what she left behind in the house, it
looked like an abduction, a Jimmy Hoffa-type of elimination. She
wouldn't have been able to keep silent for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal and local authorities in Texas and Michigan are
investigating whether O'Hair's former office manager and his
associate, both convicted felons, are responsible for kidnapping
and murdering the family members and stealing more than $500,000 in
gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   David Waters, 52, the former office manager who was found guilty
of stealing $54,000 from American Atheists accounts several months
before O'Hair's disappearance, is in custody in Austin, while Gary
Karr, 50, is incarcerated in Detroit. They are being held in
connection with the possession of firearms, which is illegal for
felons.
</P>
<P>
   Karr, however, piqued the interest of authorities when he told
an FBI investigator about unsolved homicides in Texas and missing
gold coins. Karr did not identify the victims by name, though, and
has not confessed to having any role in the disappearance. Waters
says he is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Karr's story prompted federal agents to search a 5,000-acre
ranch outside San Antonio over Easter weekend, presumably in search
of the bodies. Federal officials will not disclose whether anything
was found.
</P>
<P>
   ``There haven't been any new developments since the search,''
said Darren Holmes, a spokesperson for the FBI's San Antonio
office. ``The investigation is ongoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the mystery was the slaying of Waters' friend Danny
Fry, whose dismembered body was found on the banks of the Trinity
River near Dallas on Oct. 2, 1995. No one has been charged in Fry's
death.
</P>
<P>
   William Murray believes that federal agents have his family's
killers in custody, although they may never get a confession or
find the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, some of O'Hair's admirers and adversaries believe that if
recent reports are true, she would be vindicated. At the time of
her disappearance, news accounts said that O'Hair was having
financial difficulties and owed the Internal Revenue Service as
much as $750,000 in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The family had disappeared with the gold coins and had access to
a trust fund in New Zealand. For a month, Jon Garth Murray remained
in contact with American Atheists, reassuring members that his
family was on a business trip. No one knows whether he was making
the telephone calls under duress.
</P>
<P>
   Then all contact ceased.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Zindler, editor of American Atheist Magazine and a
longtime O'Hair associate, said a fairly sizable minority of
atheists thought that the family had stolen the money. MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
