<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Sunday,
April 18. If you have any questions, please call Patricia Hardin or
Miranda Kennedy on the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
HEART PUMPS (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) Doctors say the pumps have the
potential to save the lives of thousands of people with failing
hearts who don't qualify medically for a heart transplant or who
couldn't survive the often lengthy wait for a new heart. Bill
Yardley, 57, received a heart transplant April 14 at St. Luke's
Hospital, becoming the first patient to go from an internal
heart-assist pump to a heart transplant at a Kansas City, Mo.,
hospital. By ALAN BAVLEY. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
KOSOVO CYBERWAR (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) Some people are calling the
Kosovo conflict the first ``cyberwar.'' Computer keyboards and
phone lines everywhere make up the arsenal. These are times when
Americans can learn a lot about war by just logging on. It makes
many experts nervous. By RICK MONTGOMERY. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
3CAR GARAGE (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) Nationwide, an increasing number of
homes are being built with three-car garages, and the Kansas City,
Mo., area is outpacing the trend. By TOM PERRIN. Story will move in
the ``a'' category.
CLOWN FESTIVAL (HOUSTON, Mo.) The hometown of ``Weary Willie'' will
continue with its 12th annual Emmett Kelly Festival to honor the
man who created the sad-faced clown, despite a recent fire that
destroyed five businesses. By JIM FISHER. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
KRASKE COLUMN (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) Politics in Kansas and the nation.
By STEVE KRASKE. Story will move in the ``k'' category.
GUSEWELLE COLUMN (NAPLES, Fla.) Kansas City Star columnist C.W.
Gusewelle takes a step back a bit to just one column a week,
instead of three. By C.W. GUSEWELLE. Story will move in the ``k''
category.
BOXCAR FUNERAL (BRANSON, Mo.) Boxcar Willie, whose real name was
Lecil Martin, died Monday at 67 after a three-year bout with
leukemia. Friends and fans say Boxcar Willie was a Branson pioneer,
creating a model for living and performing in this live-music
center. By OSCAR AVILA. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
