<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2761 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-PUMPS-2TAKES-KA     04-17 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-PUMPS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART-ASSIST PUMPS BRING HOPE TO THOSE NEEDING HEART TRANSPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Bill Yardley emerged from coronary artery
bypass surgery last month changed in ways he could never have
imagined. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His belly was stuffed tight with machinery. A power cord emerged
from an incision in his side. And a rhythmic, whooshing sound like
windshield wipers radiated from his body. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When he woke up, he said, `What in the world did they do to
me?' '' recalled his wife, Joyce. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yardley's surgery had failed. But the Kearney, Mo., man was
saved on the operating table by a 2 1/2-pound pump that surgeons
implanted below his ribs. The pump was designed to work in tandem
with his flagging heart until a new heart could be found for a
transplant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yardley, 57, received a heart transplant April 14 at St. Luke's
Hospital, becoming the first patient to go from an internal
heart-assist pump to a heart transplant at a Kansas City, Mo.,
hospital. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amazing journeys from near death to technological rescue, much
like Yardley's, are being played out with growing frequency around
the country as doctors use assist pumps to keep patients alive
until hearts for transplants become available. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say the pumps have the potential to save the lives of
thousands of people with failing hearts who don't qualify medically
for a heart transplant or who couldn't survive the often lengthy
wait for a new heart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 patients in the United States have received the two
most common assist pumps, the HeartMate that Yardley received, and
the similar Novacor. Roughly 70 percent of them have received
successful heart transplants. Smaller, quieter pumps are being
developed experimentally. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some pumps, like the HeartMate, are implanted entirely within
the body, except for an air vent and a power cord that attaches to
a bedside power supply. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pumps also can be used with rechargeable batteries, allowing
patients to return home from the hospital, drive, shop, or even
ride a bicycle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The technology is advancing so rapidly that doctors expect pumps
to be implanted permanently in patients as an alternative to heart
transplants within a few years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This device will be a dinosaur,'' predicted St. Luke's heart
transplant surgeon Greg Muehlebach. ``We'll be looking back and
laughing at putting a temporary device in people.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heart disease runs in Bill Yardley's family. His mother died of
a heart attack. Two brothers have had bypass surgery. His sisters
have high cholesterol. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At age 40, what he thought was a bad bout of indigestion turned
out to be a heart attack. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove myself to the hospital and smoked my last cigarette,''
said Yardley, a retired Hallmark maintenance technician. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About three years ago, Yardley had a stiff back. He assumed his
muscles were sore from working on a friend's car the day before,
but his wife thought differently. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kind of knew he was having another one (heart attack).
He wouldn't go. I had to beg him,'' Joyce Yardley said. She drove
him to the emergency room. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The damage to Yardley's heart was so severe, doctors put him on
the transplant waiting list. It was a poignant moment. The
Yardleys' 20-year-old son, Craig, died in an auto accident in 1986.
They donated his heart and other organs for transplant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With his doctor's approval, Yardley went off the transplant list
after six months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I didn't like was being tethered, having to stay too
close (to the hospital),'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Yardley's condition deteriorated. Short of breath after
climbing a small hill, he went to St. Luke's for an evaluation.
Doctors decided to try quadruple-bypass surgery as a last-shot
alternative to a heart transplant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They would never have attempted the risky operation, Muehlebach
said, if the assist pump hadn't been available. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew if (surgery) failed we had this device as a backup,''
he said. ``It would be foolish to have taken a patient like this to
the operating room without it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The HeartMate is about the size and shape of a hair dryer. Its
job is to take over the pumping action of the left side of the
heart, the side most likely to fail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Through a tube that enters a heart pumping chamber called the
left ventricle, the HeartMate draws blood out and propels it into
the aorta, the main artery supplying oxygenated blood to the body. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the pump operates, the right side of the heart pumps
independently. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As with other medical devices, the pumps aren't risk-free.
Infection is always a possibility. Doctors say that early
HeartMates were prone to mechanical breakdown and that patients
with early Novacor pumps frequently developed blood clots that
could lead to stroke. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Hosenpud, a researcher with Medical College of
Wisconsin, found that patients who had been on assist pumps were
twice as likely to die within a year of receiving a transplant as
were other heart recipients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hosenpud thinks the survival rates have been improving. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten smarter and the devices have gotten better,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, patients were rushed from assist pumps to heart
transplants as quickly as possible. That's no longer the case. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We know now it's better to keep the patient on the device a
month or two before going to a transplant. It gets them in better
shape,'' Hosenpud said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, patients have recovered so markedly that they can
be weaned off the device without a transplant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``These pumps restored them to good health,'' said O.H. Frazier,
a transplant surgeon at the Texas Heart Institute in Houston, who
has seen three patients with the pumps, known as left ventricular
assist devices, become well enough to get off the heart transplant
list. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - MORE -
</P>
<P>
   Despite their ability to save lives, the assist devices have the
potential to create serious ethical issues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some insurance plans cover the devices, but the pumps are
expensive. The HeartMate, for example, costs about $50,000 and
can't be reused on another patient. Its implantation requires a
highly trained team of surgeons, cardiologists and nurses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although St. Luke's cares for many uninsured heart surgery
patients, Muehlebach wasn't certain whether these patients would be
offered HeartMates except in life-threatening emergencies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point in time we may say yes,'' he said. ``But the
main thing early on, we have to make this (the program) financially
viable for it to work.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each patient receiving the device adds to the number of people
on the waiting list for heart transplants. But the number of hearts
available for transplant is not increasing appreciably. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember you're taking that heart from someone
else'' by giving it to someone with the device, Hosenpud said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The longer waiting times for heart transplants have helped
demonstrate how durable the devices can be. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two American patients who have been hard to match to a donor
heart have been living with Novacor pumps for more than two years.
In Europe, two patients have been on the pumps for more than three
years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At several medical centers, studies are under way to see if
patients can be given the devices indefinitely, as an alternative
to heart transplantation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the question, `Are we creating more patients for heart
transplant?' isn't an issue anymore,'' said University of
Pittsburgh Medical Center surgeon Robert Kormos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kormos foresees the assist devices being used as a first, rather
than last, resort for people with failing hearts: ``Put it in, live
with it, and then down the road give the patient a transplant.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the March 9 surgery that gave him the HeartMate, Yardley
spent five weeks at St. Luke's Hospital, growing stronger. With his
pump hooked to a pair of batteries he wore in a fanny pack, he
started taking regular walks with his wife. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most annoying problem was the inescapable whoosh of the
machine that kept him awake at night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was lying down, it sounded like it was echoing behind
me,'' he said. ``I never did become accustomed to it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His doctors were concerned about a bowel obstruction caused by
the pump wedged inside him. On April 13, doctors moved Yardley to
priority status on the transplant list. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Around noon, as the Yardleys were walking through the hospital
corridors, transplant coordinator Nancy Long gave them that news. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stunned and overjoyed, Joyce Yardley engulfed every nurse she
could reach with a bear hug. Tears filled her eyes. She grabbed her
husband. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord is good, isn't he, honey?'' she said. She was
smiling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Yardley now at the top of the transplant list, the couple
wanted to know how long he was likely to wait for a new heart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked and asked (doctors and nurses),'' he said. ``One said
days. One said weeks. One said months.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About four hours after Yardley learned that he had been bumped
to the top of the waiting list, Long made a return visit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you planning to do tonight?'' she asked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Same thing I always do. Nothing,'' he replied. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have something more for you to do,'' she told him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By 9 p.m., Yardley was in the operating room. Five hours later,
he had a new heart beating in his chest. The HeartMate was gone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How have things changed? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yardley answered April 15 from his bed in the intensive-care
unit: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quiet. And I can sleep.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
