</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CYBERWAR-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CYBERWAR' PRODUCING UNPRECEDENTED FLOW OF INFORMATION _ GOOD AND
BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With democracy comes the right to choose whom to believe. On the
wide-open Web, that's not always a good thing, some say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web does a lot of things well, but covering a war is not
one of them,'' said John Katz, online columnist for the Freedom
Forum. ``Anyone who spends any time surfing knows how easy it is to
get bad information and how quickly it travels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see who's issuing a report. I want to know they're
accountable for that report, especially in wartime. The stakes are
way too high. If a story hits the Internet that someone's been
assassinated or troops are moving across the border, you'd better
have it right.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   War on the Web is nothing if not a study in conflicting stories.
Consider the reports available on various Web pages April 14, when
a NATO pilot mistakenly bombed a convoy of ethnic Albanian refugees
heading out of Kosovo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosova Refugees Say Serbs Attacked Convoy,'' declared a
headline, using the Albanian spelling of Kosovo. It was put out by
the Kosova Crisis Center at www.alb-net.com, sponsored by a human
rights group sympathetic to the plight of ethnic Albanians.
``Bodies Lie on Kosova Road; As Usual Serbs Blame NATO.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Serb-controlled Radio Yugoslavia's Web site at
www.beograd.com/radioyu did blame NATO, this way: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Several groups of Albanians who, after being assured by state
bodies of Serbia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia that they
would be safe in their homes, were returning from the border
crossings (when) NATO planes acted a number of times, veritably
massacring the refugees. ... The aggressors obviously knew well who
was at issue, since civilian vehicles could in no way be `mistaken'
for military ones.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The United States Information Agency at www.usia.gov weighed in
April 14 with its own report, which quoted a Pentagon spokesman as
saying, ``We're quite sure that we only hit military vehicles.''
The next day NATO spokesman Jamie Shea acknowledged that the pilot
made a mistake. The lead vehicle, Shea said, ``we now believe (was)
a civilian vehicle.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Misinformation _ by intent or by mistake _ has long gone with
the turbulent territory of war, experts point out. But the dangers
become more acute in a medium as instant and unmonitored as the
Internet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dangerous situation when you have so many people
asking, `Whom do we trust?' and searching out information wherever
they can find it,'' said social psychologist Pratkanis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Internet, you also have the option of using
direct-response tactics. Some of these special-interest sites have
links that allow you to e-mail President Clinton. That's one way of
committing you to their team.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many observers doubt that propaganda on the Web has affected
American attitudes about Kosovo. Opinion polls have been relatively
steady since NATO launched its campaign. Katz noted, ``The Web is
still being used for e-trading stocks and buying books more than
anything else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if the fighting escalates to all-out war, U.S. authorities
probably will look to the Web in their quest to control
information, said Gregory Black, who teaches history and
communications at the University of Missouri-Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to communicate with the enemy in a state of war _
that's a problem,'' said Black, co-author of ``Hollywood Goes to
War: How Politics, Profits and Propaganda Shaped World War II
Movies.'' ``This ability of any of us to log on to Serbian Web
sites is unprecedented. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``How would democracies deal with that in a total war? When all
you need is a modem and a phone line _ how does (a government)
knock that out?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government is trying, as a visit to www.b92.net
will confirm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The independent voice of Radio B-92, a station in Belgrade, was
silenced on April 2 after building a reputation for attacking the
policies of President Slobodan Milosevic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Its Web site, however, is still accessible. Though it no longer
reports the news in English, the site does bear a defiant message
aimed at the Yugoslav government. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Struggle Continues. We Shall Never Surrender.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sasa Mirkovic, the station director who wrote it, has been
replaced by a Milosevic minion. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
