<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CYBERWAR-2TAKE     04-17 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CYBERWAR-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CYBERWAR' PRODUCING UNPRECEDENTED FLOW OF INFORMATION _ GOOD AND
BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people are calling the Kosovo conflict the first
``cyberwar.'' Computer keyboards and phone lines everywhere make up
the arsenal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Help us stop bombing of Yugoslavia!'' urges the home page of
the Serbian Unity Congress, at www.suc.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Or call up www.alb-net.com and click through photographs of
ethnic Albanians shot dead by the Serb ``monsters.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These are times when Americans can learn a lot about war by just
logging on. It makes many experts nervous. After all, never before
have average people had such instant access to information spread
by groups representing all angles of a conflict. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The war strategists should be worried about it, if they aren't
yet,'' said Anthony Pratkanis, professor of psychology at the
University of California, Santa Cruz, and author of ``Age of
Propaganda: The Everyday Use and Abuse of Persuasion.'' ``What
you're seeing now is just the first round of what will become an
important, highly sophisticated tool in the age-old tradition of
wartime propaganda. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The look, feel and persuasiveness of these Web sites _ all
these will develop into something slicker and more subtle.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Browsers can pick their propaganda: www.albanian.com presents
one side of the argument; www.kosovo.net presents another side. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Someone who goes by ``Big Steve'' prefers the chat room at
www.NATO.org _ which has nothing to do with the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization. On this privately owned Web site, Big Steve
and Internet surfers from all parts of the world gather to discuss
_ and cuss _ the war. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Go Home Stupid Repulsive Americans,'' wrote a woman from
Athens, Greece. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other dispatches from the cyberwar are sadly compelling, such as
this e-mail sent April 7 by an unknown woman in Yugoslavia: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Bombing day fifteen. Today in the tram in Belgrade I saw a
woman with the button: Clinton's face with Hitler's moustache ...
. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People are leaving Belgrade slowly, 5 buses a day go to
Budapest. Four of our friends have already gone. One wonders if
democracy can be installed with bombs and fear? Fear is the best
emotion to control the mind ... fear of crossing bridges, fear of
sirens, fear of every sound, evening, fire in the night sky.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One problem, observers say, is that it's anyone's guess whether
her e-mail is legitimate or the lies of a Serb official hoping to
bend American opinion. Human rights groups that disseminate such
material tend to keep the authors anonymous, ostensibly to keep
them safe from reprisals in their homeland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tactical maneuvers on the Web already have distinguished the
Kosovo conflict from wars of the past. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last month, just as the bombings commenced, Belgrade hackers
temporarily disabled NATO's main Web site by clogging it with more
empty messages than it could handle. And all around the globe,
pro-Serbian groups reportedly have dumped unsolicited mail _
``spam,'' in Web jargon _ into the in-boxes of more than 10,000
Internet users. The Wall Street Journal recently dubbed this
offensive ``Yugospam.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Web enthusiasts such as Shari Steele say, the
Internet also has provided a vital outlet for persecuted Kosovars
and journalists looking to communicate to the free world from a
region policed by Yugoslav censors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, Microsoft Corp.'s online magazine Slate offers
``Secret Dispatches from Belgrade.'' An anonymous correspondent
reports daily on alleged Serb atrocities as well as the civilian
suffering inflicted by NATO bombs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful thing to have all this information and raw
data available to people interested in knowing what's really going
on,'' said Steele, director of legal services for the Electronic
Frontier Foundation. ``That's the essence of democracy.'' &QL; 
- MORE -
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
