r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-3CAR-GARAGE-KAN &LR;      04-17 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3CAR-GARAGE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE-CAR GARAGES AREN'T JUST FOR EASY STREET ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM PERRIN  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It's been nearly three years since the Miller
family parked two vehicles in the two-car garage attached to their
house in south Overland Park, Kan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since then, John Miller's pickup truck has been crowded out by
the pile of toys that sits in the middle of the garage, which is
also used to store bicycles, lawn equipment and freezer. The only
room left is for Stephanie Miller's minivan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the space crunch is about to end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Millers are building a house with a three-car garage just a
few blocks away in the same subdivision, Hampton Place. They hope
to move in by August. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband would always say how it would be nice to have a
three-car garage, and I said no,'' Stephanie Miller said. ``But to
me, now a three-car garage is more practical.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, an increasing number of homes are being built with
three-car garages, and the Kansas City, Mo., area is outpacing the
trend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Kansas City six months ago, and every home I saw had
a three-car garage,'' said Gopal Ahluwalia, director of research
for the National Association of Home Builders. ``And I'm talking
about average homes.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once a luxury for the wealthy, three-car garages have become an
option in the Kansas City area in new homes priced at $150,000 and
lower. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They see it as a necessity, not a luxury,'' said Bonni Spence,
a community manager for the Crystal Park subdivision in Shawnee,
Kan. ``It's a mind-set.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, according to statistics from the National Association
of Home Builders, 16 percent of new homes in the United States were
built with a three-car or larger garage. That's up from 10 percent
at the start of the decade, but it pales in comparison with the
latest figures from the Kansas City area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sams, Kansas City supervisor of residential plan review,
estimates that 40 percent to 50 percent of the 1,200-plus
single-family building permits Kansas City, Mo., issued last year
included a three-car garage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Overland Park, city figures show that 58 percent of the
nearly 1,300 permits the city issued last year included garages
built for three or more cars. That's up from 36 percent in 1994. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Lee's Summit, Mo., 54 percent of the 994 single-family home
permits issued since the beginning of 1998 included three-car or
larger garages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blue Springs, Mo., builder Tom Woods' two companies have
constructed three-car garages on houses priced in the $120,000
range and seen other builders do the same on $90,000 homes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Kansas City area, Ahluwalia said, three-car garages
are most popular in California, Oregon, Texas and Washington state.
West Coast soil isn't good for digging basements, he said, so
larger garages provide storage space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City and Texas, larger lots make the bigger garages
possible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what else is fueling the trend? Three-car families and large
sport-utility vehicles are only part of the answer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of hiring out a storage unit someplace, they're adding
another garage to put their kids' toys and bikes,'' said
residential architect Bruce Beatty, owner of Team 3 Architects in
Leawood, Kan. ``They don't use them for cars. The third bay is just
for stuff.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And ``stuff'' can mean anything from a riding mower to sports
equipment to boxes of old clothing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than three people with three cars, it's two people with
two cars and a boat or motorcycle,'' said Larry Galbreath, whose
company builds patio homes, or villas, in Olathe, Kan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until recent years, few people had any interest in putting
three-car garages on patio homes, which are built on narrower lots
with less lawn. Now, he said, about 40 percent of buyers want
them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Mike and Jean DeFabis moved from a patio home with a
two-car garage to a new one across the street with a three-car
garage. Now there's plenty of room for their two sport-utility
vehicles, a new Jaguar and storage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we ever move again, even if we don't have three cars, we'll
still have a three-car garage,'' Mike DeFabis said. ``It's
inexpensive space. ... It's not like adding living space. It's just
handier to keep stuff.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A three-car garage typically costs $7,500 to $10,000 more than a
two-car garage. Even if people say they prefer a two-car garage on
their new home, real estate agents are recommending the three-car
option to enhance resale value. More homes built on a speculative
basis are being equipped with three-car garages, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond five years ago, three-car was a nice thing and made it
sell quicker, but it wasn't a factor,'' said Darrel Hunter, project
manager for Hampton Place. ``Today, I think it is.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Backyard sheds are a common remedy for storage problems in older
neighborhoods, but many newer developments don't allow them. Many
developments also prohibit parking on the street, and a few even
have rules against parking on the driveway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That leaves a three-car garage as the only option for some
people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, what three-car garage owners gain in space, they often
lose in aesthetics, ending up with a place that looks like a garage
with an attached house, rather than the other way around. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you end up with too much garage, you don't have as much
curb appeal,'' said Ora Reynolds, general manager of residential
development with Hunt Midwest, which is developing in suburbs north
of Kansas City, Mo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Larger homes built on larger lots can hide three-car garages
with side entry, an option not available on smaller lots. To keep
the garage from being a dominant feature, architects often set one
bay back from the two others. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As a designer, the big trick is to make it not look like a
garage, so we work hard on that,'' Beatty said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another option is the tandem garage, with one regular bay and
one extra-deep bay long enough to hold two cars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County, Kan., developer Darol Rodrock said some of his
customers were omitting formal living or dining rooms so they would
have room for three-car garages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The extra storage area is that big an issue to some people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just easier to have more space,'' Stephanie Miller said.
``It's just neater and cleaner.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
