<HEADER>
A2886 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLOWN-FESTIVAL-KAN &LR;      04-17 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOWN-FESTIVAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN FAMED SON `WEARY WILLIE' WOULD SMILE AT THE WAY TOWN HAS
ENDURED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON, Mo. _ A recent fire here not surprisingly caused some
people to recall one of history's most famous news photographs: A
shot of the 1944 Hartford, Conn., circus fire that killed 168
persons, many of them children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the background the big top burns; in the foreground a running
clown vainly carries a bucket of water. It was sad-faced ``Weary
Willie,'' the nom de plume of the most famous clown of them all:
Emmett Kelly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now why would people hereabouts recall that, especially since
the fire in this town of 2,500 people April 5 was a nightmare that
destroyed five businesses and damaged two others. Still-standing
and blackened walls make Grand and Pine streets look like they'd
been bombed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, for starters, Houston is Emmett Kelly's hometown. And of a
more pressing matter, ``bring in the clowns'' is taken literally
here. The most destructive fire here in 50 years happened less than
a month before hundreds of people decked out in big shoes, baggy
pants, bulbous red noses and greasepaint were scheduled to descend
on Houston. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first weekend in May _ meaning April 30 to May 2 _ this seat
of Texas County becomes a clown mecca with its Emmett Kelly
Festival, an annual event now in its 12th year of honoring
Houston's most famous son. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The festival will still be held downtown, said Mark Forbes, a
druggist with the organizing committee who's been fielding calls
from concerned clowns and clown lovers from all over the Middle
West. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 6,000 people should show up, he said, including hundreds
and hundreds of people who love clowning to the point of wearing
clown outfits, painting their faces, taking pratfalls and doing
what clowns do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have it cleaned up,'' he said. ``But this year will be
better than ever. Emmett wouldn't have let something like this stop
him. Neither will we.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, born in Sedan, Kan., but raised from the age of 6 on a
hardscrabble farm near here, became America's most famous clown
with his woeful, joyless face; tattered outfit; and his cachet act:
trying to sweep away the spotlight with his broom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As ``Weary Willie,'' the one clown under the big top who didn't
paint a smile on his face, Kelly spent years with the Ringling
Brothers and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus, appeared in movies that
included ``The Greatest Show on Earth,'' did stints on television
and in nightclubs, and made commercials for Coca-Cola and Kodak.
Kelly died in 1979, at age 80. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hoses, not buckets as in the Connecticut circus blaze, were used
on the Houston fire, which destroyed a video store, restaurant,
gift shop, realty company and the Houston area Chamber of Commerce
office. An electrical defect has tentatively been listed as the
cause. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early reports said a large amount of Kelly's clown memorabilia,
stored in the chamber office, had been lost. Forbes, however, said
the Kelly holdings, thus the losses, were minimal _ mainly
autographed photographs, old newspapers and some commercially
available Weary Willie dolls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky,'' Forbes said. ``We'd been negotiating with
Emmett's widow, Evie Kelly Lentz, about borrowing some of his stuff
to put on display. But that had been on the back burner. So we
didn't have anything real valuable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Forbes added, the lack of mementos shows how the
festival here has evolved over its dozen years. Rather than have a
static display of items from Kelly's career, the focus has shifted
to attracting people who love clowning; conducting clown schools
and seminars led by visiting, professional clowns; holding parades
and kid circuses; and letting those attending be what they love _
clowns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Come down here for the festival,'' said Forbes. ``There'll be
clowns all over.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, not everyone here has always had the name Emmett Kelly on
his or her lips despite the fact Kelly was a local boy who had
traveled the world, met all sorts of famous people, and whose
countenance was known to millions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard of him until they started this festival,'' said
Willard Davis, 84. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don Watson, 87, knew the Kellys, who farmed four miles east of
here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't about to be a farmer, not down here with all these
rocks,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The memory here is that Kelly took off for Kansas City, Mo., to
be a cartoonist and worked at the same company as a fellow from
Marceline, Mo., named Walt Disney. It was there that he sketched
the first likeness of the sad-faced clown that was to become his
trademark. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's first professional performance was here at the Old
Settler's Reunion in the 1920s, where he performed what was called
a ``chalk talk,'' writing somebody's name on a blackboard in
script, then adding to and filling in those lines until what
emerged was a landscape or a mountain scene or some other picture
that would fairly dazzle the audience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he became a trapeze artist,'' said Bob Davis, whose
father knew Kelly well. ``In the circus in those days lots of
performers did double duty. So Emmett was also a clown.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Weary Willie motif was perfect for the time _ the 1930s and
the Depression. Kelly was every man, every hobo, every working
stiff down on his luck. Plus, said Kathryn O'Dell of the
International Clown Hall of Fame in Milwaukee, Kelly knew the value
of promotion. Weary Willie was an odd duck in the world of
clowning, O'Dell said, and Kelly played his character for all it
was worth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kelly never forgot his roots, coming back to Houston
several times over the years, wearing his clown outfit, posing with
local kids, and pleased as punch when a local park was named after
him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said there was already talk of clearing the burned-out
area and turning it into a park where the festival can become
bigger and better. Next year's show, he said, will be dubbed EK2K
or Emmett Kelly 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This town has taken some hard knocks over the past few
years,'' he said. ``We lost our shoe company and that was 450 jobs.
We're losing our blue-jean plant and that's 300 more. The only
thing on the horizon is the new maximum-security prison (South
Central Correctional facility, with 1,596 beds and 400 jobs) up at
Licking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``So the festival helps. We know one thing _ clowns will never
go out of style. They bring people in, and that's what we need.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
