<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KRASKE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIZABETH DOLE TURNS ON THE TOUGH TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suddenly, Elizabeth Dole is talking tough. Listen to what she
said last week: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a war; we must win it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing needs to be escalated.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If indeed ground troops are needed ... so be it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's gotten into Dole, who has developed a well-earned
reputation for avoiding tough stands? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, Dole's burgeoning campaign for the White House already
is in trouble precisely because she's perceived as mushy on the
issues. And that could prove devastating for a candidate who's
never held public office before. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So last week, Dole set out to prove her mettle in the
foreign-policy arena and earn another look from campaign donors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's what took her to the U.S. Naval Academy, where she
delivered an address titled ``Hawkish World View.'' And that's what
took her on a well-publicized trip to the Balkans, where she was
seen posing with refugees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dole already is far behind Texas Gov. George W. Bush in the
all-important money battle. According to reports last week, Bush
had $6.8 million on hand, while Dole had only a fraction of that _
just $578,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dole is hardly alone among GOP candidates who trail Bush by
millions of dollars. But she knows she's got to find ways to close
that gap or the race will be declared over by the Fourth of July. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking on the tough issues is the way for her to do that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former pro jocks are weighing in for Democrat Bill Bradley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those same campaign reports last week showed that former New
York Knicks players Willis Reed, Dave DeBusschere and Phil Jackson
had given to their former teammate. So has Michael Jordan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's chief competitor, Vice President Al Gore, had the
Hollywood crowd, with actors Kate Capshaw, Richard Dreyfuss, Kevin
Costner and Michael Douglas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Topeka, Kan., the buzz is that Gov. Bill Graves is
squandering his political capital. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The man who was elected with a record 73 percent of the vote in
November can brag of few accomplishments this session. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Graves' problems begin with a Legislature that's vastly
different from any he faced in his first term. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who until this year displayed an abnormal fealty to
Graves, suddenly look like tough guys. Instead of cooperating,
they're angling, scheming, seeking political advantage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republicans, who suffered serious setbacks in last
year's elections, are pushing their agenda as if they still run the
world. They're teaming up with Democrats to forge a working
majority in the House that's left Graves and his fellow moderates
on the sidelines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Graves has become just another governor with the
daunting task of overseeing a three-party, coalition-style
government of Democrats, conservative Republicans and moderate
Republicans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a mess. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Can Graves get on top of this situation or will he be consumed
by it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We'll find out in the veto session beginning April 28. If Graves
manages to get a major highway bill passed this year, you can
conclude that the governor can still get it done. A lot of
lawmakers agree that the session's fate rests on that one issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the governor falls short, the conclusion will be that Graves
has been seriously marginalized. Record re-election or not. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And if that happens, the governor will have to take a hard look
at his laid-back approach. The times may demand a firmer,
grab-'em-by-the-collar style that the governor finds so
distasteful. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking a look: Kansas City (Mo.) Councilwoman Teresa Loar, a
Republican, is considering a run for Congress next year against
Democrat Pat Danner. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
