r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      04-17 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RIGHT TIME TO STEP BACK A BIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ Out of the darkness the tireless waves wash in,
phosphorescing as they curl and expire on the sand. The tide is
rising, and the water's whisper tells of morning soon to come. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's one figure on the beach, barely visible. It's a woman
alone, in a folding chair, facing outward to the gulf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sky starts to lighten. A chirruping of birds begins. The
last star goes out, and the ghost-pale moon rides low. Somewhere
voices can be heard, and a rustle of laughter. It is a curious hour
for laughing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A jogger goes past, leaving the print of his bare feet to be
taken by the incoming sea. And after him, three pelicans gliding in
low formation a dozen yards offshore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then a squad of sandpipers comes patrolling at the edge of the
foam, with one strutting gull among them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is full light, now. And the woman in the folding beach chair
still has not moved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what she is thinking. Maybe this is the end of her stay
in a place she has loved, and she has come out early to watch the
day begin. If so, she must be thinking of the amazing quickness of
time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's a consideration that, beyond a certain point in life,
occupies us all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago this week, with my wife and our two daughters,
who were little children then, I had just returned from a sojourn
on an island an hour north from here along the coast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I sat down, then, to write the first of these columns that have
been my labor and my devotion for nearly half my career as a
journalist. The sounds and smells of the salt shore still were with
me, and it occurred that the work to which I'd set myself was a
good deal like beachcombing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The column, I said, would have no agenda, no ax to grind. Like
any beachcomber, I meant to take whatever came to hand. My only
plan was to examine, with curious eye and honest heart, some of the
commonplaces and oddities cast up on the beaches of all our years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the good days, that's what these pieces have been about: the
joys and cares and devotions we all know, that light our lives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The managing editor of the paper then was Mike Waller, gone on
now to be publisher of The Baltimore Sun. I promised Mike I would
write the column for two years. Instead it has been 20 _ three
columns a week, some 2,600 in all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has governed my life and my thoughts more completely than
ever I imagined work could. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were days when I thought another piece would never come.
And other stretches of weeks, sometimes, when the writing was so
easy it seemed almost like stealing. At its best, it has been like
an extended conversation with more friends than anyone could
reasonably hope to have. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there are new places in this world I yet mean to see, and
ones I've loved that I intend to see again. And other writing to
do. And bird dogs to follow, with a new pup coming. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To stop writing the column entirely would be, for me,
unimaginable. It is the right time, though, to step back just a
bit. So beginning today, these essays will appear once a week, on
Sundays, in this same section of the paper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What I said 20 years ago was: Let's go down where the sandpipers
run, and see what we find there and what, if anything, can be made
of it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, we'll still be working that same stretch of shore together
_ just a bit less often. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
