<DOCNO> NYT19990417.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-17 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2923 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOXCAR-FUNERAL-KAN &LR;      04-17 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOXCAR-FUNERAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXCAR WILLIE REMEMBERED AS A PERFORMER FOR THE COMMON PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRANSON, Mo. _ For every show, Boxcar Willie would dust off his
worn overalls and sing train songs such as ``Wabash Cannonball''
for the umpteenth time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Radio stations didn't play his music. He didn't make videos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But friends and fans say Boxcar Willie was a Branson pioneer,
creating a model for living and performing in this live-music
center. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was the first big-name outside entertainer to live in Branson
year-round. He was the first outside performer to own his theater.
And he encouraged others to follow his example. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 900 packed his theater again Saturday for the country
legend's funeral. Boxcar Willie, whose real name was Lecil Martin,
died Monday at 67 after a three-year bout with leukemia. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even as he clung to his overalls during his 12-year run, Branson
reached for the glitz: opening an IMAX theater, welcoming Donald
Trump's Miss USA pageant and building a modern airport for
corporate customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Branson changed, Boxcar Willie went from an outsider with new
ideas to a charming anachronism who fit right in. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And if there's any doubt whether Branson's heart lies with the
Boxcar Willies or the Trumps of the world, remember this: The
world's most famous hobo is the only Branson performer to have a
street here named for him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a friend to everybody,'' said Mayor Lou Schaefer, who
had delivered a tearful tribute at a city meeting Monday. ``He
didn't act like an entertainer. He treated people like a neighbor
would.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boxcar Willie opened in Branson in 1987 on the heels of
worldwide success. Since developing his hobo persona, he had
performed for sold-out crowds and had been inducted into the Grand
Ole Opry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Branson was still small-time. The town ``was a few theaters and
some go-kart tracks,'' recalled Larry Martin, Boxcar Willie's son.
A few local entertainers, and the occasional big name, such as Roy
Clark, performed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin said some questioned Boxcar Willie's motives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What they didn't realize was that he was as much a vagabond as
the hobos in his sorrowful train songs. He played almost 300 dates
a year after hitting it big in the 1970s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Branson, with its sprawling countryside, reminded Boxcar Willie
of the rural Texas of his youth. Right away, he immersed himself in
the community. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Taney County Child Welfare Board, raising
thousands of dollars for needy children. While other entertainers
would say they were too tired to attend charity events, Boxcar
Willie never said no, Schaefer said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He once brought a microphone and a speaker to a Highway
Department meeting to protest a proposed highway bypass. He was
ejected after arguing with transportation officials. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boxcar Willie criticized performers who worked in Branson in the
summer but had little use for the community the rest of the year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If they made a livelihood out of Branson, he thought they
should give back,'' Martin said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the mourners Saturday, such as Jim Stafford, Yakov
Smirnoff and Andy Williams, had followed Boxcar Willie's example
and had moved to Branson. They shared warm memories of the singer
and watched video clips of songs such as ``I've Seen It All From a
Boxcar Door'' that highlighted the 45-minute service. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The same entertainers had helped usher in a growth in
entertainment that Boxcar Willie welcomed as a way to bring jobs
and expand audiences. By 1993, the town boasted more than two dozen
theaters and 5.6 million tourists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the audiences grew, so did the theaters. Some became posh
venues with opulent lobbies, thousands of seats and special
effects. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boxcar Willie tried to relate to his fans. He remembered some
names even years between visits. Tom and Esther Rice of
Reynoldsburg, Ohio, were proud when he displayed one of their
letters in his theater lobby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He always made his fans feel special,'' Esther Rice said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Branson grew, other acts became more Hollywood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shows added shapely dancers in sequined costumes. Other singers,
such as Wayne Newton, dripped with Vegas smoothness. The soap-opera
star who was host of the Miss USA pageant laced the show with
double-entendres. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fans sitting in one of the 900 faded blue seats in the Boxcar
Willie Theater would see Boxcar Willie and his guitar. That was
enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One colleague remembered Boxcar Willie humbly telling fans: ``I
don't have any smoke machine or fireworks, but here are the fire
exits anyway.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Above the theater entrance, the straight-laced singer hung a
sign: ``Obscene and Profane Shirts, Hats, Etc. Prohibited.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I use the word `integrity' because he stayed true to his
music. He didn't try to change with the style,'' said Sheila
Dutton, whose family is performing at Boxcar Willie's theater this
season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The son of a railroad man never had a hit single, but audiences
kept coming back. Martin confided that his father sometimes felt
confined by the hobo image. Sometimes, he wished he could take to
the stage in a nice suit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what the fans wanted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So Boxcar Willie kept singing the train songs that hearkened
back to Branson's own humble beginnings and forged a bond with
longtime residents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dick Siegrist, a retired farmer from Shell Knob, Mo., drove 30
miles Wednesday afternoon to pay tribute to one of his favorite
singers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of favorites: Shoji, the Welks. But there was
something different about Box,'' Siegrist said, standing below the
theater marquee. ``I could relate to him. He seemed like one of
us.'' &QL; 
Boxcar Willie
</P>
<P>
   Real name: Lecil Martin &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Born: 1931 in Sterrett, Texas &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Background: After 22 years in the Air Force, Boxcar Willie
created his hobo persona in the 1970s. In 1981, he became the 60th
member of the Grand Ole Opry. He had 15 gold albums and four
platinum albums in a decade. He moved to Branson, Mo., in 1987,
where he built a theater, a railroad museum and two motels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paying respects: The family suggests memorials to the American
Cancer Society c/o Greenlawn Funeral Home, Branson, Mo. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-17-99 2222EDT &QL; 
