<HEADLINE>
FOR LAKERS: ENOUGH IS ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Dennis Rodman still wants another ring, he'll have to grow a
third nipple.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count him out.
</P>
<P>
   But only time will tell if Friday's cut can become a Laker title
waive, so all we can do is chase this odyssey all the way back to
Thursday's fateful practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers didn't know where the voice was coming from, but it
mouthed the following alibi for ``Shoeless'' Dennis'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Just schedule it, and he will come ... eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   The response:
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice of a sportswriter taking cuts in the buffet line? No,
try rookie Lakers coach Kurt Rambis, who shamelessly was shoved
into the predicament of dealing with The Worm and ``No-Show Time.''
</P>
<P>
   This last straw (or was it a swizzle stick?) was Rodman's tardy,
barefoot arrival for Thursday's workout. It was preceded by similar
practice sins, playing-time pouting, alleged elbow gloom and that
Electra-fying trip to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling problem? That would belong to Lakers owner Jerry Buss,
the misguided advocate of a player whose subsequent behavior
demonstrated a grotesque lack of respect for his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   And when the cuttin' was done, Rodman accused his suddenly
ex-teammates of not knowing how to win. He's right. But Rodman was
a dandy example. Oh, Dennis certainly knows how to win - attach
himself to a team with great players, stay in shape by maintaining
a 2-to-1 Stair-Master/tavern ratio, and selfishly avoid the
vagaries of team defense for the sake of rebounding stats.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, he joined a crowd with skewed priorities. The
posturing Lakers don't need to hire Shoeless Dennis for lessons on
how to play with passion.
</P>
<P>
   They can study the frequently overmatched Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   So ... what happens to Rodman? Well, several Laker big shots
accused him of being a genius, and that assessment could be on the
money. Sure, Rodman is about to lose a Carl's Jr. spot that shows
almost as much bun as he offered on the cover of his book.
</P>
<P>
   But this Laker banishment could render him even more notorious
... and marketable. Rodman will land on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Shoes, again, will be optional.
</P>
<P>
   A DESERT FLOWER
</P>
<P>
   Early returns from the Desert Classic pre-draft camp in Tempe
reveal that several talent watchdogs are campaigning for Xavier
small forward James Posey.
</P>
<P>
   Posey goes 6-foot-8, runs like a deer, jump likes the same
running deer when it approaches a fallen tree or something, and has
the energy of a deer that has mistaken coffee beans for pinon nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, rising Clipper hero Tyrone Nesby was one of the stars
of last year's Desert Classic and didn't get drafted. Regardless of
how stupid some NBA personnel regulars remain, Posey's name will be
called in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Desert Classic also was the scene for the unveiling of agent
Bill Duffy's mystery client, Menk Batear. Duffy, who represents
Michael Olowokandi, last year's No. 1 pick, went all the way to
China to land the 6-10, 270-pound Menk (pronounced ``Monk'').
</P>
<P>
   STAR-CROSSED BLAZERS
</P>
<P>
   As we underscored in this space a few weeks ago, Portland's
active roster has nine lottery picks who weren't originally drafted
by front-office sharpie Bob Whitsitt.
</P>
<P>
   They also have zero players on their active roster who have made
an appearance in an NBA All-Star Game. Yet. A playoff problem?
Shouldn't be.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it might be if you believe championships are traced to the
presence of Hall of Fame players. Bulls? Jordan and Pippen.
Rockets? Olajuwon and Drexler. Pistons? Thomas. Lakers? Please.
76ers? Dr. J and Moses. Celtics? We don't have enough space.
</P>
<P>
   The last team to win an NBA title without a Hall of Fame lock?
The Seattle SuperSonics.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics became champs 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   NO THIRD-STRING MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   Former Compton playground, John Muir High (Pasadena) and Kansas
University star Jacque Vaughn has become the Maytag repairman of
NBA point guards.
</P>
<P>
   The second-year pro, who rides the Utah Jazz bench as insurance
for John Stockton and Howard Eisley, still believes his time will
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned a lot,'' Vaughn said of practice wars with
Stockton, ``and I have to look at it that way. But I have to be
concerned about my future when I see guys I've done well against
getting opportunities with other teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what I can do. I just have to be patient and ready when
I get my chance.''
</P>
<P>
   SHOT-CLOCK VIOLATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Four years after steering UCLA's NCAA championship drive, former
Poly High star Tyus Edney finds himself back in a final four.
Edney, who was drafted by the Sacramento Kings in the second round
of the 1995 NBA Draft, now plays point guard for Zalgiris Kaunus, a
pro team based in Lithuania. Zalgiris has qualified for the
semifinal round of the European Championships. Its center happens
to be George Zidek, Edney's teammate and roommate at UCLA. ... How
silly can some coaches be in attempting to gain an advantage? Well
Miami's Pat Riley does not allow opposing players to use the Heat's
weight room at Miami Arena. Toronto's Butch Carter has a similar
policy. As strategy, that's pretty weak. Several teams counter by
banning the Heat and Raptors from their facilities. ... Don Nelson
really made a smooth move by dealing Dallas' next first-round pick
(a lottery biggie) just to acquire point guard Steve Nash, who
ranks last among his starting peers in field-goal percentage and is
24th in assists. ... If Allen Iverson really needs endorsements,
his crossover dribble could make him a natural as
chamber-of-commerce shill for Palm Springs. ... Their popularity
with NBC won't make the Lakers champions, but it could get them
syndicated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
