<HEADLINE>
HEAR THAT SOUND: IT'S SONICS FALLING DOWN, GOING BOOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Warning: This column has been designated a
Rodman-free zone, a subject that is already tired but will no doubt
be further regurgitated by too many newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean we won't be discussing mental problems.
Namely, the Seattle SchizoSonics, a team that has nice-guy coach
Paul Westphal exhibiting unusual behavior and thinking he should
have waited another season before coaching again. It's so bad
lately in Seattle that Jelani McCoy is viewed as a pleasant
surprise and booster of team morale.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the Schizos have a 7-6 record against the top five
teams in the Western Conference _ which is more than respectable _
but are just 6-13 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics used to be just another team who's chance at winning
an NBA title had vanished. But their problems are much deeper than
that.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, they beat the Sacramento Kings in overtime 99-98 and
celebrated more than a team that evened its record at 19-19 should
have.
</P>
<P>
   The normally laid-back Westphal blew a kiss to the crowd as he
ran off the court, upset over the Kings fans' treatment of former
center Olden Polynice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our biggest win,'' Westphal said. ``No question.''
</P>
<P>
   The next night, the Sonics went out and got blown off the court
in an embarrassing 30-point loss to the Nets in Seattle. Then there
was the NBA record-low of 19 rebounds they had in a loss to Phoenix
earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many (rebounds) did we have?'' asked point guard Gary
Payton. ``Two?''
</P>
<P>
   With such a record of underachievement, the Sonics are starting
to panic. There is speculation that Payton will be traded this
summer because he is under contract until 2003 and still considered
the best defensive player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the Sonics are just an old team. Forward Vin
Baker is the only impact player under 30, and he becomes a free
agent after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Some hard choices lay ahead, and it's unclear if GM Wally Walker
has the know-how to rebuild the Sonics, especially if you listen to
George Karl.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you feel better about the Lakers already?
</P>
<P>
   And then we have the Knicks: Also known as Team Free Fall, it's
become a three-ring circus because of the different cliques within
the team.
</P>
<P>
   There's the three newcomers _ Marcus Camby, Latrell Sprewell and
Kurt Thomas _ who have all come from losing programs and seem to be
indifferent about the team's fortunes. After a recent loss to
Indiana, while guard Chris Childs was complaining about some
teammates not caring enough about losing, the three amigos were in
the background laughing, sharing a private joke.
</P>
<P>
   The next clique is known as the God squad, led by Charlie Ward
and Allan Houston. Teammates believe they take losses too easily
because they often say it is ``God's will'' and ``everything will
be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's a third group, known as the warriors, led by
Patrick Ewing and Larry Johnson. They will do anything to win, even
playing with injuries that could, if they aggravate them, cost
significant time. Ewing has tendinitis in his left Achilles' tendon
and Johnson has battled a right knee sprain.
</P>
<P>
   All three groups seem to be pulling in different directions,
which is why this team will have to scramble to make the playoffs.
If they don't, it means good-bye not only to coach Jeff Van Gundy,
but probably to GM Ernie Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Revenge of the Mailman?: Phoenix center Luc Longley believes
Utah's Karl Malone was out to hurt him when Malone crashed into the
Aussie center last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Longley hyperextended his left knee and said Malone was trying
to even the score after losing two NBA titles to Longley when he
was with the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked pretty bloody flagrant to me,'' Longley said. ``It
looked like he went for my knee, and that's weak. I'm just amazed
that someone would do that. He had a smile on his face when he was
going back down the court. I looked at that on the video and I was
amazed. We all make our living with our bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   All business: The Pacers got booed off their floor after losing
at home to Charlotte and have decided to get serious. They dropped
their pre-game ritual, in which each player had their own dance
step during introductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pretty much took away our privilege of doing things with
flair,'' guard Mark Jackson said. ``That has nothing to do with
winning or losing, but that's something that was a privilege
because we were an elite team. We've gotten away from playing like
that, though, so until we show we're there again, we've put it on
ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Tour of duty: Former NBA players Connie Hawkins, Charlie Scott
and Dwayne ``Pearl'' Washington are in Bosnia this week for
basketball instructional clinics and visits with NATO troops. Next
week, Artis Gilmore, Dan Roundfield and Randy Smith will give
similar clinics in the war-torn country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
