<HEADLINE>
WIDE RECEIVER GARNER INJURES KNEE IN SCRIMMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's defense dominated its second scrimmage of
the spring Saturday, but the Trojans might have lost another player
to a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Troy Garner of Notre Dame High possibly damaged
the ligaments in his left knee during the 74-play scrimmage. He
will be examined today, and USC coach Paul Hackett feared the
injury was potentially season-ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look good,'' Hackett said. ``Nobody touched him.
It's so frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans lost middle linebacker Mike Pollard last week after
he tore knee ligaments.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Hackett was pleased with the defense Saturday. Free
safety Darnell Lacy had the play of the game, intercepting a pass
and returning it 75 yards for a touchdown. Senior safety Frank
Carter had two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman linebacker Armand Holland had a team-high 10 tackles
and sophomore linebacker Henry Wallace particularly impressed
Hacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wallace) is just a huge improvement from where he was,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Strong performance: Offensively, USC was led by sophomore
tailback Frank Strong, who had 75 yards in six carries. Petros
Papadakis had 40 yards in nine carries with two touchdowns. Chad
Morton had 20 yards in eight carries.
</P>
<P>
   Carson Palmer, who has been bothered by a groin pull, completed
9 of 14 passes for 57 yards and one interception. Mike Van
Raaphorst completed 11 of 15 for 107 yards with an interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Bobby DeMars of Westlake did not play, bothered by
a torn abdominal muscle. He will be examined next week before a
decision is made on whether he will participate in USC's final
three practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
