<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-AVALANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREPARING TO SURVIVE AVALANCHE SEASON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Colo. Ore., Wash.)  (rk) 
 By DEBORAH JONES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHISTLER, British Columbia _ Record snowfalls this year
contributed to disastrous slides in North America and Europe, and
avalanche centers continued to report fatalities such as a skier
buried and killed near Ophir, Colo., on April 7. Now, even as
warmth creeps up to the high Alpine, avalanche risk continues for
spring and summer adventurers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger doesn't ever go away; you can get caught in a slide
in the high mountains in August,'' said Tom Kimbrough, an avalanche
forecaster with the U.S. Forest Service at the Utah Avalanche
Forecast Center. Last summer, two climbers were killed in separate
incidents in May and June on Mount Hood, Ore., and Mount Rainier,
Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Most fatal avalanches are set off by the victim or companions,
and risk management can mean the difference between life and death.
With that in mind, because my family spends all of its free time in
the mountains of the Pacific Northwest, I signed up with my
11-year-old son, Gavin, for a free one-day avalanche tour here at
Whistler.
</P>
<P>
   We met Roger Sarrasin, a back-country guide and volunteer safety
instructor, at the base of Blackcomb Mountain and boarded a chair
lift. Immediately, we were enveloped by a veil of feathery
snowflakes, and our instruction began. ``See the arms on the
snowflakes?'' Sarrasin asked. Arms form more stable bonds with old
snow than sphere-shaped flakes known as sugar snow, Sarrasin
explained. On the ground, however, snow changes constantly,
affected by wind, humidity, pressure and temperature, while the
snow pack differs at different elevations and on lee and windward
slope sides. All factors _ with gravity _ determine whether a
person's weight will cause a slide.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 minutes into the tour, I realized that avalanche risk is
less a science than an art, and I knew I would never remember all
the variables. I was relieved when Sarrasin suggested a ski run.
</P>
<P>
   When we alighted on a ridge to plan our next euphoric dash,
Sarrasin sobered us up by pointing out a slope above a chair lift
which, he explained, is one of untold hundreds of avalanche runs at
the Whistler ski resort. But not to worry, he assured us. Only in
the back country or out of resort boundaries is there high risk,
because North American resorts use bombs to start controlled slides
and eliminate rogue avalanches.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, we heard the patrollers far above. The booms echoed off
the peaks and reverberated down the valley, and I looked at my son
and briefly wondered at the lunacy of a sport that requires bombs
for safety. Then, we were off again, momentarily forgetting that
slides kill more North Americans than any other natural hazard,
including hurricanes and earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   Those most at risk are snowmobilers, like the seven riders
killed in two separate avalanches in Alaska in recent weeks. New
technology and the fact that riders travel far and fast over
differing terrain equal risk, Kimbrough said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Snowboarders riding outside resort boundaries are often caught
in slides but perish less often, perhaps because they stay close to
resort areas where rescue is likely. While back-country skiers die
each year, as a group they have educated themselves well, Kimbrough
said.
</P>
<P>
   It's very difficult while skiing rare fresh powder to turn the
mind from play to education, but Sarrasin persisted, dispensing
wisdom between runs. Even an avalanche two inches deep can kill you
because it can sweep you into a tree or off a cliff, he warned.
</P>
<P>
   When snow slides, the bonds between the layers dissolve and the
snow behaves much like liquid water. If caught, he advised, try to
escape to the side; failing that, shed heavy gear and swim upward;
almost nobody buried deeper than six feet survives.
</P>
<P>
   When an avalanche stops, the snow sets like concrete so quickly,
and so hard, that a victim can rarely put a hand over his mouth to
form an air pocket. I tested this theory, trying in vain to chip at
a refrigerator-size chunk of avalanche debris. It was so hard and
tomblike that the ``Star Wars'' character Han Solo came to mind,
frozen into a solid block.
</P>
<P>
   Once buried, a victim's only chance is to be located and dug out
_ before suffocation _ by the trained and well-equipped buddies
everyone should travel with, each carrying a locator transmitter
and receiver strapped around the chest and a collapsible probe and
shovel in a backpack.
</P>
<P>
   Prevention is the key, of course, and to estimate risk, digging
snow pits is recommended _ an arduous, repetitive task, because
information gathered in one pit may not apply a stone's throw away
or an hour later. The pit should be deep enough to stand in, then
skis or a saw is used to carve a straight-sided column from one
side.
</P>
<P>
   As Sarrasin created a column, I was startled to see clearly
defined layers, each deposited from a storm, emerge; throughout
them lurked layers of unstable sugar snow. Risk is measured by the
pressure needed to shatter the column, and as Sarrasin tapped
lightly with his shovel, his column fractured into precise slabs.
</P>
<P>
   I imagined a slab the size of an entire slope racing down a
mountain at top avalanche speed of 120 miles an hour _ and
understood why injuries kill 20 percent of avalanche victims (the
rest suffocate).
</P>
<P>
   This past winter, freakish slides in France, Italy, Switzerland
and Austria had killed more than 70 people at midwinter (some in
buildings swept away by snow). Since last fall (avalanche season is
measured for one year starting each October), 43 North Americans
have died, compared with 46 the previous season and 35 in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche bulletins are now issued in each state and province,
and courses are organized by avalanche centers in the United States
and Canada. Two Web sites _ www.csac.org and www.avalanche.org _
have also been set up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
