<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS AGAIN DRAFT CAROLINA END WITH FIRST CHOICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ With their first selection in the 1999 NFL
Draft, the Cowboys picked. ... a defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   It should.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth time in the past six years, the Cowboys made a
move to upgrade their pass rush with their first pick in the draft
_ choosing North Carolina defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban with the
20th pick yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   However, unlike past years when the choice of an end was based
solely on need, picking the 6-foot-3, 281-pound Ekuban, a native of
Ghana, can be credited to the best-player-available philosophy that
typified all of the Cowboys selections yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys took offensive linemen Solomon Page of West Virginia
in the second round and Texas A&AMP;M All-America linebacker Dat Nguyen
in the third round. Earlier in the day, the Cowboys signed
free-agent linebacker Quentin Coryatt to a three-year contract and
restructured the contract of fullback Daryl Johnston to lower his
salary and allow him to remain with team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took the best athletes available,'' Cowboys owner Jerry
Jones said. ``It was unique the way it fell. What we did in the
free agency with Quentin and receiver Raghib Ismail and center Mark
Stepnoski allowed us to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the uncertain status of defensive tackle Leon Lett
did not affect the team's draft picks. According to a source, Lett,
a member of stage three of the league's substance-abuse program,
has violated the NFL's drug policy again and faces an indefinite
ban from the league.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the team actively tried to move up in the draft. A
source said the Cowboys made calls to the Vikings at 11, the Bears
at 12, the Steelers at 13, the Chiefs at 14, the Buccaneers at 15
and the Titans at 16 with the idea of taking either Louisiana Tech
receiver Troy Edwards, Louisiana State defensive tackle Anthony
McFarland or Florida outside linebacker Jevon Kearse.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Cowboys found no takers for their offer of the 22nd
pick in first round and a second-round pick because ``many of those
teams liked their draft position or wanted the same players'' Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the Steelers took Edwards, the Buccaneers took
McFarland and the Titans took Kearse, the Cowboys made a move with
Seattle to move up two spots to get Ekuban.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very high on our board,'' Jones said. ``He was the last
first-round defensive player left on our board.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey echoed Jones, saying ``he was the best
player available and we were fortunate to get him.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Cowboys loaded up on defensive ends with the
first pick in the past _ Shante Carver in 1994, Kavika Pittman in
1996 and Greg Ellis in 1998 _ had no bearing on their decision to
choose Ekuban, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Dave Campo said improving the Cowboys'
pass rush is a must, and the speedy Ekuban gives them a chance to
do that. Carver is no longer with the team. Pittman and Ellis
combined for nine sacks last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more pressure on the passer,'' Campo said. ``This is
another possibility for someone to come in and play. This young man
brings a speed dimension to the game. We are excited to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban has only played defensive end the past two seasons after
playing tight end as a freshman and sophomore. However, the speed
and athletic ability he showed this past season when he led the Tar
Heels with 12 sacks was impressive enough for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement goes both ways.
</P>
<P>
   When Jones called to ask Ekuban if he was ``ready to wear a star
on his helmet'' his response was barely audible.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family just jumped up and down,'' said Ekuban, whose dad is
a official with the Senegalese embassy in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was yelling and screaming. The Cowboys couldn't hear
me talk. I was in shock. I am very happy to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban is also happy to be on the same team again with Ellis,
last season's top pick who also went to North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban, who said Ellis helped him in his move to defensive end
two seasons ago, will again be looking to Ellis for guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being with Greg at Carolina was beneficial to me,'' Ekuban
said. ``It helped me mature and learn the defensive end position. I
know he'll do the same for me with the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban's presence, however, also prompts a position switch for
Ellis. He is one of several options the Cowboys are considering to
help improve their depth at defensive tackle. Campo said Ellis and
Michael Myers, who played end as a rookie last season, both have
the ability to play tackle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
