<HEADLINE>
TORONTO BEATS NEW YORK, 93-90  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Wallace used to be a Knick. John Thomas and Doug
Christie, too. Did we mention Charles Oakley, the manual laborer
who outfoxed and outboxed his former team Saturday night?
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Raptors have essentially become Vince Carter and New
York North, a scintillating rookie sandwiched between a bunch of
former Knicks who still get up for the team that did not want them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's human emotion to play well against the team that sent you
away,'' Thomas said after he combined with Oakley, Christie and
Wallace 40 points, 19 rebounds and 11 assists in Toronto's 93-90
victory at Madison Square Garden. ``There's nothing personal, but
you naturally get up more for a game like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Oakley appreciation column can wait for another day.
Frankly, the way he knocked down all five of his shots and snatched
the game's key rebound from the player for whom he was traded,
Marcus Camby, in the final seconds was proof that Oakley may have
more than a year or two left in his hallmark career.
</P>
<P>
   Who cannot wait are the Knicks, a team that might miss the
playoffs for the first time since Hubie Brown and Bob Hill could
not fix things in 1987. If you have followed this team for long, it
must be unfathomable to see them unable to stop the other team from
scoring when they need the ball back.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Knicks consistently chipped paint off the rim
during the Riley era, they always could dig in, get nasty and put
their behinds on the opposing players. They gave up 12 offensive
rebounds Saturday night to a team that had lost its last six games.
Oakley is impossible to keep off the glass, but when you can't
block out Christie, there is a major problem.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Knicks lately is like watching some saucy Fox
special, like ``Amazing Car Chases'' or the ``World's Most
Incredibly Bad Defensive Teams.'' It's chaotic, exciting. But the
ending is always bad.
</P>
<P>
   The other night against the Wizards, the Knicks had a 5-point
lead in regulation and a 3-point lead late in overtime. And lost.
They also led Detroit by 9 points in the fourth quarter of Friday
night's loss on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The chemistry problems are clear, and Oakley was at least honest
enough to acknowledge them before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to win, but they have to understand that this game
is not an individual game,'' Oakley said, ``just because the g.m.
thinks they can get a guy that is talented. But is he talented
enough to play in the system that's already here? It's hard to get
guys to compliment other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not just taking yet another potshot at Ernie Grunfeld,
the Knicks president who traded Oakley last June. Oakley was also
doing what he always did best in New York: giving you the plain,
unadulterated truth about the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys have to do what Jeff wants to do,'' Oakley said of Knicks
Coach Jeff Van Gundy. He also said the club's chemistry problems
have less to do with Camby and more to do with Latrell Sprewell,
the team's No. 1 off-season gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sprewell is a good player, but he's not really for this
team,'' Oakley said. ``This team is more half-court and Sprewell
wants to get out on the break. He's not an East Coast player.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what now? ``The pieces to the puzzle don't fit? You buy
another puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was part of the mix two years ago. Cocksure and playful
to a fault, he became a little too large for even his obscenely
baggy britches as a rookie out of Syracuse. But there he was
Saturday night, giving Larry Johnson an earful after scoring on
him.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the third quarter, Wallace had Sprewell
plastered to him on the right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Facing up the smaller defender, the 6-foot-9-inch Wallace used
two shot fakes before going around Sprewell on the right baseline
and dunking hard. Do you know how much the Knicks could use that
kind of low-post scorer at this point?
</P>
<P>
   Thomas has emerged as a decent garbage man as a reserve.
Christie still takes too many circus shots. Not all of these former
Knicks would fit into the current team's scheme. There is no reason
to think that any of them, save Oakley, could send this
slumping-again franchise into the playoffs on a winning note.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something oddly appropriate about a team that was
supposed to be bound for the lottery picking the Knicks apart in a
regular-season game of major consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Crazy, no? Oakley was said to be exiled to Toronto six months
ago, his proud career expected to die north of the border in some
National Basketball Association outpost.
</P>
<P>
   He and his team looked very much alive Saturday night. Maybe he
got out of here just in time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
