<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-AHTLETICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CAN'T MAKE THEIR PITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Just when the Rangers thought they were headed
in the right direction, they run into the Oakland Athletics and
fall flat on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Poor starting pitching and a stagnant offense have led to two
consecutive trouncings, the latest coming yesterday in a 11-3 loss
to the Athletics at Network Associates Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The debacle came the day after the Athletics dumped the Rangers,
8-2, in the first of a three-game series. The Rangers have one game
left to salvage something against the A's; otherwise, they nullify
their uplifting three-game sweep of the Seattle Mariners at the
start of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we wanted to come in here and play well, and
obviously we haven't,'' left fielder Rusty Greer said. ``Coming out
of Seattle I think everybody was looking for us to get into one of
those rolls. But you've got to hand it to the A's. They've played
great baseball and beat us two in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitching remains an underlying cause when the Rangers
begin to stumble. The Athletics hammered Aaron Sele for six runs in
four innings on Friday and Mark Clark gave up five runs in five
innings yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Four came in the first inning when Clark gave up a two-run homer
to Jason Giambi and a two-run double to Mike Macfarlane.
</P>
<P>
   Clark is 0-2 with a 10.68 ERA in three starts for the Rangers,
and has yet to pitch past the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's frustrating,'' Clark said. ``Even though I gave up
four runs in the first inning, I thought I threw the ball better
than I did in my first two outings. But, on this ballclub, if you
go out and do your job and keep us in the game, with this offense
you're going to win a lot of ballgames. I haven't done that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been one of my strengths over the past few years,
pitching deep into the game, the sixth, seventh and eighth inning.
I haven't done that here and it's frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the Rangers' pitching problems can be traced to the
rotation. Rafael Palmeiro made it a 5-3 ballgame with a two-run
homer in the sixth off Oakland starter Jimmy Haynes, but the
Athletics scored three runs in the bottom of the inning against
reliever Mike Munoz.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Tejada started the rally with a bunt hit past Munoz and
then Tony Phillips hit a roller down the first baseline. Munoz
started to let it go foul, then decided it wouldn't and tried to
make a play. Instead he threw wildly to first, allowing Tejada to
race to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should have let that swinging bunt go foul,'' Munoz
said. ``Worst-case scenario is they have runners on first and
second, best-case scenario is it rolls foul.''
</P>
<P>
   The inning unraveled from there as Scott Spiezio doubled into
the left-field corner for two runs and scored on Giambi's single to
right-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the inning right there,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
``We score two to get back in the game and in the bottom of the
sixth we give up three. That's a very important inning for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' offense rolled over after that as Haynes and
reliever Buddy Groom combined to retire the last nine hitters they
faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys played us tough last year,'' third baseman Todd
Zeile said. ``They put a lot of runs up and for whatever reason, we
haven't countered with many.
</P>
<P>
   ``That guy \RHaynes\S did a good job but I don't know how many
line outs we had. At the opposite end of the spectrum, they hit a
couple of balls off the end of the bat that fell in and some balls
that found some holes. Things are going right for them.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Rangers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have been sort of erratic for us,'' Zeile said. ``We
haven't been consistent, that's what you look for more than
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially after all the fun they had in Seattle.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
