<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMBAT
</P>
<P>
   -- NATO continued its air war, bombing targets including
refineries and chemical plants in the Serbian capital, Belgrade,
and Novi Sad, a military airport near the capital and the main road
from Belgrade to the Montenegrin capital, Podgorica, Serbian
officials said. A 3-year-old child was said to have been killed and
five people were injured in Belgrade. NATO said its warplanes
destroyed seven tanks on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   -- Serbian army and police units swept through southern Kosovo,
burning and wrecking villages and driving out the inhabitants, NATO
commanders said.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES
</P>
<P>
   -- Another 13,000 refugees streamed into Albania, relief
officials said, while 7,000 more arrived in Macedonia, where the
defense minister was quoted as saying he would not permit new
refugee camps to be built.
</P>
<P>
   DIPLOMACY
</P>
<P>
   -- Former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin of Russia, his
country's special envoy, will present President Boris Yeltsin with
proposals on Monday aimed at resolving the conflict, Russian news
agencies said.
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER
</P>
<P>
   -- Clear skies over the southern Balkans created ideal
conditions for allied attacks early on Sunday morning. Bad weather
overnight Friday to Saturday had made for poor conditions for
allied warplanes the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Yugoslavia is available
from The New York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
