<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT PICKS NOT BOLD, BUT FREE AGENTS LOOK QUITE SHARP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ With customary draft-day fluff and puff, Cowboys
coaches and hierarchy gave us their best ``we couldn't believe he
was still there'' song-and-dance yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just them. It happens every April for all NFL
clubs. The reality of October and November is often harsh on
rookies, but for this weekend each draft pick is a ``player.''
</P>
<P>
   At Valley Ranch, however, this particular draft was unlike any
other, because as coach Chan Gailey said yesterday, ``we had a good
draft before the draft even started.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the 1999 season is concerned, somebody named Ebenezer
Ekuban, somebody named Solomon Page, and a real somebody named Dat
Nguyen _ Dallas' 1-2-3 picks _ could have little if any impact on
success or failure. Although do watch that Nguyen kid.
</P>
<P>
   But Gailey was making reference to the team's success in free
agency last week. The Cowboys are very proud, and rightfully so, of
a free-agency class that was completed when linebacker Quentin
Coryatt was added yesterday. He joins receiver Rocket Ismail and
center Mark Stepnoski. All three address immediate club needs.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jones continued his ``win now'' mission, but did so with a
new plan _ this is by far Jones' boldest plunge into free agency.
</P>
<P>
   If it had only ended there yesterday _ with the draft and the
free agents. But also looming large over Valley Ranch was the Leon
Lett cloud. If another substance-abuse suspension is coming for
Lett, the defensive line is even more miserable than last season,
and last season was not acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Jones has a personal credibility issue to settle.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't draft Randy Moss last April due to character flaws,
then you can't keep Leon Lett around Valley Ranch. No Moss. No
Lett.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking of song and dance, everyone connected with the
Cowboys was doing just that yesterday on the subject of Lett. A
suspension of some sort appears to be coming, but will it be four
games or a season?
</P>
<P>
   Jones was trying to distance himself yesterday from the Moss
case being compared to the Lett case. But it's a thin line for
Jerry to be grabbing a solid toe hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Moss was such a high-profile issue,'' he said of the '98
draft controversy. ``As an organization, we were much more under
the scope than we are now. I viewed it \Rthe decision not to draft
Moss\S as a test on whether I could avoid the devil.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones wasn't comparing Moss to the devil, but instead, his own
temptation to draft him while in the midst of a
clean-up-the-Cowboys campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, what the Cowboys think was a major off-season team
upgrade due to the free agents, could have been seriously
undermined by Lett and his wandering nose. And Jones will also have
this Moss double standard issue to battle.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys already had second-guessers galore yesterday,, but
those would have been on football talent issues, not credibility
gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Their draft will be knocked for a lack of boldness, but repeated
attempts to trade up in the first round were stonewalled by teams
that didn't want to deal, or demanded a ransom of extra picks to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   So the Cowboys stuck to a take-the-best-player-available
philosophy. In the long run, that's usually the best way.
</P>
<P>
   But even the free-agency class is being questioned nationally _
not Stepnoski or Coryatt _ which leaves Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   For any local doubters on Rocket, my suggestion is this:
</P>
<P>
   Trust in Gailey, which also gives us the right to turn on Chan
if Ismail turns out to be the second coming of Anthony Miller.
</P>
<P>
   But at the position of wide receiver in the NFL, the benefit of
the doubt can be afforded Mr. Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Ernie Mills is one reason. And Patrick Jeffers, to name a
second effective receiver who came out of nowhere last season for
the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   And before that, Yancey Thigpen in Pittsburgh, along with Andre
Hastings.
</P>
<P>
   Judging Ismail's value is a tough read. Some teams with speed
receiver needs, such as the Dolphins, never gave him a sniff this
spring. Carolina, however, did want him back and was apparently
ready to match any money Jones offered.
</P>
<P>
   But when Rocket made it known he wanted to come to Dallas and be
a catcher for Troy Aikman, the Cowboys considered Ismail priority
No. 1 in free agency. This, of course, was based on the Gailey
factor in judging and developing receivers who have previously
underachieved, which certainly means Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   Between the draft, the free agents and another Lett mess, it was
a busy Saturday at Valley Ranch. And until the Lett question is
answered, and until Rocket takes the field, it's impossible to say
if a better team did emerge, even if the football signals are
rather positive.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
