r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-LONE-STAR-KRONE-T     04-17 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONE-STAR-KRONE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRONE MAKING FAREWELL RIDE TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ At Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie today,
one superstar bids farewell to the winner's circle while another
tries to get back in it.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Krone will make what she insists is the final ride of her
legendary 18-year career when she takes the track with Desert Demon
in the $300,000 Lone Star Park Derby.
</P>
<P>
   An hour before that, Real Quiet will become the first Kentucky
Derby winner to compete at a Texas track when he runs in the
$250,000 Texas Mile under jockey Gary Stevens. The appearance of
the 4-year-old colt is an occasion, but he hasn't won since the
Preakness Stakes 11 months ago, recording two second-place
finishes, including a heartbreaking defeat by a nose in the Belmont
Stakes that cost him a Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The eventful afternoon _ which Lone Star general manager Corey
Johnsen has called the greatest in Texas racing history _ begins at
1:35 p.m. with the first of 11 live races.
</P>
<P>
   The Lone Star Derby will be televised on ESPN from 5-6 p.m. The
Texas Mile _ the state's first graded stakes _ can be seen on a
tape-delay on ESPN2 at 6:30.
</P>
<P>
   Krone, 36, has refused recent interview requests. But at a news
conference in New York last week, she said she is retiring to
pursue other interests, including a college degree, and because of
the numerous injuries she has suffered in recent years. Her only
previous appearance at Lone Star was last June, when she finished
second to Shane Sellers in the, Krone had ridden 3,543 winners from
20,472 mounts and accumulated purse earnings of $81.1 million. Her
biggest victory was aboard Colonial Affair in the 1993 Belmont
Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Real Quiet's most notorious defeat was in last
year's Belmont, when Victory Gallop and Stevens nipped him by a
nose to rob him of the $5 million bonus offered by Visa for a
Triple Crown sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet has run only once since then, finishing second by a
half-length to Precocity in the New Orleans Handicap on March 7.
Seven horses will face him in the Texas Mile, including
Littlebitlively, who defeated Anet to win last year's running. Like
Anet, Real Quiet is trained by Bob Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens will be riding Real Quiet for the first time in a race,
although he has been on him in workouts. In Real Quiet's past eight
races, the mount belonged to Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awesome,'' Stevens said. ``Having worked him a couple of
times, now I understand how fortunate I was to beat him in the
Belmont last year.''
</P>
<P>
   If Real Quiet wins today, Stevens says not to expect a runaway.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the colt's habit of ``fooling around'' when he
makes the lead too quickly, Stevens said, ``I'm going to be very
content to have a target in front of me until very deep in the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Black Mercury, also trained by Baffert and ridden by Stevens, is
the early favorite in the Lone Star Derby. The 11/16 mile race is
run only two weeks prior to the Kentucky Derby and isn't a graded
stakes, so it is unlikely to produce a starter at Churchill Downs.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
