r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-EKUBAN-TE     04-17 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-EKUBAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EKUBAN OVERCOMES INEXPERIENCE WITH ATHLETIC ABILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Ebenezer Ekuban did not start playing organized
football until his junior year in high school and has played just
21 games as a defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   This inexperience did not stop him from becoming, according to
many draft experts, the top-rated player at his position. And it
did not stop the Cowboys from taking the Ghana native with their
first pick in yesterday's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This young man brings a speed dimension to the game,'' Cowboys
defensive coordinator Dave Campo said. ``We've heard nothing from
anybody in the media other than we can't rush the passer. So now
we're going to give ourselves a chance to rush the passer.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed the ``Ghana Piranha,'' Ekuban (6-foot-3, 281 pounds)
is an extremely athletic lineman with high intensity, according to
scouting services such as Mel Kiper Jr.'s and Ourlads', both of
whom rated Ekuban as the best defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting by a 4.63-second time in the 40-yard dash, he was
recruited by North Carolina to play tight end, but was moved to
defensive end before the start of the 1997 season by Mack Brown,
then the Tar Heels' coach.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after Ekuban was drafted by the Cowboys, Brown, now the
coach at Texas, called Ekuban at his father's home in Washington,
D.C., to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a proud day for him,'' Brown said. ``I told Ebenezer that
if he would switch to defensive end, he would play in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban, who moved with his family from Ghana when he was 7,
caught six passes in two years as a Tar Heels tight end. He started
twice as a defensive end in 1997, and then had a breakout year in
1998, registering 96 tackles, including a school-record 23 behind
the line of scrimmage, seven sacks, and four pass deflections.
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban wowed scouts at the Senior Bowl in January with his
athleticism and his speed as a pass rusher. In fact, Cowboys line
coach Jim Bates said Ekuban is faster off the corners than Greg
Ellis, the Cowboys' 1998 first-round pick who started in front of
Ekuban at North Carolina in 1997. Until he becomes a more
accomplished player, however, Ekuban will join the Cowboys as a
backup behind Ellis and Kavika Pittman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll come in here and he'll show what he can do, and his
playing time will be determined by how he shows,'' coach Chan
Gailey said of Ekuban. ``He's obviously going to be on the field
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ekuban: ``It was great playing with Greg, and I'm glad I
get to play with him again because he really helped me mature.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban is expected to be in Dallas today for a noon news
conference. As he packed his belongings before boarding team owner
Jerry Jones' private jet, Ekuban expressed his elation with his new
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few minutes before they drafted me, they called and said,
`Are you ready to have a star on your head?' '' Ekuban said. ``I
just couldn't believe it. I was excited. My family was jumping up
and yelling so loud that when the Cowboys called me, they couldn't
hear what I was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
