<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS USE THEIR 2 PICKS TO TRY TO STRENGTHEN OFFENSIVE LINE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The Jets twiddled their thumbs for almost
eight hours in Saturday's draft _ their first pick was the 57th
over all, late in the second round _ but discovered when it was
their turn that their most highly rated guard was still available.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' choice was Randy Thomas of Mississippi State, a
6-foot-3-inch, 306-pounder, and Coach Bill Parcells immediately
said that he would try Thomas at right guard. And with their next
pick, in the third round at No. 90 over all, the Jets picked
another lineman they will try at guard, David Loverne, who played
left tackle at San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was the first pure guard chosen in the draft. Guard was
the position where the Jets had a sudden great need because they do
not have a starter at either spot. They recently cut Todd Burger
and are proceeding as if the free-agent right guard Matt O'Dwyer
will not return.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells described Thomas, who did not play organized football
until 10th grade, as more gifted athletically than the other highly
rated guards, Doug Brzezinski of Boston College and Brandon
Burlsworth of Arkansas. Their technique is considered better than
Thomas', who was a junior college transfer and played two seasons
at Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletically, he's far superior to them,'' said Parcells, who
lauded Thomas' ability to pull. ``He plays as if he knows what he's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Loverne, who is 6-2{ and 292 pounds, will be shifted to left
guard. He is considered highly athletic and a solid pass protector.
``I'm pretty sure he'll compete strongly for this job,'' Parcells
said. ``Every time he was challenged, he responded.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the lowest the Jets have taken their first pick of the
draft _ one notch below last year, when they chose defensive
lineman Dorian Boose at No. 56. The Jets lost this year's
first-round selection as part of reparations to the Patriots in the
deal that made Parcells the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the Steelers, who had the 59th pick, had been eager
to draft him, keeping him on the telephone during the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited and waited, thinking about New York,'' Thomas said.
``Then I said: `I guess I'll be a Jet. I guess I'm at home now.'
They needed a right guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said: ``You never know where an offensive lineman is
going to fit in. You know athletically he has the ability to fit
in. We need to find out where he is technically. Hopefully, he'll
be far enough long to help us.''
</P>
<P>
   One draft publication, GM jr, described Thomas as ``among the
best athletes of all the offensive linemen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have had mixed success with Parcells' first two Jets
drafts, in which Dick Haley played the lead role in organizing the
selections. Of their 23 picks, 14 remain with the club. One is a
starter on offense _ last year's fourth-round pick, tackle Jason
Fabini _ and one on defense _ lineman Jason Ferguson, the last pick
of the Jets' 1997 draft.
</P>
<P>
   There are also Leon Johnson, one of the best third-down backs
and kick returners in recent Jets history, and Dedric Ward, the
deep threat receiver and kick returner.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker James Farrior, Parcells' first pick in his first
draft in 1997, was demoted to a backup last year. And free safety
Kevin Williams, who began last season as a rookie starter, was also
benched and will now try playing cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Two players who missed last year with injuries will get serious
looks this summer: linebacker Casey Dailey and defensive lineman
Terry Day. Doug Karczewski, a rookie guard last season, may be
given a shot at starting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
